<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAVORITES RUSH THROUGH TO THE FOURTH ROUND  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update, and delete photo note; no photos with this
story)   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The favorites at the U.S. Open, hustled through their
paces by some tricky wind currents, took care of business with such
dispatch Saturday that eighth-seeded Andre Agassi was not ready
when he received the call for his third-round match with Davide
Sanguinetti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both matches combined were like an hour and 15 minutes _
phenomenal,'' said Agassi, whose match was the third and last of
the day session in Arthur Ashe Stadium. ``I felt rather rushed; I
didn't enjoy that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   At the grizzled tennis age of 28, Agassi no longer finds it fun
to operate in fifth gear on command, which he had to do Saturday in
part because of fifth-seeded Venus Williams' 13-minute, 5-0 defeat
of an injured Larisa Neiland of Latvia.
</P>
<P>
   But Agassi suited and sneakered up in a flurry and disposed of
the 50th-ranked Italian Sanguinetti in such a hurry himself, 6-2,
6-3, 6-0, that the main stadium was left without a feature match by
midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In response, 15th-seeded Anna Kournikova was rerouted from the
subsidiary stage at Louis Armstrong Stadium. The change suited the
teen-age diva so well that she pranced through her third-round
encounter with another Italian, the 26-year-old Silvia Farina, 6-4,
6-1, to secure a Round of 16 berth against Arantxa Sanchez Vicario.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova's childhood sparring partner, the 18-year-old Russian
Marat Safin, had to settle for an assignment at the old stadium,
but he too disposed of an elder, vanquishing Thomas Muster by 6-4,
6-4, 1-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Muster, a former No. 1 player, is now 30 years old and ranked
23rd. The 60th-ranked Safin, whose powerful game has inspired
predictions that he could hit No. 1, was more attuned to the madcap
pace that defined Saturday's proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely playing on a very good level already, and I
think he can still improve a lot of things,'' Muster said. ``If he
keeps improving the bad things he has in his game, he will be even
more dangerous than now.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day that put a premium on fast play, last year's runner-up,
sixth-seeded Greg Rusedski, did himself no favors by venturing into
an interminable five-setter for the third consecutive round.
Rusedski's confrontation with another big-serving lefty,
21st-ranked Jan Siemerink of the Netherlands, began before sunset
but ended 3 hours 22 minutes later under the spotlights with a 4-6,
6-4, 5-7, 6-2, 6-4 decision in Siemerink's favor. Rusedski, who had
saved three match points in the two previous rounds and saved three
more last night, hit just 10 aces, the same as his challenger, and
converted only 3 of 15 break chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, looking at his body language, that he was getting a
little tired,'' said Siemerink, who won with an ace on his fourth
match point. ``Once the sun was going down and the lights were on,
it was more in my favor than his.''.
</P>
<P>
   If Agassi was cranky before his match, he snapped out of it
after zipping toward a fourth-round encounter with ninth-seeded
Karol Kucera of Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   If Agassi defeats Kucera, it could set up a quarterfinal with
Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to get down to what for him has often been the risky
business of surviving the Open's first week, Goran Ivanisevic
clocked in early for the main stadium's first match.
</P>
<P>
   He was there long enough before his 7-6 (7-5), 6-3, 6-4
dismissal of Paul Haarhuis to check his mailbox, and there he found
some unusual hardware _ a shiny, suggestive early birthday present
from a female fan that drew a locker room crowd. Among the
onlookers was Ivanisevic's opponent for the Round of 16, the Open's
defending champion, Patrick Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic turns 27 next Sunday, the date the Open will crown a
men's champion. Given a choice of birthday gifts, Ivanisevic, who
is not quite resigned to being the best player never to win a Grand
Slam event, would choose the men's title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of the question I've been hearing for the last six
or seven years, always the same question, and always the same
stupid answer,'' the 14th-seeded Ivanisevic said after firing 21
aces against Haarhuis. ``I know I'm maybe the best player never to
win a Grand Slam, but I'm trying. There's a chance I can win this
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic's first task is to stop fighting the man in the
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when I have to play against both me and the other
guy,'' said Ivanisevic of his history of self-destructive behavior
at the Grand Slams, particularly here at the Open, where he lost in
the first round in three of his last four appearances. ``But,
lately, I'm playing most of the time against the other guy, not
against myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After putting an end to a five-match losing streak against the
32-year-old Haarhuis, Ivanisevic claimed to be playing so well at
the Open that he intends to use serves, volleys and passing shots
to handcuff his pal Rafter. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's maybe the best I've ever played at the U.S. Open,''
Ivanisevic said of his form through three rounds, ``but it doesn't
mean anything. He's confident, I'm confident, but somebody has to
win, so it's going to be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic defeated Rafter at Wimbledon in their only prior
meeting. ``I'm pretty confident in my head, but sometimes I get a
little bit messed up there, I have to bang it, then everything
comes together,'' Ivanisevic said.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter prides himself on being a clear-headed competitor. Since
receiving a scare when he opened his title defense by scrambling
out of a five-set trap laid for him by Hicham Arazi, the Rafter has
cruised through the subsequent rounds in straight sets. His
66-minute demolition of the South African David Nainkin Saturday
was representative of Rafter's Open game plan. ``You want to get on
and get off the court as quick as you possibly can, conserve your
energy,'' Rafter said after doing just that in a 6-1, 6-1, 6-1
victory, his quickest ever at a Grand Slam.
</P>
</TEXT>
