<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BLUEJAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX AREN'T SPARED BY CLEMENS'S STRIKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ You tell yourself it's just a three-game losing
streak, something the Red Sox haven't had since they dropped four
straight to the Orioles coming out of the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   But you look at the schedule _ winless Pete Schourek Sunday,
followed by three games with the Yankees in the Fens _ and you feel
all the signs coming on.
</P>
<P>
   The dry throat. The night sweats. The nervous cough. And you
notice all your neighbors have the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Even your doctor knows better than to call it the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Not in September. Not when the Red Sox are kicking away their
comfort zone in a playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   Not when Rocket Roger Clemens allowed three hits and struck out
11 as the surging Blue Jays won their ninth in a row Saturday, 4-3,
to climb within six games of the Red Sox in the wild-card race, and
the best the Sox can offer as a comeback Sunday is a Kramer
lookalike who has been in five games since he joined the team, all
losses.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has now won 13 decisions in a row and is 18-6 after
overtaking Pedro Martinez for the league lead in strikeouts and
lowering his league-best ERA to 2.62. Given his firsthand knowledge
as a former citizen of Red Sox Nation, he was asked if the Blue
Jays have stirred some anxiety in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask each player that,'' he said. ``Depends how
thick their skin is.''
</P>
<P>
   How about his skittish old fans? ``I don't worry about them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The official line in the Red Sox clubhouse, not surprisingly, is
not to worry. They have 22 games left, and while they have lost
seven of their last 10, Texas lost to Minnesota Saturday night and
remains 6 1/2 games behind Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, so we gave them a little hope,'' said losing
pitcher Bret Saberhagen, who gave up three tape-measure home runs
in the first three innings, each one achieving a higher altitude
than its predecessor until Jose Canseco pushed the top button on
the elevator and got off on the fifth deck of the SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not concerned with (the Blue Jays),'' said
Saberhagen, who gave up hits in all six innings he pitched but no
more runs. ``I'm concerned with Texas. They have an easier
schedule. The Blue Jays have won nine in a row, or whatever it is.
They still need a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to play New York, Cleveland, Baltimore. They've
got their work cut out.''
</P>
<P>
   By any measure _ throwing a fastball into Nomar Garciaparra's
ribs, buzzing another past Mike Stanley's head, striking out John
Valentin three times _ Clemens showed the Red Sox no quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was the last batter Clemens faced before coming out
after eight innings. On that last at-bat, his first three pitches
to the Sox shortstop were measured at 99, 98, and 97 miles per hour
on the radar gun. Garciaparra tapped out to third to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the gun had,'' said Blue Jays catcher Darrin
Fletcher, ``but I think he pumped in a few at 100, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox did end the Rocket's scoreless streak at 33 innings
when they scored twice in the fifth inning on two walks, Darren
Lewis's soft single, and a wild pitch. But no other Sox player
advanced as far as third against Clemens, who allowed only Mike
Benjamin's opposite-field double in the third and Mo Vaughn's
leadoff single in the sixth in addition to Lewis's hit.
</P>
<P>
   Both Saberhagen and Clemens were gone when the Blue Jays scored
the deciding run in the eighth, Tony Fernandez (4 for 4) hitting a
two-out double off lefthanded reliever Greg Swindell and scoring on
Fletcher's bloop single. That run loomed larger when Troy O'Leary
led off the ninth against Blue Jays reliever Dan Plesac with his
23d home run.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's home runs were dwarfed by the three the Jays hit off
Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Green hit an 0-and-2 fastball that Saberhagen misdirected
over the heart of the plate 405 feet over the center-field fence.
Blue Jays, 1-0, two Toronto batters into the game. Four batters in,
it was 2-0, Jays, as Carlos Delgado golfed one 413 feet into the
second deck in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve batters in, Canseco turned on a fastball down and in and
hit it 451 feet into the fifth deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dug the team a hole early, and with Roger in such a groove
lately, I made it tough on the team,'' Saberhagen said. ``But we
played well all day. We battled back.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days earlier, Canseco was interviewed by a crew from
the Discovery Channel, seeking some insights about McGwire, his
former teammate. What scientific explanation would he have offered
for his home run Saturday? ``I hit the ball real good,'' he said
with a smile, then elaborated. ``It ran in on me, but I told myself
just be quick with my hands. My first motion was with the bat down
toward the ball instead of my body drifting forward.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, it's the Red Sox who are drifting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We competed good, that's all you can ask,'' said
steady-as-she-goes Jimy Williams. ``We're fine, we really are.''
</P>
<P>
   The next episode is up to Kramer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
