A1388 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-CLEMENS-BO     09-06 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-CLEMENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS'S CY MISSION TAKING FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ It didn't match what he did in Boston last July.
There's no way it could.
</P>
<P>
   There can only be one first time for Roger Clemens pitching
against his former team in the ballpark he once ruled, striking out
16, transforming boos to cheers, and pointing at John Harrington in
the owner's box as he came off the mound, defiant and triumphant.
</P>
<P>
   But that should not diminish what Clemens accomplished here
Saturday in the SkyDome, where the Cy Young Award took an
unmistakable tilt to the north.
</P>
<P>
   By winning his 13th straight decision Saturday in a 4-3 win over
the Red Sox, Clemens now has as many wins as Pedro Martinez, 18.
His earned run average is lower (2.62 to 2.71), his strikeout total
is higher (227 to 219), and though he has more losses than Martinez
(6 to 4), he hasn't lost since May 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox ended Clemens's streak of consecutive scoreless
innings at a club-record 33, but he dismissed that with a shrug. In
the big picture, that won't keep him from adding an unprecedented
fifth Cy Young Award to his mantle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried about the shutout situation,'' said Clemens,
who had spun three shutouts in a row until the Red Sox broke
through with two runs in the fifth on two walks, Darren Lewis's
single, and a wild pitch. ``You expect those things to come to an
end when you throw the ball over the plate to good hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Clemens struck out the first two batters he faced,
Lewis and John Valentin. He struck out Mo Vaughn and Nomar
Garciaparra back-to-back in the fourth, struck out Scott Hatteberg
and Valentin again in the fifth, struck out the side in the seventh
(Hatteberg, Mike Benjamin and Lewis), and made old friend Vaughn
the last of his 11 strikeout victims.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin, who also whiffed in the third, struck out three times
against Clemens before flying out in his final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you something,'' he said. ``It's really exciting to
be able to face him. We're friends, he played with us so long, but
all that goes away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest with you. I came out and felt really good. I
was really determined to do well against him, but he's just too
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin said he decided to be aggressive against Clemens, even
with two strikes. ``I went after him,'' he said. ``I didn't care
how many strikes I got. But he saw that, and he threw me some
(split-fingered) fastballs. He got me all three times on splits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy's throwing 95 miles an hour, then he throws you
some 90-mile-an-hour splits that are falling off the table, that's
hard to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens hit Nomar Garciaparra with an 0-and-2 fastball in the
ribs in the second inning. Two batters later, he buzzed Mike
Stanley's head with a fastball. Purpose pitches?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he said. ``I was strong early, and I overthrew a
couple of pitches. The one to Stan-o, I'm glad it missed him.
Nomar, I was trying to get a fastball in. You don't want to miss
inside with Nomar.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra said he doubted there was malice aforethought. ``He
had me 0-and-2,'' he said. ``I don't think he's looking to hit me
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a smart pitcher who understands when you try to move
your feet (in the batters' box),'' Valentin said. ``He's not
wanting to hit Nomar or Stanley. But he is telling us, I think I
can come inside, and I have the right to come inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a bully. He doesn't go out to bully people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
