A1389 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-PIRATES-BOS &LR;      09-06 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-PIRATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA SLAMS 58TH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ His name is Sean Lawrence and he pitches for the
Pirates. Make sure you spell the name correctly. Very soon, it will
be scrawled into a record book. But Lawrence can take solace in
this: His name will not be there in isolation; there have been
dozens of pitchers who have done what he did Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, already behind in the count, 3 and 1,
Lawrence decided to challenge Cubs right fielder Sammy Sosa with
what most people would call a pitch. It wasn't. It was more like a
juicy cantaloupe traveling toward home plate. A few seconds later,
Sosa was strolling around the bases after watching the attempted
fastball travel 417 feet over the right-field fence. It wasn't long
before Lawrence was in the clubhouse, the losing pitcher in an 8-4
Cubs win at Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shame in this. The home run was Sosa's 58th of the
season. At least Lawrence tried to pitch to the slugger. Sosa said
he and Mark McGwire appreciate the challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, what difference does it make?'' he said of the
pitch-around philosophy. ``We're almost there. There's been no more
pitching around.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's homer once again satisfied a crowd that was interested in
seeing two things: the Pirates' Fireworks Night promotion and a
Sosa home run. The 37,711 people here got both, watching the home
team lose its eighth game in a row. (One Pirate fan had the right
idea, waving a white towel in the seventh inning when Abraham Nunez
made two errors on one play and three in the inning.)
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is two home runs behind leader McGwire and three away from
touching Roger Maris's magical 61. But you get the feeling that the
new untouchable number will be somewhere in the 70s by the time
Sosa and McGwire finish assaulting National League skies with home
runs. They meet  &UR; tomorrow &LR;  in St. Louis. When that series is
finished, we may be long beyond discussion of No. 62 and on to
``How High Can They Go?'' Saturday night, Sosa excited the crowd in
the ninth inning by blasting a shot into the upper deck in left
field. It was foul.
</P>
<P>
   After the cheering, homering and weddings were over _ a couple
exchanged vows at the stadium _ Sosa had a prediction. He said
McGwire will break Maris's record &UR;  &LR; Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' he said. ``I hit one (Saturday night), so ...''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was a reference to the point-counterpoint homer
game the two seem to be playing. Sosa hits one. McGwire hits one.
Or two. And the questions keep coming, in a couple languages.
Saturday night there were interview requests in Spanish as well as
English.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has no problem with any of this. A few hours before
receiving his nightly standing ovation, he told everyone how he has
maintained his sanity during what has become an obsessive home run
watch. His secret? He's smooth. That's what he says. Someone asked
him how he is able to sit down before the game and giggle for 15 or
20 minutes. How is he able to do that when McGwire seems to brood
at times?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little bit more easy guy,'' Sosa said. ``I'm a little
bit more Rico Suave.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused for a second and then broke into laughter after that
one. Many will remember Suave as the quirky, one-hit wonder of
1980s pop music. He was also known for his exaggerated hipness. So
maybe Sosa doesn't want to be associated with him, since his cool
seems to come more naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is me,'' he said. ``When people are waiting to talk to
me, I try to go out there and take care of everybody. I cannot
stand in Mark McGwire's shoes. I have a lot of respect for the man.
Whatever he decides to do.''
</P>
<P>
   When the game ended, Sosa decided to talk about the Cubs'
playoff chances. He may trail McGwire by two homers, but his team
leads the Mets by one game in the wild-card race. He was asked if
this was his best Cubs team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said. ``I never played when Hack Wilson was here.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked all day and night, really. Earlier in the evening, he
went to the field and saw hundreds of fans lining a rail on the
visitors' side of the batting cage. Each of them had a different
technique, trying to persuade Sosa to sign a pennant, a hat, a
ball. Some spoke to him in Spanish. Some waved Dominican flags. One
man put his young son over his head and had him lean over the
shoulder of someone in the front row.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa approached the group and signed for a few minutes. He gave
the crowd what it wanted then and did it again in the sixth inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
