</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-GATECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC'S OPENING ACT GOES OVER WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the withering heat of Dixie, they soared to
wuthering heights.
</P>
<P>
   On a sultry, 94-degree afternoon, the Boston College Eagles
never once lost their cool and won a hotly contested 41-31 victory
over Georgia Tech in the season opener before 38,229 Saturday at
Bobby Dodd Stadium/-Grant Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles proved hotter than Georgia asphalt, withstanding the
heat the Yellow Jackets put on them with comebacks from BC leads of
17-7, 24-17, and 31-24. Thrice in the second half Georgia Tech
rallied to tie the game, but the Eagles responded with a cool and
calm offensive and defensive dissection of the Yellow Jackets. It
enabled BC to outscore its Atlantic Coast Conference hosts, 17-7,
in the decisive fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired,'' said BC coach Tom O'Brien, a weary smile creasing
his flushed face. ``It was hot out there. Was the press box
air-conditioned?''
</P>
<P>
   Told that Georgia Tech's open-air facility offered no such
amenity, O'Brien perked up. ``Oh, good,'' he said, laughing. ``I
feel better then. I feel much better.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's chipper mood was a vast improvement over a year ago,
when BC suffered a season-opening pratfall in a 28-21 loss at
Temple that was riddled with missed assignments, missed tackles,
and an overall offensive malaise. But the Eagles suffered from none
of the above Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   BC's offense rolled up 25 first downs and 491 yards of total
offense and had nary a turnover. After surrendering a season-high
303 yards rushing to Georgia Tech a year ago, BC's defense
submitted a sterling effort, holding the Yellow Jackets to 392
yards of offense, 165 rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-year senior quarterback Scott Mutryn was near-perfect,
completing 16 of 26 passes for a career-high 220 yards with no
interceptions. He threw a 15-yard touchdown pass to tight end Rob
Tardio (six catches, 52 yards) that gave BC a 17-7 lead with 21
seconds to go before halftime and scored a pair of TDs on runs of 2
and 5 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how, as the game progresses, you see things a lot
clearer,'' said Mutryn, who was spelled for one series in the
second quarter by sophomore Tim Hasselbeck. ``But, like I said
before, this is the most comfortable I've felt going into a season.
I just felt great.''
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Brien, ``I think he did a great job. Obviously, I'm going
to argue with him on a couple of decisions here and there, but he
made no bad decisions. We had some guys open that he missed, but
for the most part he was 16 for 26 for 220 yards and that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutryn's efficient passing was complemented by the impressive
rushing effort of senior Mike Cloud, who carried 34 times for 200
yards, the second-most of his career after a 211-yard effort in a
31-24 victory over West Virginia last year. Cloud scored on a
1-yard plunge that gave BC a 10-0 lead in the second quarter, and
capped a 14-play, 80-yard drive _ BC's longest _ with a 7-yard TD
burst that gave the Eagles a 24-17 lead with 5:20 left in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the most sound game of my career so far,''
said Cloud, who rushed for 154 of his 200 in the second half. ``I
started off the first half with some jitters and I wasn't running
like I usually run, but with the 34 carries I had I think the
coaches are going to have a lot of confidence in me the rest of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   After failing to execute a power squib kickoff with 21 seconds
left before halftime _ which put Georgia Tech in position to
strike, Joe Hamilton hitting David Powell with a 23-yard TD pass
with 8 seconds left that cut BC's lead to 17-14 _ junior kicker
John Matich atoned by tacking on field goals of 27 yards and 25
yards, the last of which broke a 31-31 tie and put the Eagles ahead
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, O'Brien had intoned that his team was going
to need more than 14 points to beat Georgia Tech after getting
thrashed, 42-14, by the Yellow Jackets last year at Chestnut Hill.
But did he ever imagine his offense was capable of putting up 41?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I always think I can score points,'' said O'Brien. ``I
didn't have 41 as a number in mind that I needed, but I'll take 41.
Whatever we needed, we needed 1 more. I think we have the weapons
to score this year, and we're going to put as much pressure on the
defense as we can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
