<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOVE HUNT BRIGHTENS NEAR TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The opening of dove season is sort of like comparing Mexican
restaurants. Some are more adventurous than others.
</P>
<P>
   The dove season opened Tuesday. My singing-chicken alarm clock
woke me at 2 a.m. At first, I thought I'd shoot it before I started
on doves. But, no, the chicken asks me to get up and dance.
Anything that asks me to dance can't be all bad.
</P>
<P>
   That was just the beginning of the adventure. About 2:45 a.m. I
stopped at a filling station, dressed in camouflage clothing. The
attendant gave me the rooster look, so to speak, wondering if I was
some kind of nut. I obliged by acting like one.
</P>
<P>
   By 3 a.m., I was on Loop 101 heading for Interstate 10. That's
when the two cars, one chasing the other, headed toward me, pulled
onto the shoulder and pulled in front of me. That's also when I saw
the flashes. The people in the cars were shooting at each another.
</P>
<P>
   Then they turned around and came back toward me. I had a shotgun
in my truck but never thought about it. All I could think about was
ramming the gas pedal and getting out of there, which I did.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was on toward the Harquahala Valley, an agricultural
area west of Phoenix where doves have flourished this year.
</P>
<P>
   The host was philanthropist rancher Bill O'Brien, who was having
a charity shoot for his favorite organization _ the Wendy Paine
O'Brien Foundation, a haven for troubled youths. It's named after
his late daughter.
</P>
<P>
   We met at Tonopah Joe's Truck Stop for breakfast, then we headed
for the fields.
</P>
<P>
   The area had been scouted for doves. But this morning, the rain
was falling. The flight would be late. O'Brien had three fields in
mind. The one he picked had desert terrain on one side of the road
and a fallow crop field on the other.
</P>
<P>
   By about 5:30 a.m. we were standing in the fields. I can't
remember seeing more doves. I had my limit of 10 before 7 a.m.
Others shot their due number of shells but didn't do the same. But
by 9 a.m. we had enough for a sumptuous meal.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Michael De Maria and his staff had agreed to cook a dove
feast. He is the chief chef for Michael's Restaurant at Pinnacle
Peak Road and Pima Road. He slept in while others hunted but was
well prepared by 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   All the doves we shot were small. Bruce Taubert, a deputy
director of the Arizona Game and Fish Department, said that was a
good sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means we've had good dove reproduction,'' he said. ``These
are birds that have been bred here. It bodes well for another good
dove population next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at O'Brien's Eagle Tail Ranch _ more than 500,000 acres of
it _ chef De Maria was getting ready.
</P>
<P>
   The adobe ranch house with a Persian cooling system (a tower
that naturally evaporates water into cool air) was awaiting.
</P>
<P>
   De Maria served a fabulous salad, barley, asparagus, glazed
carrots and dove breasts cooked in juniper. It was unbelievable.
The crusty bread served with the meal was the best I've ever eaten.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said he raised at least $450 for the Wendy Paine O'Brien
Foundation and perhaps a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   Gunfight aside, it was among the best experiences I've ever
had. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
