<HEADER>
A1397 &Cx1f; tic-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      09-06 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Sept. 6. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
ASTRONAUTS (Undated) _ John, Scott, Wally, Gordo.Just four of them
now. Alan died of leukemia in July. Gus died in the fire aboard
Apollo I, back in the glory days. Deke died of cancer in 1993. They
used to be seven _ America's original astronauts, men who strapped
themselves into test planes over California's deserts and then into
Corvettes and rocket ships in Florida, always competing to be the
fastest, go the highest, be the best. They're in their 70s now and
they haven't lost their famous drive to compete. ``I'm afraid John
has made us all famous again,'' said Scott Carpenter, talking about
himself and the other survivors, Gordon ``Gordo'' Cooper and Walter
``Wally'' Schirra. The Arizona Republic recently talked to all of
them about Sen. John Glenn's upcoming return to space as well as
their lives. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
OVERTIME (Undated) _ By the time his 15-year career with
Albertson's stores ended, Richard Sorrells knew the extra hours at
work were taking their toll. ``I'd come home grumping and griping _
I was stressed'' after routinely putting in at least 10 hours of
extra work a week, said Sorrells, now a Glendale business owner.
``I've got a 4-year-old daughter. She doesn't need to hear that.''
Like Sorrells, Americans are feeling as overworked as ever this
Labor Day. Frustrated by working too many hours _ both paid and
unpaid _ they are sometimes grabbing headlines by battling the
corporations whose profits depend on their extra work. From a
national lawsuit filed against Albertson's grocery stores to the
recently concluded US West strike, the number of hours spent on the
job is a flashpoint for employee discontent. By PAT FLANNERY. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOPHONES (Phoenix) _ When 64-year-old Sheila Brown moved from one
apartment to another within her complex last month, she expected to
be without a telephone for about a day. But the US West strike has
left the Phoenix woman, who lives alone and suffers from chronic
asthma attacks and other health problems, fighting to get her new
installation done on an emergency basis. She's been without phone
service for 16 days. And she's not alone. By BECKY RAMSDELL. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AZDEMS (Phoenix) _ When Arizona Democrats go to the polls Tuesday,
they're in for a severe case of ballot shock. ``There are no
Democratic candidates for a number of statewide offices, nobody for
legislative races. There's nothing,'' said Phoenix attorney Tim
Hogan, who was stunned recently when he opened his sample
Democratic primary ballot and found no reason to participate. There
really isn't anything to vote for in my district, so I guess I've
got to wonder what the point is,'' Hogan said. His dismay reflects
a growing concern over the fate of Arizona's second-largest
political party. The harsh reality is that the Democratic Party is
in its weakest position in years, and if it suffers
across-the-board losses in statewide races in November, it could
emerge powerless for a generation. By MICHAEL MURPHY. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COL (Undated) _ After four years on the Queens College
baseball team, Albert Kapikian had to face the fact that he'd never
make it to the big leagues. Never stand in the batter's box at
Yankee Stadium in his hometown, the Bronx. Never break the records
of Ruth or Maris or anybody else. It happens to a lot of guys. You
come to terms with your abilities _ or lack of them _ and move on.
Kapikian wasn't going to hit more than 60 home runs in a year, so
he had to settle for saving 600,000 lives. A year. By E.J. MONTINI.
Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
