<HEADER>
A1408 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFE     09-06 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF DAD HARD TO IGNORE 
 SEASON WILL BE LONG FOR COWBOYS LINEMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dallas Cowboys center  &UR; Dale Hellestrae says his late father's
favorite song was the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the last thing he heard,'' Hellestrae said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after hearing it played before the Cardinals' preseason
game against the Chicago Bears on Aug. 14 at Sun Devil Stadium,
Hellestrae's father,  &UR; Lawrence, suffered a fatal heart attack in
Section 210.
</P>
<P>
   Hellestrae, a Scottsdale native, has been thinking about his dad
this week as the Cowboys prepare for today's season opener against
the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a big Cardinals fan,'' Hellestrae said. ``He was an
original season ticket holder. He wished the Cardinals would go
14-2 every year. He rooted for them in every game except when they
played us. He loved those games. He loved his seats.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, 66, also loved any team for which Hellestrae played.
He was at Sun Devil Stadium in 1980 when Hellestrae helped
Scottsdale Saguaro High School win the Class 3A state title. He was
there again in January 1996, when the Cowboys beat the Pittsburgh
Steelers in Super Bowl XXX.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always liked to kid him,'' Hellestrae said. ``He would get
more worked up for games than I did. He would come to Dallas for
two games a year. My wife would have to drop him off three and a
half, four hours before the game, because he was so excited. He
would walk around the stadium and meet people. He loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, a longtime Valley mailman, was in good health. He
had cut the lawn that day and regularly rode a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   He would have been glued to the TV on Sunday for the big game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever season it was, that was his favorite sport,''
Hellestrae said. ``Whatever team I played on was his favorite
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hellestrae knows it will be difficult to return to Sun Devil
Stadium when the Cowboys play there Nov. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be tougher for them (his family members) to go
watch their first game back,'' he said of the Cardinals' home
opener against Philadelphia on Sept. 20. ``But if they can do it, I
can do it. Still, it will be hard.'' &QL; 
No Fun League
</P>
<P>
   Former Cardinals defensive end  &UR; Mike Jones discovered he had a
problem when the St. Louis Rams acquired him from the New England
Patriots last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams already had a player named Mike Jones, an outside
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   The public-address announcer at the TWA Dome in St. Louis came
up with a solution. He refers to the defensive end as  &UR; Mike D.
Jones and the linebacker as  &UR; Mike A. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rams originally were told that players can't place their
middle initials on the back of their uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the league said,'' club equipment manager  &UR; Todd
Hewitt said. ``They looked it up in the bylaws.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, league officials came to their senses.  &QL; 
Bad News Bears
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer and former Chicago running back  &UR; Gale Sayers
maintains his former team is three players away from being three
players away.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mark Hatley, club personnel vice president, thinks the Bears
are worse that that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had eight more good players, we'd be a pretty decent
football team,'' Hatley said. ``We'd have a chance to break even or
maybe a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help the Bears any that they are playing $6.4 million
short of the salary cap because of hits they've taken on five
players they've let go _ linebacker  &UR; Bryan Cox, quarterback  &UR; Rick
Mirer, defensive end  &UR; Alonzo Spellman, returner  &UR; Tyrone Hughes and
running back
 &UR; Rashaan Salaam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It put us two years behind,'' Hatley said.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of their top three draft choices from a year ago,
second-round pick  &UR; John Allred, is still on the roster, and he has
been beaten out by rookie  &UR; Alonzo Mayes at tight end. &QL; 
Lopsided affair
</P>
<P>
   Here's how dominant the Denver Broncos have been over New
England in their past 10 meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have outscored the Patriots, 105-24.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have gained 1,205 yards to the Patriots' 809.
</P>
<P>
   They have run for 511 yards to the Patriots' 149.
</P>
<P>
   It got so bad in 1996, Broncos tight end  &UR; Shannon Sharpe picked
up a phone on the sideline and said, ``President, we need the
National Guard. We need as many men as you can spare because we are
killing the Patriots. So call the dogs off. Send the National
Guard, please. They need emergency help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos, who host the Patriots on Monday night, won the '96
game, 34-8. &QL; 
Feeling out of place
</P>
<P>
   How strange it was for former Cardinals linebacker  &UR; Seth Joyner,
a member of Green Bay's Super Bowl runner-ups last season, to be
traded to the league champion Broncos last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like I am year behind my quest,'' Joyner said.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner doesn't think the Packers took the AFC winners seriously
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in a large part we underestimated this football team
(the Broncos) more because we dominated so much in the NFC through
the last part of the season,'' he said. ``I guess I feel we went
into the game with the feeling it was almost a done deal. Nobody
likes to say that, but when you look at how the game turned out and
things of that nature, I think in some ways we might have taken
them a little lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes to show that you need to respect your opponent,
no matter who they are, no matter what the circumstances are.
They're a great team to even make it to the Super Bowl.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
