<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-WASHINGTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON PULLS OUT WIN ON LATE PASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Brock Huard couldn't pull his hands away from his
face.
</P>
<P>
   He had thought it was over. Everybody did. But moments before,
with just 28 seconds remaining, he found Washington tight end
Reggie Davis, who wiped out Arizona State's national championship
hopes with a 63-yard touchdown reception.
</P>
<P>
   Someone hit the mute button on the 72,118 fans at Sun Devil
Stadium. One of No. 8 ASU's most important season openers in years
ended Saturday night with a 42-38 victory by the No. 18 Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm emotionally drained, exhausted,'' ASU Coach Bruce Snyder
said. ``We all participated, all had a hand in the outcome, we must
share in it. . . . It's a terrible loss, but we're going to rebound
from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only minutes earlier, it looked as if the Sun Devils would
survive. J.R. Redmond's 61-yard punt return set up an amazing
8-yard touchdown pass from Ryan Kealy to Tariq McDonald that put
ASU up, 38-35.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy, who appears to have recovered just fine from last
season's knee surgery, completed 20 of 35 passes for 302 yards and
three touchdowns. Redmond carried 22 times for 108 yards and caught
four passes for 68 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Huard completed 27 of 47 passes for 318 yards and four
touchdowns, two to little-known Dane Looker.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said before the contest that this game will not make or
break ASU's season. But it might shift its goals a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's offense lived up to its billing, but its defense
struggled. The unit rarely put pressure on Huard, and the
secondary's lack of depth revealed itself.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sun Devils need some good news, they got an early look at
their future, and the results were promising. Among the highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Todd Heap lived up to his preseason billing. The true
freshman from Mesa Mountain View High School made a stunning
one-handed catch in the end zone to give ASU a seven-point lead in
the first quarter. It was the first catch of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Redshirt freshman Kyion Graves pounced on a pooch kick that the
Huskies failed to pursue and set up ASU's fourth touchdown of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Redshirt freshman tailback Daveron Hightower, who rehabilitated
a serious leg injury last season, saw limited action, but when he
played, he made an impact. He scored on a 2-yard run in the second
quarter, and his pitch to Redmond on the Sun Devils' next drive
resulted in a 22-yard scoring run.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Coach Jim Lambright predicted a shootout, and that's
what he got.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils took the opening drive and marched 61 yards,
capping it with a 13-yard pass from Kealy to tight end Kendrick
Bates. Kealy made the most of his versatile offense, turning to
five different teammates during the seven-play series.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies rarely pressured Kealy until late in the game, which
was as much a statement about Washington's pass rush as it was
about ASU's skilled offensive line. If the quarterback wanted a
test for the knee he injured last season, this wasn't the game to
get it.
</P>
<P>
   Washington came right back and took advantage of a J'Juan Cherry
pass interference on third down. The highlight of the drive was a
13-yard keeper by backup quarterback Marques Tuiasosopo that caught
the Sun Devils off guard and put the Huskies at ASU's 5-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Washington closed the deal with a 3-yard pass from Huard to
tight end Reggie Davis that tied the game, 7-7, with 8:29
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils scored again on their next possession, and it was
during this drive that Kealy had his first incompletion. One of his
connections was Heap's amazing catch, which the freshman tipped
with his right arm and then pulled down, all with Washington's
Toure Butler and Marques Hairston hanging on him.
</P>
<P>
   If Heaps embarks on a mission next season, as scheduled, the Sun
Devils will miss him.
</P>
<P>
   ASU linebacker Stephen Trejo made sure the Huskies didn't score
on their next possession by sacking Huard at the Sun Devils'
27-yard line on a third-and-1 play.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies tied the game at 14 with a 16-yard run by fullback
Pat Conniff with 9:05 remaining in the second quarter. It was the
sophomore's longest run and his first career touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils' next drive was highlighted by Kealy's swing pass
to Redmond that he converted into a 47-yard play. Hightower capped
the drive with his 2-yard scoring run.
</P>
<P>
   ASU got tricky on the next series. Stephen Baker's pooch kick
caught the Huskies off guard, and they let it bounce without
reacting. Grayes pounced on it, and the Sun Devils took over at
Washington's 31.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Kealy handed off to Hightower, who pitched it
to Redmond and watched as he ran 22 yards for the score. ASU led,
28-14. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
