<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALREADY PLAYING CATCH-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Pfffffft.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of a championship bubble bursting.
</P>
<P>
   Thud.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of a football team crashing back to reality.
</P>
<P>
   A football team that stubbed its collective toe on Saturday,
tripping over its lofty expectations. A football team that snatched
defeat from the jaws of victory, watching a pivotal game slip
through its fingers.
</P>
<P>
   A football team that watched a conference rival celebrate on its
turf.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils wake up in the cellar this morning, and the
reflection in the mirror will be painful. They squandered a
14-point lead. They broke down in the second half. They engaged in
a track meet and lost. They fought back on the heroics of J.R.
Redmond and Ryan Kealy, only to give it all back in one improbable
moment.
</P>
<P>
   And now, with the season only a few days old, they're already
playing catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the field, the new motto _ Playing With Fire _ is
posted on a fence. It is meant to describe the passion demanded by
Coach Bruce Snyder. On Saturday, it was symbolic of a 42-38 loss to
the Washington Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts fumbled. They committed a few costly penalties. They
did everything they could to help the visitors prevail, including
the worst of all digressions: allowing 63-yard touchdown pass from
Brock Huard on 4th-and-17 with only 28 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terribly disappointing to all of us,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   Much was expected of ASU this season. The players talked of a
national title. Of playing at home, in the Fiesta Bowl, for the big
prize. Those expectations should be tempered just a bit, because
until they shore up a porous, peanut brittle defense, they are
nowhere near contention.
</P>
<P>
   In the fog of defeat, there are glimmers of hope. Despite a
costly fumble, Redmond willed his way into a 61-yard punt return
that set up ASU's final touchdown. And despite a barrage of blitzes
in the second half, Kealy displayed the poise of a championship
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the three touchdown passes. It wasn't the 302 yards
passing, a new career high. It was simply the execution under
duress.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 35-31, the Sun Devils marched to the Washington 8. On
second down, Kealy rifled a pass that went through the arms of Matt
Cercone in the end zone. On fourth down, he fired a perfect strike
to Tariq McDonald, a boyhood pal, appearing to save the night.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a quarterback with one of the strangest nicknames
you'll ever hear.
</P>
<P>
   Stinky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't clean his locker,'' Snyder said. ``And he still
doesn't comb his hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, not much has changed since Kealy's performance over
the final six games of 1997, where he threw 11 touchdowns and only
three interceptions, when he capped the finest season ever posted
by a freshman quarterback at ASU.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is more confident and he knows our system better, but
there's an edge to that,'' Snyder said. ``There's an edge when
you're expected to be good. Can you live up to that? There was a
point in camp when he was pressing like hell, and it was because of
that. Because of the expectations. He worked through it, and now
he's overcome that.''
</P>
<P>
   The real concern with Kealy is his legs, and whether he'll be
the Danny Manning of college football. He tore a ligament in his
right knee in the final game of last season, matching an injury he
suffered to his left knee the previous year. In his first real
test, he survived quite nicely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through a lot in the last two years,'' Kealy said.
``But I have all the confidence in the world bouncing back from
this injury. I think there will be more pressure on me to make
plays this year. But everyone has more experience. Last year, I
didn't have much confidence because I hadn't succeeded at this
level. Now, I know what I can do, what I can't do, what I'm
supposed to do. I have a better idea of what my role is on this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is good.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if he can do something about the nickname. And a defense
worthy of his moniker. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
