<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 03:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1415 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OVERTIME-AZR &LR;      09-06 1833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVERTIME-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORCED OVERTIME PUSHING THEM TO THE LIMIT, WORKERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time his 15-year career with Albertson's stores ended,
Richard Sorrells knew the extra hours at work were taking their
toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd come home grumping and griping _ I was stressed'' after
routinely putting in at least 10 hours of extra work a week, said
Sorrells, now a Glendale business owner. ``I've got a 4-year-old
daughter. She doesn't need to hear that.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Sorrells, Americans are feeling as overworked as ever this
Labor Day. Frustrated by working too many hours _ both paid and
unpaid _ they are sometimes grabbing headlines by battling the
corporations whose profits depend on their extra work.
</P>
<P>
   From a national lawsuit filed against Albertson's grocery stores
to the recent US West strike, the number of hours spent on the job
is a flash point for employee discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the problem with America today _ all these companies do
is look at the bottom line,'' Sorrells said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, 34,000 US West employees in 13 states returned to
work after a 15-day strike protesting salaries, benefits and the
telephone giant's policy of forcing long hours of overtime work.
</P>
<P>
   A tentative agreement hammered out over the weekend would cap
the amount of weekly overtime that phone company employees are
required to work at 16 hours next year and 8 hours in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   While there are few national statistics documenting use of
overtime or legal challenges of employer overtime policies, one of
the few measures devised by the federal Bureau of Labor Statistics
suggests that we are, in fact, working more overtime than we used
to.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1988, U.S. factory employees worked an average of 3.9
hours of overtime a week. By July 1998, Bureau of Labor figures
show, it was 4.8 hours a week, an increase of more than 25 percent
and near the all-time high of 4.9 set five times in 1997 and once
this year.
</P>
<P>
   An Arizona survey of local communications and public utilities
industries found employees working an average of 42 hours a week in
1997. So far this year, it's 43.7 hours, while 10 years ago, it was
42.3 hours. &QL; 
OVERTIME LOSES APPEAL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Americans are feeling overworked, chances are it's because
they often are. But it isn't necessarily new. As early as 1992,
Harvard University economist Juliet Schor warned in her bestseller,
``The Overworked American,'' that heavier workloads were making
Americans surly and wishful for simpler lives.
</P>
<P>
   Where once overtime was viewed as a good way to earn extra
bucks, it is now often seen as a stressful drain on leisure or
family time. And it may not be as good a financial deal as it once
seemed: The Cato Institute, a national think-tank, concluded last
year that the average employee loses much of their gains from
overtime pay to taxes.
</P>
<P>
   And workers who build a lifestyle around overtime pay may have
trouble scaling back when overtime evaporates. Some companies ask
managers to warn employees about the dangers of basing their
standard of living on overtime pay. &QL; 
MARKET FORCES OVERTIME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the use of overtime by employers continues unabated, the
longer hours coming as a logical economic consequence of today's
labor market, said Peter Hom, professor of management at Arizona
State University and an expert on compensation administration.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment is low. The economy is strong. To keep up with
demand for their products, employers must either pay more to hire
and train new workers, or ask current workers to work longer.
</P>
<P>
   It's cheaper to pay employees overtime than it is to hire new
workers in a tight market, then provide benefits.
</P>
<P>
   International forces have spurred changes in the domestic labor
market as well. With offshore competition and what Hom calls
``variable pay practices'' becoming more common _ special benefits,
flexible shifts and such _ competition is stiff for new, reasonably
priced employees.
</P>
<P>
   If overtime seems painful to workers, Hom says, there is a
benefit: When the economy shrinks, companies are less likely to lay
off employees if they relied on overtime instead of hiring new
workers.
</P>
<P>
   But the flip side, he adds, is a decline in employee
satisfaction. A 500-employee survey Hom conducted for a national
retail chain found that heavy overtime led to employee discontent
and disloyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees are feeling greater work-family conflicts,'' Hom
said. And it isn't simply among women, who traditionally felt
sharper conflicts between work and family.
</P>
<P>
   Hom said men and women also complain about conflicts with other
off-time activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That conflict seems to be of great concern to employees _ the
infringement of personal time,'' Hom said. ``It's going to lead
employees to quit employment (and look) for other employers with a
more friendly environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The same conflict often exists for managers, most of whom are
not covered by the overtime regulations but have to work long hours
as well. Their stress often is compounded by having to continually
ask more of overworked subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have family lives, too,'' said Bill Ankrom, vice
president of the Western region for Methods West, a Phoenix
machine-tool company. If managers' morale slips, so too will that
of other workers.
</P>
<P>
   Ankrom said the manufacturing industry is rife these days with
examples of companies whose cadre of managers are unhappy, and the
unhappiness spreads to workers at large. Methods West has avoided
problems, he said, by offering bonuses to managers working long
hours without overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   The situation appears no different among government workers.
Angel Rodriguez, field representative for Council 97 of the
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, said
his union often hears complaints about overtime.
</P>
<P>
   At the Arizona Department of Motor Vehicles, for example,
Rodriguez said the department responded to complaints about long
customer lines and poor service by calling on employees to work
longer hours.
</P>
<P>
   The agency budget is limited, so overtime workers are offered
``flex time'' _ coming to work an hour or two later the day after
overtime is worked _ rather than overtime pay or compensatory time
off that is accrued and taken later.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said many state employees don't like flex time because
it does not allow them to schedule compensatory time off to mesh
with their personal schedules.
</P>
<P>
   It is especially vexing for employees with children. Overtime
work upsets child-care routines, and flex time is usually offered
at times when employees cannot make up for time lost with family
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees suffer, because they don't find family life
satisfying, they have to adjust their child care and it creates
some problems,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the practice is legal. Federal laws allow employers to use
flex time to ensure workers do not work more than 40 hours a week.
Unlike private-sector workers, government employees can be forced
to take time off in lieu of overtime pay. &QL; 
FEWER WORKER COMPLAINTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Albertson's case aside, it is unclear whether the longer
hours have led to in an upswing in legal challenges. Some experts
believe lawsuits are on the rise because workers no longer fear
reprisals _ they know they can find new jobs in the booming job
market.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the U.S. Department of Labor saw a steady decrease in
worker complaints filed during this decade. From 1989 to 1997, for
example, the number of wage-and-hour complaints filed with the
department declined about 45 percent to 34,649 from 63,965.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Nutini, a labor lawyer at the Phoenix law firm of Lewis &AMP;
Roca, suspects workers who feel they are being mistreated simply
walk away from their jobs, knowing they can be easily re-employed
in the current economy.
</P>
<P>
   But John Fraser, acting administrator of the Labor Department's
wage and hour division, thinks employees are worrying about job
security and as a result, are less likely to complain.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a good labor market, Fraser argued, workers increasingly
find themselves in ``contingent work relationships'' _ holding jobs
under contract or under limitations imposed by employers. Simply
put, they don't think challenging their employer is a safe option.
</P>
<P>
   Many cases now litigated by the Labor Department are identified
by the department itself by aiming enforcement at specific
industries. The department's hot list these days includes the
agriculture, garment and health care industries.
</P>
<P>
   With one month left in the federal fiscal year, the Arizona
district office has brought 699 overtime or minimum wage cases,
recovering $3.9 million in back wages for employees. The number of
cases is fewer than in past years, mirroring a national decline
blamed on long slide in the size of the Labor Department budget.
</P>
<P>
   Overtime violations typically result from employees being paid
regular wages for overtime, or being told to take time off in lieu
of legally required payment, said Cynthia Watson, the Labor
Department's Arizona District director.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law does not limit the overtime work employers may
demand, provided that non-salaried workers are paid at least 1{
times their normal wage for more 40 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Routine violations often make the job of labor organizers easier
because employees have common complaints against what they see as
an unfair employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the major issues in organizing workplaces,''
said Jim McLaughlin, Phoenix market-share coordinator for the
United Food and Commercial Workers Union. ``They're trying to
squeeze every dime out of labor.''
</P>
<P>
   The UFCW has helped current and former Albertson's employees _
both union and non-union _ sue the company, claiming they were
routinely expected to put in extra time on the job, but off the
clock. A federal judge has been asked to certify it as a national
class-action lawsuit, expanding it to include nearly 7,000 employee
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Read, Albertson's executive vice president for public
affairs, called the claims ``absolutely false'' and said company
policy ``is very clear and unequivocal. Off-the-clock work is
clearly not policy. It is not expected, and frankly, not
tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorrells _ one of the lawsuit's original plaintiffs and one of
five from Arizona _ was liquor department manager for a Glendale
Albertson's when he was fired last year. Albertson's accused him of
not performing certain duties, duties he says were impossible to
fulfill during regular working hours.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sorrells runs his own cleaning business and he calls his
firing a blessing. He sets his own hours. When he works longer, he
takes home more money. His income is slightly higher than before.
His family life is better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the fourth or fifth day (after being fired), my wife said,
`Man, you're so much nicer,' '' he said. &QL; 
 &UR; Pat Flannery can be reached at 444-8629 or at pat.flannery &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 0345EDT &QL; 
