<HEADLINE>
WAGNER CREDITED FOR WORK IN RETURN TO INJURY SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Try as he might,  &UR; Tony Batista couldn't pull the
rabbit out of the hat for the Diamondbacks this time.
</P>
<P>
   The infielder had come up with more than his share of heroics,
including a home run and triple in a 2-1, 11-inning victory over
the Pirates in Pittsburgh on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With Saturday's game in the 12th inning, Batista felt the heat
as the third and final strikeout victim of Houston left-hander
 &UR; Billy
 &UR; Wagner as the Astros recorded a 6-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it works for you, sometimes it doesn't,'' he said.
``We'll just have to try to do better the next time. He (Wagner)
was throwing very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a triumph within a triumph for Wagner, who during the
Astros' previous visit to Bank One Ballpark on July 15 was struck
in the left side of his head by a line drive off the bat of Arizona
catcher  &UR; Kelly Stinnett.
</P>
<P>
   A walk to Stinnett, who hit in the order just before Batista,
was the only blemish against Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I hate to say it because we lost, you have to be
happy for Billy Wagner that he was able to come back and pitch
again,'' Diamondbacks  &UR; Manager Buck Showalter said. &QL; 
3 million fans &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks drew 43,638 fans Saturday, bringing their
season total to 2,985,344, meaning they will reach the 3 million
mark in today's finale of the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The team is averaging 44,559 after 67 home dates, third in the
major leagues behind Colorado and Baltimore. &QL; 
Still closed &QL; 
Although the temperature has cooled a bit, team officials say the
retractable roof will remain closed for the rest of this homestand
(through Wednesday) and perhaps for the next homestand (Sept.
14-20). The team hopes to have the roof open for the final three
games of the season against the San Diego Padres on Sept. 25-27. &QL; 
Almost ready? &QL; 
Right-hander  &UR; Bobby Chouinard, on the disabled list since Aug. 22
because of tightness in his shoulder, is expected to pitch in a
rehabilitation assignment for Triple-A Tucson today and could
rejoin the big club later this week. &QL; 
Silent auction &QL; 
The wives of Diamondbacks players will hold a silent auction on
Monday between 9 a.m. and 3 p.m. at Bank One Ballpark's Cox
Communications Clubhouse to benefit the Muscular Dystrophy
Association. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
