</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME RUN CHASE BRINGS INCREASED SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While most of the free world follows every sneeze from &UR; Mark
 &UR; McGwire, some people that are paid to be very nervous follow the
slugger's every move.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball has assigned two security people to act as
McGwire's bodyguards as the assault on home run No. 62 continues.
They follow him home, go out with him and even escort him off the
team charter when it arrives in St. Louis, taking him down the
jetway instead of through the airport like the rest of his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball, fearing a worst-case scenario, even has
asked the FBI to place undercover agents at Busch Stadium this
weekend. It's all precautionary but also shows the society we live
in today.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to get into a situation where several fans say they
have one of McGwire's famous home run balls,  &UR; Kevin Hallinan, head
of major league security, has set up guards in the most likely
areas where the slugger's home runs might land.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hallinan will personally place an unknown mark on
the batch of balls to be used once McGwire has 61 home runs, which
will allow baseball officials to distinguish the authenticity of
what will become the most famous baseball in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just say this: We are confident we will be able to
identify that ball,'' Hallinan said. &QL; 
Is hell freezing? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly whispers at this point, but a silent minority is
wondering what has happened to  &UR; Greg Maddux in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a slam dunk for the National League Cy Young Award a
month ago, Maddux has become very mortal. The four-time Cy Young
winner is 5-5 since the All-Star break. In his last start, a highly
anticipated match-up against Houston's  &UR; Randy Johnson, Maddux
allowed 10 hits, three home runs, as he and the Braves lost to the
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux has allowed 31 hits in his past 26 innings. His ERA over
his past five games is 6.33. Possibly the most amazing statistic of
the past month is that Maddux has allowed three home runs in a game
twice in his past three starts. Maddux hadn't done that in his
first 392 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about it,'' Maddux said. ``I haven't been
pitching good. I've been up. I've been over the plate. I've been
behind. I gave up some runs (against Houston last week). I could
have given up some more runs very easily.'' &QL; 
Now it can be told &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's  &UR; Vladimir Guerrero, possibly the best young player in
the game today, was signed after an Expos scout saw one at-bat of
the then-16-year-old at a tryout camp in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fred Ferreira, Montreal's director of international operations,
is the scout who saw Guerrero arrive on the back of a motorcycle
and practically plead to join the tryout. Ferreira happily agreed.
</P>
<P>
   While the rest is history, Guerrero was despondent that day
after he pulled a groin muscle while running to first base after
hitting the first pitch he saw that afternoon under the intense
Dominican Republic sun.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that day, Guerrero ran a 60-yard dash in 6.6 seconds,
which was more impressive considering he was wearing two different
shoes, one several sizes larger with a rag stuffed into the toe.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the players were telling me I should talk to this kid,''
Ferreira said. ``The first thing we had him do was throw, and right
away you could see he could really throw. He was really distraught
(after the injury), sitting over in the dugout with his head
between his legs. I went over and talked to him, tried to cheer him
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira signed Guerrero that afternoon. One side note: The
Dodgers had checked out Guerrero earlier that year and rejected him
as too skinny and too slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the tools,'' Ferreira said. ``You always look for the
tools. It always seems to me that he's like a guy playing
slow-pitch softball when everyone else is playing hardball. He's
just standing there saying, `C'mon, man, throw one over the plate.'
'' &QL; 
Dodger blues &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not only is closer  &UR; Jeff Shaw's season unraveling, as his three
blown saves in his past four chances demonstrate, but the Dodgers
appear to have no chance to make interim General Manager  &UR; Tommy
Lasorda's guarantee of a playoff berth come true.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who entered the weekend only one game over .500
since the  &UR; Bill Russell- &UR; Fred Claire dumpings, were eight games
behind the Chicago Cubs in the wild card race.
</P>
<P>
   Their chances were basically tossed in the trash once  &UR; Gary
 &UR; Sheffield's season ended last weekend because of a severely
sprained left ankle, an injury that will take six weeks to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Also out for the season is reliever  &UR; Antonio Osuna, who will
undergo arthroscopic elbow surgery this week.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield batted .316 with 16 home runs and 57 RBIs in 90 games
since Florida made the blockbuster trade with the Dodgers, and
finished at .302, 22 home runs, 85 RBIs and 22 stolen bases for the
season. It was Sheffield's first 20-20 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the fans, or anyone on the outside, say this is frustrating
for them, well, magnify that 1,000 times for us,'' first baseman
 &UR; Eric
 &UR; Karros said. ``We've had opportunities. We get right to that point
where there's a game we have to win, and the bottom line is that we
don't get it done.'' &QL; 
No mas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colorado outfielder  &UR; Dante Bichette, a spokesman for a
nutritional company that produces the controversial supplement
androstenedione, has decided to stop using the controversial pills.
</P>
<P>
   Bichette will continue to use other supplements from the company
and will continue to commercially endorse other EAS products.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not to say I won't get back on (andro) down the road a
little bit,'' Bichette said. ``But I want it understood that I
still believe very strongly in what they're doing at EAS. Those
guys are trying to provide a safe alternative (to steroids).
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason (I stopped taking andro) is just all the junk that
has come out with it. I just don't want to promote something that
everybody's all scared about. I'll wait until some more research is
done, but I still think it's a safe supplement.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
