<HEADLINE>
KICKOFF COVERAGE LACKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Arizona State Coach  &UR; Bruce Snyder has fretted for
months about his team's kicker and punter, both of whom are new,
but both performed reasonably well Saturday against Washington. The
kickoff coverage team, however, could use some work.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stephen Baker, &UR; a freshman, handled the kickoff chores well,
placing the ball relatively deep. His first try went into the end
zone, but it was called back because of illegal procedure on the
Sun Devils. His next attempt landed at the 2, but Washington's  &UR; Joe
Jarzynka returned it 42 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The net gain of 24 yards helped Washington score on its first
drive. Washington's  &UR; Ja'Warren Hooker later returned a kickoff 61
yards, and ASU seemed to give up kicking deep. Baker pooched one
kick, which ASU recovered, setting up its fourth touchdown of the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Baker had only one punt attempt in the first half and boomed it
55 yards. Place kicker Mike Gauthier missed a 42-yard field goal
attempt near the end of the first half and made a 42-yarder in the
fourth-quarter. &QL; 
A fast start &QL; 
Pac-10 Commissioner  &UR; Tom Hansen, &UR; who attended Saturday night's
game, has been impressed by the conference's performance in the
opening week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Arizona beat Hawaii, Oregon beat Michigan State and
Washington State beat Illinois. Oregon State also won its opener
over Nevada. The major disappointment was Stanford, which lost to
San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought before the season we'd have two really fine teams in
UCLA and Arizona State,'' he said. ``And I thought from Oregon,
USC, Washington and Arizona, we would happen to find some other
teams that were very, very good. And that's been the case so far.
This is a fine Washington team on offense, and Arizona played a
very strong game, and Oregon was just outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that I said at media day that's been so true is we
have just some outstanding quarterbacks. These two here (ASU's
 &UR; Ryan Kealy and Washington's  &UR; Brock Huard) are sensational.'' &QL; 
Flag bearer &QL; 
Backup quarterback  &UR; Steve Campbell was awarded the honor of
carrying the team's flag and leading the Sun Devils out of the
locker room before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bruce Snyder bestows the honor on a senior who shows a
commitment to the team. Campbell, a senior, is either second or
third team. Snyder hasn't made that clear. If starter Kealy had to
be replaced, it's possible Snyder could chose redshirt freshman
 &UR; Chad
 &UR; Elliott instead of Campbell. &QL; 
Briefly &QL; 
Washington receiver/kick returner Hooker suffered a partially
separated left shoulder during the first quarter and didn't return
to action. Hooker suffered the injury on a 61-yard kickoff return
in the first quarter. His prognosis for the rest of the season was
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker means a lot to the Huskies offense. He was the NCAA
indoor 55-meter champion last spring and is one of the fastest
players in the country. A sophomore, he was expected to be one of
the most exciting players in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies didn't seem to miss him much Saturday. Receiver
 &UR; Dane
 &UR; Looker caught 8 passes for 85 yards and a touchdown in the first
half alone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game will be replayed at 4 p.m. today on Fox Sports
Arizona cable network. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
