<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-HEAP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAP SHINES IN DEBUT  
 FRESHMAN MAKES 1-HANDED TD SNAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Todd Heap has a tough act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   His own.
</P>
<P>
   Barely four months out of Mesa Mountain View High School, in his
first college game, on his first college play, Heap made the catch
of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   It was a leaping, falling, juggling, one-handed grab in the end
zone, with not one but two defenders belting him in midair.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't enough for Arizona State as the Sun Devils lost to
Washington, 42-38, on Saturday on opening night for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen playing in their first game usually are supposed to
watch and learn and stay out of the way. Heap, apparently, is a
somewhat unusual freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Already, he has two nicknames. ASU Coach Bruce Snyder calls the
6-foot-5, 220-pound Heap ``The Retriever.'' John Pettas, ASU
quarterbacks coach, calls him ``Jim Thorpe, All-American.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the description, Heap lived up to it on a single play,
retrieving a Ryan Kealy pass in the back of the end zone. Heap
tipped the ball, took a hit from defenders Marques Hairston and
Toure Butler and hooked the ball with his right hand while falling
down. The catch, worthy of any All-American, capped a 14-play,
71-yard drive and gave ASU a 14-7 lead with 2:19 left in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just glad to be in the game,'' said Heap, whose uncle
and grandfather played basketball for ASU. ``Kealy put it up. . . .
I didn't think he was going to throw it. But he put it up, and I
got a hand on it. I just saw the ball coming, and I had to make the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody else had a chance to get it but me.''
</P>
<P>
   In a game where the big plays practically outnumbered the small
plays, this might not have been the biggest. But it certainly was
the most spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Heap was ``The Republi''c's Class 5A Player of the Year last
season, a terror at tight end and linebacker for Mountain View. But
this wasn't Westwood High on a Friday night in Mesa in front of
friends and family. This was Pac-10 rival Washington in Sun Devil
Stadium on a Saturday night in front of 72,118, many of whom
perhaps never had heard of Heap.
</P>
<P>
   They have now.
</P>
<P>
   And they had better enjoy Heap's work while they can. He is
expected to serve a Mormon mission for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Devil Stadium has provided the launching pad for many
careers. Among those who started there is Washington quarterback
Brock Huard, who came in as a freshman two years ago and rallied
the Huskies before ASU prevailed, 45-42.
</P>
<P>
   In his return engagement, Huard, now a junior and a Heisman
Trophy candidate, exacted some payback, passing for 318 yards and
four touchdowns to lead Washington's upset.
</P>
<P>
   Heap wasn't the only ASU freshman who contributed. Tailback
Davaren Hightower, who redshirted last year while recovering from a
broken leg, scored the first touchdown of his career, a two-yard
run in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Baker, who also redshirted last year, handled punting
and kickoff duties. His first punt went 55 yards (he later added a
35-yarder) and successfully pooched an onside kickoff. It was
recovered by Kyion Grayes, a first-year freshman.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a touchdown and a 28-14 lead for ASU in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But ASU's offense fizzled in the face of a newfound Huskies pass
rush, and the Sun Devils had no answers for Huard and the
Washington offense. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
