<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2-QB SYSTEM LIKELY TO CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _  &UR; Keith Smith and  &UR; Ortege Jenkins are two
quarterbacks in a system instead of a race.
</P>
<P>
   For now.
</P>
<P>
   Or forever.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's season-opening victory on Thursday night at Hawaii was
nothing if not further evidence that coach &UR; Dick Tomey will continue
to rely on both for as long as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The whole season?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what may happen,' Tomey said after Smith helped lead
Arizona to a 27-6 victory. ``OJ's going to keep playing. Keith is
going to keep playing. We're trying to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith emerged as a leader in this mini-drama as the Wildcats
prepare for a Pacific-10 Conference opener on Sept. 12 at Stanford,
which was upset Saturday, 35-23, by San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   Smith came on in relief of Jenkins, who struggled in the opening
quarter at Aloha Stadium. But Smith spoke as if he were prepared
for the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``OJ and I were talking on the sidelines about if we don't start
right, one of us automatically has to pick it up,'' said Smith, who
was 17 of 22 for 218 yards passing as opposed to Jenkins' 3 of 11
for 19 yards. ``You can't guarantee you're going to be great all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be off in some games, and that's when he has to
step in and do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins wasn't looking for excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't get things going,'' he said. ``Keith did a great
job. he was hot as I'ver seen him.'' &QL; 
Getting back &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Trung Canidate, the projected starter at running back from
Central High, is expected to practice this week after undergoing
rehabilitation for a stress fracture to his right foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' said Tomey, who was unhappy with a spotty running
game at Hawaii. ``We tried to get him to do things in rehab that
are tougher than he'll face in a game. If Hawaii had been the last
game in his career, I think he could have played.'' &QL; 
Briefly. . .  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of Arizona's loudest fans Thursday night were from the crew
of the USS Tucson, a submarine stationed at nearby Peral Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise, surprise. The Wildcats were not expecting Stanford's
loss to San Jose State. The Cardinal has a new offensive
coordinator. ``I'm not expecting them to show too much against San
Jose State,'' Tomey said Saturday before the upset. Tomey didn't
know how prophetic he was.
</P>
<P>
   And do-it-all  &UR; Chris McAlister was seen running to the Aloha
Stadium locker room midway through the game. He was moving almost
as fast as he did in the 100-yard touchdown return of the game's
opening kickoff. Trouble? Not really. As McAlister explained it, he
was under pressure from having consumed too much liquid before
kickoff. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
