<DOCNO> NYT19980906.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 03:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1422 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-GOMEZ-AZR     09-06 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONNA LEAVE YOU, BABE  
 MCGWIRE TIES RUTH'S 60; MARIS NEXT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS - Baseball's highly exclusive 60-home run club
admitted its third member Saturday afternoon when Mark McGwire
ripped a 381-foot line drive into the left-field seats at Busch
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is now in the company of Babe Ruth and Roger Maris, the
only other men ever to hit 60 home runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   At 34, he is also the oldest player to reach 60. Ruth was 32
when he hit 60 in 1927, and Maris was 27 when he set the record of
61 in 1961. That only three players in the 129-year history of the
game have reached this milestone helps deliver some perspective of
exactly how difficult this feat is.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's afternoon began brilliantly when he laced a flat
fastball, the third pitch he'd seen from Cincinnati starter Dennis
Reyes, over the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd of 47,994, which had already been standing
when McGwire was announced, roared its approval with a deafening
sound for all of downtown St. Louis to hear.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire went hitless in his other three at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unbelievable,'' McGwire said of the phenomena he has
created. ``What can you say? If you want to say it has brought
America together, it has. So be it. Let's just ride the wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen!
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Manager Jack McKeon was asked after the game if, with
first base open and runners at second and third, he contemplated
walking McGwire in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I thought about it,'' the crusty McKeon said. ``But I
also thought about all those people who have been calling my voice
mail asking me to heal the country. So I decided to heal the
country, and we pitched to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is unleashing its mystic powers in all the right ways
these days. All the talk of the recent strikes has basically been
eliminated. The focus is where it should have been all along _ on
the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has indeed returned to its proper place, and McGwire
isn't just part of the bandwagon, he's driving the sucker.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 NFL season will begin today, and while football's
television ratings will once again tower over baseball's, don't let
that be the true barometer of which is the hotter sport.
</P>
<P>
   Because baseball plays so many games, its TV ratings will always
be smaller. What McGwire and Sammy Sosa are doing for the game this
summer can never be measured by how many households are watching
what.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is back at the top of the heap precisely because of
McGwire's personal charge on the single-season home run record. No
other sport captivates the country's attention quite like baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Want proof? How many of you know the record for most yards in an
NFL season? How about most points in an NBA season? It's a good bet
very few know.
</P>
<P>
   However, just bring up the number 56 or 61 or 755, and any
baseball fan will be able to recite in order: Joe DiMaggio's
hitting streak, Maris' single-season home run record and Hank
Aaron's career home run total.
</P>
<P>
   It's a game steeped in tradition and interwoven into the very
roots of our society. Even nearby societies, especially in Latin
America, have adopted the national pastime of the United States as
theirs, too.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's quest for 61 has flooded all of our memories with
everything we have always loved about the game.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it's very cool to be an avid baseball fan again.
Earlier this year, Commissioner Bud Selig predicted the game was in
the early to middle stages of what would amount to a powerful
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you want about the commish, but the man looks like an
awfully talented prophet these days.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the next few days, possibly today, McGwire will step
to the head of the single-season home run class. His undeniable
passion for the game practically jumps out when he speaks about
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The game is nearing the top of the sports heap once again.
Magical seasons like this don't happen every year. Baseball is new
to our area, but it's important we all sit back and soak in exactly
what is happening.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire is our generation's Babe Ruth. His achievements
have taken a stranglehold on the country unlike anything we've seen
in decades.
</P>
<P>
   As Ruth once notably put it, baseball truly is the greatest game
ever invented. Hallelujah for what's going on right now. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
