<HEADLINE>
HE'S GOT ANSWERS 
 BATTING COACH REVIEWS SOSA, MAC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Jeff Pentland became the Chicago Cubs batting
instructor on July 15 last season and is generally considered the
force behind Sammy Sosa's remarkable and unexpected power assault
on the National League this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pentland lives in Tempe during the off-season. He graduated from
Arizona State in 1968 with a degree in biomechanics and was batting
coach for the Sun Devils in the late '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning as he prepared to leave for the club's trip to
Pittsburgh, Pentland answered these questions on Mark McGwire,
Sammy Sosa and the home run mania of the 1998 Major League Baseball
season:  &QL; 
 &UR; QUESTION: Are you surprised at Mark McGwire's accomplishments this
year? &QL; 
 &UR; ANSWER: In a way. I've known Mark McGwire since he was in high
school. When I was at Arizona State we competed against him when he
was at Southern Cal. He wasn't that good then, and his early years
of professional ball were not very good. Mark almost didn't make it
to the big leagues. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: What happened?  &QL; 
 &UR; A: To his credit, he had the ability to make adjustments. In fact,
he's made significant adjustments in going from the American League
to the National. He's become a better hitter since going to the
Cardinals.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: How is that?  &QL; 
 &UR; A: The American League is a breaking-ball league. When McGwire was
with Oakland, he tended to hang on his backside so he didn't
transfer his weight nearly as much as he does in the National
League, a fastball league. With Oakland, his swing was loopier and
longer. With the Cardinals, he had to shorten his swing because
they were throwing him fastballs inside.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: Is McGwire so good because he's so big?  &QL; 
 &UR; A: Normally size is not a positive in baseball. Large men with long
arms are at a disadvantage because their swing takes longer, which
gives them less time to read the pitch. McGwire is that rare
combination of power, quickness and coordination.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: Do you think McGwire's accomplishments have been tainted because
of his highly publicized use of the over-the-counter dietary
supplement androstenedione?  &QL; 
 &UR; A: I don't know much about that sort of thing. When I went to
Arizona State, they were talking about blood doping where you save
your blood and re-enter it into your system. It's always something.
But like I said, body building and body-building drugs are not
usually an advantage for hitters.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: How about Sammy? What is he doing differently this season? &QL; 
 &UR; A: Sammy has natural talent, natural easy power, but he was
swinging as hard as he could at every pitch. All I had to do was
convince him to keep his front foot back longer so he could more
effectively explode into the baseball with all his weight. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: But for the most part, are home run hitters born rather than
made?  &QL; 
 &UR; A: Major league hitters tend to choose what they want to be. I used
to watch Rod Carew, who was one of the game's best singles hitters.
But when he wanted to, I've seen him put 10 balls in a row over the
fence in batting practice. Same with Wade Boggs. These guys chose
not to be home run hitters. I tell young hitters you can't get
locked into just one specific way of doing something.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: What's the most difficult thing about being a home run hitter? &QL; 
 &UR; A: That's easy. The major stumbling block is the inability to
repeat the same swing the same way every at-bat. Sammy is pretty
amazing that way. He repeats his swing consistently and rarely does
he come out of it.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: He's also become more selective? &QL; 
 &UR; A: Sometimes a player's game can all come together by correcting
one flaw. You open up their mind and this opens up their physical
ability. Most of your athletes have no idea how good they are. I
don't think Sammy ever thought he would be here. But once he
realized he was this good, he captured it and ran with it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
