<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS CAN'T SLAM DOOR ON HOUSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Diamondbacks' uniforms should not be stained by
tears of despondence. They have nobody to blame but themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They had plenty of opportunities to extend their club-record
winning streak to eight games on Saturday and set an expansion
record in the process. The stark reality is that time after time,
they couldn't come through, leaving the door open for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12th inning, the Astros finally slipped through, scoring
on a bases-loaded groundout by Ricky Gutierrez for a 6-5 victory at
Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, the leader in the National League Central Division,
raised its record to 89-53. Arizona fell to 57-86. The teams end
their three-game series today at 4:35 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks jumped to a 3-0 lead in the first inning and
managed to stay a step ahead of the Astros until the seventh
inning, when a base hit by Sean Berry scored Derek Bell with the
tying run to make it 5-5. Bell had led off the inning with a
bad-hop single that bounced over the head of Arizona second baseman
Andy Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Fox again figured prominently in Houston's winning effort in the
12th.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou doubled off left-hander Alan Embree with one out.
Embree walked Richard Hidalgo. Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter
called on right-hander Felix Rodriguez, who promptly hit Russ
Johnson to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks figured they still had a good chance to escape,
given the fact that Gutierrez had grounded into a team-high 16
double plays. Arizona's infield was set at double-play depth.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez obliged _ sort of. He hit the ball on the ground
toward Fox, but the ball was hit too slowly. Fox came in, saw he
couldn't get Alou at the plate or tag Johnson, then had to spin,
throw and settle for a force-out of Johnson at second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest thing was that the ball wasn't hit that hard. I
was caught in No Man's Land. It was just one of those things,'' Fox
said. ``That just shows that you don't have to hit the ball hard to
be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (winning streak) was a nice run we had, and it would have
been good to keep going, but we just couldn't put them away.''
</P>
<P>
   After Houston pulled to within 3-2 in the top of the second, the
Diamondbacks had two men on base with one out in the bottom of the
inning, but Jay Bell fouled out to Jeff Bagwell at first base, and
Devon White grounded out to Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   A one-run inning in the third could have been more, but Damian
Miller, whose two-out triple drove in David Dellucci, was left
stranded at third as Karim Garcia grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona had the bases loaded with nobody out in the fourth but
could only increase its lead from 4-3 to 5-3. Right-hander Scott
Elarton, who entered the game in place of starter Shane Reynolds,
struck out White, retired Lee on an RBI groundout and struck out
Matt Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks stranded two men in the fifth against Elarton
and two more in both the ninth and 10th innings against
right-hander Doug Henry, who pitched at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you don't score yourself and give them that many
opportunities, things will be difficult for you,'' Diamondbacks
Manager Buck Showalter said. ``We just couldn't push one across.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Billy Wagner, who was hit in the head by a line
drive in the Astros' previous visit here in mid-July, retired the
side in order in the 11th and struck out the side in the 12th to
raise his record to 4-3. The only blemish was a walk to Kelly
Stinnett, who hit the line drive that injured him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
