<HEADLINE>
US WEST CUSTOMERS STILL WAITING FOR SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BECKY RAMSDELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When 64-year-old Sheila Brown moved from one apartment to
another within her complex last month, she expected to be without a
telephone for about a day.
</P>
<P>
   But the US West strike has left the Phoenix woman, who lives
alone and suffers from chronic asthma attacks and other health
problems, fighting to get her new installation done on an emergency
basis. She's been without phone service for 18 days.
</P>
<P>
   And she's not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the work stoppage, we had a whole bunch more people
define themselves as emergency cases than we normally do,'' US West
spokesman Jim Roof said.
</P>
<P>
   The company typically gives emergency cases priority, but
doesn't formally track how many of those requests are received.
Roof estimated that only a small number of the 500 orders received
daily are labeled emergencies. And it's also hard to tell how many
of those cases are valid emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   What customers define as an emergency situation isn't always
critical in US West's view. For instance, people who are concerned
about elderly parents in another state can't get emergency service,
Roof said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The compelling emergency case situation is going to be someone
with a medical condition of significance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Strikers began returning to work last week to tackle a backlog
of 13,000 new orders and several thousand repair orders. New orders
are keeping the backlog at about that number, Roof added. It will
be four to six weeks before the backlog is cleared and orders
return to a normal three- to four-day wait for hookup, he
estimated.
</P>
<P>
   As a thank-you gesture to US West customers, the company offered
free directory assistance Saturday and Sunday. Company officials
said they didn't know how many customers took advantage of the
offer Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Crews are now doing more business orders than residential ones
to minimize the financial effects on companies. Some crews were
working specifically on emergencies during the strike, but those
cases are now assigned to the crew working in the area, Roof said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear from businesses, `If I can't get my calls, I'm not in
business,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said she told US West of her health condition, but added
that it hasn't helped. She said she often wakes up during the
night, choking and struggling to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phone, years ago, used to be a luxury. Now it's a
necessity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One of her friends, Olivia L'Heureux, lives close by and checks
on Brown daily. Both women say the lack of service is the strikers'
fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do blame the strikers,'' L'Heureux said. ``I really don't
have a lot of sympathy for them.''
</P>
<P>
   A local union leader said he sympathizes with Brown, but US West
has restricted overtime hours for returning workers.
</P>
<P>
   They are permitted only eight overtime hours a week, said Joe
Gosiger, president of Communication Workers of America Local 7019.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have them question why the company, US West, is
limiting the amount of voluntary overtime to our people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roof said the company is limiting overtime because it was one of
the union's biggest issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we don't want to get people back and just load them
up with overtime,'' he said. ``We're trying to be as sensitive as
we can to the Number 1 issue they mentioned again and again and
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's installation was scheduled for Aug. 20 but was delayed
by the strike. After a series of attempts to get service, Brown
said she was told her order would be taken care of around Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Roof said part of the delay in Brown's case was that she
requested two phone lines. Her first line is scheduled for
installation Tuesday, but Roof said he has requested both lines be
done then.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who doesn't have a computer, said she only asked for one
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't order two. What do I need two for?'' she asked. ``I
just want my own little phone ringing again.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Becky Ramsdell can be reached at 444-7115 or at
becky.ramsdell &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
