<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-DESROCHERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES SEE GOALIE AS PRIZE CATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Patrick DesRochers says he was destined to live his
life around the nets. For the longest time, though, he thought it
would be fishing nets.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Louis, has owned and operated a successful marina on
Georgian Bay, Ontario, ever since he can remember. As a child, he
spent much of his youth fishing off the pier of the family
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've caught just about everything,'' Patrick said. `I really
got pretty good at reeling them in.''
</P>
<P>
   Not nearly as good, it turns out, as turning them back.
</P>
<P>
   DesRochers (pronounced DE-row-SHAY) was the top-rated amateur
goalie in North America last season. After posting a 26-17-3 record
with a 3.35 goals-against average and a .901 save percentage for
the Sarnia Sting in the Ontario Hockey league, the Coyotes made the
6-foot-3{, 199-pounder their first-round pick in June's NHL draft.
</P>
<P>
   The 14th overall pick, DesRochers was the first goalie taken.
Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith said the scouting staff liked
him so much that the team was prepared to move up several spots to
snare him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid has got it all,'' said Dave Farrish, head coach of
the Coyotes' minor league affiliate in Springfield, Mass., where
DesRochers likely will play in 1999-2000. ``He's got all the
tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrish should know. An avid outdoorsman himself, he used to
keep his boats docked at the DesRochers family marina. For years,
young Patrick diligently would gas up the vessel, help keep it in
ship-shape, and even offer fishing tips to the former pro hockey
player.
</P>
<P>
   But DesRochers has turned out to be the prize catch.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since they hooked him, the Coyotes will get a
chance to monitor his progress up close as the team's rookie camp
opens today at the Cellular One Ice Den in Scottsdale. DesRochers,
18, is one of dozens of prospects and various first-year players
who have been invited to attend the weeklong workout before
veterans report next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Others participating include the 1996 first-round draft picks,
center Daniel Briere and defenseman Dan Focht, '97 picks such as
German-born left wing Robert Francz and defensemen Scott McCallum
and Curtis Suter, and four other members of the '98 draft class,
including center Erik Westrum, a sophomore at the University of
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``He paid his own way here so he could keep his amateur status
and (NCAA) eligibility,'' Smith said of Westrum, the 187th player
drafted overall. `He's going to have to pay for his own hotel, his
own sticks, his own meals. He's really making a commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   But most eyes will be locked on DesRochers, whom NHL scouts have
called a can't-miss franchise goalie. It will be a while before
he's ready to challenge incumbent Nikolai Khabibulin for the
starter's job in Phoenix, but someday, it definitely will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have high hopes for him,'' Smith said. ``That hasn't
changed one bit since the day we drafted him back in June.''
</P>
<P>
   DesRochers has all the attributes that scouts say a good goalie
should possess, namely size and strength. He's so big that he
smothers the puck. He's so strong that he doesn't have to flop to
his knees at the first sight of a slap shot. He also has uncanny
side-to-side mobility for a goalie so tall, an intangible that
completes the package.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes with all sorts of credentials,'' one scout told
``The'' ``Hockey News.'' `I think he's right on schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great physical makeup to be a goalie,'' another scout
said. ``He is an opposing presence to oncoming forwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Stopping pucks has become a family tradition every bit as much
as the family marina business. Patrick's dad and two of his three
older brothers played goalie, so he almost seemed destined to
follow in their footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to do something with all that goalie equipment,'' he
said, laughing. `I kind of had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   `It's been great, though. My goal has always been to play in the
NHL and get a chance to win the Stanley Cup someday. I never really
thought about being the first goaltender picked in the draft, but
in the last year or so, the thought definitely crossed my mind that
it could be a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are in no rush to put him in their sweater, however.
For now, the club is secure at the position with Khabibulin,
veteran Jimmy Waite and two other prospects who are close to
getting there, Scott Langkow and Sylvain Daigle.
</P>
<P>
   DesRochers will figure into the mix, but not for at least a
couple more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goaltenders need time to develop, and I know that,'' he said.
``It's important to take that next step, but not to make it too
quickly, so I'm not in any big hurry. I feel I'm developing on
schedule, but I'll leave it up to the Coyotes to decide when I'm
ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better for me to go to the minors and play lots of games
rather than going up to the big team right away and just sit on the
bench. But someday, I hope to be there. (Khabibulin) is an
excellent goaltender, and I look up to him big time. But I don't
know. We'll see what happens in the future. A lot of things can
happen in the game of hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   After training camp, DesRochers will report to Sarnia for his
fourth and final year of juniors, or he could wind up with the
Canadian national team, which is based in Calgary. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
