<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-PHOENIX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCCER LEAGUE NOT HOT ON PHOENIX FOR EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CRAIG MORGAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Professional sports leagues long have viewed
exhibition games in non-league cities as litmus tests for
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's Desert Series in 1993-94 is a good example. Despite
mediocre attendance figures in the Valley, the Winnipeg Jets soon
became the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition tradition continues tonight at Scottsdale Stadium
when the USISL's D-3 Arizona Sahuaros take on Major League Soccer's
Colorado Rapids in the league's sponsored event in the Valley. The
Sahuaros have sold 2,500 tickets for the game and are optimistic
that more fans will buy at the gates.
</P>
<P>
   But those who think tonight's game is a precursor for an
expansion MLS franchise may be jumping the gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I would say our fervor for an Arizona team is tepid
at best,'' MLS Commissioner Doug Logan said. ``There are a number
of criteria we look at when considering expansion, and right now
Phoenix has a lot of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan said those problems include the lack of a proper facility,
the lack of committed investors and the Valley's unaccommodating
summer heat.
</P>
<P>
   The MLS hopes to add two teams in 2000 or 2001 and another two
in 2002 or 2003 to reach its ideal size of 16. With 12 teams
already in the fold, Phoenix doesn't even rate a mention on the
league's wish list: Seattle, Charlotte, Cincinnati, Pittsburgh, San
Diego, Houston, Portland, Anaheim, Rochester, N.Y., and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Houston and Philadelphia are considered the front-runners for
the first wave of expansion. Philadelphia is the largest market
without a team, and Logan said Houston's combination of ethnic
minorities, solid investment groups and a domed stadium makes it a
virtual lock.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Northwest is the focal point of the latter expansion
plans with Seattle and possibly Portland the leading candidates.
Logan said the league is strongly considering adding a second team
to the New York/New Jersey area and Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of these plans stand the second-year Sahuaros with
high hopes. The team recently reached an agreement to play its
games at Scottsdale Stadium after playing all of last season and
most of this year at Mesa's Dobson High School. The move was widely
viewed as an upgrade within the organization. But Logan said
Scottsdale still is far from optimal for soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not up to our standards,'' Logan said. ``From a
fan's standpoint, it's very marginal.''
</P>
<P>
   The field of play at Scottsdale stretches across the outfield
and a portion of the middle infield to minimize the amount of dirt
in play. The problem is that most of the seats at Scottsdale are
situated alongside or behind the infield, leaving fans far from the
action.
</P>
<P>
   Since the MLS is committed to television contracts with ABC,
ESPN and Univision that require weekend afternoon games, a Phoenix
site may have to be indoors anyway to avoid exposing fans to
temperatures that usually exceed 100 degrees. Logan likes Sun Devil
Stadium but fears a lag in attendance because of the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One Ballpark is the only such indoor facility in the Valley
that could house soccer. But the ballpark's general manager, Bob
Machen, said the field is no more conducive to soccer than
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very difficult to overlap seasons with the
Diamondbacks also playing in the summer,'' Machen said. ``We've
learned a lot about turf management this year, and we feel like
we've done an excellent job considering the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``But obviously, soccer is much tougher on a playing surface. If
we added soccer to baseball in the same season, having to remove
the mound and keep up the sod, it would be a very difficult thing
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Rio Salado Crossing would be another possibility.
Sahuaros President Ali Alexander has spoken with Michael Bidwill,
Cardinals vice president and general counsel, about sharing a
stadium but characterized those talks as premature.
</P>
<P>
   The money problems come next. In a sports landscape dominated by
the Colangelo and Bidwill families, neither camp seems overly
interested in the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, we were confronted by a group about the
possibility of starting up a team and we took a pass,'' Suns
General Manager Bryan Colangelo said. ``We're always aware of
different types of opportunities in sports, and the MLS is
interesting due to its early success in terms of fan support. But
at this time, there's really not a high level of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said it probably is more prudent to build slowly and
focus on a move to the A league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to build a solid foundation in management
and sponsors,'' he said. ``I think it would be a mistake to go too
fast like some of the past teams tried to do. For me the MLS is not
out of reach, but it's something we'll have to earn.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every project needs a rabbi, and we look for a bell cow no
matter where we go,'' he said. ``I don't want to dissuade any
community from pursuing a franchise. We can't afford to exclude
anyone. But we have to look at realistic expectations, and I don't
think it would be fair to consider Phoenix right now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
