<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PENNANT-RACES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 CONTENDERS STILL IN HUNT FOR 2 SPOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1998 baseball season will end three weeks from today. In the
meantime, there are two hotly-contested playoff races taking place.
</P>
<P>
   While five of the six division races are practically over, the
American League West and the National League wild-card races have
five clubs vying for two postseason spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like being in a pennant race,'' said St. Louis
Manager Tony La Russa. ``It's the ultimate test for every member of
a club. You go through the highs, the lows and when it's over,
especially if you've won or made a spirited run, you feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   But, at the time, there was no telling the members of the 1993
San Francisco Giants about the good they had done for the game by
winning 103 games and pushing the Atlanta Braves to 104 victories
and an NL West championship.
</P>
<P>
   The players, coaching staff and manager were despondent on the
day they were trounced in Los Angeles on the last day of the
season, knowing Atlanta had already won. No amount of consoling
could lift the spirits of the Giants that day.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who put on as good a show as baseball has seen, were
spent, all because they had put everything out for six months and
come away with no more than a second-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Battling for a postseason spot in baseball has always meant
more, because the sport has so few playoff berths.
</P>
<P>
   It was only three years ago, with the addition of the wild card,
that the game allowed a second place team to reach the playoffs.
Securing a playoff spot in baseball meant more because a club had
to finish in first place to advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's why baseball has such a special spot,'' said
Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter, who guided the 1995 New York
Yankees to the playoffs. ``What you do in April and May matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike basketball and hockey, where 16 clubs make the playoffs,
or football, where 12 make it, baseball allows only eight of its 30
to move on.
</P>
<P>
   With due respect to the 1995 Mariners-Angels race, the
Braves-Giants race of 1993 was probably the last great one in the
game. But no matter if a race is great or not, just being in a
playoff race is special.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim and Texas are scrapping for the final spot in the AL
playoffs while the NL wild-card race, which looks like a dandy at
this stage, is being fought by the Giants, Chicago Cubs and New
York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty is that only one of those clubs in each race will
play beyond Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, who were surprising the baseball world by pulling
away from Texas in the past few weeks, received their gut-check in
the form of a major injury.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad, easily the best all-around player on the Angels
roster, pulled up lame last week while running to first base. A
severe hamstring injury may keep him out of the lineup the rest of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this season is a test, I want to know when you pass, when
it's finally over,'' Anaheim Manager Terry Collins told Angels
writers last week. ``I've had enough of it. It's time for us to get
some breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming breaks has always been a part of baseball. The true
character of a club rarely surfaces until it is met with adversity.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Angels will find out what makes them tick over the next
three weeks. The Angels and Texas will play five times in the
coming weeks. They will be games that will be engulfed with playoff
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   One potential problem for whoever wins the final two playoff
spots is being emotionally empty when the postseason begins. It was
a problem that definitely affected the 1993 Braves, who were
eliminated by Philadelphia, clearly inferior, in the first round
that season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the experience of reaching the playoffs has always
out-weighted whatever side effects getting there might create.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like a playoff game,'' said Baltimore
shortstop Mike Bordick, who has played in the post-season for
Oakland the Orioles. ``The intensity of the games is incredible.
It's rare for any regular season game to measure up to what you
feel in the playoffs. It's the ultimate.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what they're fighting for. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
