<HEADLINE>
MOURNING A FALLEN BROTHER  
 SIBLING'S DEATH HARD ON COWBOYS SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Ten months later, Dallas Cowboys safety Kenny
Wheaton's pain hasn't gone away.
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton, a Tempe McClintock High School product, still can't get
his younger brother, Derrek, off his mind. It has consumed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about him 24 hours a day,'' Wheaton said. ``It will be
that way as long as I'm alive. Not a day will pass by when I'm not
thinking of him.''
</P>
<P>
   He still gets chills thinking about the phone call he received
in Dallas on Nov. 20. It was 3 a.m., and his older brother, Robert,
called to tell him that Derrek, 19, had been murdered outside a
Phoenix convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only get three hours of sleep every night, maximum,
because of the incident,'' Wheaton said. ``I have nightmares. It's
hard for me to do anything at night except sit there and think
about what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton still can't understand why his brother was gunned down.
Family members told him it was a case of mistaken identity, but
that hasn't made it any easier for Wheaton, who will be with the
Cowboys today when they open their season against the Cardinals at
Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was such a happy person,'' Wheaton said of Derrek. ``He
always had a smile on his face. His friends called him `Sunshine.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask my coaches at McClintock. Derrek was the best athlete of
the three. All three of us brothers were very close, as close as
any three you'd ever find.''
</P>
<P>
   Derrek, a freshman cornerback at Phoenix Community College, had
stopped for gas at a convenience store as he returned home from the
school's football banquet. He had won two defensive honors that
night and hoped to transfer to Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a page from his girlfriend, Derrek went to a pay
phone and was on the line when a car pulled through the parking
lot. Gunshots were fired, and Derrek died instantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never had a chance to run,'' Wheaton told the ``Dallas''
``Morning News.'' ``He didn't know what hit him because he had his
back turned.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Wheaton's frustration is that the case is unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Phoenix) police, they're so full of it. They give us the
runaround,'' Wheaton said. ``They haven't told us anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police spokesman Mike McCullough said he understands the
family's frustration but said the investigation is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leads we learn of are still being worked by homicide
investigators,'' McCullough said. ``At this point, it's too early
to explain to the family as far as who, what, when and where.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members claim the police have been slow to follow up on
tips because they consider the shooting to be gang-related and
difficult to solve.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother was not the type of person to hurt a soul,''
Wheaton said. ``Anyone who knew him could vouch that he's not in
any gang.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his family isn't doing well. ``I try to help
financially,'' he said. ``I try to be there for them. As hard as it
is on the entire family, they still are supportive. They come to
the games. They'll always still be there for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton wears D.K.W (his brother's initials) RIP on his practice
uniform. It's written with a felt-tipped marker, but it might as
well be etched indelibly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wear it every practice,'' Wheaton said. ``When I need
strength, when I'm tired or when I'm down, I put my right hand on
my chest and get that strength from touching his initials.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton also has taped his brother's obituary to his locker and
carries his picture with him at all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people wonder how you can always be thinking about him
and focus on what you do. It's possible. I think about him every
time I'm on the field, lifting weights. I think about him in
between plays. I think about him every day, all day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
