<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-REAX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WADSWORTH DEAL BRINGS CARDS FULL CIRCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Everyone knew something was up when the flight
attendant on the Cardinals' charter plane came on the public
address system and said Bill Bidwill Sr. had a special
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Memories were tested to recall the last time the team's
reclusive owner did that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was going to tell us that Mark McGwire broke the
home run record,'' said linebacker Jamir Miller, one of the
defensive captains.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who'd seen Coach Vince Tobin tap backup defensive lineman
Mike Moten on the shoulder and escort him off the plane before
takeoff could have guessed differently.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals held out hope for 44 days while Andre Wadsworth
simply held out. Finally, the impasse was resolved on Saturday with
Wadsworth, the Cardinals first-round draft pick, signing a six-year
contract that could be worth as much as $42 million if he achieves
escalator incentives. Wadsworth receives a club-record $10.49
million signing bonus entering today's opener against the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis was one of those cheering
the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after the announcement I went right up and shook Mr. B's
hand,'' McGinnis said. ``It was a very good emotional bump for all
of us. Mentally for this team, there's no question that this is
really outstanding. I had full confidence we'd get this done. I've
been in the league too long to think it wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   That was echoed by one of the behind-the-scene deal-savers, team
vice president Michael Bidwill, who just returned from vacation in
France. While on the continent, Bidwill was briefed by telephone of
the raging firestorm last week over allegations that the club had
killed a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best player in the draft was not going to get away from
us,'' Michael Bidwill said. ``Everybody knew what the ramifications
were. It was time to play football. The two parties came together
and made an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a moment too soon, according to Wadsworth's new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who should benefit from the improved pass-rush that
Wadsworth can provide is the secondary, anchored by four-time Pro
Bowl starter Aeneas Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it will be like the difference between having the fire
department one block away and two miles away,'' said Williams, one
of the team's defensive captains. ``The airplane seemed to start
traveling a lot faster. There was a lighter load.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said all the hype and projections are now moot. Wadsworth
is a pro football player who has to make his mark on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least this stops the questions about whether he'll sign,''
Miller said. ``Hopefully he'll come in here and prove that he is
the best defensive lineman drafted in the '90s. I'm happy the guy
is here, but now he has to do his thing and help us win. There will
be no congratulations until the end of the season and we go to the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Tobin: ``This makes us a better team. We're in kind of a
unique situation here. Last week we signed (cornerback) J.B. Brown,
and we put him in the game after he'd practiced about seven snaps
with us. This week we're going to play a guy who hasn't even been
on the field with us. I guess this sets back coaching a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   But it advances the players' faith in ownership. Quarterback
Jake Plummer seemed to speak for the team on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just proves to a lot of guys that, even though this took
longer than we thought, the team is committed to winning,'' Plummer
said. ``It shows that the Cardinals will step up and take
responsibility and do what is right to help the team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
