r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTRONAUTS-AZR &LR;      09-06 1527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRONAUTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MERCURY ASTRONAUTS CHEER ON JOHN GLENN
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John, Scott, Wally, Gordo. Just four of them now. Alan died of
leukemia in July. Gus died in the fire aboard Apollo I, back in the
glory days. Deke died of cancer in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; They used to be seven _ Ameri ca's original astronauts, men who
strapped themselves into test planes over California's deserts and
then into Corvettes and rocket ships in Florida, always competing
to be the fastest, go the highest, be the best.
</P>
<P>
   They're in their 70s now and they haven't lost their famous
drive to compete. It's just that their lifelong contest between
``brothers,'' which is what they call each other, is played out in
more ordinary settings with less expensive equipment. They still
try to outrun, outski, outbike and outplay each other on tennis
courts, hills, tracks and golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   When NASA unveiled the seven heroes-to-be at a news conference
in April 1959, a reporter asked who would like to be first in
space. They all raised their hands. The competi tiveness and the
attention of an admiring world would be a part of their lives from
that moment on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid John has made us all famous again,'' said Scott
Carpenter, talking about himself and the other survivors, Gordon
``Gordo'' Cooper and Walter ``Wally'' Schirra. The Arizona Republic
recently talked to all of them about Sen. John Glenn's upcoming
return to space as well as their lives.
</P>
<P>
   While Glenn has been training in Houston for the second trip of
a lifetime, the others aren't exactly playing croquet. None is
retired. They are still striving in life, even though their places
in history are secure.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper wants to go to Mars. It's a dream he has held onto since
reading Buck Rogers comic strips as a kid. He's only 71, the
youngest of the original astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   Still at his high school weight, Cooper jogs and race-walks 15
miles a week, plays tennis twice a week and plays golf on nights
and weekends. He flies airplanes when ever he can, and is rearing
two teenagers _ his second batch.
</P>
<P>
   Though Carpenter, 73, doesn't have any plans to go back into
space, he is ferociously active.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skiing is the best way to fly and keep my feet on the
ground,'' he jokes. He also rides horses, plays tennis and golfs
regularly. He's working on his third book. &UR; All three of the former
astronauts say they weigh the same as when they were suiting-up for
space.
</P>
<P>
   Without the fanfare of going into zero atmosphere, they are
breaking new barriers now: those of age, of lifetime endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Although Carpenter believes older people may feel empowered by
Glenn's return to space, he hopes that young people will learn some
thing from it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep your mind alert and your body fit through
your whole life. John is a perfect exam ple of someone who has done
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The other former astronauts are, too.
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges Schirra, 75, de scribed having with Glenn at Alan
Shepard's funeral in July indicate that the old competitive juices
have been running strong _ even on a solemn day when they buried
one of their brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Schirra quietly jabbed Glenn: ``John,'' he said, ``why don't
they just send up Strom Thurmond if they want an old senator in
space?'' He then ribbed Glenn for taking the mission because he
needed the flight hours. Glenn had been in space only once. Schirra
had flown on Mercury, Gemini and Apollo missions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The astronauts meet at least a couple times a year. They ski at
Vail, Colo., where they go fast and work out hard. Each May in
Florida they distribute money to science and engineering students
from the As tronaut Scholarship Foundation they established.
</P>
<P>
   At one of those occasions three years ago, Glenn, then 74, told
them he was interested in going back up. He asked the others what
they thought about it. For a moment, Schirra thought, it sounded
like a rocking chair fantasy. He recalled telling Glenn, ``Oh,
John, grow up; get over this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Glenn had been considering it for some time. &UR; Flying in space
was important to him, and he finally saw an opening in the field of
aging research. After all, his body in the 1960s was one of the
most thor oughly documented human speci mens on Earth. If you
wanted to measure changes, here was a willing subject. He started
talking to re searchers on aging and to NASA.
</P>
<P>
   ``John told me about this dream, but I never really thought it
would happen,'' Carpenter told The Repub lic.
</P>
<P>
   But Carpenter, who has always had a deep friendship with Glenn,
is not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``John meets all the challenges he sees. Here's a chance to do
something that's a hell of a lot of fun, and to do some meaningful
science. It's the climax of his life spent in service to the
country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Would he go back up himself?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told John I'd be his backup again, but this time I'd make
sure something would happen to him so I'd get to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter's time in space, pilot ing the Aurora 7 spacecraft
through three revolutions of the Earth, gave him a deeply spiritual
connection with &UR; Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``From space, Earth is a lonely, isolated, fragile outpost in
the mid dle of nowhere. You don't fully appreciate that until you
see it from a distance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That moment of concern for the Earth led him to undersea
research after his astronaut service ended. With the Navy's Sealab
Program he helped transfer space technology to deep-sea studies. He
lived in a capsule on the sea floor for 30 days, and still helps
direct an ocean research institute in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Now he divides his time between New York City and Vail. He has
written two books about the ocean and is writing a family history
with one of his four grown children.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was one of the first to encourage Glenn to take the new
flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``An aging body in good shape can do just as much as a younger
body in good shape,'' he says. He thinks that the medical experts
consistently underestimate what people are physically capable of
achieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think it a matter of physical ability, never a
matter of age,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   He also recognizes that the Glenn flight might help him with his
own dream of going to Mars. For now, he works full time for his own
aerospace consulting firm, the Gal axy Group in Van Nuys, Calif.,
which is his big workshop for developing home energy systems and
new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the California coast near San Diego, Schirra lives
with his wife of 52 years in Rancho Santa Fe. Like Glenn, he is
still married to his original partner.
</P>
<P>
   After his astronaut days, Schirra served as CEO of a number of
businesses and as a board member of some large firms, including
Kimberly-Clark, maker of Kleenex and feminine-hygiene
products. &UR; Schirra flew in the Mercury, Gemini and Apollo programs,
and he thinks test pilots should be pilots, not passengers. He
isn't as excited about Glenn's coming mission as the other
astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be a strap hanger, like a subway rider,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Schirra would rather see Glenn at the helm if he's going to
bother going up. That's the only way he would consider going up
himself, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trained to be a test pilot. I wouldn't want to go on as
a passenger. I wouldn't want to leap in the back and hang on,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he understands why Glenn wants to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, too, would do what I could to get out of the U.S. Senate in
a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Ribbing aside, Schirra is proud of Glenn for going back up. He
thinks it will do wonders for NASA. All the former astronauts have
a pater nal concern for the space agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Glenn story reminds him of the old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``When was the last time an astronaut was on the cover of Time
and other news magazines?'' he asked. ``And what do you know about
any of the experiments aboard Mir? Who flew our last shuttle?''
</P>
<P>
   NASA confirms that media inter est in the upcoming Glenn flight
is surpassing all recent missions. The only comparable interest was
the post-Challenger launch of the space shuttle in September 1988,
and the first Hubble Telescope mission in December 1993, said Rob
Navias, a NASA spokesman in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fascination from a historical and a human interest
perspective,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, though the mission will showcase a wide range of experi
ments, it is being seen by many as an historical turning point in
how we think about older people. Old barriers are about to be
broken.
</P>
<P>
   And, again, it will be Glenn out in front.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always the one to be out there in front,'' Schirra said
with a laugh. ``That's John.''
</P>
<P>
   The surviving Mercury 7 astro nauts have been contracted by
major television networks to provide ex pert commentary Oct. 29
when Glenn goes back up.
</P>
<P>
   Last time it was Carpenter who watched the rocket rise in 1962
and said on behalf of a breathless world, ``Godspeed, John Glenn.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll likely say it again for us, one more time with feeling, on
the morning of Oct. 29. &QL; 
 &UR; Maureen West can be reached at 444-8167
 &UR; or maureen.west &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
