<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS HEAVE BIG SIGH OF RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, TEXAS - Wake the children.
</P>
<P>
   Call the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Our long nightmare is over.
</P>
<P>
   One day before the Cardinals' season opener, Andre Wadsworth
ended his 44-day holdout and agreed to a breathtaking contract that
left Bill Bidwill sucking oxygen from one of those little drop-down
masks on the team flight.
</P>
<P>
   The owner broke the news while en route to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentlemen, (``inhal''e) I'm pleased to announce we have signed
our No. 1 draft choice (``inhal''e) to a contract that will
``inhale'' pay him (``inhal''e)forty-(``inhal''e)-two (``inhale
inhale'' ``inhale'' ``inhal''e) MILLION dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals players let out a cheer.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson wept.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis kissed his line coach, Joe
Greene.
</P>
<P>
   You don't see such giddyness at 30,000 feet except maybe on a
weekend Southwest free-drink coupons flight to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plane felt lighter,'' Aeneas Williams said of the soaring
spirits. ``I thought we had dropped our luggage.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``had'' to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth wasn't going to sit out the season and turn down a $10
million bonus, the third largest offered a rookie in NFL history.
How would his agents explain ``that'' strategy to prospective
clients?
</P>
<P>
   Nor could the Cardinals allow their top pick _ whom draftniks
call Wadsworth the next Bruce Smith _ to get away.
</P>
<P>
   Management already had taken a public-relations flogging.
Editorialists expressed righteous outrage, much of it directed at
Bill Bidwill Jr., who nixed a deal last week. The voice of reason,
talk radio called for frontier justice.
</P>
<P>
   All the optimism and civic goodwill generated by the draft had
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals critics saw the impasse as the latest example of
front-office incompetence and a lack of commitment to winning.
</P>
<P>
   Players were upset. Coaches shook their heads. On Friday,
McGinnis said the only thing he could say about the prospect of
opening the season against the Cowboys without the 6-foot-3,
278-pound defensive end in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing. But he had to be thinking what everyone else was:
``This is'' ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides had to compromise. (Both did.) The Cardinals lost
what little leverage they had after Brad Ottis, who was scheduled
to start at left defensive end until Wadsworth was ready to move
in, fractured his foot and was lost for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Someone had to blink (The Cardinals did).
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth's $10.491 million signing bonus is the largest in club
history. His six-year deal includes the kind of monetary exchange
that usually involves a Brinks truck, pantyhose masks and automatic
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But thankfully, it's over. No more posturing. No more
negotiating in the media. No more talks about voidables and
escalators and other terminology that leaves most fans glassy-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, no more wild speculation. When I got the news
Saturday I was sitting alone on the grassy knoll pondering the
latest conspiracy theory.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you heard this one. The one about how Dallas owner Jerry
Jones asked Wadsworth's agents, who are Deion Sanders' agents, to
encourage their client to hold out until after the Cowboys game,
presumably as a personal favor.
</P>
<P>
   It's nonsense, of course. Both sides wanted to get this done.
They had to make this happen.
</P>
<P>
   And they did. Now that Wadsworth is a Cardinal, it is time, to
quote our president, to move on. If the guy is half the athlete
everyone says he is there is no doubt what the Cardinals must do
today.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about Wadsworth missing two-a-days. Never mind the fact
he is a rookie and hasn't memorized the playbook.
</P>
<P>
   For what this guy is making, here's what the team should do.
Introduce him to his teammates. Give him jersey No. 90. After a
pregame meal of T-bone steak (rare), present him a wallet-size
color photo of Troy Aikman and three words of instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go get him.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
