r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AZDEMS-AZR &LR;      09-06 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZDEMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA DEMOCRATS IN WEAKEST SPOT IN YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Arizona Democrats go to the polls Tuesday, they're in for a
severe case of ballot shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no Democratic candidates for a number of statewide
offices, nobody for legislative races. There's nothing,'' said
Phoenix attorney Tim Hogan, who was stunned recently when he opened
his sample Democratic primary ballot and found no reason to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really isn't anything to vote for in my district, so I
guess I've got to wonder what the point is.''
</P>
<P>
   His dismay reflects a growing concern over the fate of Arizona's
second-largest political party. The harsh reality is that the
Democratic Party is in its weakest position in years, and if it
suffers across-the-board losses in statewide races in November, it
could emerge powerless for a generation.
</P>
<P>
   The defection of former Democratic gubernatorial candidate Eddie
Basha, though temporary, is enough to dishearten even the most
hard-core party loyalists. But he was only the highest profile
Democrat to bail out, not the only one. Others, put off by the
Democrats' weak showing this year, did the same.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, expressing frustration with both parties, opted to
re-register as an independent, meaning he will sit out the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix political consultant Steve Tuttle registered as a
Republican after seeing a barren Democratic field in his north
Phoenix district.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really believe yourself to be an honest-to-God
Democrat, it is frustrating. You have to ask yourself, what the
hell are they doing?''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats such as Tuttle and Basha aren't giving up all hope.
After casting ballots for GOP friends on Tuesday, they plan to
re-register as Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But they may come back to a party _ should the Democrats' worst
nightmares materialize _ that's little more than a political speed
bump to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The state GOP is trying to sweep all major races in the Nov. 3
general election and seize control of the next redrawing of state
political boundaries, after the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   If they do that, the state Democratic Party will be even further
diminished and demoralized, and Republicans will rule over Arizona
politics for well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's at stake is whether we will be in the ballgame or not
in the next decade,'' said Melodee Jackson, the state Democratic
Party's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to live under lines drawn by the Republicans, we
might as well go and do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Corporation Commissioner Renz Jennings, the party's only
statewide officeholder, ``It's pretty important to have a two-party
state . . . and we're dangerously close to having a totally
Republican state.''
</P>
<P>
   He is retiring this year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the signs for Arizona Democrats are ominous.
</P>
<P>
   Party members who do go to the polls Tuesday will find few, if
any, contested races. Democrats didn't even bother to field
candidates for three statewide offices, treasurer, superintendent
of public instruction and mine inspector. The party's U.S. Senate
candidate, attorney Ed Ranger, has no political experience.
</P>
<P>
   In the governor's race, Republican Gov. Jane Hull has a
commanding lead over Democrat Paul Johnson in the polls, and she
has a huge advantage in fund-raising. Key Democrats, including
Basha, are expected after the primary to endorse Hull.
</P>
<P>
   In legislative races, the party is so disorganized it missed a
sure bet in District 3, a Democratic stronghold that includes the
Navajo Reservation. Because of a mix-up, Democrats failed to field
any House candidates in the district this year, giving Republicans
a rare opening. Both parties are fielding write-in candidates for
seats in the district.
</P>
<P>
   And former Democratic chairman Steve Owens, in his second bid to
unseat GOP Rep. J.D. Hayworth, gave his opponent a major opening
last week by saying he had invited President Clinton to help him in
the state's sprawling Congressional District 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's being politically tone deaf,'' said Hayworth, noting that
many other Democrats around the country are putting distance
between themselves and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not since (former Rep.) Karan English brought in (handgun
control advocate) Sarah Brady have we had such a fundamental
misreading of the constituency.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, though, see signs of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Because they have only a handful of contested primary contests,
the party's brightest lights have been able to conserve campaign
funds and avoid political blood-letting. Strategists point to
intraparty GOP warfare in the races for attorney general and
Arizona Corporation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though primary turnout may be low, there are many, many
pluses. We do not have John Kaites and Tom McGovern killing each
other,'' Jackson said, referring to the Republican candidates for
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Democrats' attorney general candidate, former U.S.
Attorney Janet Napolitano, may be the party's best hope for
avoiding an across-the-board defeat in statewide races this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also feel they have a chance, albeit slight, of
regaining parity with the GOP in the state Senate. If they can do
that, and avoid being crushed in statewide contests, Democratic
strategists say that the party's resurgence is possible. They point
to a projected large increase in the state's Hispanic population, a
traditionally Democratic group.
</P>
<P>
   Up until the 1980s, Democrats enjoyed a comfortable advantage in
statewide voter registration. Since then, Republicans have gained
an overwhelming edge in Maricopa County, the state's largest
county, and made significant inroads into the state's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   In Hayworth's large district, Republicans this year for the
first time have a slight voter registration advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman attributes the shift to a large influx of
Republicans to suburban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Californians who come here are coming from Orange County
and not Marin,'' he said. ``I think there is a growing conservative
majority in Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is Republican domination of the Legislature, the
state's congressional delegation, the executive branch, the
corporation commission and the Maricopa County Board of
Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some Democrats said they don't see hope for the
party's revival unless a dynamic leader emerges.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the party had many dominant figures, including
Gov. Bruce Babbitt, U.S. Rep. Morris Udall and Sen. Dennis
DeConcini.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until another Bruce Babbitt comes along to sort of
reinvigorate the party, it's kind of hard to imagine it coming
back,'' one prominent Arizona Democrat said. ``It literally is
going to take that.'' &QL; 
Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-8546 or at
michael.murphy(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
