A1442 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      09-06 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIGGER HITTER THAN BIG MAC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After four years on the Queens College baseball team, Albert
Kapikian had to face the fact that he'd never make it to the big
leagues; never stand in the batter's box at Yankee Stadium in his
hometown, the Bronx; never break the records of Ruth or Maris or
anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   It happens to most guys.
</P>
<P>
   You reach an age when you must come to terms with your abilities
_ or lack of them _ and move on. Kapikian understood this and
adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't hit more than 60 home runs a year, so he settled for
saving 600,000 lives a year.
</P>
<P>
   All of them under the age of 5.
</P>
<P>
   For this, Dr. Kapikian will receive no fat endorsement deals, no
multimillion-dollar signing bonuses, no standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   His face has never been on a magazine cover, playing card or box
of Wheaties.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, he wonders why a writer for a newspaper in Phoenix
would want to speak with an obscure research scientist in Bethesda,
Md.
</P>
<P>
   So I tell him.
</P>
<P>
   It's because he receives no fat endorsement deals, no
multimillion-dollar siging bonuses, no standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   It's because his face has never been on a magazine cover,
playing card or box of Wheaties.
</P>
<P>
   It's because kids all over America _ all over the world _ know
the name Mark McGwire and don't know the name Albert Kapikian.
</P>
<P>
   He laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm better at this, thankfully, than I was at baseball,'' he
says. &QL; 
PRODUCES A VACCINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After 25 years of work, Dr. Kapikian and scientists at the
National Institutes of Health, produced a vaccine against
rotavirus, an infection that kills hundreds of thousands of
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who work on research studies are like baseball
players,'' he says. ``We must think of it as a long season. Our
percentage of success is small. But the work is a joy. And, in a
way, it's getting paid for performing a hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Rotavirus is the leading cause of severe diarrhea among
children. Just about every boy and girl in every country, rich or
poor, contracts it sooner or later. In America, somewhere between
50,000 and 100,000 kids wind up in the hospital because of it. Few
of them die, however, because health care here is good.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, millions had died, and would continue to die without
people like Kapikian. I stumbled on his name in a brief wire
service story.
</P>
<P>
   He the son of Armenian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   His mother worked in a tie factory. His father was a photo
engraver. He got into research after medical school, thinking he'd
work in the field for only a short time. That was 40 years ago. &QL; 
`WOULDN'T TRADE MY LIFE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't trade my life for anything,'' he says. ``I have a
wonderful family. I've worked with dedicated, talented people. And
now, this vaccine could have a major impact on a part of the world
where children suffer most. That would mean everything to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug company Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories worked with
Kapikian's group and will produce the vaccine. Getting it to
children will require working with the World Health Organization
and others. It's expensive, complicated, political.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it will happen,`` Kapikian says. ``It must.''
</P>
<P>
   Generations from now, children reading about the exploits of the
home-run king McGwire may owe their existence to Kapikian, a
one-time prospect out of Queens College.
</P>
<P>
   But they won't know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our field has many other rewards,'' he says. ``I think of the
children who'll get to live to adulthood, all the potential they
possess and what they may accomplish with their lives. There's
plenty of satisfaction in that. More than I could dream of.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's something to think about next time they're trying to
pick a face for a Wheaties box:
</P>
<P>
   Guys like Mark McGwire provide the home runs. Guys like Albert
Kapikian provide the McGwires. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
