<SLUG> BC-LA-SWISSAIR-VICTIM-1stLd-Writethru-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY, FRIENDS RECALL SWISSAIR CRASH VICTIM'S ZEST FOR LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Fixing ambiguous attribution in 11th graf. Other minor fixes made
throughout.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ernest Thompson was eagerly bound for another leg
of his lifetime odyssey to absorb his family heritage in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, the resident of suburban Chatsworth wound up among
the 229 killed aboard Swissair's ill-fated Flight 111 off the Nova
Scotia coast Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The retired Rocketdyne engineer's death seems unfair, his
grieving family and friends said Saturday as they sifted through
photographs and meaningful passages by Thompson, an avid reader and
passionate writer.
</P>
<P>
   Even at age 70, he still had a passion to learn more about his
wife of 45 years and four grown children, whose hands he would
proudly clasp while walking down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved life and everything that went with it. He was
gregarious, is another word that comes to mind,'' said Guy Ervin
III, who worked with Thompson for 25 years at Rocketdyne and last
saw him a week before the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a little numb. It just doesn't seem fair. There he
was, off on another one of his adventures. What were (the
passengers) thinking? It's just frightening,'' Ervin said at his
Chatsworth home Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At least twice a week, Thompson attended ballroom and folk
dancing classes with his wife, who learned of the fatal crash while
attending an Armenian folk dance Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He would frequently serenade his wife, who works as an office
administrator at a property management company, to encourage her
into retiring so that they could spend the rest of their lives
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would sing the song `I Wanna Dance With You' to me and say,
I want you to retire 'cause I want to dance with you,'' his widow,
Mary, said Saturday, pulling from her wallet a palm-size
anniversary card from her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``To 30 years of thick and thin, better and worse, happiness,
trials and tribulations, warmth, love _ in other words to life _
shared with a wonderful woman as dear to me today as the day we
married, Ernie,'' his message read.
</P>
<P>
   ``We nicknamed him `Earnest Ernest.' That was him,'' Ervin said.
``He always paid close attention to things going on and was always
eager to listen to what people had to say. Of course, you had to
listen to him because he had things to say, too. That was his
quality, the importance of being earnest, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Oswego, N.Y., Thompson was an Army paratrooper before
graduating from Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in Troy, N.Y. He
later worked as an engineer for Pratt &AMP; Whitney Aircraft in Windsor
Locks, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956 he moved to suburban Canoga Park, working in
aeronautics. In 1961 he became a welding engineer at Rocketdyne,
where he worked for 26 years, assigned to projects requiring
special welding techniques, such as in the building of rocket
engines and the space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Though retired for more than 10 years, Thompson was routinely
called back as a consultant at Rocketdyne's Santa Susana Energy
Technology Engineering Center _ even as recently as two weeks ago
to help with a ``fast breeder'' nuclear reactor project for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had special knowledge that nobody else did,'' Ervin said,
calling Thompson a meticulous worker who always had stories to tell
of his travels.
</P>
<P>
   His fascination with Greece stemmed from his Greek father, said
his widow. ``He was constantly learning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   His trip would have included spending three weeks with an elder
hostel group touring the antiquities of Greece, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sorry that I wasn't going with him. I guess it wasn't
meant for me to go,'' his widow said Saturday at their Chatsworth
home.
</P>
<P>
   She added that the Saturday before he traveled, she was
concerned about his trip, worried about the recent bombings of the
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that I was not comfortable with him going on this
trip,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, the family instead focused on Thompson's love of
life.
</P>
<P>
   When away from his consulting work, Thompson immersed himself in
his family _ always the one to wait around at his children's new
homes for utility workers to show up, or to ``cat-sit'' for a
vacationing family member.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was interested and interesting,'' said one of Thompson's
daughters, Kathy, 42, at the family home Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no task too big if his children needed something,''
added son Stephen, 39, of Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   His other surviving family members include daughter Kim
Thompson-Janecke, 44, of Seattle and son David, 36, of Simi Valley
in neighboring Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Hills labor law attorney Jana DeMeire, 39, also was
among the passengers on the MD-11 jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   DeMeire had left for a two-week vacation in Greece, said her
father, Frank DeMeire, 65, who had come from his home in Costa Rica
to watch his daughter's cats while she was away.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, he said, had planned to travel with her, but missed
a connecting flight in New York.
</P>
<P>
   DeMeire said that on the day before his daughter left, she spoke
to him by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wished her a bon voyage,'' he said. ``I was going to meet
her when she got back. We were very close.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMeire said his daughter was ``very outgoing, very friendly,
had lots of friends.'' She also volunteered at the Venice Family
Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just looked forward to seeing me when she got back,'' said
her father, who described what he has been going through since the
crash as ``hell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
