<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1509 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     09-06 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Sept. 13.)  
 (HLW)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SPIN CYCLE: HOW THE WHITE HOUSE AND THE MEDIA MANIPULATE THE
NEWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Howard Kurtz. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the bad marriage between President Clinton's
spinmeisters and a deeply mistrustful press corps, the media
reporter for The Washington Post shows how both sides connive to
control and package the news. The book, which features a new
chapter on the Lewinsky relationship, is ``a revealing, highly
detailed insider account,'' Wendy Kaminer wrote here earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAKING WAVES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Mario Vargas Llosa. Edited by John King. Penguin, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   In a collection of essays written over a 30-year period, the
Peruvian author reveals an enduring fascination with history and
politics, as well as a desire to balance social justice and
individual freedom, employing models from Sartre to Faulkner to
Isaiah Berlin. Last year in the Book Review, Jay Parini called this
``a diverse and representative volume that allows us, for the first
time, to trace this enigmatic, often brilliant writer's ...
intellectual journey.''  &UR; WHO KILLED PALOMINO MOLERO? &LR; 
(Noonday/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $11), one of two novels by Vargas
Llosa that have recently been restored to print, is a detective
story about the murder of a singer and a meditation on the elusive
nature of truth, love and evil. In 1987 our reviewer, Richard
Lourie, called the writing ``spare, rich and cruelly beautiful.''
The same publisher has reissued  &UR; THE REAL LIFE OF ALEJANDRO MAYTA &LR; 
($13), which interweaves two narratives: that of the title
character, a guerrilla who leads a failed uprising in the Peruvian
mountains, and that of the novelist-narrator, who struggles to
reconstruct Mayta's life and times. ``It is the reader in the end
who 'writes' the story, piecing it together from all the lies and
contradictions, the unreliable testimony and historical `data'''
Robert Coover wrote here in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEX ON THE BRAIN: THE BIOLOGICAL DIFFERENCES BETWEEN MEN AND
WOMEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Deborah Blum. Penguin, $13.95.
</P>
<P>
   Are women sentenced to be nurturing and passive? Are men doomed
to be aggressive? Judging from the physiological and behavioral
research into such loaded questions, our actions appear to be
driven in surprising ways by both biology and culture. ``Blum
manages the tricky art of good science reporting'' and writes
''clearly and accessibly,'' Ann Finkbeiner said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY LIFE, STARRING DARA FALCON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ann Beattie. Vintage Contemporaries, $13.
</P>
<P>
   This novel's narrator, a naive housewife who is both passive and
sympathetic, is victimized in ways large and small by a would-be
actress who blows into her New Hampshire town. Beattie ``is as good
at acute observation as she ever was,'' Jim Shepard wrote here in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DIVING BELL AND THE BUTTERFLY: A MEMOIR OF LIFE IN DEATH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jean-Dominique Bauby. Vintage International, $11.
</P>
<P>
   A French magazine editor, after suffering a major stroke at the
age of 43, was left totally alert but unable to move anything but
his left eyelid, a condition that nonetheless allowed him to write
this lyrical book by means of an alphabetical code. ``The author
displays a writerly control equal to his honesty,'' our reviewer,
Thomas Mallon, said last year.  &UR; LOOK UP FOR YES &LR; , by Julia Tavalaro
and Richard Tayson (Penguin, $12.95), is another vivid survival
story by a stroke victim, in this case a Long Island woman who
awakens paralyzed in an unfamiliar hospital after a seven-month
coma. Tavalaro is ``endowed with extraordinary powers of memory and
description,'' Paula Friedman said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GUT SYMMETRIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jeanette Winterson. Vintage International, $12.
</P>
<P>
   This novel, whose title refers to both the human body and the
grand unified theory pursued by physicists, unfolds in the minds of
its three main characters: a Princeton scientist, his longtime wife
and a woman physicist who becomes romantically involved with both.
Last year our reviewer, Bruce Bawer, admired the author's ``fresh,
vivid way of putting things.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FIRST MODERNS: PROFILES IN THE ORIGINS OF TWENTIETH-CENTURY
THOUGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By William R. Everdell. University of Chicago, $16.
</P>
<P>
   The author locates the roots of modernism in discontinuity, a
fractured worldview that rejects smoothness as illusory and began
percolating through math, physics and painting in the late 19th
century. Everdell ``has himself recombined the parts of our era's
intellectual history in new and startling ways,'' Hugh Kenner said
here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONE OF US &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By David Freeman. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $11.95.
</P>
<P>
   During the last days of British rule in Egypt, an ambassador
tries to turn the young King Farouk into a proper Englishman, a
misguided plan that results in cuckoldry and revenge. In this
historical novel of clashing cultures, ``Freeman has splendidly
re-created a fading colonial world,'' Jonathan Wilson wrote here
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE LATE THE SWEET BIRDS SANG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Kate Wilhelm. Orb/Tom Doherty, $13.95.
</P>
<P>
   In this science fiction tale, the sterile survivors of a global
environmental catastrophe turn to mass cloning, but the clones'
communal upbringing deprives them of imagination and creativity.
The author's ``cautionary message comes through loud and clear,''
Gerald Jonas said here in 1976.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
