<P>
   NIRELAND-DISARM (Dublin) _ Gerry Adams, the leader of the
political wing of the Irish Republican Army, said on Sunday that he
could not guarantee that the IRA would agree to disarm during the
negotiations in the new Northern Ireland Assembly. By James F.
Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH-FLOODS (Chor Shibola) _ More than 20 million
Bangladeshis have had their homes swamped by monsoon-season
flooding, that, so far, has lasted almost two months, twice as long
as any other recorded. The waters have inundated more than half of
the country, killed more than 520 people, shut down many roads,
damaged more than 4,000 schools, wiped out a big chunk of the main
rice crop; and now threaten to bring deadly diarrhea and other
diseases. The prime minister of Bangladesh, Sheik Hasina Wazed, has
pleaded for international relief. By Celia S. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-IRAN-ASSESS (Cairo, Egypt) _ Analysis: the roots of the
conflict between the Taliban and Iran. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RDP (Moscow) _ What do the Communists want? Plus the
day's developments. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ North Korea changes its constitution
to name the late Kim Il Sung an eternal president. By Nicholas D.
Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-POLITICS (Ushuaia) _ On Graciela Fernandez Meijilde,
one of the leading presidential candidates, whose son was among the
`disappeared.'
</P>
