</P>
<P>
   CROWDED-UNIVERSITIES (Undated) _ Large public universities
across America are seeing enrollments surge to unexpected heights
this year, forcing them to scramble to find beds for students.
Colleges usually accept more students than they expect to attend,
to ensure dorms and classrooms seats are full. But this year, the
public institutions were caught by surprise: more students took the
admission offer. By Jo Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-UNREST (Undated) _ With the walkouts at Northwest, GM,
Bell Atlantic and U S West, this summer has seen the largest number
of major strikes in years, pointing to a new aggressiveness on the
part of unions at a time of tight labor markets and booming
corporate profits. But just when unions, after years of declining
real wages, are finally winning contracts that keep ahead of
inflation, labor leaders fear that the slowing economy and swooning
stock market will knock their wage gains down a few notches. By
Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
