   TECH-STOCK-STARTUPS (Undated) _ How the stock-market plunge,
which has hit technology stocks especially hard, has altered the
entreprenurial ecosystem for high-tech start-up companies. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUIT (Undated) _ A look at the legal cases that
Microsoft and the government are likely to present, based on their
witness lists. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-YACHT (Menlo Park, Calif.) _ Jim Clark, founder of
Silicon Graphics and Netscape, has been busy building a
computer-controlled yacht, whose technology may yield yet another
start-up company. By Evantheia Schibstead.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-SUITS (Undated) _ So far, software companies are able to
sidestep lawsuits involving the Year 2000 bug, because no damage
has yet occurred. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   PCORDER-INGRAM (Undated) _ PC Order, a provider of technology
for selling computers online, plans to announce a deal with Ingram.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Among high-tech companies internal
mailing lists are de rigeuer. They serve a number of purposes in
the Silicon Valley culture, none more important than a free-for-all
forum in which employees can vent anger and frustration with their
own company -- and often, its management. Such was the nature of
Bad Attitude and Very Bad Attitude, two mailing lists for Netscape
employees. But now that Microsoft is demanding access to the
postings as evidence in its antitrust case, companies are having
second thoughts about allowing open criticism that can later be
used against them in court. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
