<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-TRENDS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS XEROX RUNNING THE NETWORKS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are only so many original ideas out there, right? Then
again, maybe the big shots have decided to put the same show on the
air twice, at different times and on different networks, as a
service to harried consumers. (Sure. And the different titles and
different casts are just a necessary means of getting around some
union red tape.) Thus, on the fall schedule we have:
</P>
<P>
   A family comedy about an independent woman juggling her job
(barmaid), her dreams (finding a better job) and her
responsibilities (an oddball family). On NBC it's called ``Jesse,''
with Christina Applegate (``Married . . . With Children'') as a
spunky single mom. On Fox it's ``Costello,'' with comedian Sue
Costello as a spunky single ma'am.
</P>
<P>
   A family comedy about a little kid living with two bachelors. On
ABC it's ``Brother's Keeper'' (the boy is 8; the older guys are his
dad and uncle). On UPN it's ``Guys Like Us'' (the boy is 6; the
older guys are his brother and the brother's roommate). For good
measure, there's also ``Holding the Baby'' on Fox, in which an
infant lives with his father and uncle.
</P>
<P>
   The American Dream as seen by an African American family moving
to the white suburbs. On ABC it's ``The Hughleys.'' On Fox it's
``Living in Captivity.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, a ``Twin Peaks'' Update
</P>
<P>
   If cherry pie and a good cuppa joe start turning up in scripts
this fall, the ``Twin Peaks'' TV renaissance will be virtually
complete, if not a little unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   Lara Flynn Boyle started it last season when she joined ``The
Practice'' as a hard prosecutor with a soft spot for Dylan
McDermott. Of course, ``Peaks'' fans will always know her as Donna
Hayward, Laura Palmer's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   This season, five more people with close ties to the ``Peaks''
phenomenon of the early '90s are back with TV series. It could have
been six, but Fox said ixnay to a new version of ``The Invisible
Man'' featuring Kyle MacLachlan (Agent Dale Cooper). The ``Peaks''
rundown:
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Lee _ Laura Palmer herself _ plays a physician in ``L.A.
Doctors'' on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Madchen Amick, formerly the abused waitress, Shelly Johnson, is
one of Mr. Roarke's mysterious assistants on ABC's remake of
``Fantasy Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherilynn Fenn, the sexy Audrey Horne, is now a recovering
alcoholic on Showtime's new series, ``Rude Awakening,'' which
premiered last month.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Frost, a co-creator of ``Twin Peaks,'' has a new series on
CBS _ ``Buddy Faro'' _ with Dennis Farina playing a private eye.
</P>
<P>
   Moira Kelly, who played Boyle's character, Donna Hayward, in the
1992 film, ``Twin Peaks: Fire Walk With Me,'' is, like Boyle,
playing a prosecuting attorney _ in CBS's ``To Have and To Hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, Please
</P>
<P>
   The next Chuck Norris?
</P>
<P>
   Gotta be the well-padded Sammo Hung, whose ``Martial Law''
precedes Norris' ``Walker, Texas Ranger'' on Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   The next almost perfect match?
</P>
<P>
   A tossup: Debra Messing and Eric McCormack of ``Will &AMP; Grace'';
Paula Marshall and Jeremy Piven of ``Cupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The next laughingstock?
</P>
<P>
   Neck and neck between ``The Army Show'' or ``The Secret Diary of
Desmond Pfeiffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Best reason for a title change
</P>
<P>
   ``That '70s Show'' was going to be ``Teenage Wasteland,'' but
producer Terry Turner says Pete Townshend of The Who wouldn't give
his permission. The producers toyed with ``Reelin' in the Years,''
then settled on ``Feelin' Alright,'' but focus-group participants
who liked the concept kept calling it ``That '70s Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' Turner said, ``we just gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   Second-best reason for a title change
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. Doctors'' was originally going to be ``L.A. Docs.'' But
producer Mark Johnson said a change was made to avoid any
misconception that the series was about hunky stevedores on the
wharves at San Pedro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
