<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-TV-MCBEAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND THE CHIEFTAINS WILL DO THE MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of writers in Hollywood now wish ``Ally McBeal'' had
sprung from their laptops, but most have a legitimate excuse. They
were busy working on Irish-themed series for the coming season when
Ally emerged from David E. Kelley's prolific shop.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised, however, if the following TV treatments pop
up soon as the febrile honchos at the networks and the studios try
to play catch-up _ and cash in on two trends at once.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Alley McReal'': Searching for truer grit, MTV merges ``The
Real World'' with ``Road Rules'' to focus on a dozen Gen-X'ers
living out of Dumpsters in a seedy part of Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Bali McKneel'': An inner-city Catholic priest moves his
parish to a diocese across the international date line so his
Saturday night show on ABC can air on Sunday and attract a larger
audience.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cali McHeal'': Hector Elizondo plays a courageous physician
who, with the help of the IRA, infiltrates the Colombian drug
cartel for no particular reason in this lighthearted CBS spinoff of
``Chicago Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Deli McDeal'': From NBC Studios comes this comedy about a
high-powered theatrical agent who won't sign new clients until
they've shared a corned-beef sandwich with her.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Finale McReel'': American Movie Classics takes a look at the
endings of the best-loved Irish-themed films of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Galley McVeal'': PBS introduces a Saturday cooking show
devoted exclusively to dishes incorporating the meat of calves
raised on Irish whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Rally McWheel'': Fox tracks down obscure footage of the
wackiest crashes from the Irish road-racing circuit.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Sally McField'': A&AMP;E aims to snare some unsuspecting viewers
with this coyly titled installment of ``Biography,'' slated to air
around St. Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Tamale McPeal'': Pepsi underwrites a syndicated series based
on Hemingway's ``For Whom the Bell Tolls,'' shot on location inside
Taco Bells around the world.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Valley McMeal'': Like, three teenagers get work at, like, a
burger place in, like, Southern California. Starring, like,
whoever's been in the latest horror film. On The WB.
</P>
<P>
   Getting out of the city
</P>
<P>
   No big surprise that the Los Angeles/New York axis continues to
dominate when creators are situating their new series. (Boston,
Chicago and San Francisco tend to serve as the most creative
alternatives.) After all, writers write what they know _ and what's
least expensive to shoot _ and not too many of them live in Des
Moines.
</P>
<P>
   So, bonus points to these five new shows for hauling out the
atlas and venturing beyond Hohum, U.S.A., even if a couple of the
places are fictional.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Guys Like Us'' (UPN). Can Cleveland be cool enough to
accommodate Drew Carey and former MTV game-show host Chris
Hardwick?
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Legacy'' (UPN). Set in and around Lexington, Ky., this
period piece (late 1800s) is actually shot in Virginia. But, in an
industry where North Carolina can sub for Massachusetts (``Dawson's
Creek''), it's close enough.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``That '70s Show'' (Fox). ``Laverne &AMP; Shirley'' was set in
Milwaukee in the '70s. Now comes this series, set in fictional
Point Place, Wis. Must be the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Maggie Winters'' (CBS). Faith Ford played a Southerner in
D.C. for a decade on ``Murphy Brown,'' so she didn't want this
coming-home comedy to make her another Daughter of the Confederacy.
They settled on Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Wind on Water'' (NBC). True, ``Magnum'' and ``Five-O'' did
the Hawaii thing, but they never strayed far from Honolulu. This Bo
Derek vehicle, while it may lack traction, manages to bounce all
over the geographically blessed Big Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
