<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1569 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FALL-MONDAY-SPI &LR;      09-06 1872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-MONDAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW THIS FALL ON MONDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a look at the new TV shows on Monday this fall. Check
local listings for times, channels.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer
</P>
<P>
   UPN
</P>
<P>
   The people behind this show were wise to create a gimmick _
namely, that the ``p'' in Pfeiffer is not silent _ just so critics
might have something to write about. The show itself isn't worth a
lot of ink.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, ironically, it's a hoot. For one thing, there aren't
many comedies set during the Lincoln administration. And who knew
that Lincoln's butler was his closest confidant? In execution,
though, ``Desmond Pfeiffer'' is just another White House scandal
awaiting prosecution, or at least an apology. The crime: using the
Oval Office and the Lincoln bedroom for questionable comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The producers and the network have been invoking the name Monty
Python in describing the sort of modern-day satire they're
attempting here. It's good to have lofty goals, but such talk does
a grievous disservice to the brave comedy of the Python troupe.
</P>
<P>
   Chi McBride (``The John Larroquette Show'') and Dann Florek
(``L.A. Law,'' ``Law &AMP; Order'') probably thought they were getting
into something fresh and distinctive with ``Desmond Pfeiffer.''
Turns out they're up to their armpits in it. Bottom line:
Puh-feiffer isn't puh-funny.
</P>
<P>
   _ The King of Queens
</P>
<P>
   CBS
</P>
<P>
   You may have already seen _ and rejected _ this show. ABC had a
midseason entry earlier this year titled ``That's Life.'' The
premise was identical: Working-class dude finally gets his ``guy
sanctuary,'' complete with big-screen TV, only to have some
unfortunate relatives move in and disrupt his idea of nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   Leah Remini (``Fired Up'') and Kevin James (``Everybody Loves
Raymond'') make ``The King of Queens'' a bit more engaging than
``That's Life,'' but not so appealing as to cause one to alter
one's viewing habits. Indeed, an inexplicable cast change after the
pilot was shot may make it even less engaging. Jack Carter,
perfectly acceptable as the father of Remini's character, Carrie
Heffernan, was jettisoned in favor of Jerry Stiller (``Seinfeld'').
</P>
<P>
   Carter's scenes have now been reshot with Stiller, but to what
advantage? With ``Seinfeld'' reruns on every day, we already see
plenty of George Costanza's annoying father.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hyperion Bay
</P>
<P>
   The WB
</P>
<P>
   This slick relationship drama might not seem to be the logical
stablemate for ``7th Heaven,'' but those programmers at The WB are
pretty cagey. ``Hyperion Bay'' is nothing more than the parable of
the prodigal son, updated for Windows 98. What better to follow a
show about a minister's family?
</P>
<P>
   Mark-Paul Gosselaar, who had a mini-career as the hunky blond
heartthrob, Zack Morris, on ``Saved by the Bell'' and ``Saved by
the Bell: The College Years,'' goes the dark-haired route as the
star of his first prime-time series. Gosselaar is the prodigal son,
Dennis Sweeny, a geeky kid who left the decaying seaside town of
Hyperion, Calif., in a beater Honda and returns in a Mercedes
drop-top with a drop-dead girlfriend (Sydney Penny). He's back in
town to open and manage a new division of the software company that
has made him rich and powerful, and he is the great hope of
Hyperion's failing economy.
</P>
<P>
   The town is happy to see him, save for older brother Nick (Dylan
Neal). Nick used to be the star of the family _ great athlete,
perfect marriage _ and he's the one who stayed behind to work in
their father's construction business, Sweeny &AMP; Son.
</P>
<P>
   Nick's resentment of Dennis sets up the necessary conflict in
this reasonably well-crafted drama, but it can't possibly sustai a
season unless ``Hyperion Bay'' aspires to becoming a daytime soap.
Another disadvantage: ``Hyperion Bay'' goes up against ``Ally
McBeal,'' ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' and, in most parts of the
country, ``Monday Night Football.'' The WB is accustomed to small,
cultish audiences, but the audience for this one might fit into
Dennis Sweeny's Mercedes coupe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Conrad Bloom
</P>
<P>
   NBC
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Bloom is one of the last unmarried nice guys in New York
City, so it follows that women are flocking to him like CNBC
pundits to a camera.
</P>
<P>
   But not for reasons you might imagine. Conrad is a guy who can't
say no, and so the women in his life _ his boss, his co-worker, his
sister, his ex-girlfriend and his mom _ are happy to take
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot episode, Mark Feuerstein (``Fired Up'') plays
Conrad with just enough backbone to keep him upright, allowing
Linda Lavin to steal the show as his recently widowed mother,
Florie. With equal measures honey and vinegar, Lavin lays claim to
the best Jewish mother role in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Feuerstein is pleasant enough as a put-upon ad copywriter, but
``Conrad Bloom'' has the look and feel of so many other NBC
comedies of recent vintage that, if it were tossed into a blender
with its two Monday night bookends _ ``Suddenly Susan'' and
``Caroline in the City'' _ the viewer probably wouldn't see much
difference in the end result.
</P>
<P>
   _ Guys Like Us
</P>
<P>
   UPN
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was Jenny McCarthy. This year, it's Chris
Hardwick's turn. Who knew that the MTV game show, ``Singled Out,''
was such a launching pad to sitcom mediocrity?
</P>
<P>
   Hardwick plays Sean Barker, a musician whose layabout bachelor
lifestyle is seriously threatened when his roommate's 6-year-old
brother moves in with them. As always happens in these shows, the
youngster _ Maestro Harrell in this case _ is cuter than the latest
Beanie Baby. And, as UPN sitcoms go, this one is a slight
improvement over its many embarrassing predecessors. But, while
imparting some valuable information _ example: The words to
``Amazing Grace'' fit perfectly to the theme song from of
``Gilligan's Island'' _ this is still a very average entrant on a
very crowded schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Hardwick's overacting is tempered somewhat by Bumper Robinson's
less frantic portrayal of roommate Jared Harris, a smooth-talking
ladies' man, but it's hard to imagine making a second date with
``Guys Like Us.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DiResta
</P>
<P>
   UPN
</P>
<P>
   John DiResta and Leila Kenzle have that warm-and-bubbly kind of
chemistry that can make all the difference in a TV show. It seems
they genuinely like each other, or maybe they're just fabulous
actors. Either way, it well serves a comedy that is otherwise
unremarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``DiResta'' is based on DiResta's 12 years as a New York City
subway cop, an experience he has already milked as a stand-up comic
and as the star of his own off-Broadway show, ``BEAT, A Subway
Cop's Comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind DiResta's tough-guy exterior is a real softie, both on
the job (New York's squalid subway tunnels) and at home (a rented
house in Queens). Kenzle decided to leave ``Mad About You'' to play
DiResta's headstrong wife, Kate, who is usually right about most
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``DiResta'' is going for the same ``Honeymooners'' feel that its
time-slot competitor, ``The King of Queens,'' is seeking.
``DiResta'' comes a little closer, possibly because John DiResta
looks a little like Jackie Gleason, possibly because DiResta and
Kenzle make a nice TV couple.
</P>
<P>
   _ Will &AMP; Grace
</P>
<P>
   NBC
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, Debra Messing is going to hit it big. Casting
directors love those wide-set eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Stage experience doesn't hurt, either. From a pre-Broadway
workshop of ``Angels in America: Perestroika'' to a Seattle
appearance in ``The Importance of Being Earnest'' (Intiman, 1993),
Messing's resume has gotten her steady work in TV, including
recurring roles on ``NYPD Blue'' and ``Seinfeld,'' two seasons on
``Ned &AMP; Stacey'' and a well-received though short-lived stint as a
scientist on last season's ``Prey.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether ``Will &AMP; Grace'' is the vehicle that carries Messing to,
say, the Helen Hunt stratum is anybody's guess. But ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' is certainly one of the more polished comedies emerging
from the studio factories this fall. Some will label it
controversial because one of the principal characters is
homosexual. Others will be annoyed that the show doesn't wear the
homosexuality issue on its sleeve the way ``Ellen'' did in its last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Messing's character, Grace, isn't the gay one. That would be
Will, played smartly _ and not stereotypically _ by Eric McCormack.
Will and Grace are clearly soulmates, both looking for love, and
both aware that romance between them, despite their perfect
chemistry, isn't an option. If for no other reason than the
opportunity to explore a male-female relationship that doesn't
hinge on their ending up in the sack, ``Will &AMP; Grace'' looks like a
refreshing new TV comedy.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Brian Benben Show
</P>
<P>
   CBS
</P>
<P>
   In the HBO comedy series ``Dream On,'' Brian Benben played to
small but extremely devoted audiences. CBS is banking on that
loyalty by using Benben's unusual surname in the title of his new
show.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like a little pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what ``The Brian Benben Show'' is all about. Benben
plays a competent Los Angeles news anchor who gets bounced down to
feature reporter in favor of a new Ken-and-Barbie anchor team.
Benben wants his old job back, and he uses every trick he knows to
get back to the top in the high-anxiety world of TV news.
</P>
<P>
   Benben goes more for laughs than for dead-on realism, and he
succeeds some of the time in the pilot episode. The rest of the
pilot, however, has that unnatural, forced feeling. Kind of like a
bad TV newscast.
</P>
<P>
   _ L.A. Doctors
</P>
<P>
   CBS
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent series (``EZ Streets''), Ken Olin played a
troubled cop with a mysterious dark side. In ``L.A. Doctors,''
Olin's character, Roger Cattan, isn't without attitude, but as an
idealistic physician dismayed by the red tape of HMOs and managed
care, he is definitely painted several shades lighter.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers expecting a hospital show in the manner of ``ER'' and
``Chicago Hope'' may be disappointed. ``L.A. Doctors'' has the same
stylish appeal as ``L.A. Law,'' combining breezy banter with stormy
issues in an office setting.
</P>
<P>
   Olin is joined by Matt Craven, Rick Roberts and Sheryl Lee in
trying to practice medicine the way Hippocrates intended. The main
problem with the pilot episode is a serious case of goshdarn
earnestness. Being idealistic is fine; being unrealistic is
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   RETURNING MONDAY SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal''
</P>
<P>
   ``Caroline in the City''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cosby''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dateline NBC''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Loves Raymond''
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie''
</P>
<P>
   ``Melrose Place''
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday Night Football''
</P>
<P>
   ``7th Heaven''
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly Susan''
</P>
<P>
   EXISTING SHOWS MOVING FROM MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   ``America's Funniest Home Videos'' to Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Personal'' to Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Boat: The Next Wave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice'' to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY SHOWS GONE FOR GOOD
</P>
<P>
   ``Brooklyn South''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Closer''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cybill''
</P>
<P>
   ``Damon''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fired Up''
</P>
<P>
   ``George &AMP; Leo''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good News''
</P>
<P>
   ``House Rules''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the House''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly Kelly''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Naked Truth''
</P>
<P>
   ``Push''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sparks''
</P>
<P>
   ``Style &AMP; Substance''
</P>
<P>
   ``Timecop''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
