   MICROSOFT-SUIT (Undated) _ A look at the legal cases that
Microsoft and the government are likely to present, based on their
witness lists. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-PAPER-MEDIA (Undated) _ Ralph Cipriano, a reporter, filed
a libel suit against The Philadelphia Inquirer after the editor,
Robert Rosenthal, publicly questioned the objectivity and value of
Cipriano's reporting on the Archdiocese of Philadelphia. Cipriano's
lawyer is James Beasley Sr., who has already won $40 million in
jury verdicts against the newspaper. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Ralph Cipriano is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``f'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are tonight's other regular features:
</P>
<P>
   TECH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Mailing lists serve a number of purposes
in the Silicon Valley culture, none more important than a
free-for-all forum in which employees can vent anger and
frustration with their own company. Such was the nature of Bad
Attitude and Very Bad Attitude, two mailing lists for Netscape
employees. But now that Microsoft is demanding access to the
postings as evidence in its antitrust case, companies are having
second thoughts about allowing open criticism that can later be
used against them in court. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news
file.)
