<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-TUESDAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW THIS FALL ON TUESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a look at the new TV shows on Tuesday this fall. Check
local listings for times, channels.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Hughleys
</P>
<P>
   ABC
</P>
<P>
   The Hughleys are pursuing the dream, which still comes with a
house in the suburbs. For Darryl Hughley, however, it might be a
nightmare on Elm Street.
</P>
<P>
   Hughley, played by comedian D.L. Hughley, is a successful
businessman with a nice family. He's not a bad guy, but he can be a
little chippy at times, quick to question the most innocent
intentions because he's a black person in a white neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl's wife, Yvonne (Elise Neal), is the diplomat who smooths
things over, but Darryl is going to have to come around one of
these days, or all the neighbors will be talking about him, but not
necessarily to him.
</P>
<P>
   Of two new sitcoms with nearly identical premises (the other is
``Living in Captivity'' on Fox), ``The Hughleys'' may have the
edge, because it's edgier. Maybe it's that Chris Rock is one of the
executive producers. Maybe it's that the neighbors aren't made out
to be idiots.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, it's pronounced HYOO-gleez, not HYOO-leez.
</P>
<P>
   _ Costello
</P>
<P>
   Fox
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of those who might think Costello is Italian instead of
Irish, the producers changed the name of Sue Costello's character
to Sue Murphy for this working-class comedy set in South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, though. Sue Costello is Irish from Southie. If
she were Italian, she'd live in the North End.
</P>
<P>
   Costello could light an entire city with her energy. She's
bright, funny, and fun to be with. Some of that comes across in the
pilot of ``Costello,'' but not all of it.
</P>
<P>
   It may be the curse of the comedian as actor. Some are able to
pull it off. Others never quite get it. Or it could be that the
writing isn't capturing Costello's true nature.
</P>
<P>
   And naming the show ``Costello,'' as if she's as well known as,
say, Bill Cosby, is a bit much. The feisty Costello probably
doesn't mind the pressure _ the show is indeed based on her life _
but it seems a bit presumptuous to expect viewers to recognize the
name. ``Mouthy in Southie'' might have worked better.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encore! Encore!
</P>
<P>
   NBC
</P>
<P>
   ``Encore! Encore!,'' starring Tony Award winner Nathan Lane, is
still a mystery, mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Given a nice spot between ``Mad About You'' and ``Just Shoot
Me,'' it ought to do reasonably well. But NBC chose not to show it
to critics during the July press tour. ``Retooling,'' they said.
Perhaps to make it look less like ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   The premise has Lane playing Joseph Pinoni, an opera star forced
to retire to his family's Napa Valley vineyard. Though he has left
the stage, Pinoni has not abandoned theatricality. Master of the
grand entrance, he works hard at being the center of attention. His
best friend, Joseph (James Patrick Stuart), is described as ``a
wealthy dilettante and self-styled artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? It should. David Angell, Peter Casey and David
Lee, the creative collective behind ``Frasier,'' are the creators
of ``Encore! Encore!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Brimstone
</P>
<P>
   Fox
</P>
<P>
   When someone suggests that Ezekiel Stone can go to hell, he can
reply smugly, ``Been there, done that, thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone, you see, is already dead, and because he killed a man in
cold blood during his days as a New York cop, he went to hell when
he died. He's back on Earth now under a devilish work-release
program that requires him to round up 113 escapees from Hades, all
of whom who happen to possess supernatural powers. In fact, Satan
has promised Stone redemption if he can round up all 113.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. One hundred and thirteen miscreants divided by 22
episodes a year. That's five seasons. Stone won't need redemption;
with that many shows in the can, he'll be in eternal syndication,
where the pay is better.
</P>
<P>
   But Stone can't worry about royalties right now. He knows that
if he doesn't round up the escapees, the whole world is doomed _
and he goes back to hell. Peter Horton plays Stone with a touch of
black humor, but ``Brimstone,'' like ``Millennium,'' will probably
seem a little dark and inaccessible to most viewers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Felicity
</P>
<P>
   The WB
</P>
<P>
   Living up to heavy-duty buzz can be torture for a new TV show.
And the buzz champ for the '98-'99 season is ``Felicity,'' which
means expectations will be completely unrealistic, and backlash
virtually certain.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, ``Felicity'' airs on The WB, a small network that gives
shows time to grow, and time to suffer the inevitable disaffection
of people who like the sizzle more than the steak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson's Creek'' experienced it last season, but settled in
comfortably after riding the roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Felicity,'' The WB has another chance to position itself
as the network of well-made, relationship drama, regardless of the
expectations. Keri Russell plays Felicity Porter, a teen-ager who
disapoints her parents by choosing to go to college at a university
in New York, even though her dad could have pulled some strings to
get her into Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Felicity herself is a little bummed after tasting her first bite
of the Apple. She chose a school in New York because a boy she
hardly knew in high school chose the same university. And it turns
out he's already attached.
</P>
<P>
   So Felicity, growing up fast in a strange place, wrestles with
her choices _ stay or go, pre-med or art, paper or plastic _ and we
get to watch. Russell makes it eminently watchable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mercy Point
</P>
<P>
   UPN
</P>
<P>
   Finally! A good hospital where you can get quality care whenever
you suspect one of those wormy alien creatures is living inside
your chest.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that HMOs haven't yet figured out the maximum
permissible hospital stay for an alienectomy. At Mercy Point, it's
probably 20 minutes. We're in the 23rd century, after all, when
modern medicine is even able to eliminate the embarrassment of
decapitation.
</P>
<P>
   To work at Mercy Point, situated at the farthest known explored
point of the galaxy, it helps to have an odd name, such as Dr.
Grote Maxwell, or Dr. Haylen Breslauer, or Dr. Caleb Jurado, or Dr.
Rema Cook.
</P>
<P>
   The most normal name at Mercy Point belongs to the head nurse.
At least it sounds normal: Annie. But it's spelled ANI, for Android
Nursing Interface. Looks like the nurses' union lost the battle
over the hiring of cyborgs.
</P>
<P>
   Quality-wise, ``Mercy Point'' is closer to ``Babylon 5'' than it
is to ``ER.'' But that's not all bad. ``Babylon 5'' has better
fashion sense.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sports Night
</P>
<P>
   ABC
</P>
<P>
   Attention, sports fans (and non-sports fans, too). ``Sports
Night'' may be one of the most attractive new shows of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Fitted to the comedy model, ``Sport Night'' isn't your average
comedy. ABC doesn't even call it a comedy, though it will play with
a laugh track. (Creator Aaron Sorkin, who wrote ``A Few Good Men''
and ``The American President,'' wishes it wouldn't.)
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of ``Sports Night,'' possibly reflecting the
involvement of Ron Howard's Imagine Television, is that the
characters are amazingly, refreshingly real. No buffoons, no wacky
neighbors. Even the boss (Robert Guillaume) seems relatively
normal. The humor derives more from reality and less from rimshot
jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Krause and Josh Charles are the main players, portraying
co-anchors of an ESPN-style cable show called ``Sports Night.''
But, while the series is set in the workplace, it appears to be
more about relationships _ a nifty trick that most comedies never
master.
</P>
<P>
   RETURNING TUESDAY SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clueless''
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Improvement''
