<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-WEDNESDAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW THIS FALL ON WEDNESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a look at the new TV shows on Wednesday this fall. Check
local listings for times, channels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seven Days
</P>
<P>
   UPN
</P>
<P>
   This is not a misprint. ``Seven Days'' is a UPN show that looks
halfway decent. Maybe even three-quarters decent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the pilot was shot as a movie, which can be
misleading. Will the ensuing episodes have the same production
values, the same high-caliber feel? Impossible to know, but we can
hope, can't we?
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan LaPaglia (``New York Undercover'') plays Frank Parker,
a former high-maintenance CIA operative who's confined to a mental
hospital when he is recruited for a covert operation by an elite,
military intelligence unit. His mission: Go back in time to undo a
present-day calamity. His problem: The way-back machine hasn't
quite passed inspection, but since it can only send someone back a
maximum of seven days, there's no time for fine-tuning. Parker must
court disaster to prevent disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The machine works, but not without putting Parker through a
couple of rugged spin cycles. Still, the weirdest part of his job
isn't going back in time or trying to prevent the mayhem that has
already taken place, it's the consequence of his actions. For
example, let's say Parker puts the moves on the sexy Dr. Olga
Vukavitch (Justina Vail), which, it is safe to say, will probably
happen in every episode. After he goes back in time and changes the
course of events, the romantic overtures he made before entering
last week have been erased. So it's back to square one. Talk about
sexual tension! Every time the guy gets to first base, the game is
called on account of it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   As a time-travel drama that doesn't get gunked up in sci-fi
jargon, ``Seven Days'' could have broad appeal if it weren't up
against ``Dateline NBC,'' ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' ``The Nanny,''
``Beverly Hills, 90210'' and ``Dawson's Creek.'' UPN's expectations
are never outrageously high, but it may have a hard time carving
out a share of Wednesday's typically splintered audience.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, LaPaglia's laconic Parker and Vail's smoldering
Vukavitch provide a bubbly romantic subtext to the main story. The
presence of estimable supporting players like Norman Lloyd and Nick
Searcy doesn't hurt, either. ``Seven Days'' is good escapist fare
with an eye for quality.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maggie Winters
</P>
<P>
   CBS
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Winters is not Corky Sherwood. Period.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Maggie, like Corky of ``Murphy Brown'' fame,
left a small town to work in the big city. Never mind that Maggie's
marriage, like Corky's, didn't work out. Maggie is from the
Midwest, not the South. So there.
</P>
<P>
   Still, seeing Faith Ford as someone other than Corky is a tall
order. Maybe if we think of ``Maggie Winters'' as the small-screen
version of the movie ``Hope Floats,'' Ford will remind us of Sandra
Bullock and take our minds off Corky Sherwood.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. Now we can cope. But Maggie can't. Jobless and
divorced, she's back in Shelbyville, Ind., a shell of the girl
``Most Likely To Succeed,'' living with her mother.
</P>
<P>
   One has to assume Maggie won't wallow in self pity for 10
seasons. But if she doesn't snap out of it by Thanksgiving, she may
need a swift kick from Murphy Brown.
</P>
<P>
   _ To Have and To Hold
</P>
<P>
   CBS
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Ally McBeal'' last season re-legitimized the
hourlong romantic comedy/drama. With ``To Have and To Hold,'' CBS
hopes to offer a comfortable transition from an hour of sitcoms
(``The Nanny,'' ``Maggie Winters'') to an hour of ``Chicago Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in Boston, ``To Have and To Hold'' is part of this season's
Irish invasion. Moira Kelly and Jason Beghe play public defender
Annie Cornell and police detective Sean McGrail, respectively.
They've known each other forever, are madly in love, and often end
up on different sides of a criminal case. When troubled, Annie
confides in her sister, who's married to Sean's firefighter
brother. Sean also has two other brothers, both cops, and a mother
(Fionnula Flanagan) who may be a few shingles short of a roof.
</P>
<P>
   Annie and Sean argue a lot, but don't be fooled. They're
inseparable. And occasionally insufferable. If there's a Celtic
word for schmaltz, it would fit nicely here.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charmed
</P>
<P>
   The WB
</P>
<P>
   As if this show didn't already have enough going on, what with
the reunion of producer Aaron Spelling and former ``90210'' star
Shannen Doherty, the pilot had to be reshot after Lori Rom abruptly
left the cast. In her place: one-time child star Alyssa Milano,
most recently of ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   Milano, Doherty and Holly Marie Combs (``Picket Fences'') play
the sisters Halliwell: free-spirited Phoebe, the youngest;
ambitious and driven Prue, the eldest, and earthy and creative
Piper, the one who usually acts as buffer between the other two.
</P>
<P>
   After inheriting a grand old Victorian home in San Francisco,
the sisters learn that, by putting aside their differences and
working together, they can summon supernatural powers they never
knew they had. Naturally, these witchy women use their abilities
only for good, but they have to keep their talents a secret because
the neighbors might not understand.
</P>
<P>
   The original pilot was of C-plus to B-minus quality, and unless
Milano turns in the bravura performance of the century (or someone
punches up the script), the second pilot will be about the same.
Also, with ``Party of Five'' in the same time period going after
the identical audience demographic, the Halliwell sisters may have
to work overtime to charm their way to renewal.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Secret Lives of Men
</P>
<P>
   ABC
</P>
<P>
   Surprise! The secret lives of men do not revolve around beer,
nachos and the Victoria's Secret catalog. Guess that's just one of
those urban legends.
</P>
<P>
   The secret lives of men revolve around golf and Italian food. At
least in the cases of Phil, Michael and Andy.
</P>
<P>
   They play golf every week. It's their outlet, their means of
bonding over shared experiences. And when they're not on the
course, they're at their favorite trattoria, bonding over shared
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   This could get really old, but the first episode of ``The Secret
Lives of Men'' is reasonably amusing, thanks to some actors who
have been around the block and actually may have bonded over shared
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Whitford, Peter Gallagher and Mitch Rouse play guys who are
well north of their 20s and not entirely comfortable with their
singleness, possibly because the ex-wives got the kids, the houses
and the money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while their maturity as actors lends a reassuring depth,
it's hard to imagine ``Secret Lives'' as appointment television on
a weekly basis.
</P>
<P>
   Where'd that catalog go?
</P>
<P>
   RETURNING WEDNESDAY SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   ``Beverly Hills, 90210''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago Hope''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dharma &AMP; Greg''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Drew Carey Show''
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nanny''
</P>
<P>
   ``NewsRadio''
</P>
<P>
   ``Party of Five''
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek: Voyager''
</P>
<P>
   ``3rd Rock From the Sun''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Guys, a Girl and a Pizza Place''
</P>
<P>
   EXISTING SHOWS MOVING FROM WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   ``Sister, Sister'' to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart Guy'' to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spin City to Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Steve Harvey Show'' to Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wayans Bros.'' to Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   EXISTING SHOWS NEW TO WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   ``20/20'' (additional night, absorbing ``PrimeTime Live'').
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY SHOWS GONE FOR GOOD
</P>
<P>
   (UNLESS OTHERWISE NOTED)
</P>
<P>
   ``Built to Last''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ellen''
</P>
<P>
   ``Murphy Brown''
</P>
<P>
   ``PrimeTime Live'' (absorbed by ``20/20'')
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sentinel'' (returning midseason)
</P>
<P>
   ``Significant Others''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Simple Life''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tony Danza Show''
</P>
