<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-FRIDAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW THIS FALL ON FRIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a look at the new TV shows on Friday this fall. Check
local listings for times, channels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two of a Kind
</P>
<P>
   ABC
</P>
<P>
   ABC stumbled last year with a couple of Friday night clunkers
named ``You Wish'' and ``Teen Angel.'' It rebounds this season with
two new replacements that more faithfully uphold the network's
youth-oriented TGIF tradition.
</P>
<P>
   One is ``Brother's Keeper,'' discussed elsewhere on this page.
The other is ``Two of a Kind,'' featuring the Olsen twins in their
first series since the demise of ``Full House'' three years ago.
This time, Ashley and Mary-Kate don't have to share a role. They
play the identical but not very similar twin daughters of a widowed
college professor who's struggling with single parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the season's more hackneyed themes, but ``Two of a
Kind'' manages a palatable treatment, particularly for ABC's
intended TGIF audience.
</P>
<P>
   _ Living in Captivity
</P>
<P>
   Fox
</P>
<P>
   Most of the sitcoms that roll off the assembly line each season
are painfully average. This appears to be one of them, despite the
auspices of Diane English and Joel Shukovsky, the husand-and-wife
team that created ``Murphy Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   A hit series involves a fair amount of lucky casting, and
``Murphy Brown'' had it. ``Living in Captivity'' may end up having
a similar dream cast, but you wouldn't know it from the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Dondre T. Whitfield (``Between Brothers'') and Kira Arne play an
upwardly mobile African-American couple who have moved to a gated
community in the suburbs. Living next door is an ignoramus muffler
monger named Carmine Santucci (Lenny Venito), who is severely
overdrawn at the brain bank.
</P>
<P>
   To balance things out, another neighbor is Will Marek (Matthew
Letscher), a frustrated writer who is to political correctness what
Miss Manners is to behavioral etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in the first episode, the Cooks encounter racism in its
most blatant and most subtle forms, all to the accompaniment of a
laugh track. Eee-ew.
</P>
<P>
   _ Legacy
</P>
<P>
   UPN
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Bonanza'' and ``The Big Valley'' on UPN! But it's not
exactly a western. More like a southern.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Cullen plays Ned Logan, widowed head of a proud and
prominent family in post-Civil War Kentucky. Ned has four kids of
his own, but his heart is big, and he takes in a roguish
17-year-old orphan named Jeremy Bradford (Ron Melendez).
</P>
<P>
   Whenever trouble strikes _ and the Logans seem to court it _
Jeremy is implicated. But patriarch Ned stands by the kid in the
fine and honorable tradition of Ben Cartwright and Victoria
Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legacy'' is called ``Legacy'' because Ned Logan, a horse
breeder, firmly believes in the philosophy of his Irish forebears,
that is, to build a family through unconditional love and firm
support while providing opportunities to others who are less
fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   It's a noble legacy, but even within the Logan family it is a
source of controversy. At least it's predictable controversy. (And
they get the good old barn fire out of the way in the first
episode.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Buddy Faro
</P>
<P>
   CBS
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Faro used to be king of the L.A. private eyes. Then he
disappeared in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's back, thanks to another private eye named Bob Jones,
who found Buddy wasting away in Margaritaville. Bob cleaned Buddy
up, put some gas in Buddy's old T-bird, and Buddy is once again Mr.
Smooth, albeit in a time warp.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Buddy has Bob and Bob's lovely assistant, Julie
Barber, to keep his calendar.
</P>
<P>
   In the demo tape sent to critics, the story of Buddy's return
from exile moves more slowly than a latte line at Starbucks. CBS
says this will be ``fixed,'' so ``Budd Faro'' may yet be worth a
visit. But the original also tries to be hip and amusing, and
succeeds only part of the time, resulting in a lightweight drama
that has more style than substance.
</P>
<P>
   Once back in L.A., Dennis Farina's Buddy Faro is a swaggering
caricature, the sort of role Farina does well. Frank Whaley,
meanwhile, is unspectacular as the unspectacular Bob Jones, and
Allison Smith seems to get the standard window-dressing treatment
as Julie Barber.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trinity
</P>
<P>
   NBC
</P>
<P>
   Matthew McNair Carnahan named his creation ``Trinity'' because
it was inspired by ``conflicting feelings about being Irish
American, about spirituality, and about connecting with family in
an increasingly fragmented world.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that answer helps explain the tediousness of the first
episode, which drags noticeably through the introduction of the
McCallister family: an Irish cliche to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   There's Bobby (Justin Louis), the cop; Liam (Sam Trammell), the
union leader tied to organized crime; Kevin (Tate Donovan), the
priest; Amanda (Bonnie Root), the substance abuser, and, just for
good measure, Fiona (Charlotte Ross), a successful stockbroker
who's having an affair with her married boss. There's also Clarissa
(Kim Raver), Bobby's wife, who seems very chummy with Liam.
</P>
<P>
   As if to recharge their souls, and despite some enormous
differences, the kids get together every Sunday for dinner at the
McCallister home. It's a touching idea, but the McCallisters are
going to have to pick up the pace to keep viewers from nodding off
before dessert.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brother's Keeper
</P>
<P>
   ABC
</P>
<P>
   The single-parent syndrome strikes again.
</P>
<P>
   In this permutation, a geeky, stick-in-the mud guy with a young,
impressionable son gets a wake-up call when his trouble-prone,
pro-football-playing brother moves in because his
million-dollar-a-year contract says he needs to live with a
responsible party.
</P>
<P>
   The twist here is that the requisite female character in the
show isn't a nanny. She's a sports agent who babysits the brother,
not the son.
</P>
<P>
   In the history of sitcomedy, this isn't the paragon of funny.
But Sean O'Bryan, as place-kicker Bobby Waide, the pain-in-the-neck
brother, makes the extra point to give ABC a chance for Friday
night victory.
</P>
<P>
   RETURNING FRIDAY SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy Meets World''
</P>
<P>
   ``Candid Camera''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dateline NBC''
</P>
<P>
   ``Homicide: Life on the Street''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids Say the Darndest Things''
</P>
<P>
   ``Millennium''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nash Bridges''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sabrina, the Teenage Witch''
</P>
<P>
   ``20/20''
</P>
<P>
   EXISTING SHOWS NEW TO FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   ``Dateline NBC'' (additional show).
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Personal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Boat: The Next Wave.''
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY SHOWS GONE FOR GOOD
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Matters''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gregory Hines Show''
</P>
<P>
   ``Meego''
</P>
<P>
   ``Players''
</P>
<P>
   ``Step by Step''
</P>
<P>
   ``Teen Angel''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Visitor''
</P>
<P>
   ``You Wish''
</P>
</TEXT>
