<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-SATURDAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW THIS FALL ON SATURDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a look at the new TV shows on Saturday this fall. Check
local listings for times, channels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wind on Water
</P>
<P>
   NBC
</P>
<P>
   According to experts, wind on water is one of the things that
helps make waves. But even with Bo Derek riding a horse in a white
bikini (Bo's in the bikini, not the horse), ``Wind on Water'' will
be lucky to cause a ripple this season.
</P>
<P>
   The luckiest person in ``Wind on Water'' may be Raymond J.
Barry, who dies in the first episode, leaving Derek to play a
feisty widow trying to keep the family's Hawaiian ranch from being
swallowed up by a slimy developer.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Derek's two sons are expert surfers and awesome
snowboarders who venture out on the extreme-sports circuit to earn
enough money to keep the ranch running.
</P>
<P>
   This makes for lush photography of the Big Island, but not much
else. With dull writing and duller acting, ``Wind on Water'' could
very well put the viewer into a tropical depression.
</P>
<P>
   _ Martial Law
</P>
<P>
   CBS
</P>
<P>
   The TV commercials for ``Martial Law,'' featuring Hong Kong
martial arts guru Sammo Hung, pretty much say it all. Hung plays
Sammo Law, a visiting cop from China who doesn't carry a gun, so he
has to get creative when bringing evildoers to justice. The
well-timed and vigorous opening of a door, for instance, is a good
way to knock the wind out of a miscreant's sails, as well as the
teeth out of his mouth. But even normal, everyday items can become
part of Law's arsenal: combs, credit cards, staplers. He's the
MacGyver of law enforcement, and proponents of gun control may be
hailing ``Martial Law'' as a breakthrough cop show.
</P>
<P>
   This is good, because the series probably won't win any other
awards. Though a complete pilot wasn't available for review,
``Martial Law'' obviously falls into the same category as ``Nash
Bridges,'' ``Walker, Texas Ranger'' and ``Diagnosis Murder'':
simplistic, unimaginative entertainment for viewers not interested
in being challenged.
</P>
<P>
   While there certainly is room on mainstream TV for escapist
programming that doesn't engage too many brain cells, a little
twist of originality would be welcome. (See ``Fantasy Island,'' for
instance.) The demonstration tape of ``Martial Law'' seems to
follow the trite formula so closely that viewers should be able to
figure out the ending by the first commercial break. The only
unknown will be Sammo's weapon of choice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fantasy Island
</P>
<P>
   ABC
</P>
<P>
   This isn't your father's ``Fantasy Island.'' The new Mr. Roarke
(Malcolm McDowell) is a shade more mysterious, almost ominous, and
there's no Tattoo yelling, ``Ze plane! Ze plane!'' But there's a
new female assistant (Madchen Amick) who can take on the identity
of anyone she chooses, and there's Fyvush Finkel running one of the
eeriest travel agencies around.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Sonnenfeld, the same guy responsible for ABC's summertime
hit, ``Maximum Bob,'' is adding his dark and humorous touch to this
remake. Though not nearly as quirky as ``Maximum Bob,'' it does
show signs of emerging from the large (but very average) cauldron
of typical Saturday escapist fare.
</P>
<P>
   The key will be in the writing, which didn't exactly crackle in
the demo tape provided critics. But it was better than average,
which is every critic's fantasy this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cupid
</P>
<P>
   ABC
</P>
<P>
   This may be one of the best new shows to be canceled before most
of the country even knows it existed. Or it could be the sleeper of
the new season.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 p.m. slot on Saturday is usually ABC's kiss of death, but
if anyone can reverse the hex, surely it's the Roman god of erotic
love. Shoot, if ABC had named this series for Cupid's Greek
counterpart, Eros, it might have solved its Saturday ratings
problem for good.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Jeremy Piven is brilliantly cast as a man who claims
to be the mischief-maker of myth. He says he has been sent to Earth
to relearn his craft and won't be allowed back among the gods until
he has made 100 lasting matches.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Cupid, a k a Trevor Hale, is institutionalized, and
he becomes the pet project of psychiatrist Claire Allen (Paula
Marshall). Dr. Allen doesn't believe for a moment that Hale is
Cupid, but he does seem to be having an effect on people's
heartstrings. Maybe even hers.
</P>
<P>
   Piven and Marshall are wonderful together, and ``Cupid'' is a
romantic comedy worth keeping.
</P>
<P>
   RETURNING SATURDAY SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   ``America's Most Wanted: America Fights Back''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cops''
</P>
<P>
   ``Early Edition''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pretender''
</P>
<P>
   ``Profiler''
</P>
<P>
   ``Walker, Texas Ranger''
</P>
<P>
   EXISTING SHOWS NEW TO SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ``America's Funniest Home Videos.''
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY SHOWS GONE FOR GOOD
</P>
<P>
   (UNLESS OTHERWISE NOTED)
</P>
<P>
   ``C16''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Magnificent Seven'' (returning midseason)
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleepwalkers''
</P>
<P>
   ``Total Security''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
