<HEADER>
A1577 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FALL-SUNDAY-SPI &LR;      09-06 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-SUNDAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW THIS FALL ON SUNDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a look at the new TV shows on Sunday this fall. Check
local listings for times, channels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Holding the Baby
</P>
<P>
   Fox
</P>
<P>
   In England, it's rare for a television show to reach 50 or 100
episodes. The British concept of a ``series' is more akin to the
American ``limited series'' notion: a predetermined run _ say, 10
or 20 shows _ and then everyone says goodbye and is off to another
project.
</P>
<P>
   However, Granada Television, one of the biggest creators of TV
programming in England, obviously sees profit potential in the U.S
model. Its American cousin, Granada Entertainment USA, helped bring
an Americanized ``Cracker'' to U.S. TV last season. ``Cracker''
crumbled just shy of a full season, but Granada is undeterred. Its
second Americanization effort is ``Holding the Baby'' in
association with former ``Home Improvement'' producer Howard J.
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Morris would very much like to get to 100 episodes _ the
equivalent of almost five seasons _ but he has his work cut out for
him. Airing opposite the second half of ``60 Minutes,'' his new
show isn't likely to draw a big audience unless Mike Wallace does a
guest spot.
</P>
<P>
   Those who do tune in may be pleasantly surprised. Despite a
single-parenthood premise that has been massaged one way or another
since the beginning of TV, ``Holding the Baby'' has a charm that is
easygoing, unthreatening _ and decidedly un-Foxy. How it fits as a
lead-in to an edgier, more sarcastic show like ``The Simpsons''
isn't clear, but the producers and the actors can't worry about
that.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal derives from Jon Patrick Walker, as single dad Gordon
Stiles, and Jennifer Westfeldt, as grad student Kelly O'Malley.
O'Malley would like a job at the ad agency where Stiles works, but
the desperate Stiles, recently abandoned by his wife, sees greater
nanny potential in the young woman.
</P>
<P>
   One difference between this show and others that have plowed
similar ground is that the hassles of raising an infant aren't
usually the focus of an entire series. More like a few episodes. If
``Holding the Baby'' avoids the usual pitfalls of such ``baby
shows,'' the surest sign of its success may be when they change the
title to ``Holding the Toddler.''
</P>
<P>
   _ That '70s Show
</P>
<P>
   Fox
</P>
<P>
   If your only memory of 1976 is the Bicentennial celebration,
then ``That '70s Show'' is a pretty good refresher.
</P>
<P>
   It's also pretty amusing, which probably has the suits at Fox
breathing easier, since ``That '70s Show'' constitutes one half of
a very big gamble. The other half was the moving of ``King of the
Hill'' to Tuesday nights.
</P>
<P>
   A proven performer in the cushy slot between ``The Simpsons''
and ``The X-Files'' on Sunday, ``King of the Hill'' is being asked
to anchor what has been a difficult night for Fox. In its place,
viewers get not an animated comedy but a live-action show that
stirred up controversy even before its premiere.
</P>
<P>
   The show is an attempt to portray with some accuracy the
fashions, the attitudes and the tenor of the '70s through the
experiences of six teenagers. Its first episode showed some of them
sneaking a few brewskis down to the basement and later enjoying the
effects of wacky tabacky. The episode centered on the hallowed
ritual of a teen getting his own car, so the decision to do scenes
about intoxicating substances _ with no immediate repercussions _
was certainly questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the same treatment in an episode of ``The Simpsons''
or ``King of the Hill'' might not raise a peep of protest.
Regardless, the producers have promised to deal responsibly with
the tough coming-of-age issues.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy aside, ``That '70s Show'' stands out because of
spiffy, energetic writing and a well-cast group of young actors,
particularly Topher Grace and Laura Prepon as two kids who've been
friends since they were 4 but are discovering that they really, uh,
like each other.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Army Show
</P>
<P>
   The WB
</P>
<P>
   As the law of diminishing returns takes hold, network executives
are saying there just isn't enough writing talent out there to keep
up with the demand (by whom we're not sure) for TV comedies. The
result: Each season, the networks are forced to put on increasing
amounts of substandard fare because the alternative _ putting on
nothing at all in a particular time slot _ isn't a widely accepted
programming tactic.
</P>
<P>
   That explains the presence of ``The Army Show'' in The WB's fall
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army Show'' is a bad show. The only possible reason for
its existence is to perpetuate the tradition of midseason
replacements. It makes ``McHale's Navy'' look like Shakespeare,
which would make Capt. Binghamton the equivalent of Lear (the king,
not Norman).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps trying for its own bit of the Bard, ``The Army Show''
has a character named Caesar _ Pvt. John Caesar, a computer hacker
who's been sentenced to a four-year hitch in the Army instead of
jail time. John Sencio, who got his acting training at MTV, plays
Caesar too brutally to imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Even more painful is watching the capable David Anthony Higgins,
who spent four seasons on ``Ellen,'' dealing with material that
would be sophomoric if only it hadn't flunked freshman comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The premise: Some goldbricks are enjoying the life of Riley at a
``forgotten'' military base named, appropriately enough, Fort
(William?) Bendix. The series borrows liberally from its TV
predecessors _ from ``Sergeant Bilko'' to ``Gomer Pyle, USMC'' to
``MASH'' _ but nothing in the pilot episode gives any evidence that
``The Army Show'' will ever be all that it can be. Desertion is
highly recommended.
</P>
<P>
   RETURNING SUNDAY SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   CBS Sunday Night Movie
</P>
