<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRICK-MUSEUM-ART-900(     09-06 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRICK-MUSEUM-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR TRIES GENTLE CHANGES FOR THE FRICK 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Samuel Sachs II, director of the Frick Collection,
may work at a Chippendale desk in a paneled room built more than
eight decades ago as the boudoir of Adelaide Childs Frick, but he
spends his days looking toward the future.
</P>
<P>
   Flashing across his computer screen is a picture of the Frick's
famous living hall with its 16th-century paintings, fine French
furniture, Renaissance bronzes and magnificent Persian carpet. With
the click of a mouse, he made the hall spin in every direction.
Nine months in the making, the museum's new Web site
(www.frick.org) offers the usual menu of practical information but
also includes a virtual-reality tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had hits from all over,'' Sachs said. ``Four-thousand
people in the first two days pulled up the Web site from countries
like Australia, New Zealand and Scandinavia.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Sachs, 62, left the financially troubled Detroit
Institute of Art, where he had been director for 12 years, to
become director of the Frick, replacing Charles Ryskamp, who
retired after a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, with judicious infusions of technology and a good deal
of patience, Sachs is trying to transform one of the most famously
old-fashioned institutions in Manhattan into one that is more
user-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his ideas, like the Web site and a multilanguage digital
Acoustiguide, are coming to fruition. He knows that other ideas,
like expanding the institution's exhibition space, extending its
hours, opening a cafe and even relocating the entrance may be a bit
ambitious for what has long been viewed as a place where nothing
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Since it opened to the public in 1935, the limestone mansion at
1 E. 70th St. built for Henry Clay Frick, the Pittsburgh coal and
steel industrialist, quickly became one of the city's most popular
attractions among dedicated art lovers, with attendance of more
than 250,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The last gasp of America's Gilded Age in the heart of the Upper
East Side, the Frick offers an intimate look into what was once a
grand home. Its artwork and objects from the 14th to the 19th
centuries _ fine French furniture of the 18th century, bronzes,
Chinese porcelains and Limoges enamels _ are arranged as though the
Fricks still lived there.
</P>
<P>
   The walls are lined with Holbeins, Vermeers, Rembrandts,
Turners, Gainsboroughs and Van Dycks, and rooms are filled with
Bouchers and Fragonards. Europeans particularly identify with the
Frick because its setting is the U.S. equivalent of an Italian
palazzo, a French chateau or an English stately home.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs refers to his mission as one of ``fine-tuning'' rather
than making major changes. The trick, as he well knows, is to make
the museum more dynamic without ruining what people love about it.
</P>
<P>
   When Frick died in 1919, he left his home and art collection to
a board of trustees with instructions that they become a study
center for art and related subjects. The institution has a large
endowment for its size, more than $200 million, but little space to
mount temporary exhibitions. It also has a notoriously guarded
nine-member board, run by Henry Clay Frick II, Frick's grandson,
and several other family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do things very carefully,'' said Helen Clay Chase, the
oldest of Frick's 15 great-grandchildren. ``When I think of my
great-grandfather's legacy I know that he very much wanted to make
it accessible to the public, and we want it to be more welcoming.
But at the same time, we want to be sure that the serenity is not
disturbed.''
</P>
<P>
   While many museums are courting the newly rich to become members
of expanded boards, the Frick has kept its board at its original
size, giving the impression that it is a private club. Some
supporters say privately that they fear any changes will ruin the
Frick's special character; others say the Frick needs to keep up
with the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extraordinary thing about the Frick is that it has always
changed, but all the while giving the illusion that it's the
same,'' said Everett Fahy, a former director of the Frick who is
now chairman of the department of European paintings at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. ``During my tenure, we added a new
wing, put in the garden on 70th Street and installed a state-of-art
security system.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many misconceptions about the Frick Collection, Sachs
said. ``The first is that we don't make acquisitions. We do. Many
people don't realize that about 30 percent of the collection has
been acquired since Frick's death. The second is that if we were
offered a painting, it would be turned away.''
</P>
<P>
   Another misconception is that the institution is unable to lend
any of the collection. Although it cannot lend the two-thirds that
belonged to Frick, as stipulated in his will, it does lend artworks
and objects acquired since his death.
</P>
<P>
   High on Sachs' agenda is to spread the word that the Frick is
not a members-only institution, and that despite its large
endowment, the institution still needs money to preserve the
building. (Fund-raising efforts are under way for replacement of
the copper roof and windows, which must be done this year, Sachs
said.)
</P>
<P>
   As all museums are doing, the Frick has reached out to a growing
group of younger supporters. ``There are lots of people who love
the Frick,'' Sachs said. ``But they don't think they'd be welcome
here. I want to make this a more welcoming place, not mess it up.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Already the front door has been made more welcoming. Until
recently, visitors were greeted by a dark entrance with only a
guard to direct them. There is now a well-lighted information desk
where people can pay their admission fee ($7 for adults and $5 for
students and the elderly) and pick up a free Art Phone, the latest
version of an Acoustiguide.
</P>
<P>
   Though hardly revolutionary, Acoustiguides signal a huge leap
into modernity for the Frick. And this one is the latest
incarnation, a random-access digital guide with more than three
hours of recorded information. The guide looks like a high-tech
cellular telephone, and it discusses every room and the major
paintings, furniture and objects, without requiring visitors to
follow a prescribed tour. By October it will be available in
English, French, Spanish, Japanese and German.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since about 35 percent of the visitors are non-English
speaking, I thought it was important to offer several languages,''
said Mr. Sachs. ``If we find we need Russian, we'll add it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides its permanent collection, the Frick has always organized
small, well-focused temporary exhibitions, and Sachs has begun
aggressively working on broadening the kinds of shows it will
offer, adding some that have been popular in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Two on the schedule are ``Victorian Fairy Painting,'' a smaller
version of the show that was at the Royal Academy in London, which
opens on Oct. 14, and ``The Medieval Housebook,'' pages from an
illuminated manuscript that show life in a princely court at the
end of the Middle Ages. That show, from Germany, will open in the
United States at the National Gallery of Art in Washington in
November and at the Frick in May.
</P>
<P>
   Like all museum directors, Sachs wants to draw a larger
audience. But once he gets visitors into the museum, he would like
to keep them there longer, he said. One way is with a cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great gentleman's house, and if you come and visit,
you wouldn't be surprised if you were offered a small amenity,'' he
said. But the issue of how to give visitors a refreshment in a
manner befitting the setting is touchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are days when I think, yes, it would be nice to have a
place people could have tea or coffee,'' said Mrs. Chase. ``And
then there are other days when I think, do we need to hear the
clutter of dishes?''
</P>
<P>
   Other changes on Sachs' wish list include extending the Frick's
hours on Friday and Saturday evenings to coincide with the late
closings of other institutions along Fifth Avenue's Museum Mile. He
also says that entering the Frick through the 70th Street garden
would be more welcoming.
</P>
<P>
   More ambitious is his desire to expand the museum, building
temporary exhibition galleries under the Fifth Avenue garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rome wasn't built in a day,'' Sachs said when asked if it was
true that board members were aghast at the idea of an expansion.
``These things take time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his progressive thinking, however, there is one rule _
particularly unpopular among parents of young children _ that isn't
about to change: Children under 10 are not allowed in the museum,
to protect the many pieces of fragile furniture and objects.
</P>
<P>
   The rule has been supported by state officials, Sachs said. ``I
don't think it's restrictive. I think it's reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   But ever mindful of a new generation of visitors, Sachs said he
would like to welcome children as soon as they are old enough to
enter: ``I'm thinking we should have a tea party for 10-year-olds,
as a rite of passage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
