<HEADER>
A1584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-06 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES LEARN POISON E-MAIL LETTERS HAVE A LONG LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When managers blunder at certain high-technology companies, they
are sure to read all about it _ not in the morning papers, but on
their companies' internal computer networks, from their own
subordinates, and often in language that would make a sailor blush.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the managers say they welcome the uncensored, sometimes
vitriolic outpouring.
</P>
<P>
   More than a handful of high-technology companies permit, even
encourage, employees to vent frustrations, passions, hopes and
suggestions in internal company mailing lists and bulletin boards.
The topics range from rants against the cafeteria food or restroom
toilet paper to critiques of new products.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any universal rule on such mail lists, however, it
is that these cathartic exchanges are never to be shared with
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   The issue came to the fore last week when it became known that
Microsoft Corp. had subpoenaed the archives of two such e-mail
lists _ known as Bad Attitude and Really Bad Attitude _ from
Netscape Communications Corp. Microsoft officials said they hoped
that the archives would provide evidence for use in their defense
against the federal government's antitrust lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape officials declined to comment last week, saying their
lawyers were still studying the subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Microsoft will find evidence _ or whether a federal
court will even permit access to Netscape's archives _ remains to
be seen. What is certain is that Netscape's ``Bad Attitude'' files
are typical of the level of candor that high-technology employees
often are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape adopted the ``Bad Attitude'' concept from Silicon
Graphics Inc., which has an internal e-mail list of the same name.
Apple Computer's employees, meanwhile, can post to a wide-ranging
discussion called Can We Talk, while the At-Home Network has the
Attitude, Cnet has Spam, and Starwave lets employees e-mail
anonymous suggestions and complaints to the company's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are so bright and creative,'' said Kandis Malefyt,
Netscape's senior vice president of human relations. ``The worst
thing you can do is snuff out their opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   Managers and employees alike say the discussion groups serve two
key purposes. Foremost, they are a way to let employees vent
frustrations, or as one Bad Attitude veteran put it, ``for
catharsis and telling the truth without fear of reprisals.'' They
also enable executives to gauge the sentiments of the rank and file
_ and, if they choose, to mollify those feelings.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Netscape's Bad Attitude became so inflamed two
years ago when the company's chief executive, Jim Barksdale,
decreed that employees could not bring dogs to work that the
company decided to change its policy. The impact can be more
substantive, too: Earlier this year, Netscape changed an e-mail
feature of its Netcenter portal site after employees complained
about it on Bad Attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Last Christmas, Cnet announced that employees would be allowed
to invite a date to the company holiday party. Days later, the
company rescinded the offer, saying that employees would have to
pay $45 to bring a guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone went completely up in arms and started ranting about
it over Spam,'' said Jan Fleischer, managing editor of Cnet Game
Center, a site devoted to video game news and reviews. ``Finally
the executive staff stepped in and said: `We're taking this back.
Everyone please come and please bring a guest.'''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Wood, a spokeswoman for Cnet, said that the company paid
close attention to Spam, in part to take the company's pulse.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean that any and all commentary is acceptable.
During the Christmas party incident at Cnet, one employee sent
repeated, angry e-mails not just to Spam but to another
company-wide message area. In response, the employee received a
not-so-subtle response from a manager: ``Looking for a promotion
any time soon? Don't hold your breath.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges can indeed become strident. At Apple several years
ago, a former employee, Lori Kaplan, complained on Can We Talk that
the company should not say it has a multicultural environment and
then spend holiday money exclusively on Christmas decorations. Ms.
Kaplan said that the responses were so insulting that she asked the
company to intervene on her behalf, which she said it did.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing sentiments from a number of companies, Ms. Wood of Cnet
said the company expected employees to follow company guidelines
when participating in Spam. ``Harassment won't be tolerated,'' she
said. ``People are governed by the same policies as when they talk
face to face.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, companies, their employees and intellectual property
lawyers say that Microsoft's subpoena has awakened them to a
potentially dangerous aspect of these e-mail exchanges: They can
stick around for a long time and may someday even wind up in court.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees say they will now exercise more caution, lest
what they write wind up in litigation. For its part, Netscape said
it would continue to allow employees to participate in Bad
Attitude.
</P>
<P>
   However, one notorious Netscape gadfly, Jamie Zawanksi, has
closed down ``Really Bad Attitude,'' a more elite internal mail
list at Netscape, whose participants had to prove they could flame
``so hard that bile flowed from eye sockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal scholars say that Zawanski is right to be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're creating a pool of bad evidence,'' said John Steele, a
partner and intellectual property specialist with the Palo Alto,
Calif., law firm of Fenwick &AMP; West. Steele noted that while judges
increasingly have come to disregard casual, informal, even
sarcastic e-mail, juries continue to regard them as meaningful
evidence. Steele recommends that companies either restrict the type
of feedback permitted or erase the e-mail as a matter of course.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the Bad Attitude discussions at Netscape are
turned not inward, but outward at Microsoft, for potentially
destroying the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is going to pay some jackass lawyer $200 an hour to
find out that we hate our cafeteria food, don't like the security
posters, had a sucky news feed, and think `Navigator' was a cooler
name than `Communicator,''' one Netscape employee wrote in Bad
Attitude. ``And I smile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
