<HEADER>
A1592 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNRUNNER-BOOK-REVIEW     09-06 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNRUNNER-BOOK-REVIEW-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GUN RUNNER'S DAUGHTER': THE TALE OF ESTHER AS MODERN-DAY
THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neil Gordon's first novel, ``Sacrifice of Isaac,'' was an
international murder story that used the biblical story of Abraham
and Isaac as a kind of thematic refrain. His new book is ``The Gun
Runner's Daughter,'' and this time the biblical reference is to the
Book of Esther, in which the Jewish people were saved from
annihilation by the secretly Jewish wife of the Persian king. The
Esther in this more modern guise is a sexy and savvy
Israeli-American woman named Allison, Alley to her friends. By
cleverly manipulating the legal system, and by sleeping with the
enemy, she saves at least some Jews from a cynical, politically
motivated federal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Transforming biblical parables into modern-day thrillers is a
creative approach to the problem that writers face in these
post-Cold War days: the absence of convincingly dangerous
international evildoers. The Bible as inspiration is not the only
thing that is creative about ``The Gun Runner's Daughter'': Gordon
has devised a complicated plot bursting with skulduggery and
finishing off with a satisfying surprise. But the very
imaginativeness of the plot makes one wonder why he falls back on
so many hackneyed and melodramatic devices in the telling of his
tale that he robs himself of his own originality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gun Runner's Daughter'' is in this sense a promising yarn
that fails to rise above the level of the standard, and rather
tired, thriller conventions. The most standard of Gordon's standard
devices is a style of inflated portent that is presumably aimed at
giving the story an exceptional air, making it suspenseful and
raising the emotional stakes for the dramatis personae.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the innocent wake unafraid,'' Gordon's narrator intones
in the first chapter, creating a sentence that is not only well
within the ``It was a dark and stormy night'' tradition of
melodramatic writing but is also simply wrong. Plenty of guilty
people wake unworried, while the innocent come to consciousness
terrified.
</P>
<P>
   The book contains lots of those single-sentence, or nonsentence
paragraphs that seem almost mandatory in standard thriller writing.
This device is supposed to impart a narrational terseness to the
story, but it has been so overused by now that it is about as
original as a sport-utility vehicle for city driving.
</P>
<P>
   Other passages are overwrought and vague at the same time:
``Then, not for the first time, but stronger than ever before, a
sense of disbelief swept over him, sudden amazement at the swift,
absolute fatality of what had happened.'' Or, ``And then, with an
interior sense of factitiousness that was only too familiar, she
leaned toward him and raised her voice through the mounting volume
of the band.''
</P>
<P>
   When the characters are not experiencing absolute fatality or
familiar factitiousness (whatever that is), they are using a lot of
the more common four-letter vulgarisms, so frequently in fact that
the dialogue, rather than seeming natural and informal, takes on
the forced quality of people trying too hard to be natural and
informal. And then there is Gordon's handling of emotion, usually
by means of some exaggerated physiognomic effect. The condition of
the main characters' stomachs is referred to often enough in this
novel to turn them into characters themselves. ``Real frustration
was in Dee's stomach now.'' Somewhat later: ``Alley's stomach was
plummeting now.'' And then: ``A strange lightness was in Dee's
stomach now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gordon tells a good story, especially if you can suspend
disbelief enough to accept the basic premise. This is that Alley's
father, Ronald Rosenthal, an Israeli-American arms dealer, has been
arrested on charges of breaking the U.N. embargo against selling
arms to the Bosnian Muslims. One just wonders why he uses a kind of
borrowed style to tell what would otherwise have been a far more
tingling and saucy adventure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The prosecution is taking place even though the Clinton
administration wants arms to be smuggled to the Bosnian Muslims
who, after all, faced genocide during the civil war in the former
Yugoslavia. But the infinite cynicism of international politics, as
depicted by Gordon, leads the administration to throw the book at
Rosenthal in order to give credibility to its false assurance to
the British and the French that it is respecting the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   The chief prosecutor in the case is a well-born, ambitious young
man named Dee Dennis who happens to have had a sexual encounter
with Alley 10 years earlier when both were teen-agers summering on
Martha's Vineyard. The romance is resumed as trial preparation
takes place, so Alley is actually sleeping with her father's
prosecutor, and this causes a conflict-of-interest problem. Also in
the picture is a radical investigative journalist, Nicky Dymitryck,
who is striving to get the goods on an arms-dealing associate of
Rosenthal's named Eastbrook, who is running for the Senate in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Into this morass of conflicting interests and hypocritical
maneuverings, Alley devises a plot to turn the case against her
father around. Her complicated steps, which are based on her
knowledge of her father's hidden files, are intricately plotted and
plausibly based on court procedure and the law. Alley turns out to
be a master manipulator and a superb amoralist as well as a sexy
one, and, as her scheme unfolds, Gordon's story picks up
considerably in both momentum and quality, despite the occasional
slip into portentous cliche: ``While in Allison Rosenthal's
stomach, deep in her stomach, joy was born,'' Gordon writes at one
crucial point in the legal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Alley's manipulations include using the services of some bearded
Orthodox Jewish gunmen, arranging for her own arrest on charges of
embezzlement, and cleverly manipulating Dee in the evidence that he
introduces against her father during the trial. Gordon clearly
knows how to create a good yarn. The plot here is well-constructed,
very clever, so much so that you don't figure out what Allison is
up to until the end.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE GUN RUNNER'S DAUGHTER'
</P>
<P>
   By Neil Gordon
</P>
<P>
   316 pages. Random House. $24
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 1726EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
