<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-CAST-CHANGES-425&AMP;     09-06 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-CAST-CHANGES-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MEN OF A CERTAIN AGE, THREE ROLES TO SAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One set. Three characters. At least nine lives.
</P>
<P>
   That's the scorecard for Yasmina Reza's hit play ``Art,'' which
last week embarked upon its second Broadway cast, as its seventh
cast in the West End of London continued performances. In an era in
which few straight plays on either side of the Atlantic survive
cast changes, ``Art,'' which in June won the Tony Award for best
play, has become something more than a small theatrical industry.
It has turned into a blessed employment opportunity for a growing
group of not-so-young male actors in the hunt for ever more elusive
substantive roles.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cox, Henry Goodman and David Haig are now ensconced on
Broadway, replacing New York's initial ensemble of Alan Alda,
Victor Garber and Alfred Molina. Two of the British newcomers to
New York will be changing roles in a play in which they already
appeared in London.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Alda, Garber and Molina will open in Los Angeles in
January. Another cast will take on a 44-week national tour that
will probably start in San Francisco a year from now. Albert
Finney, Tom Courtenay and David Dukes have all taken their turns in
London.
</P>
<P>
   And in the spring, it looks likely that New York will play host
to an all-``Frasier'' company during the seasonal hiatus of the NBC
series. John Mahoney, Kelsey Grammer and David Hyde Pierce are in
negotiations to take on the roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of prime beef on the hoof,'' said George Wendt,
the 49-year-old American television star of ``Cheers,'' who is now
playing the role of Yvan in London. ``There's no shortage of
middle-aged actors, that's for sure, with 20 to 30 years
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Yasmina Reza, the play's 39-year-old playwright, said
the ideal age of actors for ``Art'' is around 50. (The comedy is
about a longtime three-way friendship bruised, perhaps irrevocably,
by a dispute over an all-white painting.) ``If they are too young,
they have no history, and so the breakup of a friendship doesn't
mean so much,'' she said in a phone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Actors with a history seem to appreciate aspects of the work
that might prove frustrating to younger men. ``The play allows the
actors involved, if they take the offer, to work in a different
way, which is not necessarily about impressing with your skills,
but about sharing a common humanity,'' said Goodman, Broadway's
current Serge, who comes to this trio having played Marc in the
third West End cast. ``Without being sentimental about it, there's
an ensemble opportunity in the play.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the absence of an obvious starring role can sometimes be
problematic for a play's success, the equal division of the spoils
seems to have worked to the advantage of ``Art.'' Though the
apparent philistine Marc has attracted the bigger names (Alda on
Broadway, Finney in the West End premiere), the emotionally beset
middleman Yvan is the one who tends to generate awards. Both
Broadway's Molina and Ken Stott in London were nominated for best
actor prizes. (The character's breathless monologue halfway
through, as close as a nonmusical these days gets to a showstopper,
doesn't hurt.)
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the dermatologist, Serge, who is the character who
buys the contentious painting. The role has attracted the likes of
Courtenay and Garber. It is now being played in London by Dukes,
remembered on Broadway for his work in shows like ``Bent'' and ``M.
Butterfly.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, more than fine ensemble opportunities account for the
platform the play allows its actors. In the pragmatic world of the
theater, no trophy confers the success of cash in the bank, and
here, too, ``Art'' tells an estimable tale.
</P>
<P>
   The original West End production recouped its investment in a
swift seven weeks. On Broadway, where the production cost $1.5
million, or triple the London version, the show had paid for itself
within nine weeks and has so far made around $2 million, said David
Pugh, who with actor Sean Connery, produced the play in London.
(They were joined by Joan Cullman on Broadway.) Internationally,
the play has had 125 productions in 30 languages.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first West End cast finished its six-month run, the
producers have furthered the cause of the middle-aged actor by
signing the successive London companies to 13-week contracts. (The
current New York company has signed on for 16 weeks.) Sometimes,
said Matthew Warchus, the director of the play in both cities, one
of the three roles is not even cast a week before rehearsals, which
makes for a certain tension as well as a useful flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   The short tours have allowed Goodman and other actors to return
to the play again, often in different roles. Haig, New York's
current Yvan, was London's second Marc, while Roger Allam, London's
third Serge, was the production's fifth Marc.
</P>
<P>
   The requirements of the play allow for casting ideas, such as
the ``Frasier'' one, that have set Pugh, for one, to thinking. He
talks hopefully of Tony Shalhoub doing the play with his ``Big
Night'' collaborators Stanley Tucci and Campbell Scott, and reports
that he is now spending a lot more time in video stores mulling
casting combinations.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. Reza, whose play ``The Unexpected Man'' is
expected off-Broadway this winter, is open to any possibility _
black and Hispanic companies, for example _ as long as the actors
are of a certain age and male. ``These are really men's words,''
she said. ``I don't want any women to play it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
