<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minor Victory for Intuit in Suit on Year 2000 Woes
</P>
<P>
   Intuit, the maker of the financial software Quicken, has won the
opening round in a lawsuit that tests how active software companies
must be in avoiding problems their customers might suffer as a
result of the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal of the lawsuit was mainly based on the reasoning
that no demonstrable damages had yet occurred because the program
had failed as a result of the Year 2000 problem. Intuit said it
expected to offer free upgrades of its older software to avoid Year
2000 problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram Micro in Deal With PC Order
</P>
<P>
   Ingram Micro, the wholesale distributor of computers, has signed
a deal to deliver custom-built computers more efficiently to
corporate customers. PC Order, a 2-year-old company that provides
electronic commerce technology and will fill Ingram's orders,
maintains a database on pricing and availability of 600,000
computer products from 1,000 manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   HBO Plans a Family Cable Channel
</P>
<P>
   HBO plans to start a 24-hour, commercial-free family programming
cable channel called HBO Family next year. Also in the works are
family channels from Nickelodeon and the Children's Television
Workshop, which is due in January, and a channel still in
development by Hallmark Entertainment, Jim Henson Co. and the
Odyssey network. Already operating in the competitive field is Fox
Family Channel, which began in August.
</P>
<P>
   The Risks of Electronic Candor
</P>
<P>
   Many high-technology companies permit _ even encourage _
employees to vent frustrations, passions, hopes and suggestions in
internal company mailing lists and bulletin boards. Now Microsoft
has subpoenaed the archives of two such e-mail lists from Netscape
Communications for possible use in the government's antitrust case
against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Book TV for C-Span on Weekends
</P>
<P>
   C-Span is spending more than $1.1 million to start Book TV,
weekend programs devoted to nonfiction books.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneur Builds High-Tech Ship
</P>
<P>
   Jim Clark, the founder of Silicon Graphics and co-founder of
Netscape Communications, has a new venture. He is building a highly
computerized 155-foot sailboat, called Hyperion, for an estimated
$30 million. It is scheduled for a mid-November voyage and, because
no commercial system existed for the computerized operating and
navigational system that Clark had envisioned for Hyperion, he and
three ex-Silicon Graphics engineers created their own.
</P>
<P>
   Very Few New Films on Labor Day
</P>
<P>
   Long holiday weekends are typically a popular time to introduce
films. But movie companies tend to shy away from Labor Day, when
many families are distracted by back-to-school activities.
</P>
<P>
   Counting Down to Jan. 1, 2000
</P>
<P>
   Budd Goldman, an inventor, has developed the Millennium Clock.
The desktop clock is a relentless reminder of the remaining days,
hours, minutes and seconds until the arrival of Jan. 1, 2000 _ as
determined by the time zone of the person who sets it.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Markets Closed Monday
</P>
<P>
   U.S. financial markets and banks are closed Monday in observance
of Labor Day. Most financial markets in other countries are open.
</P>
</TEXT>
