A1603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILLY-PAPER-MEDIA-2T     09-06 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-PAPER-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER-EDITOR CLASH TAKES NEW TWIST: LIBEL SUIT AGAINST PAPER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Little has been certain here in recent years as
the city's population and employment base dwindled. Still, people
could usually count on two things: that The Philadelphia Inquirer
was investigating a major local institution and that James E.
Beasley Sr., a malpractice lawyer, was suing a major local
institution _ often The Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   In two epic libel battles, Beasley won $40 million in jury
verdicts against the newspaper, although one of the judgments, for
$6 million, has been sent back for a retrial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an Antichrist as far as The Inquirer is concerned,''
Beasley said.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine the reaction in The Inquirer's newsroom recently when
Ralph Cipriano, a reporter, filed a libel suit against the paper
after the editor, Robert Rosenthal, publicly questioned the
objectivity and value of his reporting on the Archdiocese of
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer? Beasley.
</P>
<P>
   For journalists, accustomed to libel suits from outsiders,
Cipriano's in-house action was heresy. But Cipriano, who filed his
suit on Aug. 7, said that Rosenthal's public criticism _ the editor
was quoted in The Washington Post as saying that the reporter ``has
a very strong personal point of view and an agenda'' and ``There
were things that Ralph wrote that we didn't think were truthful'' _
had given him no other choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have literally destroyed his professional status as a
responsible reporter,'' Beasley said in an interview here, ``to
satisfy the intemperate outburst of a frustrated editor.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to say what hit the newspaper's staff harder: that
the editors' disputes about coverage with a combative colleague had
escalated to public insults and a libel suit or that the colleague
had made common cause with a lawyer who, in the words of the media
editor, Beth Gillin, ``is very much despised'' in the newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   In the four weeks that have followed, tensions have escalated
further. Late last month, Cipriano, 44, was dismissed after he
refused to give editors his notes related to reporting on the
archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he had turned to the newspaper's longtime antagonist
for aid, Cipriano said he wanted the best possible representation.
``The only thing I did was file a lawsuit to exercise my
constitutional rights,'' he said. ``How was I going to function as
a reporter after Bob Rosenthal said that about me?''
</P>
<P>
   Some in Philadelphia see a logic in the continued clashes
between Beasley, the senior partner in a firm that uses
www.tortlaw.com as its World Wide Web address, and the newspaper,
which has won 18 Pulitzer Prizes in 23 years, many for documenting
abuse or mismanagement in mental hospitals, the city police
department, state courts and the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mindset of a plaintiff's personal injury attorney is that
your life's endeavor is righting wrongs,'' said Frederick L. Voigt,
the executive director of the Committee of 70, a Philadelphia civic
group. ``There's a great commonality with journalists in terms of
mentality,'' he added. ``Both are on a mission. And sometimes those
missions are going to come into conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   The words ``mission'' and ``conflict'' tend to crop up in
conversations about Cipriano as well _ though usually along with
the words ``good writer.'' Cipriano spent 11 years at The Inquirer,
covering the New Jersey suburbs, writing features and obituaries
and, last November, an article disclosing the eligibility problems
of a University of Pennsylvania football player _ disclosures that
led the school to forfeit the five games the team won in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he clashed often with Inquirer colleagues,
according to both Cipriano and some editors. When he arrived, he
objected to smoking in suburban bureaus. He argued about diversity
training sessions in the early 1990s. Cipriano _ who is of Italian
and Lebanese descent and says ``when I look in the mirror, I see
olive skin'' _ objected to being pigeonholed as a white male.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a strong sense of right and wrong,'' he said. ``I have
had it since I was a little kid. I know what's right and what's
wrong, and I stick to my principles. I have a tenacious character,
and I don't give up easily.''
</P>
<P>
   These were not qualities that endeared him to the hierarchy of
the Archdiocese of Philadelphia when Cipriano covered religion in
1992 and 1993. Cardinal Anthony Bevilacqua was coping with the
thinning out of congregations that resulted from the city's
dwindling population.
</P>
<P>
   ``This archdiocese was looking for consolidation,'' recalled
Arlene Notoro Morgan, who is The Inquirer's assistant managing
editor for readership. ``And every time a church goes down, a part
of somebody's past goes with it, and they mourn it and get upset
about it. Some of those people found their way to Ralph.''
</P>
<P>
   Cipriano covered protests and Bevilacqua's spending decisions.
The public relations consultant to the archdiocese, Brian Tierney
of the Tierney Group, started raising objections to Inquirer
editors. In an interview last month, Tierney confirmed, ``We did
repeatedly say that we would not cooperate in any story in which
Ralph is the lead reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Cipriano's editors folded his reporting about the
church closings and simultaneous spending on accouterments for a
conference center into a longer profile that Cipriano was preparing
on Bevilacqua. He protested that decision, contending that the
reports should stand on their own. And when there were delays in
running the profile, Cipriano said, ``I stopped writing anything,
for maybe a month,'' to press his editors into running the critical
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the profile was published in February 1993, Cipriano
agreed to switch beats and began covering the neighborhoods of
south Philadelphia. None of his editors will speak on the record
about his work in the years that followed, but their attitudes can
be inferred from details offered by Cipriano. By 1997, he said, his
editors told him he was unreachable too often and required him to
carry a cellular phone and to write more articles.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   There had been many changes at the newspaper over those four
years. Maxwell King, the editor who had succeeded Eugene Roberts in
1990, was himself preparing to step down. There were disparaging
comments around the city that The Inquirer was not the paper it had
been when Roberts' staff won 17 Pulitzers in 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had done some great stuff. but they really got soft,''
said Howard Altman, the news editor of The City Paper, an
alternative weekly. ``There was a move toward not offending
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is Cipriano's contention in his suit that The Inquirer
``did not wish to offend the archdiocese'' and risk losing readers
among the area's 1.4 million Catholics that particularly makes the
newspaper's editors bristle.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Editor William Ward said, ``I'm offended at the
accusation'' that the paper's staff was solely motivated ``by a
desire to raise circulation, or is caving to outside influences,
when I know these people have not done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal, who has been on vacation, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the editor of The Inquirer's Sunday magazine, Avery
Rome, assigned Cipriano to write another profile of Bevilacqua. In
a sequence that in Cipriano's account was an eerie echo of the 1993
battles, he discovered what he described as damaging information
about the cardinal that his editors were reluctant to print.
Infuriated by their objections and sure he was being unfairly
singled out for punitive treatment, he sought help from union
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gillin, who is also a shop steward for Local 10 of the
Newspaper Guild, corroborated Cipriano's account of a two-page
warning about his work habits and productivity that a city desk
editor gave to him. Several editors said they would not comment on
personnel matters.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, by the spring of this year, convinced the best of
his work would not make it into The Inquirer, Cipriano wrote a
10,000-word article on Bevilacqua for The National Catholic
Reporter, a weekly newspaper based in Kansas City, Mo. Among other
things, the article said the cardinal had authorized spending $5
million on renovations for three office buildings, his house, his
vacation home and improvements to a cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Frank Lewis, a reporter for The City Paper,
wrote an article detailing Cipriano's battles with clerics and
editors. Cipriano was quoted as referring to the cardinal as ``a
Pharisee.''
</P>
<P>
   When Howard Kurtz, the media critic for The Washington Post,
asked Rosenthal about Cipriano's contention that, for The Inquirer,
the cardinal was ``a sacred cow,'' the editor responded with his
criticisms of Cipriano's work.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ms. Gillen, ``People think that it was a stupid
thing'' for Rosenthal to have publicly criticized his reporter. ``I
agree,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Cipriano, she said, called her at home the day The Post
published Rosenthal's remarks and asked, ``Can the union file a
libel suit?''
</P>
<P>
   Cipriano said that it was a union lawyer who encouraged him to
file the suit, which also names the paper's parents, Knight Ridder
and its Philadelphia Newspapers Inc. unit, as defendants. But it
was Cipriano who selected Beasley, the paper's nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Both in the suit and in an interview, Beasley echoed Cipriano's
contention that the newspaper's fear of declining circulation _ now
433,489 on weekdays and 871,659 on Sundays, down from 545,000 daily
in 1983 and 1.01 million on Sundays in 1985 _ made it reluctant to
take on the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   It is an irony not lost on the newspaper's current and former
editors that Beasley, who won libel judgments for a lawyer and a
judge whom he argued were tarred by aggressive reporting done to
bolster circulation, is now arguing that The Inquirer has gone soft
to raise circulation. They are reluctant to comment on the record
about the lawyer, however.
</P>
<P>
   But the deputy foreign editor, Marc Kaufman, expressed the
feelings of several colleagues in commenting on Cipriano's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the newsroom feel kind of awful for everyone
involved,'' he said. ``Ralph was generally liked, however much
people might have thought that he had kind of tunnel vision on this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   People also liked Rosenthal, Kaufman said, ``and feel the paper
is getting ready to take another major step up, not down. Everybody
feels a little let down that they weren't able to work it out.
Everyone feels a little knocked around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
