<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-STOCK-STARTUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY START-UPS SUFFER MARKET JITTERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass., N.Y.)   (jw) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a month of hot and heavy flirting about a prospective
merger, last Monday was going to be the day that CKS Group and
USWeb finally got serious and set the price. Then the stock market
started falling, dragging with it the already-depressed shares of
both companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things just froze,'' Mark Kvamme, the chief executive of CKS,
an interactive advertising agency, said in describing how the $340
million deal with USWeb, an Internet programming and services
company, came to a standstill. ``We just stayed in our offices
watching the market on our computers. We just hit return, return,
return'' to get up-to-the-second quotes on how far each company's
stock had fallen.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, their screens showed that CKS stock was
down 18 percent while USWeb had dropped 16 percent. That was close
enough that the two companies were able to proceed with their deal,
which was announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And that was the way things were playing out in the offices of
start-ups throughout the high-flying technology industry, which had
been watching a slide in market value for weeks before Monday's
plunge. After that day of frozen panic, by the end of the week,
much of the business was cautiously proceeding as before.
</P>
<P>
   Sure the Nasdaq market, where most technology company stocks are
traded, closed Friday down 22 percent from its high on July 20, but
it is still essentially flat for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for many technology executives, the jumpy movement of the
market within a narrow range last week created the sort of nervous
anticipation felt on a plateau in one of those darkness-enclosed
roller coasters: you know the next move will be sudden and fast;
you just do not know whether it will be up or down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no real effect on the mood here yet,'' said Garrett
Gruener, a venture capitalist with Alta Partners in San Francisco.
``But if the Nasdaq were to drop another 20 percent, that wouldn't
be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   If the market fell further and looked as if it was not going to
bounce back, the voluminous investments by venture capitalists and
public stock investors in small technology companies would slow,
bankers and investors say. And the existing companies would have to
scramble for cash.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, there is still a lot of money poised to be invested
in promising new start-up companies involved in information
technology and the Internet. Less certain, however, is how many of
the two- and three-year-old companies now lined up to sell stock to
the public will be able to do so in a suddenly skittish market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not pain or panic here in the Valley,'' said David
Cowan, a venture capitalist with Bessemer Venture Partners in Palo
Alto, Calif. ``But there is concern. A stalled stock market will
create billionaires at a lower frequency.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, more than a few longtime technology financiers see the
fall in technology stocks from outer orbit to mid-stratosphere as a
sign of some rationality in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I lost a lot of money, but I think it's very
healthy,'' said Richard Burnes Jr., a partner in Charles River
Ventures, an old-line venture capital firm in Waltham, Mass.
``Stock prices had taken on a life of their own, and that is very
dangerous for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnes said he was worried about the billions of dollars that
have poured into venture capital funds. Over the last few years,
the soaring market for technology stocks has allowed many of these
funds to post returns of 50 to 100 percent a year as they take the
young companies in their portfolios public or sell them at equally
high prices to bigger technology companies. Now, anyone who can tap
out a business plan in Powerpoint has come to expect ready cash and
lucrative terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrepreneurs come into our office who don't have $1 million
in revenue and they expect to value their companies at 30, 40, 50
million dollars,'' said Fred Wilson, a partner at Flatiron
Partners, a New York venture capital fund. ``That's absurd. You
can't make money investing in companies like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Flatiron, he said, has stopped making investments and has
encouraged the companies it owns to raise cash as a cushion in case
of a downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Other funds say they are still investing, only more cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at things differently than I did two weeks ago,''
said Geoffrey Yang, a partner with Institutional Venture Partners
in Menlo Park, Calif. ``We will still invest, but the prices we pay
could come down 20 to 25 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   And the mad rush may have slowed, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deals that would have been done in a week are now taking six
to eight week to get done,'' Yang said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet other observers say all this talk of discipline will be
quickly set aside as the venture capitalists realize they need to
put to work the billions of dollars they have raised for their new
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much capital out there that the supply will drive
up the prices of deals,'' Cowan said. ``That means the return of
the funds will ultimately go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the venture capitalists write their first checks to the
budding entrepreneurs, their minds almost immediately turn to the
``exit strategy.'' That is, how they can sell the company at a
tenfold multiple, either to the public or to another company. In
tougher times those multiples may not be possible.
</P>
<P>
   For now, deals of all sorts have slowed until the state of the
market becomes more clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``A record number of public offerings have been pulled in the
last month or two,'' said Alex Lynch, the co-head of the public
offerings practice at Brobeck Phleger &AMP; Harrison, a law firm that
specializes in high-technology firms.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best indicators of the strength of the market will be
the fate of the public offerings planned for the next few months.
These include E-Bay, a rapidly growing Web site that lets people
run their own auctions, and the Globe, a New York-based chat
service aimed at Generation-X.
</P>
<P>
   Even if these companies are not going to be able to proceed with
their public offerings, they will still be able to raise money from
venture capitalists and other private investors.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies that had already gone public issued more stock
over the summer, taking advantage of the surging market to build a
cash reserve to ride out a period of tight money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We completed a secondary offering two months ago, adding $22
million to the $47 million we already had in the bank,'' said Jason
Olim, the chief executive of CD Now, an online music store. ``Our
burn rate is probably $10 million a quarter,'' he said, referring
to the deficit spending common at start-up companies. ``So we have
a stockpile of cash that will last us longer than a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as stock prices fall, some midsized technology
companies may find themselves in a position to buy other companies
whose stocks have been hit even harder than their own.
</P>
<P>
   Some entrepreneurs say that a perhaps less visible consequence
of the careening market for technology stocks is the toll it takes
on employees with the perhaps enviable problem of coping with the
sudden appearance and disappearance of paper wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get concerned about the morale of people in the company if
everyone is looking at the stock price all day,'' said Christos
Cotsakos, the chairman of the E-Trade Group, an online stock
brokerage firm. ``When your stock price rockets up like a meteor,
it creates false expectations. Then when the price gets hammered,
it drives people crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in recent years, every dip in the market has been followed
shortly by another surge. And many longtime executives worry that
too many newcomers to technology companies have never seen a truly
down market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's scary to me is a lot of kids are coming here
who think that their options are automatically going to go up by 40
percent a year,'' Kvamme of CKS said. ``It's terrible when people
start to believe they are invincible.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet to many young entrepreneurs, it seems perfectly clear that
the Internet, is, in fact, changing everything, and that they can
ride this wave to prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see only progress, only growth,'' said Olim, the 29-year-old
founder of CD Now. ``Value is being created at such a dramatic pace
that it overwhelms any macro-economic phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Kvamme, a 34-year-old alumnus of Apple Computer who has seen a
few of Silicon Valley's earlier surges and dips, says that things
are a lot more vulnerable now than they might seem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a feel-good business,'' he said last week. ``Any time
there is uncertainty, it erodes confidence. Then decisions take
longer; people stop spending. And once they stop spending, things
only get worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
