<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980906.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1612 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVING-MUSICIANS-ART-     09-06 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVING-MUSICIANS-ART-620(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGUE FOR FREQUENT FLIERS: TRANSPORTING INSTRUMENTS REQUIRES A
VIRTUOSO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo of Gordon Gottlieb is being sent to NYT photo
clients. 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gordon Gottlieb laid out the Polaroid shots of the
massive daiko drums he bought in Japan while touring Asia with the
New York Philharmonic in July. He rattled off their dimensions: The
biggest drum is 29 inches long and 90 inches in circumference with
a head that is 24 inches across. Each was hand-crafted from a
single piece of wood and took up to four years to make.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb is nearly as famous for his international collection of
instruments as for his technical prowess as a percussionist. And
his latest additions, the gleaming drums, sat safely in his Chelsea
loft, having moved through Kennedy Airport without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always this easy.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, after performing in Brazil, Gottlieb stood at the
same airport, 15 fiberglass cases in a heap by his side, as he
waited in vain for the cartage company he had hired to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   First he got angry. Then he got serious. Somehow he hauled the
cases out of the terminal and persuaded two taxis to drive in
tandem back to his loft, the cases piled high in their front and
back seats, tied into their trunks and strapped to their roofs. He
rode in the first and prayed the second would follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was desperate,'' he remembered. ``Here I was, stranded with
an army's worth of valuable stuff, in bad shape, and with no one to
get me out of the mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget the years of training, the hours of rehearsals, the
nightly performances and even the stage fright. For thousands of
musicians who, like Gottlieb, play instruments larger than a
piccolo, just getting there is more than half the battle. And in
summer, when musicians crisscross the continent _ and sometimes the
world _ on the festival circuit, the living is far from easy.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the professionals come in: the travel agents and
cartage companies and production managers who get their clients,
and their clients' equipment, to their destinations and home again.
</P>
<P>
   After his fiasco, Gottlieb turned to Gary Boxer, the owner of
Sound Moves LLC, a Manhattan company dedicated solely to
transporting equipment for musicians and recording studios. Boxer
counts among his ``few hundred'' clients percussionist Jack
DeJohnette, saxophonist Michael Brecker and pop singer James
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Needs vary, from the special dolly required to transport a harp,
to the coffinlike container custom-designed to hold a bass
saxophone, to ``holding pens'' for equipment too large to haul in
and out of pint-size apartments. But the goal is the same: getting
the client from point A to point B with minimum hassle.
</P>
<P>
   Large ensembles may have it easiest, relying on production
managers to handle the logistics of transporting instruments,
equipment and even wardrobes. Hank McHugh, the production manager
for the Dave Matthews Band, has moved the group among some 100
sites since April. A veteran of 23 years with performers like Tom
Petty and the Heartbreakers, Hall and Oates, and Bob Dylan, McHugh
approaches his job with assured nonchalance.
</P>
<P>
   He oversees the contents of six 48-foot-long trucks, part of a
caravan that also includes six buses for the five musicians, 21
crew members and 12 drivers. Each morning by 7, McHugh and his team
plot the layout for a new stage, keeping it as similar as possible
to the last one. At 8, they begin a four-hour ordeal of unloading
trucks packed with instruments, lighting, sound equipment and
speakers, and making repairs to anything that is broken in the
process. They also set up the band's opening act.
</P>
<P>
   After the show, the crew takes it all back down, in a mere 90
minutes. ``It's amazing how things come apart more quickly when
you're thinking about going to sleep,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Not every instrument can withstand the conditions in an airplane
baggage hold. Most string instruments, made of tender, aged wood,
fly in the cabin with their owners.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Salm, the cellist with the Raphael Trio, knows the
intricacies of moving her instrument across continents and oceans
perhaps a bit too well. In addition to shuttling among apartments
in New York; Venice, Italy, and Vienna, Austria, this summer, she
performed at festivals ranging from Juneau Classics and Jazz in
Alaska to Music in Ouray in Colorado, where the trio is the
ensemble in residence, to the Chenango Festival in Hamilton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salm works with Jean Furukawa at VTS Travel in Manhattan,
who first makes sure that an appropriate plane and seat are found
to transport the musician and her cello. (Not all planes are
suitable because of the variations in the distance between the
seats and the overhead compartments. And cellos must almost always
rest in a window seat in a bulkhead row.)
</P>
<P>
   In her student days, she could often talk the cello's way on
board, Ms. Salm said. But today she buys a full-fare ticket for her
instrument. When she travels as part of an ensemble, her colleagues
share the cost. Frequent-flier miles earned by the cello may not be
honored by the airline. After the security check, Ms. Salm carries
her cello on board, where it is strapped into a seat using a
seat-belt extension. Some airlines, like British Airways, require
that a trained specialist do the strapping.
</P>
<P>
   War stories abound, from the amusing (in retrospect) to the
unnerving (like the time she was booked on a flight but her cello
was booked on standby).
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, there was a real horror story. Returning to
New York from London, her cello already ticketed, Ms. Salm was
informed that the plane was completely full, and despite the
cello's fully paid ticket, it was being bumped for a human
passenger. The cello would be relegated to the baggage hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a choice,'' she remembered. The airline promised
that the cello would be hand carried on and off the plane. At
Kennedy Airport, she claimed her suitcase and waited for the cello
at the designated rendezvous. And waited. ``Finally, three people
came over and said: `Aren't you Susan Salm? We don't know how to
tell you this, but there's no cello on that plane.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told them the value of the instrument they had just
lost, they freaked, maybe even more than I had.''
</P>
<P>
   A day later, the airline found Ms. Salm's Marconcini cello, made
in Ferrara, Italy, in the 1700s and worth about $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling with instruments ``never becomes a joy,'' said Rose
Hirschel, the owner of Musicians' Travel Services, a Manhattan
company that has specialized in making arrangements for musicians
for 15 years. Insurance is necessary, since airlines are not
responsible for damage to instruments, she said. ``My experience
has been that airline employees are not so much impressed about the
value of an instrument but rather the age.''
</P>
<P>
   New Federal Aviation Administration guidelines for carry-on
baggage, implemented on April 15, have also adversely affected
musicians like violinists, who normally stow their instruments in
overhead compartments. A violin case now falls outside the new size
guidelines. But the woodwind players often have the hardest time
clearing security.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about the intricacies of the mechanism in a
wind instrument _ the rods and keys _ that are more likely to
arouse suspicion,'' Ms. Hirschel said. ``That and oboe players, who
travel with reed tools. They have all sorts of curious ways of
getting through.''
</P>
<P>
   To a security agent, those tools, with which oboists make the
reeds for their instruments, can look like an arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use knives, files and screw drivers,'' said Bert Lucarelli,
who taught an oboe seminar this summer at Music Mountain in Falls
Village, Conn., and performed at the Festivalde Artes de Itu in
Brazil. ``When I think of it, I'm smart, and put it in my luggage.
When I forget about it, that's another story entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Lucarelli forgot, he was playing in London. After
much debate with customs officials, he finally persuaded them to
give his tools to the pilot, who carried them back to New York. ``I
played oboe for them when we landed because they couldn't believe
this had anything to do with my instrument.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass saxophones are perhaps the most difficult instruments to
ship, Ms. Hirschel said, because their cases resemble small
coffins. And though the instruments ride in the cargo hold, ``it
still requires a certain type of charm to get the case onto the
plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Vince Giordano has perfected that charm. A free-lance musician
and former leader of Vince Giordano's Nighthawks, a big band that
has serenaded society functions ranging from the wedding of Steven
Spielberg and Kate Capshaw to President Clinton's Inaugural Ball,
he plays perhaps the most unwieldy trio of instruments imaginable:
a bass saxophone, a string bass and a tuba. For him, ``traveling
has always been a crazy adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the adventure was trying to get cases that
would withstand the abuse of airline baggage handlers, one of whom
once threw a case with such force that the wheels penetrated the
shell and damaged his gold-plated antique saxophone.
</P>
<P>
   He went to a metal shop, which riveted large sheets of
one-eighth-inch-thick aluminum to the case, increasing its weight
to 122 pounds with the horn inside, making it virtually ``airline
proof,'' he said. But then a new FAA regulation banned oversize
cargo on commercial airplanes. Giordano would now have to ship his
saxophone on a cargo plane, adding a day on each side of the trip
to make sure the instrument was there when he landed. The cost:
$120 each way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all leads to the joke, `You should have taken up the
flute,''' he said with a sigh. ``I wish I had a quarter for every
time I heard that, because I'd be able to pay all my excess baggage
costs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
