<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: BOARD GAMES FOR FUN OR EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Mo., N.J., Minn., Puerto Rico)  (lb) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Labor Day is generally a celebration of time off from work and
school. Millions of people will spend the day in back yards, beside
pools, or at beaches and camp sites. Many of those will pass the
time with games _ sports, cards and board games _ without realizing
that they are playing with patented inventions.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, hundreds of ball games, computer games, board games,
card games, arcade games and athletic games win patents each year.
Some are variations on games like poker or blackjack; others are
electronic, miniature or portable versions of traditional games
like basketball or football, and still others are creative hybrids
like golf-pool tables.
</P>
<P>
   Board games generally depend on players rolling dice to move
game pieces around a specific course, but the objectives of newly
patented games are often surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Up to six people could while away Labor Day playing Laurence
Brown's political board game. Players are randomly assigned a role
_ either as elected politicians or as members of a particular
constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Each turn begins with the roll of three differently colored
dice. A card is then drawn from a set that raises political
questions on which the players vote. The cards are divided into
public-interest fields like domestic and international affairs,
taxes, crime or the federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cards raise constitutional or ethical dilemmas.
Players can be ejected from the game if they are impeached for
unethical behavior or conflict-of-interest voting, or because their
votes violate the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who lives in Springfield, Va., says in his patent that
the object of the game is ``to direct voter attention to the
perspective of issues from various points of view and public
interest and to hone voting judgment and skill.'' He received
patent 5,769,715.
</P>
<P>
   Mathematics may not sound like a subject for an enjoyable board
game, but Patrick Thompson believes people can sharpen their math
skills with his game. Thompson, from Joplin, Mo., designed a board
divided into several pie-shaped wedges. Within each wedge are small
boxes bearing the numbers 1 through 15, and there is a set of cards
with instructions to add, subtract, divide or multiply.
</P>
<P>
   Each player is assigned a section of the game board, draws a
card and then rolls one, two or three dice. The player has up to 60
seconds to follow the instructions on the card he drew to calculate
a solution using the numbers on the dice to arrive at a figure that
appears on his part of the board. The object is to cover that
number with a chip and keep playing until all the numbers in the
section are covered.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson says that if a player ``rolls 4, 5 and 6, and draws the
add card, he could add all three to get 15,'' and then cover the
number 15 on the board. The player loses a turn if the calculation
is not done within the time limit. Players can challenge one
another's calculations, and remove an opponent's chips if the
challenge is successful. Thompson received patent 5,772,209.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since Labor Day often includes picnics and barbecues, Ruth Bard
Pierce's new board game might be enjoyed more on another day. The
game is called ``Fat Chance,'' the objective is ``winner loses
all,'' and play revolves around losing as much weight as possible.
Players are issued tokens that represent pounds of excess weight,
and a predetermined amount they have to lose to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   The game board is laced with routes that players can choose to
follow _ one is called Healthy Lifestyle, another is Crash Diet and
a third is named Excuses. Players roll dice and move game pieces
along the route they have selected. Each space along the path
indicates how much weight the player loses or gains within each
turn.
</P>
<P>
   Players who choose the Healthy Lifestyle path lose weight more
slowly than those on the Crash Diet, but crash dieters gain back
more. Along the way, players can land on question-and-answer
spaces, which require them to draw a card and answer a question.
Correct answers mean more pounds lost. The winner is the first
player to lose all of his or her weight. Ms. Pierce, who lives in
Annandale, N.J., received patent 5,704,611.
</P>
<P>
   For teen-agers preparing for their first driver's license test,
Gilberto Lopez has created a game that uses tokens, dice and cards
to reinforce the rules of the road. Lopez, who lives in San Juan,
Puerto Rico, designed a board with playing spaces that look like
roads, traffic signals and traffic hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Players roll the dice, move around the board and earn points by
memorizing and obeying safety rules, signs and speed limits. Cards
drawn on certain spaces raise questions just like those ``on the
written driver's license examination,'' Lopez says in his patent.
He won patent 5,749,580.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Schmid's patent doesn't cover a game, but rather
clothing with a game-board design and detachable playing pieces.
Ms. Schmid, who lives in Shelby Township, Minn., came up with the
idea of clothing bearing game-board patterns across the front or
back, and a series of hook-and-loop, or Velcro, fasteners.
</P>
<P>
   Game pieces like dice, tokens, chips, or player icons attach to
the garment at the fastener spots. To play the game represented on
the clothing, the garment is taken off and laid flat. Players then
pull the game pieces off and they're ready to go. Ms. Schmid holds
patent 5,734,991.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
