<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Sept. 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much cooler air will surge across the Great Lakes states into
the interior Northeast on Monday. A cold front marking the leading
edge of the autumnal air mass will be accompanied by clouds and a
broken band of showers and thunderstorms. The strongest
thunderstorms are expected later Monday afternoon and evening in
the Middle Atlantic States, where several hours of sunshine will
add energy to the developing storms.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the front, winds from the north will gust over 25
miles an hour. A few showers will develop in the very cool air over
the northern Great Lakes and southern Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Another day of unseasonable heat will prevail from Virginia to
the interior Southeast. Sunshine will be plentiful in most
locations, although thunderstorms will erupt near the central
Appalachians as the cold front approaches from the north. Clusters
of clouds and thundershowers will brush the Gulf of Mexico coast.
Locally heavy showers are expected near the Texas and Louisiana
shores.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sunshine will boost temperatures to near 100 degrees
again over Texas and Oklahoma. Near the periphery of the hot air
mass, scattered afternoon thunderstorms will develop over parts of
the central Plains. Meanwhile, cool, dry air will spread over the
northern parts of the Plains and Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The western states will stay very warm with a mixture of
sunshine and clouds. Afternoon thunderstorms will form over many
mountains from the Sierra to the western slopes of the central
Rockies. A weak front will bring increasing clouds to the
northwestern coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Autumn by the Bay
</P>
<P>
   A surge of autumn chill will reach the Northeast this week
signaling summer's waning days. But in San Francisco late summer
and early fall are typically the warmest time of year. In midsummer
the city is often cooled by breezes from the 60-degree ocean water.
With the jet stream far to the north, weather systems are weak, so
local winds are the dominant influence. At this time of year, the
jet stream moves south, steering stronger lows and highs into the
Pacific Northwest. Clockwise flow around highs brings brisk winds
from the east, which temporarily push the maritime air out to sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
