<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-OPPOSITION-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIA JOURNAL: MEET MACHIAVELLI? THE MONKEY WRENCH IN CAMBODIAN
DEMOCRACY? 
 (NK)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ ``Read this,'' said Sam Rainsy, stepping
out of the room to dress for a political rally. ``A different point
of view.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a pro-government newspaper with a front-page editorial
that declared: ``Mr. Sam Rainsy, the machiavellian, maverick,
opportunistic, selfish, foolish and irresponsible politician, a
self-proclaimed opposition leader, must be prosecuted to the full
extent of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a familiar characterization here in a country where Sam
Rainsy, 49, seems intent on keeping the political pot boiling until
he can achieve his goals. Not only the government but also many
diplomats see him as a power-hungry spoiler too convinced of his
own righteousness to even consider a compromise with his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Sam Rainsy's own view and that of many Cambodians is
different. He sees himself, as do his many supporters here and
abroad, as a democratic idealist who has ``lost any illusion about
working with rotten people in a rotten system.''
</P>
<P>
   He is ready to paralyze the Parliament, to bring down the
government, to force this exhausted and poverty-stricken country
into a new round of elections and confrontations if that is what it
takes to achieve what he calls a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dream of a modern Cambodia,'' he said, returning from his
bedroom in a clean white shirt. ``I have lived more than half my
life in Europe and I have spent many months in the United States
and I can see the difference between a modern society and a
backward society.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, a modern Cambodia means, first, the rule of law. It
sounds elementary, but it is crucial. Without that, we just have a
feudalistic system of warlords, of people who have guns and money
and who are just above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   He was clearly referring to the power structure of Hun Sen, who
has led the country _ first as a Communist, then as a prime
minister, then as the leader of a coup _ for most of the last two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pretend we have a market economy but I call it a jungle
economy,'' Sam Rainsy said. ``The difference is, there is no legal
framework. This is a real revolution because they are powerfully
entrenched interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks after a parliamentary election in which his party, the
Sam Rainsy Party, finished a distant third, Sam Rainsy has brought
the country to a standstill with a vigorous campaign of protests
and rallies and political maneuvers that threaten to block the
formation of a new government.
</P>
<P>
   In Cambodian terms, his campaign is already something of a
revolution: He is not using guns. Instead, in a style he has
perfected over the last few years, some diplomats say he is
taunting Hun Sen's government to use its guns against him, to
discredit itself and make martyrs of him and his followers.
</P>
<P>
   On March 30, 1997, unknown assailants threw four grenades at a
rally he was leading in a park, killing 16 people and wounding more
than 100. Sam Rainsy blamed Hun Sen for the attack; Hun Sen said
Sam Rainsy himself was behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the last two weeks, Sam Rainsy has led thousands of
people in a rambunctious sit-in at the same park, which he has
called Democracy Square.
</P>
<P>
   Through determination, intelligence, political astuteness and
physical courage _ and with the partnership of his wife, Saumura _
Sam Rainsy has become a powerful political force.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of him and his wife, one Western analyst with long
experience in Cambodia said, ``They are people who have a zeal and
who see themselves as historical figures in a struggle for the
future of Cambodia.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Educated in France and Britain, eloquent in three languages, Sam
Rainsy inspires strong feelings of both adulation and mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   He has unsettled many foreigners with the gutter language of his
attacks on Hun Sen and with his diatribes against the Vietnamese
minority. A wave of violence has taken the lives of at least five
ethnic Vietnamese in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of his efforts, the parliamentary election held
on July 26 has produced only political turmoil. In a vote Sam
Rainsy disputes, the election was won by Hun Sen's Cambodian
People's Party, which took 64 of the 122 seats.
</P>
<P>
   In second place, with 43 seats, was the royalist party of
Norodom Ranariddh, who was ousted by Hun Sen in a coup a year
earlier from the co-premiership the two men shared. The party of
Sam Rainsy, who had in turn been ousted from the royalist party by
Prince Ranariddh in 1995, won 15 seats.
</P>
<P>
   None of the three parties won the two-thirds needed to form a
government. Sam Rainsy has persuaded the prince to join him in his
protests and in his refusal to form the needed coalition with Hun
Sen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be the democratic alibi in such an
authoritarian system,'' Sam Rainsy said. ``If I cannot be part of
the cure, I do not want to be part of the disease.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that the prince is as convinced as Sam Rainsy of
this position. But analysts say Sam Rainsy may have maneuvered him
so deeply into his protests that it will be difficult for the
prince now to do an about-face and accept pomp and financial
rewards of a coalition government that Hun Sen is offering.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Rainsy may or may not be sincere in the democratic ideals he
espouses. But he shares with his two rivals a frank and deep-seated
mutual animosity that is more than enough to sustain his campaign
against them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
