u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HBO-FAMILY-535&AMP;ADD-NY     09-06 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HBO-FAMILY-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASHING IN ON A PROGRAMMING TREND 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mention HBO, and most people think adult thoughts. The pay-cable
network is best known for sophisticated movies, R-rated comedy and
big-time boxing, with the occasional provocative documentary thrown
in. The words ``family fare'' definitely do not come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   But having seen how rapidly the market for family programming is
expanding, HBO is now leaping into that world, too, with a 24-hour,
commercial-free supplementary cable channel called HBO Family,
which the company is busily preparing for a February debut.
</P>
<P>
   HBO, which is owned by Time Warner, has done some family
programming in the past, ranging from serious documentaries like
``Smoke Alarm: The Unfiltered Truth About Cigarettes'' and ``Faces
of Addiction'' to quirky children's shows like ``Fraggle Rock'' and
``Little Lulu.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was sporadic, and not perceived as a real attribute of
our service,'' said Sheila Nevins, HBO's senior vice president of
original programming. ``Now we've decided to go into family
programming in a big way.''
</P>
<P>
   In competitive terms, HBO may already be a little late. HBO
Family is being developed at the same time as several other new
family-oriented cable services, including the completely revamped
Fox Family Channel, begun last month; Noggin, a co-venture of
Nickelodeon and the Children's Television Workshop, due in January;
and a channel still in development by Hallmark Entertainment, Jim
Henson Co. and the Odyssey network.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Paxnet, a new broadcast network of 95 UHF stations,
started last Monday, with its schedule completely devoted to family
shows, mostly reruns of series like ``Touched by an Angel,''
``Eight Is Enough,'' ``Bonanza'' and the ``Father Dowling Mystery
Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all of these start-ups, the new HBO effort is intended to
catch the wave of demand that has helped Nickelodeon become second
only to ESPN as the most profitable network in cable television and
has enabled the Disney Channel to raise its ratings 34 percent and
expand its subscriber base 56 percent _ to 41.8 million households
_ in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's an overcrowded marketplace,'' Ms. Nevins said.
``We will be distinctly different. We understand the competition,
and we think there's room for one more.''
</P>
<P>
   She also sees an opportunity for HBO to make money from this
venture. New programming that the network develops can be sold in
the international marketplace, where demand for well-produced
children's shows is high. She would not discuss financing, but an
HBO executive who spoke on condition of anonymity said HBO would
invest about $18 million in programming for the new channel.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nevins said the new channel, like HBO itself, would be free
of commercials (unlike Nickelodeon, Fox Family Channel or the
broadcast networks) and of shows designed with the selling of toys
or other products in mind (like Fox's ``Power Rangers'' and
``Spiderman'' or WB's ``Men in Black'').
</P>
<P>
   ``And it will have the HBO edge,'' she said, describing it as
``slightly sarcastic but not anti-parent, like Nickelodeon,'' and
``educational but not as heavy-handed as some shows on PBS.''
</P>
<P>
   The slogan promoting it, matching the network's initials, is
``Honest, Brainy, Outrageous.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The channel will have a combination of original programming
(some for very young children, some for older children), some shows
based on traditional children's books, like ``Babar,'' and PG-rated
movies from HBO's vaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to differentiate ourselves as not just being a
kiddie channel,'' said Ms. Nevins' colleague, David Baldwin, senior
vice president of program planning. ``And many of our subscribers
still perceive HBO to be a movie network, and we want to use that
inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the channel would have preschool programming in the
morning, movies or children's specials from noon until 4 p.m.,
educational game shows for older children in the later afternoon,
and family movies at night.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nevins said she hoped the children's shows would set HBO
Family apart from the competition. For preschoolers, she said: ``We
wanted something that wasn't furry animals getting all
snuggly-wuggly and saying `Let's all cooperate' or `What can we do
on this nice rainy day?' We thought the best thing is to go back to
pots and pans and all those ordinary things that kids really love
to play with _ a mop or a pail or a pencil.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``A Little Curious,'' a preschool show co-produced
by John Hoffman of HBO and Curious Pictures, creators of
``Pee-Wee's Playhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Characters named Bob the Ball, Mr. String, Mop, Doris the Door
and Pad and Pencil (a sultry pair of lovebirds who sound like
Morticia and Gomez in ``The Addams Family'') all cavort in three
different video forms _ traditional hand-drawn animation, computer
animation and puppets. Each show teaches two or three basic
concepts, like the difference between ``slippery'' and ``sticky''
or ``near'' and ``far.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all the other series for younger children are being
developed with one of three top children's production studios
(Nelvana, Cinar and Hit Entertainment), and include ``George and
Martha,'' ``The Adventures of Paddington Bear,'' ``Anthony Ant,''
``Pippi Longstocking'' and ``The Country Mouse and the City Mouse
Adventures.''
</P>
<P>
   The older children's offerings include a program called
``Crashbox,'' which will feature game shows about historical
figures, math, vocabulary, animals and ecological topics, all
linked to World Wide Web sites where viewers can actually play the
games and get responses.
</P>
<P>
   Dolores Morris, the HBO Family vice president supervising the
older children's programs, is especially proud of ``30x30: Kid
Flicks,'' which is a half-hour series featuring films or ``video
diaries'' made by children, ages 8 to 18, and discovered in various
school, museum or community-center film programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to say we're putting the edge back in education,'' Ms.
Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   HBO subscribers will be able to get HBO Family at no additional
charge _ if their cable systems have enough capacity to carry it
and choose to offer it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
