<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN OR LOSE, FANS LOVE GOING TO BALLPARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The critics are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the current economic trend in major league baseball,
the Seattle Mariners don't need Randy Johnson, Jose Cruz, a new
manager or six new relief pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   All they need is more Beanie Babies. Which leads to another
conclusion. The M's don't need a new stadium. They need a toy
store.
</P>
<P>
   Each day of every summer, half the teams playing baseball will
make their fans unhappy. Any composer, performer or producer with
such a record of failure would be drummed out of show biz.
</P>
<P>
   The late Bill Veeck verbalized this basic challenge to the sport
he loved. And he determined that it was necessary to ensure that
his fans went home with some positive memory.
</P>
<P>
   Veeck sponsored baseball's first Bat Day. He gave free tickets
to anybody who showed up at the ballpark with a musical instrument
and then he led the concert.
</P>
<P>
   Between innings Veeck would call lucky-seat winners down onto
the field. The ``prize'' might be a new car, a lifetime supply of
bubble gum or a gaggle of live geese, and a Bo-Peep staff to herd
them off the field like sheep. On ``Turkey Day'' he gave away live
birds, but first you had to catch them. The White Sox still have a
``Dog Day'' when mutts and their owners get in free, a legacy of
Veeck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the Indians win last night?'' a fan would ask his
neighbor, who attended the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the guy might respond. ``But between innings they gave
some fan a wheelbarrow containing 7,000 silver dollars. He couldn't
move it an inch. You shoulda been there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the M's win last night?'' the 1998 baseball fan is asked
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, but we all got Mariner Moose Beanie Babies. You shoulda
been there.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's owe their remarkable attendance to the legacy left by
Veeck. He was the first executive to order his players to wear
their names on the back of their uniform shirts. He let female fans
in free every Saturday in Cleveland. He sponsored Joe Fan Nights
and on one occasion burned a soldier's home mortgage in a bonfire
hauled out into center field on a trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Veeck introduced fireworks and exploding scoreboards. After a
home run ignited the first explosion, the Tigers threatened to
protest. When he installed baseball clown Max Patkin as his first
base coach, the Yankees threatened to protest. When Veeck sent a
midget up to the plate as a pinch hitter for the St. Louis Browns,
Detroit did file a protest.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody threatened to protest when Veeck upgraded the food served
at his ballparks in St. Louis, Cleveland and Chicago. He blended
his hot-dog spices to achieve a perfect formula, rather than accept
the standard brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The packing houses told me some consumers were offended by
garlic,'' Veeck confided during one visit to Seattle. ``They told
me other people won't tolerate even a small amount of red pepper.
So they were turning out hot dogs that didn't offend anybody,
because they didn't have any taste.''
</P>
<P>
   At Veeck's ballparks they got tasty hot dogs, along with a
baseball game and a few circus acts.
</P>
<P>
   And fans returning home from a day game might celebrate Turkey
Day at the ballpark with a feast like this.
</P>
<P>
   Peanuts and Turkey
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds turkey tenders
</P>
<P>
   7 tablespoons lemon juice, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons ketchup, divided
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoons oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Tabasco to taste
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup light cream (or evaporated milk)
</P>
<P>
   Cooked rice to serve four
</P>
<P>
   Whack the turkey tenders into cubes about 1 and one-half inches
square. Marinate 1 to 3 hours in a mixture of 6 tablespoons lemon
juice, the minced garlic, 3 tablespoons ketchupand the salt.
</P>
<P>
   At dinner time heat the oven broiler and distribute the turkey
hunks on skewers. (If you use bamboo rather than metal skewers,
make sure they have been thoroughly soaked in water.)
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan combine the leftover marinade with the peanut
butter, 1 tablespoon oil, 1 tablespoon lemon juice, 1 tablespoon
ketchup, light cream, sugar, and Tabasco to taste. Warm over low
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Place the skewers on a flat pan covered with aluminum foil,
about 2 inches from the heat. Broil a couple of minutes on each
side but try not to overcook the turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Divide turkey hunks over four plates with some rice. Top the
meat with peanut sauce and serve, possibly with some:
</P>
<P>
   Stir-fried Cabbage
</P>
<P>
   1 small head cabbage
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped ginger root
</P>
<P>
   6 chopped green onions, including tops
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   Core the cabbage and cut into inch-wide strips. Slice strips
into 3 or 4 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large skillet and stir-fry the garlic, green
onions and ginger 2 minutes. Add the cabbage and continue to
stir-fry until it is soft to the bite. Add salt and pepper and this
should serve four.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know how Veeck marked the occasion when his highly touted
Cleveland Indians were eliminated from the American League race in
1949? He staged a funeral procession at the ballpark. The
pallbearers, wearing black suits and top hats, marched slowly out
from the dugout and then buried the pennant in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Say, that would be a terrific promotion for the '98 Mariners.
They could bury the pennant and Lou Piniella's cap in the same
hole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
