<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1629 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDTERM-POLITICS-ART-     09-06 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDTERM-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES(800)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH PARTIES VIEW LEWINSKY SCANDAL AS ELECTION DAY WILD CARD
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MIDTERM-POLITICS-RACES) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As they take to the trail this Labor Day for the
traditional opening of the fall campaigns, Republican and
Democratic candidates say the Lewinsky matter, a jittery stock
market and tumult abroad have thrust them into the most unsettled,
and unpredictable, election season in years.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty has already altered the calculations of
Republicans, who say they have the most to gain, particularly from
President Clinton's difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Newly emboldened, Republican officials have revised their
earlier predictions of modest gains and now say the party could
capture more than a dozen additional seats in the House and,
perhaps, even pick up five seats in the Senate. That would hand
Republicans the magic 60 votes needed to cut off a filibuster when
Democrats try to block a vote.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Democrats find themselves on the defensive, and
party leaders are lowering their expectations; most have stopped
brazenly forecasting that they will retake the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so much better than a couple months ago,'' said Brent
Siegrist, the Republican leader of the Iowa House. ``I do think
Clinton's troubles help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans now have the slimmest House majority held
by any party in the last half century, few Democratic leaders are
upbeat about their party's prospects for retaking the House, and
some party candidates are distancing themselves from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running my own race _ and I don't plan on running any
events with him,'' said Ken Lucas, a Democrat who is locked in a
tight House race in Kentucky. The latest Democrat to spurn Clinton
is Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening, who said he ``will not pursue
the attendance of the president'' as planned for a fund-raising
event next month.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Boston, at the annual meeting of the American Political
Science Association, the corridor chatter among academics was not
about political theory but fresh gossip about the Lewinsky
investigation and how it would play out on Election Day. Perhaps a
telling piece of evidence was that among the hundreds of academic
papers presented, the association ran out of copies for one in
particular demand: ``Compassion, Political Trust and Public
Opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., said the ``formless uncertainty''
in the electorate may be welcome news for Republicans trying to
maintain their 11-seat majority in the House. He suggested that
voters may want to keep GOP control of Congress as a check on the
turbulence in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, what people want is stability in our government,
which I think bodes well for incumbents,'' McDermott said. ``I wish
they wanted to throw out the Republican majority and bring in
Democrats, but I think the uncertainty fosters the stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Voter participation in the statewide primaries this year has
been the lowest on record, which suggests that turnout in November
could be the lowest in history, according to a study by Curtis
Gans, director of the Committee for the Study of the American
Electorate. He and other experts said that could bode well for
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Their hope is that while Democrats will be uninterested,
Republicans will be energized by Clinton's troubles and will
eagerly head to the polls to vote against his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like '94, where we had a bump up out of
anger,'' Gans said. ``What you have at this point is disengagement
but not profound anger _ except on the Republican right.'' If
conservative voters are motivated by their anger at Clinton, he
said, that would give Republicans an edge in close contests.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the theories about depressed Democratic turnout and
an excited Republican electorate, polls thus far have not shown any
major upheaval in how people expect to vote or broad disaffection
with the Democratic Party. Despite signs that Clinton's personal
approval is eroding, his job approval rating remains impressive.
And despite Democrats' complaints that the Lewinsky debacle is
crowding out their attempts to talk about issues, there is no
statistical evidence that Clinton is dragging down Democratic
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, much of the sense of a changed electoral landscape in
both the Republican and Democratic parties is founded on anecdotal
evidence. Two weeks ago, Stuart Rothenberg, an independent
political analyst, predicted that the Democrats would pick up two
or three seats in the House. Now, he says, the Republicans could
capture 10 or 15 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain his change of heart, Rothenberg said: ``I don't
have micro or macro data that shows either a national move or a
move in individual races. We're going on gut here. You don't
discount gut. But you don't go too far.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of this year, politicians in both parties,
noting that voters seemed relatively content and disengaged from
politics, had forecast a status-quo election, where incumbents
would be safe and Republicans would cling to control Congress by
roughly the existing margins.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the buoyed spirits among Republicans, there are
still two months before Election Day. Politicians around the
country say they are bracing for a political hurricane with untold
consequences: They know it will hit but they do not know when _ or
with what force.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a massive, dramatic shift in the makeup of Congress
would be a surprise because far fewer than 100 House seats are
considered hotly competitive. That is because there are fewer open
seats than is traditional and many incumbents face particularly
weak rivals this year. A surging economy through much of the year
and unusually high approval ratings for Congress discouraged many
challengers from running.
</P>
<P>
   Several candidates said the biggest wild card will be the report
by Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth Starr, which may be
issued this month. This is the first time since Watergate was
unfolding in 1974 that a general election campaign has occurred
amid a full-scale presidential scandal. But by Labor Day of 1974 it
was already clear to most strategists that Republicans would take a
huge hit that November. (Republicans lost 48 seats in the House and
five in the Senate.) This year, it is not as clear what the
reverberations could be for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates also said that the dramatic downturn _ and partial
rebound _ of the stock market this week and the economic and
political crisis in Russia starkly reminded them how outside forces
could intrude on their carefully laid campaign strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``These developments have changed what was a very placid
election season to one that has a lot more uncertainty,'' said
Chris Bayley, a Republican running for Senate from Washington
state. ``Six months ago everyone assumed that since the economy was
good, incumbents would be favored and it would be harder for
challengers.'' Citing the financial crisis in Asia, he said,
``Everybody is much more nervous now.''
</P>
<P>
   William Carrick, a veteran Democratic strategist in Los Angeles,
put it this way: ``I've never seen anything like this _ it's a
very, very strange season. We're all analytically groping for what
is this election about: Is it a referendum on the president? It
doesn't appear to be so. But it's clearly not a referendum on
Congress. Then you add in this enormous reluctance by the American
public to even get engaged in following the politics of any of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many Republican candidates said they were uncertain
whether to make the Lewinsky matter an issue, several said they now
planned to raise the broader topic of trust. The scandal also seems
to have brought a broader overlay of moral scrutiny to the
campaign, and on Friday led Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., one of the
president's most persistent critics, to acknowledge that he is the
father of a child born out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every one of us is going to have to run on
integrity,'' said Fay Boozman, a Republican running for the Senate
from Arkansas. ``I think there is a strong sense of the lack of
integrity of elected officials, and the breaking of the public
trust by elected officials. Bill Clinton is the headliner of that
because he is the President, but it crosses party lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some Democrats, spurred, perhaps, by the strong rebuke of
Clinton last week by Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., said Clinton's
problems would force them to discuss issues like morality. ``Here
in this particular race, integrity and taking responsibility for
your actions and honesty are big factors,'' said Lucas, the
Democrat running in Kentucky. ``And I think the recent events in
Washington are highlighting that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some Democrats said they feared that all the talk of trust
would drown out the discourse about their party's marquee issues
such as education, health care reform and preserving Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will distract from the ability of candidates to articulate
the issues we think are important,'' said Jay Inslee, a Democrat
seeking a House seat in Washington. ``It's kind of like a wreck on
the freeway. The traffic going the other way is watching the wreck
instead of paying attention to where we're going. It's a
distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many candidates in both parties have felt somewhat
neglected as the press focuses its energies less on electoral
politics and more on scandal in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Even the high-profile contests such as for governor of
California and senator from New York have drawn relatively little
attention. Contributing to the dilemma for candidates is that,
judging by the polls and by interviews with strategists, no single
issue seems to be gripping voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask about anything under the sun,'' said Rep. Adam Smith,
D-Wash. ``But no real issue is grabbing folks.''
</P>
<P>
   David Osterberg, a Democrat who is taking on Sen. Charles
Grassley of Iowa, is so frustrated by his failure to draw attention
that he is trying a new stunt: paddling across the state in a
canoe.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rath, a longtime Republican strategist in New Hampshire,
predicted that rather than energize voters, the Lewinsky matter
would make voters even less engaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think people want this whole process to go away,'' he
said. ``There's a tiredness in the electorate. They don't have the
stomach for a highly contested election season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
