<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1631 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TALK-0907-COX     09-06 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TALK-0907-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATIC, GOP LEADERS SEE CLINTON AT LEAST FACING CENSURE
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Political pressure mounted against President
Clinton on Sunday, as
</P>
<P>
   a prominent Democrat said he should be formally censured and
Republican Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott countered that
impeachment proceedings appear increasingly likely.
</P>
<P>
   With Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr due to report on his
investigation into the Monica Lewinsky scandal as early as this
week, Lott said that, based on what Clinton has already admitted,
it was doubtful that Congress would simply censure the president.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not saying that . . . that it's not a possibility, but
right now I'd say that's not likely,'' Lott, R-Miss., said on the
NBC-TV's Sunday program, ''Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Censure -- a formal way for Congress to register its collective
condemnation without exacting further punishment -- could be
considered ''nothing,'' by some people, said Lott. ''I don't think
that the circumstances now call for something, you know, that would
be interpreted by anybody as 'nothing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's comments came on the heels of a Saturday announcement by
Maryland Gov. Parris N. Glendening, a Democrat, that he was
cancelling a scheduled fund-raiser with Clinton, out of fear that
the White House scandal could mar Glendening's own tough
re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Clinton still plans to participate in
similar fund-raisers, such as events scheduled for later this month
in Florida and New York, and that Glendening's move was not part of
a trend.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have to say that has been an exception,'' White House
Communications Director Ann Lewis said on the CNN program, ''Late
Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lewis, ''There's been a lot of interest in presidential
events, and that interest continues.''
</P>
<P>
   Glendening, who was to appear on Tuesday with Clinton at an
elementary school in a Washington suburb, denounced Clinton's
behavior in the Lewinsky matter, cancelled his Tuesday appearance
and a fund-raiser that had been set for Oct. 2, but stopped short
of prescribing punitive action against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., however, said he favored
censuring Clinton and hoped that would avert the need for a
wrenching impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who took to the Senate floor on Thursday to upbraid
Clinton for his admitted affair with Lewinsky and his seven-month
campaign to deceive the public on the matter, said censure would be
a way of ''setting up a standard of accountability, saying to the
country, to history, to our children, 'What the president did was
wrong and unacceptable.'''
</P>
<P>
   Also appearing on ''Meet the Press,'' Lieberman said he hoped
''that will be the maximum we will want to do to end this sad
chapter in our history.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats were not so sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Jim Moran, D-Va., told the Fox television network's
''News Sunday'' program that the best Clinton can hope for is
censure, but he doubted the House of Representatives would stop
there.
</P>
<P>
   ''I now don't think that's really an option,'' Moran said. ''I
think we're bound to go through with impeachment proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments were echoed by veteran Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we have before us, and we ought to get on with it, is an
impeachment procedure,'' Moynihan said on ''This Week,'' ABC-TV's
Sunday news program.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a crisis of the regime,'' said Moynihan. ''You cannot
have this kind of conduct as normal and acceptable and easily
dismissed, unless there is a great effort to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if in addition to what we know there are things we don't
know, that would make it worse,'' he said, referring to the
possibility that Starr's report could contain revelations that
further damage Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   It is the role of the House, beginning with the Judiciary
Committee, to determine whether Starr's report contains allegations
that merit impeachment proceedings. If the House votes to impeach,
the Senate would try Clinton and vote on whether to remove him from
office. A two-thirds majority vote is required.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Constitution deliberately does not spell out
impeachable offenses, stating only that presidents may be impeached
on charges of ''high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defenders have said that it is premature to talk about
impeachment before Starr reports to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the moment we know one thing conclusively: the president
engaged in some rather significantly immoral acts,'' Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., said on the CBS television network's ''Face the
Nation'' program.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not clear whether that constitutes a statutory offense
that in any way approaches the constitutional standards on
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan said, however, the threshold for impeachment is high,
yet broad.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are the moral issues which are also relevant. An
impeachment process does not turn on legalities,'' Moynihan said.
''It's for being someone we don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, whose criticism of Clinton has formed a rallying
point for Democrats in recent days, said he believed Clinton could
survive censure and restore to his administration the credibility
and moral authority needed to govern.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that doing so ''may be the greatest test,'' of
Clinton's career.
</P>
<P>
   ''My highest hope here is that President Clinton is able to
repair the damage that his misconduct has done and go on to end his
presidency in two and a half years honorably and effectively,''
said Lieberman. ''I'm confident he can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas, however, concurred with
Lott. ``It is almost certain that a House committee is going to
consider more than one article of impeachment,'' Gramm said on
CBS's ``Face the Nation.'' ``I think we have passed the point where
we might wish this away.''
</P>
<P>
   Allegations surfaced in January that Clinton had an affair with
Lewinsky, a former White House intern, and later urged her to lie
about it under oath. Clinton denied both charges at the time in a
sworn statement in connection with the Paula Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit, which has since been dismissed. He also denied
both charges in an explicit statement to the American public. He
admitted on Aug. 17 to a relationship with Lewinsky that was ''not
appropriate,'' but insisted he had not counseled her to lie about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who returned late Saturday from a trip abroad, had no
public appearances on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
