<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-TANZANIA-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MORE SUSPECTS ARRESTED IN TANZANIA BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania _ Investigators have arrested two more
suspects in the bombing of the U.S. Embassy here and have made
significant progress in determining how the bomb was made and taken
to the embassy, FBI and local police officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests came in the same week that agents investigating the
simultaneous attack on the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya, began
focusing on a Muslim businessman from the Comoros, a republic of
islands off East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The two explosions on Aug. 7 killed 258 people and wounded
thousands. Of those killed, 11 died in the blast here. Two men have
been arrested so far and charged in U.S. District Court in New York
in connection with the attacks after being deported from Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, federal agents said the bombings were the work
of Al Qaeda, which they said was an international terrorist
organization financed and controlled by Osama bin Laden, a Saudi
Arabian businessman who supports militant Islamic causes.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reported Sunday that an arrest warrant had
been issued in New York for the Comoros businessman, known as
Abdallah Mohammed Fadhul, along with a sealed complaint against
him.
</P>
<P>
   A law-enforcement official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Sunday that there was a sealed complaint charging a new
suspect in the Kenya bombing but would not say if it was Fadhul.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is clear that FBI agents are searching for Fadhul. On
Wednesday, several U.S. agents accompanied by the Comoros police
raided two homes on the island of Moroni, searching for him. The
agents took Fadhul's wife and brother into custody for questioning
and collected evidence from the houses.
</P>
<P>
   Fadhul, who remained at large Sunday night, was reported by The
Associated Press to have been living with his wife in Sudan until
shortly after the embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   In Nairobi, law-enforcement officials who spoke on condition of
anonymity said they had determined that at least four men had been
involved with the bombing there. The two already arrested in
connection with the blast are Mohammed Saddiq Odeh and Mohamed
Rashed Daoud Owhali.
</P>
<P>
   Owhali told investigators that he and another man had driven a
delivery van carrying the bomb to the embassy in Nairobi, court
papers say. He said he had thrown a small explosive device at
guards at the embassy's rear entrance just 10 seconds before the
bomb exploded, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, who has not been identified, is believed to have
died in the blast, but Owhali survived and was arrested in a
hospital, law-enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Odeh left Nairobi on a plane to Pakistan the night
before the bombing. He has admitted to the FBI that he was a member
of the organization that planned the bombing but has denied taking
part, court papers say. Despite his statements, law-enforcement
officials say they suspect that Odeh provided logistical support to
the bombers.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators in Nairobi are also looking for a fourth man
who goes by the first name Abdallah, according to witnesses who
have been interviewed by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   James Nganga, the manager of the Hilltop Lodge _ a seedy hotel
where Odeh and other suspects stayed in the three days before the
bombing _ said agents had searched his records for the name
Abdallah Sadiq and asked him repeatedly if he knew a man by that
name. The agents also showed him at least five pictures of people
he did not recognize, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Early last week, FBI agents detained and questioned Abdallah
Mohammed, the Nairobi manager of the Islamic charity Mercy
International. The charity, with branches in Sudan and Somalia, is
suspected to have links to bin Laden, law-enforcement officials
said. Agents have seized the organization's records, though
Mohammed was later released.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Wednesday agents raided the homes of Abdallah Mohammed
Fahdul in the Comoros.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Horan, the FBI's special agent in charge of the
investigation, declined to say if Fahdul was a suspect in the case.
Nor would she comment on other aspects of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investigators here said in a news conference on
Saturday that they had determined what the bomb had been made of
and who had carried it to the embassy. But they would not give
details, saying that doing so would jeopardize the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Rajabi Adadi, Tanzania's director of criminal investigation,
told reporters that the police had two suspects and three new
witnesses in custody. He did not name them.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Piernick, head of the FBI investigators in Tanzania,
said investigators ``have made extraordinary discoveries,'' but he
would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are now well aware of the composition of the bomb and are
also well aware how the device was delivered and who delivered
it,'' he said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Adadi said one suspect arrested was a Tanzanian businessman and
the other was a foreigner. Adadi declined to comment on unconfirmed
local press reports that one of the suspects was a Sudanese
businessman named Amin Abdul Majid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police have some leads regarding the event,'' Adadi said.
``They know who took the device to the embassy, and they also know
some of the people responsible for the event and others whose roles
have not yet been proven.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the three witnesses in custody had all played a role in
the preparations for the bombing, though unwittingly, and were now
cooperating with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Local newspapers reported that one of these witnesses was Thomas
Lyimo, a well-known merchant who owns a string of milk and yogurt
outlets in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
   There have been unconfirmed reports in Kenyan and Tanzanian
newspapers that the ingredients for the bombs came from the Middle
East and were transported by sea through the Comoros to Tanzania.
Reports in the Nairobi press said the explosives were taken from
Tanzania to Nairobi by truck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
