<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFGHAN-IRAN-ASSESS-AR     09-06 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-IRAN-ASSESS-ART-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSION BUILDS BETWEEN IRAN AND AFGHANISTAN'S TALIBAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Although all-out war appears unlikely, the tens
of thousands of Iranian troops deployed in a threatening buildup
along the Afghan border have drawn attention to the hostility
between two of the world's most conservative Islamic governments.
</P>
<P>
   To some non-Muslims in the West, the bearded Shiite Muslim
clerics who govern Iran and the bearded Sunni Muslim Taliban
militants who now control most of Afghanistan may appear
indistinguishable, united by religious fervor and a shared belief
in an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
   But they represent two wings of a great Islamic divide. And as
the Taliban have consolidated their hold on power, imposing a
strict vision of Islam across Afghanistan, Iranian leaders have
responded with contempt and dismay.
</P>
<P>
   They have accused the Taliban _ whose restrictions, particularly
on women, are far more rigid than those enforced in Iran _ of
giving Islam a bad name. They have provided support to the rival
Afghan militia that is the Taliban's sole remaining foe.
</P>
<P>
   And now there is the issue of the disappearance of scores of
Iranians, including at least 11 diplomats, who were caught up in
the fighting in Afghanistan last month. Iran has raised the
prospect of taking military action against the Taliban unless
reports that the Iranians were captured or killed can be quickly
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   A commentary on Iranian radio on Saturday said the country had
the right ``to take all necessary action'' against the Taliban
movement under an article of the U.N. charter that guarantees a
right to self-defense. That has prompted a harsh reply from Taliban
leaders, who were quoted Sunday as saying that their followers were
prepared to spill blood to fend off any incursion.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Sunday, Arab diplomats and other experts said they
thought it unlikely that Iran really intended to mount a full-scale
invasion. They said the Iranian buildup, which began last week with
military exercises that included 70,000 troops, was almost
certainly intended as a show of muscle.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, officials at the State and Defense Departments,
as well as intelligence analysts, said there were no new signs that
Iran was preparing an attack. ``There was apparently a skirmish on
the border, and some Afghan border guards may have been killed, but
it seems to involve drug traffickers and is not related to this
buildup,'' said one American official.
</P>
<P>
   One senior American official who monitors the region said that
if Iran did retaliate, air strikes were more likely than a major
land offensive. The officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab diplomats and other experts said that having suffered
through a long war with one neighbor, Iraq, from 1980 to 1988, Iran
probably had little appetite for becoming involved in what could be
another protracted conflict.
</P>
<P>
   That assessment appeared to be strengthened by comments
published Sunday from Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, who was reported to have told a gathering of students on
Thursday that there would be ``no confrontation with Taliban.''
</P>
<P>
   But the diplomats and experts said deep public anger in Iran
over the fate of the diplomats made any prediction risky. They said
a possible scenario remained for Iran to provide military support
for a limited attack into southwestern Afghanistan in which the
leading role would be played by several thousand exiled Afghan
fighters who have been given refuge in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed al-Sayed Said, a senior researcher at Al Ahram Center
for Strategic Studies in Cairo, said that even such a ``very
limited operation'' could serve Iran's purposes if it succeeded in
forcing the Taliban to turn their attention away from beleaguered
opponents and thus prevented the movement from consolidating its
hold over Afghanistan as a whole.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I don't think Iran has to do anything,'' said Ahmed Rashid, a
writer on Afghan affairs who was quoted in a Reuters dispatch from
Pakistan. ``It has thousands of fighters exiled in Iran, and all it
has to do is rearm them and relaunch them.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Pakistan, the United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia
recognize the Taliban movement as Afghanistan's legitimate
government. The United Nations and all other members still
recognize the deposed president, Burhanuddin Rabbani. But along
with Russia, Iran has been among the most active in providing
support to militias opposed to the Taliban, according to
Tehran-based diplomats who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Although it denies the charge, the diplomats say that in the
past two years Iran has regularly used military aircraft to fly
military and other supplies to the northern city of Mazar-i-Sharif,
which was a main opposition headquarters until it was captured by
Taliban forces on Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   That city was also the base for the Iranian diplomats and the
journalist who have been missing since the takeover, adding to a
sense of Iranian outrage from a collapse that itself was a blow to
Iranian influence and prestige. The Taliban leader, Mullah Mohammad
Omar, has said that the diplomats are ``probably dead.''
</P>
<P>
   A report last week fom the human rights group Amnesty
International also contributed to Iranian anger. It said that
thousands of civilians were killed in the capture of the city and
that most were Shiites from Afghanistan's Hazara ethnic minority.
Because Iran sometimes portrays itself as a guardian of Shiites
worldwide, experts in the region said Sunday it may feel under some
pressure to respond with military force if it can be proved that
the Shiites were attacked for reasons of religious faith.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Iranian newspapers have debated the wisdom of a
military move against the Taliban, with hard-line conservative
publications supporting a strike and most moderate dailies
advocating self-restraint.
</P>
<P>
   With its ban on most work by women, and its prohibitions of
television, radio and most other forms of entertainment, the
Islamic regime imposed by the Taliban in Afghanistan since they
took control of the capital, Kabul, in 1996, is certainly the
world's strictest _ more so than even Saudi Arabia's.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years after they established the Iranian Republic
in 1979, Iran's revolutionary leaders took a similar pride in
rewriting what had long been accepted rules of conduct. The country
follows strict precepts of Islamic law. The rigid rules that still
govern, for example, how a woman must dress when she appears in
public, mean that Iran still ranks among the world's most
restrictive societies.
</P>
<P>
   But most revolutionary passions have mellowed in Iran over the
last two decades, and some social restrictions have been
considerably eased, to the extent that Iranian officials now point
to the Taliban as an example of misguided religious excess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
