u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-BONUSES-ART-9     09-06 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-BONUSES-ART-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS SWEETEN OFFERS AS DEMAND FOR TEACHERS EXCEEDS SUPPLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., Mass., Calif., Neb., Alaska, N.Y., Mont., Iowa, Ky.,
Texas, Ariz.)  (ART ADV: Photo of Lasheaka Timmons in a classroom is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Baltimore this summer, prospective special-education teachers
were in such demand that they were offered more money than the
union contract requires: those with just a year's experience got
the starting salaries of four-year veterans _ the equivalent of a
$2,000 raise before ever putting chalk to blackboard. And like
applicants in all other subject areas, they were also entitled to
reduced-rate mortgages and low-interest $1,500 loans for
relocation.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, teaching candidates will soon be able to
compete for an even bigger windfall: Acting Gov. Argeo Paul
Cellucci signed a law last month establishing $20,000 signing
bonuses for nearly 200 of the most promising rookie teachers who
apply to work in the commonwealth's schools next year.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a new law curtailing bilingual education, California
districts remain so desperate for teachers who speak languages like
Spanish and Vietnamese that some are offering bonuses of up to
$5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Long accustomed to being supplicants in the labor force,
candidates for public-school teaching jobs _ especially in special
education, math and science _ are being put in the decidedly
unfamiliar position of being wooed with financial sweeteners.
</P>
<P>
   In making those overtures, recruiters from even the smallest
districts have logged thousands of miles in the spring and summer,
with those from teacher-needy states like Nevada and Alaska
canvassing universities in upstate New York, Montana and Iowa,
where there are far more rookie teachers than available jobs.
</P>
<P>
   New York City recruiters, frustrated in their search for
qualified math and science teachers, looked as far as Austria,
where they hired 23 instructors eager to escape widespread teacher
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Even substitute teachers, the second-class citizens on so many
faculties, have found themselves in demand: so depleted are the
ranks of substitutes in Kentucky that the state has allowed some
districts to hire those with only high school diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past,'' said Marcia Brown, the director of personnel
administration for the El Paso Independent School District in
Texas, ``what this school district has had to offer has been enough
to attract teachers: the climate, good sound programs and a safe
working environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now,'' she said, ``because every district across this
country is running short, especially in the high-need areas, the
competition is tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Outbid countless times this past year by districts in Dallas and
Fort Worth, which offered signing bonuses of $500 to $2,000 to
hundreds of teaching candidates who committed virtually on the
spot, El Paso has decided to join the fray. Beginning later this
fall, new math teachers hired in El Paso will have their $25,012
starting salaries increased by $2,000 bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Buffeting the current market are rising enrollments _ the
schools in Las Vegas have had to hire 2,000 new teachers over each
of the last two summers, largely to accommodate an influx of 20,000
new students _ as well as a drought of college graduates choosing
teaching careers, especially in math and science.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on districts is building as total public and
private school enrollment is expected to reach a record 52.7
million this fall, which the Department of Education says would
exceed the record high last fall by 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   And the competition promises only to get fiercer. The department
expects new enrollment records to be set for at least the next
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Public school rolls are expected to grow by 4 percent over the
next decade, to 48.3 million from 46.4 million, as hundreds of
thousands of teachers hired in the late 1960s and early 1970s
retire.
</P>
<P>
   While education experts say that signing bonuses and other perks
signal a new respect for teachers in some quarters, they say they
worry that such measures will amount to little more than a Band-Aid
on a profession that is in danger of hemorrhaging.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, as districts around the country seek to fill
vacancies even after schools have opened for the year, they say the
best they can offer are virtual carrots. Yet they say they have
learned that even the most modest of gestures can cinch a
candidate's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Lasheaka Timmons, 23, who graduated last spring with a degree in
secondary education and social studies from the University of
Arizona, was offered a job teaching a continent away at West
Baltimore Middle School, through Teach for America, which places
rookie teachers in urban districts. But Ms. Timmons said she would
have had to turn down the job, and work instead in Phoenix, without
the $1,200 loan to cover moving expenses that school officials
offered her through the municipal workers' credit union.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Timmons is to pay back the loan at a rate of 13 percent _
better than that offered by most credit card companies _ through
weekly deductions from her paycheck over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just out of college, unless you come from a background where
your parents can afford to help you, especially coming from
Arizona, you wouldn't be able to relocate,'' she said. ``It
definitely makes you feel they want you.''
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore officials say that such perks, as well as mortgage
loans that are discounted by one-eighth to one-quarter of a point,
provided the teachers settle within the city limits, have been
mentioned as critical enticements by several dozen of the more than
700 teachers hired over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Baltimore schools opened last week, the district had
been unable to fill nearly 100 vacancies, especially for
special-education and elementary school teachers, needed to reduce
class size, and officials said they were still hiring. ``If you
could slant your story that way,'' Albrie Love Jr., personnel
director for the Baltimore schools, told a reporter, ``I would
appreciate it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, where 59 percent of teaching applicants failed
an entrance examination last spring, officials said they hoped to
use the $20,000 bonuses, spread over the first four years of a
teacher's career, to entice 175 of ``the best and the brightest''
into the profession each year. Under the program, up to 300
high-performing veteran teachers would receive bonuses of $50,000
divided over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Kathleen Kelley, president of the Massachusetts Federation
of Teachers, said it would take far more than bonuses to elevate
the working conditions for teachers in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affects so few people,'' Ms. Kelley said. ``It's a drop in
the bucket, and it doesn't take a systemic look at the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Lupe Cruz, a bilingual education teacher in California with more
than a decade's experience, said she ranked the reputation of the
superintendent and his sense of teamwork as her top priorities in
choosing this summer to move from a nearby district to the Alum
Rock Union Elementary School district in East San Jose. Of no
weight, she said, was the $1,000 signing bonus that she received
for being a certified bilingual education teacher.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she says that she intends to spend the bonus money on
her students.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's $1,000 when you look at it,'' she said. ``It's not
going to pay for a major vacation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
