u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HOMERUN-BALL-TAXE     09-06 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOMERUN-BALL-TAXES-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMO TO FANS: GENEROSITY COULD HAVE DIRE CONSEQUENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ If a fan catches the ball that breaks baseball's
home run record and generously gives it to the slugger, it could be
more than a great baseball event. It could be the taxable event of
a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Fans attending games featuring Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa might
want to buy extra tickets for their accountants. According to the
Internal Revenue Service, the bleacher bum who paid $6 to $10 for a
ticket _ not the multimillionaire slugger _ could owe federal gift
tax. For a fan giving a million-dollar ball to McGwire or Sosa, the
federal tax could reach $150,000 or more. And states also have gift
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The person receiving a gift owes no tax.
</P>
<P>
   The gift tax applies to ``any property'' worth $10,000 or more,
according to IRS regulations. It makes no difference under the tax
code whether the gift is cash, a diamond necklace or a
record-setting baseball. The tax is computed on the fair market
value of the gift.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the new, customer-friendly IRS has
the chutzpah to try to collect the tax from, say, a 12-year-old
baseball fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can confirm your understanding of how the gift tax works,''
an IRS spokesman, Steven J. Pyrek, said Sunday. ``The giver of the
gift is required to file the gift tax return. We'd have to take a
look at all the circumstances: the value of the gift and who owns
the baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   A ball that breaks Roger Maris' record of 61 homers could fetch
$1 million or more, sports collectors say. Already a donor who
asked to remain anonymous has offered to pay $1 million for the
ball to publicize the cause of three American nuns and a lay worker
who were murdered in El Salvador in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The ball is the property of major-league baseball until it
leaves the field. Then whoever catches it owns it. The tax
permutations are more complicated than figuring a slugging
percentage, but tax experts lay out several options:
</P>
<P>
   _ If the fan keeps the ball, the fan owes no tax now. But the
ball would become part of the fan's estate, taxable after death.
</P>
<P>
   _ The only way to avoid tax entirely is to give the ball to a
charity. Any charity could then sell the ball for a profit, which
would not be taxed.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the fan sells the ball, the fan owes tax on the profit,
just as the seller of any property would. The transaction would put
the fan in the highest tax bracket, with 39.6 percent due. The tax
on a million-dollar ball would be $396,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a taxable event when the fan catches the ball, but it
is if he sells the ball or gives it away,'' said Philip J. Benoit,
a certified public accountant with Weikart Tax Associates in
Manhattan. ``If a fan catches a ball, it's worth what the market
will pay at auction. You'd probably want to get three appraisals.''
</P>
<P>
   A fan who wants to sell the ball would be wise to keep it for at
least a year. Then it becomes a long-term capital asset, subject to
the maximum capital-gains tax rate on collectibles of 28 percent,
or $280,000 on $1 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If the fan gives the ball to the player or the baseball team,
the gift tax is triggered. But the tax would probably not cost the
fan money unless the ball had a value of at least $625,000. Any tax
on a gift up to $625,000 would probably be wiped out by the IRS's
unified credit. That lifetime credit allows every person to
transfer that amount _ either while alive or after death _ free of
estate and gift taxes. But it's a pay now or pay later situation: a
person who uses part of the unified credit for a gift has less of
the credit left to reduce estate taxes after death, according to
the IRS instructions for Form 709, the gift tax return.
</P>
<P>
   Anything beyond $625,000 would be taxed at a rate of at least 40
percent. So a person giving away a ball worth $1 million would owe
at least 40 percent of the remaining $375,000, or a tax of
$150,000.
</P>
<P>
   People often avoid gift taxes by not filing the gift tax return.
In the case of the Maris chase, however, it would be quite a trick
for the fan who catches the ball to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRS looks at a transaction when we look at the tax
return,'' said Pyrek, the IRS spokesman. ``The returns are selected
for audit based on a mathematical formula, not on what we see on
TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't the fan and the player make a deal to have the player
pay the gift tax?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the player pays your gift tax for you, then you'll have to
pay income tax on the gift tax you received,'' said Lawrence A.
Frolik, who teaches tax law at the University of Pittsburgh School
of Law.
</P>
<P>
   If the fan gives the ball to a spouse, no tax is due, because
the tax code allows unlimited gifts between spouses. Also not taxed
are the first $10,000 in gifts to anyone else during a calendar
year, gifts to charities or political organizations, or tuition or
medical expenses paid for someone.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa have said they would not pay for a baseball.
``I'm a baseball player,'' Sosa said, ``not a baseball fan.''
McGwire has warned, ``I wouldn't pay a dime for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players, however, have said they would accept the ball if a
fan gave it to them. Deni Allen, 22, who caught McGwire's 60th home
run on Saturday in St. Louis, gave him the ball in exchange for a
round of batting practice and a few season tickets. Allen will have
to file Form 709 if the value of the 60th ball is determined to be
worth $10,000 more than the value of what he received.
</P>
<P>
   Many baseball fans would love to see the ball displayed at the
National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum in Cooperstown, N.Y.,
where Maris' home run ball resides. Gifts to the Hall of Fame are
not taxed. And the Hall gives any donor a lifetime pass, a
certificate and a T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   A person who wants to give the ball to the player could ask the
IRS to view the gift as a charitable donation, especially if the
ball ended up in Cooperstown. Such a private-letter ruling was
granted in 1995 to the Kansas City Royals, when the team owner,
Ewing Kauffman, gave the entire team to a community foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar amounts are far beyond 1961, when 19-year-old Sal
Durante of Brooklyn caught Maris' 61st home run in the right-field
bleachers at Yankee Stadium. He offered it to Maris, who turned it
down. Durante sold the ball for a taxable $5,000 _ that's $27,200
in 1998 dollars _ to a restaurant owner, who eventually gave it to
Maris, who sent it to Cooperstown. It's not known if the restaurant
owner filed a gift tax return. Durante is now a bus driver and
grandfather living on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   The would-be Durantes are prepared. In the last row of the
left-field bleachers at Wednesday's game in Chicago while Sosa
batted, a fan held a scorecard in one hand and wore a baseball
glove on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already talked with my tax attorney,'' said the fan, who
did not give his name. ``He said to catch it and send it to
Cooperstown for the charitable deduction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
