<HEADLINE>
MIDTERM RACES TO WATCH THIS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDTERM-POLITIICS) 
(Also moved in `a' category) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the congressional and gubernatorial races to watch in
November's midterm elections:
</P>
<P>
   Senate:
</P>
<P>
   Current Lineup: Republicans 55, Democrats 45.
</P>
<P>
   Seats at stake: 16 Republican; 18 Democrats; 5 open (three are
Democrats and two are Republicans).
</P>
<P>
   To invoke cloture you need three-fifths of the Senate
membership, or 60 votes.
</P>
<P>
   California - Barbara Boxer (D), incumbent, vs. state Treasurer
Matt Fong (R):
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Boxer is a prodigious fund raiser, she finds herself
in an unexpectedly tight race against Fong, whose moderate stands
on most issues and ties to the Asian-American community could make
him formidable. Ms. Boxer is seeking her second term.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina - Ernest Hollings (D), incumbent. vs. Rep. Bob
Inglis (R):
</P>
<P>
   After five terms Hollings is facing a vigorous challenge in what
has become a solid Republican state.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois - Carol Moseley-Braun (D), incumbent, vs. state Sen.
Peter Fitzgerald (R):
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moseley-Braun has tried to deflect her personal
controversies by underscoring Fitzgerald's staunchly conservative
record. But he is wealthy and has launched a massive advertising
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada - Harry Reid (D), incumbent, vs. Rep. John Ensign (R):
</P>
<P>
   Reid's advantage as the incumbent may not be as valuable because
of a huge influx of new voters into the state and because Ensign is
grabbing some of the senator's support from casino interests.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky - Democrat Wendell Ford is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Scotty Baesler (D) vs. Rep. Jim Bunning (R):
</P>
<P>
   This promises to be a bruising contest and Sen. Mitch McConnell,
R-Ky., chairman of the National Republican Senatorial Committee,
has staked his reputation on electing Bunning from his home state.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina - Lauch Faircloth, (R) incumbent, vs. John
Edwards (D):
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth is considered one of the Senate's most vulnerable
incumbents and he faces a tough fight from Edwards, a wealthy
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   New York - Alphonse D'Amato (R), incumbent, vs. the winner of
the Sept. 15 Democratic primary:
</P>
<P>
   National Democrats would love to oust D'Amato, and a hard-fought
battle is expected from whoever wins the primary: Geraldine
Ferraro, Rep. Charles Schumer or Mark Green, the New York City
public advocate.
</P>
<P>
   House:
</P>
<P>
   Current Lineup: Republicans 228, Democrats 206, 1 Independent.
</P>
<P>
   All seats are up for re-election
</P>
<P>
   So far, there are 34 departures _ 24 retirements and 10 running
for other office.
</P>
<P>
   Governors:
</P>
<P>
   Current Lineup: Republicans 32, Democrats 17, 1 Independent.
</P>
<P>
   Seats at stake: 24 Republicans; 11 Democrats; 1 Independent.
</P>
<P>
   There are 18 incumbent Republican governors seeking re-election;
six are retiring. Six incumbent Democratic governors are seeking
re-election, and five are retiring or are barred by state law from
seeking another term.
</P>
<P>
   California - Republican Gov. Pete Wilson is barred from seeking
a third term. Attorney General Dan Lungren (R) faces Lt. Gov. Gray
Davis (D).
</P>
<P>
   While neither candidate is known as a scintillating campaigner,
this is the marquee race of them all because of the state's size
and political importance.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia - Democratic Gov. Zell Miller is retiring. State Rep.
Roy Barnes (D) faces Guy Millner (R).
</P>
<P>
   Barnes is a conservative, anti-abortion Democrat and Millner is
expected to make education a top issue and to far outspend the
Democrats even though both candidates are wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama - Fob James (R), incumbent, vs. Lt. Gov. Don Siegelman
(D):
</P>
<P>
   After a bruising primary where he was painted as a candidate of
the far right, James has to repair his image and is expected to
portray the moderate Siegelman as too liberal for the state.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico - Gary Johnson, (R), incumbent, vs. Martin Chavez
(D):
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say this represents one of their best chances to knock
off a Republican; Johnson is a relative newcomer to politics and
Chavez is considered a dynamic moderate Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois - Republican Gov. Jim Edgar is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Glenn Poshard (D) vs. Secretary of State George Ryan (R):
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are worried because Poshard is so conservative that he
has alienated many in his party, and because Ryan is expected to
far outspend him.
</P>
<P>
   Other important races where there is still a primary:
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii - Benjamin Cayetano (D), incumbent, vs. the winner of the
Sept. 19 Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland - Parris Glendening (D), incumbent, vs. the winner of
the Sept. 15 Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island - Lincoln Almond, (R), incumbent, vs. the winner of
the Sept. 15 Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts - Paul Cellucci (R), incumbent, vs. the winner of
the Sept. 15 Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota - Republican Gov. Arne Carlson is retiring. Both
parties have their primary on Sept. 15. The Democratic candidates
include Ted Mondale, Attorney General Hubert Humphrey III, Mike
Freeman, Mark Dayton and Doug Johnson. The Republican nominee is
likely to be St. Paul Mayor Norm Coleman.
</P>
</TEXT>
