<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980906.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1666 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORK-COX     09-06 1866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What about the kids?
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When stumped by child raising, Terry Maple, director of Zoo
Atlanta, goes back to the basics: ``What,'' he thinks, ``would a
gorilla do?''
</P>
<P>
   Maple is the father of three girls: 11, 16 and 18. And from the
very beginning, he believed the best way to care for babies _
whether humans, apes or lions _ is to keep them close to their
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Maple rejects the theory that it takes a village to raise a
child. Instead, he says, it takes just one set of attentive, loving
parents _ and he thinks work trends that separate children from
their mothers and fathers for longer and longer stretches cause
many of society's woes.
</P>
<P>
   But are parents' work schedules really to blame for so many of
today's problems? And if all women suddenly quit their jobs _ and
it usually is the woman who quits, statistics show _ and returned
to the home, would our children be better off?
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is more complicated than that,'' said Jay Belsky, a
professor of human development at Pennsylvania State University.
Belsky, who wrote a 1986 study that criticized day care, has since
softened his position. ``Child care _ relative to what else is
going on in a family _ has only a modest impact at best.'' A better
indicator, he said, is the financial and emotional stability of a
family.
</P>
<P>
   Many social workers and child advocates agree. They say parents
and society should look at other trends that have fundamentally
changed traditional family life, such as:
</P>
<P>
   Almost one in every three children now lives in a single-parent
home, according to the Census Bureau, an indicator that can
determine how much attention and supervision a child gets and the
amount of financial resources available.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhoods are no longer the rock of community standards.
Neighbors who once could band together to support and discipline
children don't know one another and certainly don't trust one
another with such responsibilities. That means there are fewer eyes
and ears to keep children on the right path.
</P>
<P>
   One in five children is impoverished, which often contributes to
a snowball effect of other ills, including inferior day care, bad
schools, lack of supervision and broken families.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is, middle-class suburban kids are doing
better than ever. Their prospects have never been brighter,'' said
Bill O'Hare, coordinator of Kids Count at the Annie E. Casey
Foundation, a private charitable organization for children in
Baltimore. ``But on the other hand, we have huge pockets of
inner-city minority kids who are falling further and further from
the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Shifting responsibility?
</P>
<P>
   For many, however, day care remains an easy target. Even
advocates admit that standards for child care are lacking. At this
summer's White House Child Care Conference, for example, experts
reported that less than 20 percent of day care is of high 70
percent is mediocre and another 15 percent is actually harmful.
</P>
<P>
   And day care remains the most volatile symbol of the
uncomfortable reality that many parents are paying others to care
for their kids.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the boom in day care and after-school programs in
the past three decades, no matter how wonderful the center or solid
the curriculum, opened the door for a fundamental shift _ and in
some cases, abdication _ of parental responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk in our society about how important children are,''
said Janet Scott, 62, a Gainesville social worker who has done
family counseling for more than 30 years. ``But we're killing them
(psychologically) through neglect and abuse pretty damn fast, so
maybe they're not as important as we say they are.''
</P>
<P>
   And the results are bleak. From just plain snottiness to
pregnancy and juvenile violence, the seeds of neglect in the early
years are bearing fruit of teenage rebellion and adult discontent,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   A poll conducted by Public Agenda, a nonprofit public opinion
agency, found only 37 percent of Americans thought today's children
_ once adults _ would make the country a better place. And less
than 15 percent of respondents thought it was common for children
to treat people with respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is the surprise?'' said Laura Schlessinger, a critic of
child care and a nationally syndicated talk show host with more
than 20 million listeners. ``If you don't take responsibility for
your children, if you don't make sure you're there when they need
you, why would you expect that everything is going to turn out
OK?''
</P>
<P>
   According to Kids Count, the 1995 teen birthrate was 36 per
1,000 nationally; up from 31 per 1,000 in 1985. Violent crime by
juveniles has almost doubled in 10 years. In 1995, law enforcement
agencies reported a rate of 507 per 100,000 arrests. In 1985, that
rate was 305 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Those two areas are important because researchers and family
advocates are increasingly tying such problems to a lack of
supervision. Public Agenda found in a 1997 survey that one in three
teens reported there was no adult at home when they arrived from
school.
</P>
<P>
   Other surveys have reported teen mothers saying they most
probably got pregnant between the hours of 3 and 6 p.m. And
researchers have reported most crime committed by kids occurs after
school, not after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The peak hours for juvenile crime were 2 to 8 p.m., according to
a report sponsored by Fight Crime _ Invest in Kids, a national
anti-crime group composed of police chiefs, prosecutors and crime
victims. And two-thirds of all juvenile crime occurred between 2
and 11 p.m., according to the group.
</P>
<P>
   A question of interest
</P>
<P>
   But working parents and day care operators say it's ludicrous to
compare using day care to neglecting your child.
</P>
<P>
   The longest-running and largest study of child care, conducted
by the National Institute of Child Health and Human Development,
found most children who attended were no more likely to have
attachment or behavioral problems than those who stayed at home.
</P>
<P>
   (That study was done after Belsky announced in 1986 that
children who spent more than 20 hours a week in day care failed to
attach to their mothers as well as children who stayed at home.
Since working on the NICHH study, Belsky has revised his stance.)
</P>
<P>
   And advocates say, if used in balance, day care can be a great
influence on children.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is ever going to love a child as much as the parents.
We are not substitutes for that and don't want to be,'' said Jody
Martin, who develops the curriculum for Children's World, a Golden,
Colo., corporation that runs 575 day care centers. ``But warm and
nurturing people are a plus in any child's life. And when you
combine that with a developmentally appropriate learning
environment, day care _ when you get past the stigma _ can be a
huge plus in a child's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Patti Truslow, a kindergarten teacher at Mary Lin Elementary
School in Candler Park, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Truslow said she would be unable to distinguish children merely
on the basis of whether they were at home or at a center before
they began kindergarten, because the best predictor of success is
far more subtle.
</P>
<P>
   It's not where the child spent time, but how he or she spent
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only common denominator I have seen is, you can definitely
tell which children have had someone read to them,'' said Truslow,
who has taught kindergarten for 12 years. ``They know more about
the world and they're much more eager to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Cumming resident Connie Williard said her 17-year-old son,
Derek, is an example of how child care can have a positive effect
on a child. Williard went back to work shortly after he was born,
and Derek stayed in day care until he started school. Once he
reached school age, he was in after-school programs for several
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had stayed home with him, he would not have had any other
children to play with _ especially with so many other moms
working,'' said Williard, 39. ``He would have been stuck at home
watching television.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he learned how to share and negotiate with other
children, she said. He also learned how to organize his day, with
workers telling him when it was time to do homework and when he
could play.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Montgomery, 35, also has used day care for her children,
Joshua, now 7, and Joel, 4. Both sons attend a Children's World
child care center in Smyrna, which provides a classroom for Joel
and an after-school program for Joshua.
</P>
<P>
   Like Derek, Montgomery's sons have grown through the experience,
learning to be more independent, outgoing and polite, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But both mothers say child care has worked for their families
over the years because they hold the ultimate responsibility. ``How
a kid turns out has nothing to do with whether you use day care or
whether you're working,'' said Williard. ``It all comes down to
whether an individual is interested in their child. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   A time to teach values
</P>
<P>
   Yet, too often, the balance seems precarious and doubts remain.
</P>
<P>
   Lanita Collins, 16, was adopted at 13 months old and is one of
three children of a divorced mother. From 13 months to 3 years, she
went to day care. From ages 3 to 9, she was home with her mom. When
her mother, Cassandra, returned to work, she was enrolled in
after-school programs until she was old enough to watch her
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Campbell High School student goes home after school and
starts chores, from making dinner to doing laundry.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said her experiences have been good, making her more
independent and responsible. She is a B student, attends church and
baby-sits.
</P>
<P>
   She is fiercely proud of her mother and the decisions her mother
has made.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when asked about how she would handle her own children,
Lanita said she would like to stay home with them for several
years, if possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to stay out until kindergarten,'' she said.
``Maybe I would go part time. But you know, I think it makes it
easier to make sure children are respectful, to make sure they have
the values you want them to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Montgomery, who said she is pleased with her day care
situation, also pines occasionally to be home like her mother had
been. ``As a child, I probably did not think of it as a gift, but
it was a given: Mom would always be around.'' That, Montgomery
said, gave her and her two brothers a security that sticks for
life.
</P>
<P>
   And security, Maple said, whether it be for kids or cubs, is one
of the keys to happiness.
</P>
<P>
   He points out that animals were raised in nurseries in the '70s
before a widespread movement to leave babies and young animals in
their family groups. The nursery experiment was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a bunch of little anti-social tigers, anti-social apes,
anti-social bears, who didn't know how to mate, function or live,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, humans believe they, too, can tear bonds without
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much stress and strain on the modern family _
trying to do too much in too little time,'' Maple said. ``Why do we
think the results will be any different?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
