<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETLINER'S FLIGHT DATA RECORDER IS FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: a 1stLd-Writethru with additional information is scheduled
to move by 9 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ Divers found the flight data recorder of
Swissair Flight 111 Sunday on a rocky stretch of sea bottom
littered with debris and at least three major pieces of wreckage of
the MD-11. The discovery raised hopes that investigators would soon
know why the plane crashed offshore here on Wednesday night,
killing everyone aboard, after a pilot reported smoke in the
cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   No additional remains of the 229 victims were identified on
Sunday _ the body of one passenger, a French woman, was identified
Friday and taken home _ nor were large numbers of victims found.
But officials were clearly relieved that the Navy diving tender,
the Sechelt, had found one of the plane's two ``black boxes.'' The
box, which is actually orange, was brought ashore late on Sunday
afternoon, where technicians immersed it in fresh water and sealed
it for immediate shipment to a Transportation Safety Board
laboratory in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Work there will begin immediately on arrival, said Vic Gerden,
the board's chief investigator, but a key question was whether the
device, which stores data in computer chips, would have to be
repaired before data could be examined. Another question was
whether an electric power failure, which investigators suspect
occurred on the plane about six minutes before impact, had disabled
the data recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gerden said in a briefing on Sunday evening, ``I would
say that the recovery of the flight data recorder is a very
important step in the progression of this investigation.'' Gerden
entered the briefing room knowing only that one of the boxes had
been recovered; an aide later crept on stage to whisper which one.
</P>
<P>
   (Investigators and searchers say they believe that the other
box, the cockpit voice recorder, was nearby, and a submarine, the
Okanagan, was still searching for it.)
</P>
<P>
   Also on Sunday, the medical examiner here said that the victims'
remains were simply in too many pieces to perform DNA analysis on
all of them, and that some of the smaller pieces would be put in
plastic bags and frozen until lawyers and ethicists could decide
what to do. The medical examiner, Dr. John Butt, said he had
conferred with his counterpart in Suffolk County, on Long Island,
who handled the remains of the passengers and crew from Trans World
Airlines Flight 800 two years ago, and concluded that the bodies
here were in much worse condition.
</P>
<P>
   The newly discovered wreckage field is about five nautical miles
southwest of Peggy's Cove, just outside the area in which searchers
had been conducting sonar mapping of the bottom. They found three
major pieces of the plane, at least one of which shows metal ribs
that divers believe are part of the fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   The crash site is about 180 feet beneath the surface, in an area
with only about 10 feet visibility and the divers' ``bottom time''
is limited to 6 to 10 minutes, officials said. Weather conditions
on Sunday were near the lower limit of those in which divers can be
dropped, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980906.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-STOCK-DOONESBURY     09-06 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-STOCK-DOONESBURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING TO DOONESBURY AS AN ECONOMIC INDICATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TECH-STOCK-STARTUPS) 
(lb) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has Doonesbury, the political comic strip by Garry Trudeau,
become the latest sell signal?
</P>
<P>
   The most recent story line, which began on Aug. 24, features
Mike Doonesbury and his fledgling Internet company, Mikim Inc. Like
most of its peers, it is losing money _ lots of it. But as Mike
explains to his daughter, Internet companies are supposed to lose
money. That's why they go public.
</P>
<P>
   As easy as Internet companies are to lampoon, the sight of them
in the comics may be the clearest indication yet that their stocks
have reached a top. Since peaking in July, when valuations were the
most elevated, these stocks have dropped sharply. Yahoo is down 27
percent, for example, and Amazon.com has fallen 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the mainstream press and humorists start to pick up on
something, it does send something of a message,'' said Edward
Mathias, managing director at the Carlyle Group in Washington, who
has spent more than 15 years collecting various clippings,
including editorial cartoons, on business and the stock market in
the popular press.
</P>
<P>
   Cartoonists and others ``are very topical about what they do,''
Mathias said. While they may not be a leading indicator, they
affirm that a particular topic has penetrated the public
consciousness. And whenever something becomes as well known as
that, an investor should assume that its popularity is reflected in
the price of any assets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   What makes many Internet companies easy targets, for Trudeau's
satire or for worried investors wondering what to unload from their
portfolios, is their lack of profits. While investors typically
value public companies by some multiple of what they earn, many
Internet companies are measured by anything but.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in future profits,'' said Paul Cook, who
manages the Munder Netnet Fund. He argues that Internet companies
need to spend today to build market share tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these companies could be profitable today if they
were satisfied with their current station,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some investors' willingness to ignore profits creates an
atmosphere ripe for ridicule. As a result, Mike Doonesbury is proud
of his company's burn rate, the amount of money he spends over
whatever he takes in as revenues. His daughter scolds him for being
``braggy'' when she overhears him tell someone the company could
lose $2 million this year _ easy.
</P>
<P>
   The same atmosphere was the subject of Michael Wolff's ``Burn
Rate,'' a tongue-in-cheek look at Wolff's own Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors seem to have dispensed with even the pretense of
profitability. How else do you explain the ability of Broadcast.com
Inc., which went public in July, to report increasing quarterly
losses and still see its stock jump by nearly 7 percent the same
day?
</P>
<P>
   This overreliance on growth in revenue and market share at the
expense of profitability, a cornerstone of any successful business,
makes other investors scornful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the silliest thing I've ever heard,'' Susan
Byrne, the president of Westwood Management, said. While she is
enthusiastic about the vast potential of the Internet, calling it
``the rails of the new millennium,'' she remains convinced that a
company must have a business plan if it is to profit from the
Internet's popularity. Market share does no good if the business
model does not explain how a company can make money.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, said Michael Murphy, a money manager and
technology-stock analyst who recommends selling short some of the
Internet stocks, is that ``a good chunk of the Internet companies
will never be profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Mike Doonesbury may now be too late. With the overall
market, and especially small stocks, down, the opportunity to win a
favorable reception from investors is shrinking. ``In markets like
this, people get religion,'' said John Fitzgibbon, the editor of
The IPO Reporter, a weekly newsletter in New York.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last week, newspaper readers knew that
Doonesbury's Mikim was faced with the abrupt withdrawal of its
principal financial backer. But Mike himself still wanted to press
ahead with a stock sale, in the hope that gullible investors would
believe the appearance of success is the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A luxury car might help,'' Mike ventured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
