<HEADER>
A1683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIGAM-COX     09-06 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIGAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mississippi fight brewing over voters' right to decide
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUPORA, Miss. _ She's from a two-stoplight town west of
Starkville and east of Winona. She wears demure church dresses,
plays the piano and works for a state legislator when she's not
taking care of her two children.
</P>
<P>
   And this summer, Elizabeth Stoner has become a household name in
Mississippi. Stoner has a bee in her bonnet about voting rights and
specifically about the right to vote for or against gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Casinos were legalized in river and Gulf Coast counties in 1991
by the state Legislature, but Stoner thinks regular Mississippians
should have their say. So she filed an initiative in June that
would put the issue to a statewide vote, giving Mississippians a
chance to kick the casinos out.
</P>
<P>
   If they vote to ban gambling, the 30 riverboats docked in eight
counties along the Mississippi River and the Gulf Coast would have
two years to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``My issue isn't really gambling, it's the right to vote,'' said
Stoner, who refuses to say whether she personally is for or against
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Although individual counties voted on whether to allow gambling
once it was legal, the law prohibited those counties from later
changing their minds and voting gambling out. Stoner's boss, state
Rep. Charlie Smith, last year unsuccessfully tried to change that
law and allow the counties to re-vote on gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stoner has poked her stick into the cage of the gaming
industry, which has brought 50,000 jobs and $250 million a year in
state and local taxes to the poorest state in the country. And the
gaming industry is roaring.
</P>
<P>
   So big is gambling in Mississippi that the National Gambling
Impact Study Commission plans to hold one of its national hearings
in Biloxi on Thursday at the Mississippi Coast Coliseum. The day
before, pro-gaming forces plan to hold a rally on the Biloxi Town
Green to honor what Gov. Kirk Fordice has called ``the Mississippi
miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaming officials filed an appeal challenging Stoner's
initiative, and a Hinds County judge in late July ruled against
Stoner, saying that the wording of her initiative made it invalid.
Stoner plans to re-word her initiative and try again.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi is a referendum state, which means any voter can
file an initiative to change the state's Constitution. That's what
Stoner is trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians have come out on both sides of the issue, but Gov.
Kirk Fordice and Lt. Gov. Ronnie Musgrove, both gambling opponents,
have spoken against the initiative, saying it would cause more
trouble than it would solve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've invited people from all over the country to invest
literally hundreds of millions of dollars to build hotels, barges,
infrastructure, so we can't now say, `Oh, we changed our minds, you
have to leave, we're now not going to allow gambling,''' said state
Rep. Danny Guice, a Republican from the coast. ``I have no doubt it
will be struck down one way or another, but in the meantime, it has
had a chilling effect on the growth of gaming in the state. The
bigger casinos are going to stop and take a wait-and-see
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Stebbins, executive director the Mississippi Gaming
Association, said he was surprised by the initiative, but he thinks
Mississippians are too tied to casinos to let them disappear. He
disputed Guice's statement that casinos are now afraid to expand,
pointing to a new merger between the Hilton hotels and the Grand
Casino chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are comfortable with the political and economic climate
in Mississippi,'' he said. ``And I think a lot of residents feel
gaming is a big part of the tourism business here and it will never
go away.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative has a long way to go before being placed on the
ballot. Even if Stoner gets the language right and it receives the
blessing of the courts, she must then collect almost 100,000
signatures to have the question placed on the ballot. She is hoping
it will be on the 1999 or 2000 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   But some people believe if the initiative makes it that far, it
has a good chance of passing. After all, only eight of the state's
82 counties allow gambling. The rest of the counties don't stand to
lose as much if gambling is banned, and therefore might vote it out
for moral reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Former state Sen. Ollie Mohamed, a Democrat from the Delta, said
that although he voted for gambling in 1991, he now wishes he
hadn't, and he thinks other people who initially wanted casinos are
regretting them.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling's economic benefits do not outweigh its social costs,
he said, and although thousands of jobs have been created, most of
them are low-paying service jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as a state (were) grasping for revenue no matter how we
derived it, or what the cost might be to our people and state in
the future,'' he said. ``And it has caused many bankruptcies and
foreclosures. I've seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoner, who won't reveal much about herself because, she says,
she feels she might be in danger, says she is not affiliated with
any group, but many groups have come out in support of her
initiative. Attorneys with the American Family Association, a
conservative Christian group, have agreed to represent her. And
many churches have voiced support.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
