<HEADER>
A1684 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABORDAY-CAMPAIGN-COX     09-06 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABORDAY-CAMPAIGN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Politicians no longer need to labor on this day
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Labor Day is traditionally considered the startup of the fall
political season, but for some of Georgia's top political
candidates this weekend that could be a misnomer.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few small-town parades, Georgia's gubernatorial
candidates will use the last holiday of the summer to catch some
much-needed rest before the final two months of a campaign season
that never showed signs of a late summer slow-down.
</P>
<P>
   Warm-weather holidays once marked by old-fashioned barbecues and
rallies on courthouse squares have given way to media-driven races
and carefully crafted 30-second scripts that keep campaigns in
perpetual motion throughout the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor Day as a watershed has gone by the wayside,'' said Steve
Anthony, the state Democratic Party's executive director. ``There
was no break.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially for gubernatorial candidates, who, following the
evolving political script in the '90s, have been at it for more
than a year. Down-ballot contests, where TV advertising is still a
rarity or where tight budgets won't allow protracted media buys,
still will kickstart after this weekend. But they'll be
overshadowed by races that have come to rely more and more on a
media-honed message to reach more than 4.1 million voters scattered
over Georgia, one of the largest Eastern states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hear(ing) these guys speak from the stump is less important
than it was 25 years ago,'' state GOP Chairman Rusty Paul said.
``You don't have to be able to talk at all as long as you've got a
good, solid message and you get it on the air as much as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly how political scientists expect the race to
continue into the homestretch, since Republican nominee Guy Millner
and Democratic nominee Roy Barnes set the tone early. Other
ballot-topping contests for lieutenant governor and U.S. Senate are
expected to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Millner dipped into his own personal fortune to launch a TV
blitz against Barnes within days of the July 21 primary, and kept a
steady string of attack ads running during what conventional wisdom
considered the dead days of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes countered with ads of his own, as well as media-driven
events like an eight-city fly around with leaders of the National
Rifle Association, even as most voters were thinking more about
back-to-school shopping and end-of-summer get-aways .
</P>
<P>
   Instead of shooting at each other over long Labor Day weekend,
most candidates will take some time off for season-opening dove
hunts. Both Millner and Barnes have scheduled hunting excursions,
and Barnes will be the grand marshal of a parade in south Cobb.
Millner's immediate calendar revolves around opening a half-dozen
campaign offices around the state later next week, two in Cobb
County, Barnes' home turf.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Senate candidates also plan to attend dove shoots on
Saturday. Incumbent Republican Sen. Paul Coverdell will travel to a
dove-hunting event in Dooly County, while Democratic challenger
Michael Coles will got to a hunt in Cartersville. On Labor Day,
Coverdell will attend the Catfish Festival Parade in Camden County,
as Coles visits the Communications Workers of America picnic in
Duluth.
</P>
<P>
   In the race lieutenant governor, Democrat Mark Taylor will
attend dove shoots in Cartersville and Hancock County. He may also
attend a parade. Republican Mitch Skandalakis will participate in
parades in Acworth and Douglasville.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
