<HEADER>
A1686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-SIGNS-COX     09-06 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-SIGNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As campaigns heat up, so do races to steal signs
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's as American as doctoring the baseball, fudging on your
taxes or rolling through a stop sign when nobody's looking.
</P>
<P>
   It's the time-honored campaign strategy of deep-sixing an
opponent's yard signs.
</P>
<P>
   Lies and distortions will irk a candidate. But to really send
him to a frenzy, steal his signs.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Bart Ladd (R-Atlanta), a Republican candidate for the
state senate seat representing Dunwoody, says he was inflamed when
supporters of primary opponent Gerald Bartels stole his signs and
replaced them with their own. He finally retaliated.
</P>
<P>
   They ``put up their sign in my supporter's yard,'' said Ladd,
who outpolled Bartels in the July 21 primary and was well on his
way to a 2-1 runoff victory. ``I'll be darned if they'll put up
their signs in my supporter's yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladd said that on the day of the Aug. 11 runoff, as he yanked
the offending sign, a Bartels supporter jumped from the bushes with
a camera and caught him on film. In all, Ladd admits to yanking
only a couple of signs that day.
</P>
<P>
   The Bartels side, not surprisingly, tells it differently.
</P>
<P>
   Bartels campaign worker Randall Reusche, who snapped the photos,
said Ladd, who flies for Delta Airlines, spent election day
piloting his van through neighborhoods and plucking his opponent's
signs.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the incredible luck of capturing Ladd on film if he had
only torn down a couple of signs, Reusche says. The photos show
Ladd nabbing a Bartels' sign from the right-of-way on Winters
Chapel Road and next to a Ladd yard sign which remained untouched.
Signs on right-of-ways are all illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We even saw him run over a sign,'' said Reusche. `` I can
understand a dirty tricks committee doing that. But the candidate
himself?'' Reusche admitted taking some Ladd signs, but only those
that stood where Bartels signs had been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   As the November elections approach, campaign signs _ and the
incessant complaints about their disappearance _ will soon blanket
the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they have put up signs; they have been torn down,''
says Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia professor who wrote
``Dirty Little Secrets,'' a book detailing the nefarious side of
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   He found when asked about dirty tricks, the top gripe of
politicos was sign stealing. ``Of course, they were all victims and
never done it themselves,'' said Sabato. ``It's stealing; it's
vandalism. The whole thing is silly and petty and I can't imagine
it affects 10 votes. I guess it's an emotional release for the
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``release'' was seen in 1985, when then-Atlanta City
Councilman Mayor Bill Campbell had 60 signs stolen by family
members of Grace Davis, his opponent. Davis explained that her
signs had disappeared and her people must have ``gotten overanxious
and retaliated.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's 1997 mayoral opponent, Marvin Arrington, groused that
city sanitation workers continually yanked down his signs, even
when on private property.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Robert Collins, husband of Annie Collins, a candidate
for DeKalb County chief executive officer, was arrested at 4:40
a.m. after allegedly stealing now-CEO Liane Levetan's signs.
Levetan dropped charges but complained that signs cost $2 to $3
each.
</P>
<P>
   On August 10, three men were arrested in Cherokee County and
charged with with tearing down signs of slow-growth candidate Emily
Lemcke, who defeated County Chairman Hollis Lathem. The men said a
developer paid them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   More cases seem to surface as candidates now hide in bushes and
patrol the night in their vehicles, attempting to catch the
sign-stealin' varmints red-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Former state Rep. Vinson Wall of Gwinnett County, admits that
opponent Mike Coan ``got me good'' in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Wall says he was frustrated by his signs disappearing, ``And I
took it upon myself to tear down, no, to remove one of his signs.
Just then, he comes running out of the bushes. It was a setup. He
got me good.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall lost the election to Coan and was beaten by him again in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got all sorts of calls (from political people) and they
said, `You screwed up, you got caught,''' said Wall. ``It's an
accepted practice in politics. You get the other guy's signs if you
can.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Mark Burkhalter (R-Alpharetta) has often dreamed of
catching a sign pilferer and claims his fantasy recently came true.
</P>
<P>
   Burkhalter said he was driving home late at night and noticed
his signs missing. He said he drove around and saw a van stop, the
driver get out, chuck a large sign into his van and speed away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He then started driving in the parking lots of a shopping
center at a high rate of speed and I kept following,'' said
Burkhalter, who admits the chase gave him an adrenaline rush. ``I
then cut him off and he was stuffing things away. He came out,
swore at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkhalter claims it was his Democratic opponent, John Paul
Pritchard, whom he faces in the November general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baloney,'' says Pritchard, who denies stealing signs.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was followed four nights in a row, including once
where Burkhalter turned off his lights while driving. Finally,
tired of the antics, Pritchard said he entered a parking lot and
jumped out of his van, only to find it was Burkhalter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he has nothing better to do at midnight than
drive around and watch his signs,'' said Pritchard. ``It all seems
strange to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
