<SLUG> BC-PCORDER-INGRAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER WHOLESALER IN DEAL WITH TECHNOLOGY SUPPLIER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif.)  (lb) 
 By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ingram Micro Inc., the United States' largest wholesale
distributor of computers, has signed a deal with PC Order.com Inc.,
a provider of electronic commerce technology, to create an online
transaction system intended to let Ingram Micro deliver
custom-built computers more efficiently to corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   For PC Order, a 2-year-old company that plans to go public soon,
the deal will expand its market share to more than three-quarters
of all electronic commerce transactions in the corporate PC sales
market. PC Order, based in Austin, Texas, is already the
transaction-technology supplier to Compaq Computer, Hewlett-Packard
and IBM, among others.
</P>
<P>
   For Ingram, which already had a small online sales operation,
the 5-year deal involves linking the company's PC customers more
directly to Ingram's suppliers and assemblers, which company
executives said should lead to lower costs and faster delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Computer companies have been moving ever faster toward
build-to-order systems, which require quick access to component
data that is possible only through sophisticated electronic
commerce systems like PC Order's, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   PC Order, whose system involves Internet hardware and software
for automating sales transactions and specifying the configuration
of custom-made PCs, also maintains a continuously updated database
on pricing and availability of more than 600,000 computer products
from more than 1,000 manufacturers. It is this information that
Ingram or its subcontractors would use in ordering the components
that go into the PCs.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Tuesday's announcement, Ingram also plans to describe
a new online ordering service, called Prime Access, for companies
that resell machines that Ingram distributes.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, PC Order filed a registration with the Securities and
Exchange Commission to issue up to $35 million in stock. Because PC
Order is in the so-called quiet period that precedes an initial
public offering, neither it nor Ingram would discuss the financial
details of their deal.
</P>
<P>
   PC Order grew out of Trilogy Systems, a business software
company founded in 1989 by Christina Jones, now PC Order's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram Micro, based in Santa Ana, Calif., has evolved from
simply distributing computers to actually manufacturing them on
behalf of Compaq, IBM, Hewlett-Packard, Apple Computer and others.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram's sales were $16.6 billion last year, nearly triple their
1994 level from 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980906.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CURRY-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-06 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CURRY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: 3 WEEKS TO JUDGMENT ON METS' SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There were 40,311 fans at Shea Stadium on a
sun-drenched afternoon, 40,311 people who could have been
frolicking in pools, relaxing on beaches or sitting in
air-conditioned living rooms watching football. Actually, they
might as well have been doing something else Sunday because John
Smoltz emphatically brought the Mets back to reality in steering
the Atlanta Braves to a 4-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz reinforced why the Braves are the superior team and why
they might be the best team in the National League if Bobby Cox
never has to use the bullpen phone. What the loss did to the Mets
was remind them how difficult their path to a wild-card berth will
be and, most important, how their season will be judged in the next
three weeks. For better or worse, richer or poorer.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have been a feisty team with a strong starting
rotation, a usually reliable defense, a Jekyll and Hyde lineup, an
always intriguing bullpen and a marquee player and soap opera
candidate in Mike Piazza. The Mets do the little things correctly
for Manager Bobby Valentine and have always been gritty and often
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   This season is very much alive for the Mets even after Smoltz
was awesome with a three-hitter supported by 12 strikeouts. The
Braves also supplied a power show with four homers. But it will be
a failure for the Mets unless they are still breathing in three
weeks. If the regular season concludes on Sept. 27 in Atlanta and
the Mets do not qualify for a 163rd game, as in the post-season, it
will be a disappointing journey. This might sound harsh for a club
on pace to win 89 games, but it is true.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to see,'' Valentine said. ``We'll have to see how
it turns out.''
</P>
<P>
   Not really. Not when a team is this close to its first
post-season berth since 1988 and might have more talent than the
Chicago Cubs, who lead the wild-card race by one game. Not when
there are no guarantees that Al Leiter and especially Piazza will
be re-signed for 1999. Not when the Yankees could be the story of
October again, the Yankees who work in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I've been spoiled with some of the teams I've played on,
but when you're in this with two other teams and there's no obvious
favorite, you'd like to think we would seize the moment and take
it,'' said Leiter, who has played for two World Series winners.
``Every team thinks about this in spring training. Now we're right
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz revealed that he could sense the Mets were a desperate
team as he tossed crisp fastballs and curveballs and widened the
strike zone by a few inches because umpire Larry Vanover allowed
him to. It took Smoltz five pitches to zoom through the fifth and
seven more to handle the seventh. He whiffed Tony Phillips and John
Olerud three times apiece and was privately smiling when Piazza did
not play because of a bruised finger on his left hand. It is
stunning how naked the batting order looks without Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing with a sense of urgency because they can't let
games slip away,'' Smoltz said. ``That's what I think is happening
over there. They don't think they're out of any game. They feel
like they have to win every game.''
</P>
<P>
   With the way Smoltz pitched, the Mets had no chance. Because the
Pittsburgh Pirates edged the Cubs, 4-3, in 10 innings, optimistic
fans would reason that the Mets did not lose anything because they
remained a game behind Chicago. But the Mets lost twice. They lost
a chance to tie the Cubs and to win a game when Rick Reed, who
leads them with 16 victories, started. Every lost opportunity is
critical with 19 games left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate goal is to get to the playoffs,'' General Manager
Steve Phillips said. ``If we fall short and don't have total
success, there will be small successes to look for.''
</P>
<P>
   Too small. Phillips said it ``would be an interesting case study
for a sociologist to study the fans' perception of the team and
their reaction to the team over the course of a season.''
Obviously, Phillips was referring to how Piazza has been loathed
and now lauded by the fans. It would also be worthwhile to analyze
how the Mets would feel if they did not snatch the wild card, an
appetizing post-season spot that was inches from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we won 91 or 92 games and the Cubs won 93, I don't think
that would be a failure,'' Leiter said. ``The Marlins won 92 last
year and won the World Series. Gosh, I hope we wouldn't be
considered failures for winning 92 games. We're close. You hope
that we can do what it takes to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Or else the season is not a success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
