<DOCNO> NYT19980906.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1697 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-RDP-1STLD-WRITE     09-06 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETLINER'S FLIGHT DATA RECORDER IS FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Subs to add 16 grafs at end of story)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ Divers found the flight data recorder of
Swissair Flight 111 Sunday on a rocky stretch of sea bottom
littered with debris and at least three major pieces of wreckage of
the MD-11. The discovery raised hopes that investigators would soon
know why the plane crashed offshore here on Wednesday night,
killing everyone aboard, after a pilot reported smoke in the
cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   No additional remains of the 229 victims were identified on
Sunday _ the body of one passenger, a French woman, was identified
Friday and taken home _ nor were large numbers of victims found.
But officials were clearly relieved that the Navy diving tender,
the Sechelt, had found one of the plane's two ``black boxes.'' The
box, which is actually orange, was brought ashore late on Sunday
afternoon, where technicians immersed it in fresh water and sealed
it for immediate shipment to a Transportation Safety Board
laboratory in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Work there will begin immediately on arrival, said Vic Gerden,
the board's chief investigator, but a key question was whether the
device, which stores data in computer chips, would have to be
repaired before data could be examined. Another question was
whether an electric power failure, which investigators suspect
occurred on the plane about six minutes before impact, had disabled
the data recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gerden said in a briefing on Sunday evening, ``I would
say that the recovery of the flight data recorder is a very
important step in the progression of this investigation.'' Gerden
entered the briefing room knowing only that one of the boxes had
been recovered; an aide later crept on stage to whisper which one.
</P>
<P>
   (Investigators and searchers say they believe that the other
box, the cockpit voice recorder, was nearby, and a submarine, the
Okanagan, was still searching for it.)
</P>
<P>
   Also on Sunday, the medical examiner here said that the victims'
remains were simply in too many pieces to perform DNA analysis on
all of them, and that some of the smaller pieces would be put in
plastic bags and frozen until lawyers and ethicists could decide
what to do. The medical examiner, Dr. John Butt, said he had
conferred with his counterpart in Suffolk County, on Long Island,
who handled the remains of the passengers and crew from Trans World
Airlines Flight 800 two years ago, and concluded that the bodies
here were in much worse condition.
</P>
<P>
   The newly discovered wreckage field is about five nautical miles
southwest of Peggy's Cove, just outside the area in which searchers
had been conducting sonar mapping of the bottom. They found three
major pieces of the plane, at least one of which shows metal ribs
that divers believe are part of the fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   The crash site is about 180 feet beneath the surface, in an area
with only about 10 feet visibility and the divers' ``bottom time''
is limited to 6 to 10 minutes, officials said. Weather conditions
on Sunday were near the lower limit of those in which divers can be
dropped, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The field is 2,000 to 4,000 yards east of a broken buoy that
searchers originally believed had been sheared off by the plane in
the last seconds of its flight. But they said on Sunday that
metallurgists had found rust at the break and were not sure that
the jet had ever touched it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, medical teams continued work on human remains around
the clock, processing a backlog. ``The issue of data processing is
enormous,'' said Butt, speaking to reporters via a video link from
the military base where a temporary mortuary has been set up.
``This is an issue involving, regrettably, fragmented remains,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody would be able to view these and find a point of
identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 150 and 170 families have responded to requests for
medical records, or given blood samples to be used for DNA testing,
he said; Canadian consulates are tracking down other families.
</P>
<P>
   Butt said that once the pilots' remains had been identified by
DNA, they would be tested for carbon monoxide poisoning, to seek if
they died from smoke inhalation. So far, he said, no human remains
show signs of burns.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was meeting daily with the families to try to help
them understand the situation. ``I think that in my own heart is a
need to help that process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM CAN START HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Among other details announced on Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   _ The captain of the plane, Urs Zimmerman, 50, was hired by
Swissair in 1971 and had been a captain since 1987. He was
qualified as a flight instructor and had accumulated about 9,300
hours of flying time, including 900 in the MD-11. .
</P>
<P>
   _ Weather at the time of the crash was good, with a broken cloud
ceiling at 13,000 feet and an overcast ceiling at 24,000 feet.
Under the clouds, visibility was 15 miles, with no rain or fog; a
mild easterly wind was blowing.
</P>
<P>
   _ None of the cargo on board was listed on the manifests as
hazardous, except for 75 pounds of dry ice, which cannot cause
fires. Investigators are going back to shippers for more detail on
what they sent on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM CAN END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   For the families who are still here waiting for answers about
their loved ones, the mourning continued. More than 300 relatives
traveled to Peggy's Cove, one of the nearest points of land to the
crash site. For the second day, the village's lighthouse and the
rocks around it became a site for prayers and a repository for
flowers and mementos.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so brave,'' said Murielle Provost, a Red Cross
official who has been counseling families. ``You see them trying so
hard to control their emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, many families seemed to feel a need to leave
something at the water's edge and to take something back with them.
Coast Guard and Navy recovery workers began to bring back bottles
of sea water from the area near the crash to give to families. At
Peggy's Cove, safety workers gathered rocks along the shore because
the waves on Sunday were too treacherous for families to wander
down to collect them.
</P>
<P>
   In dozens of churches along St. Margaret's Bay and in Halifax,
the crash was the focus of sermons and prayers. At St. Mary's
Basilica, a soaring Roman Catholic cathedral in Halifax, Monsignor
Martin Currie addressed a small group of victims' families who
gathered to celebrate the Eucharist with the church's parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   Currie compared the crash to a blackout, in which the families
were suddenly left in the dark and are now trying to find a way to
turn the lights on again. But he reassured them that they would
find a way _ through faith and by caring for one another _ to
continue their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting Robert Frost, he said: ``In three words I can tell you
all that I have learned about life: It goes on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
