<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HYDE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE CHIEFS TO DISCUSS RULES ON STARR REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mo., Mich., Texas, N.Y.)  (Eds: See also CLINTON-STARR, MIDTERM-POLITICS) 
(ART ADV: Photo of Henry Hyde is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Democratic and Republican leaders this week
will try to resolve an increasingly contentious debate over
exempting the Judiciary Committee from many House rules as the
panel reviews President Clinton's conduct in the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee, headed by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., is
seeking sweeping powers never granted to a House panel as it
prepares to accept the report from the Whitewater independent
counsel, Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   For example, House officials say, the committee is seeking the
authority to cite witnesses for contempt without first having the
approval of the full House. This option was first reported in The
Washington Post over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Any exemptions in rules for handling the report would be subject
to the approval of the full House.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats, led by Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, have
complained that Republicans are laying the framework for handling
Starr's report outlining possible impeachable offenses without
consulting Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In response to these complaints and fears that a floor fight
over the issue could hurt Republican credibility in the inquiry and
perhaps in the November elections, Speaker Newt Gingrich agreed
last week in a 10-minute telephone call with Gephardt to hold an
unusual meeting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Hyde and Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., the
Judiciary Committee's ranking Democrat, will brief Gingrich,
Gephardt and Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, the majority leader, on how
the panel intends to handle Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been concerned about what we've read lately on the
committee setting up procedures to receive the report,'' said Laura
Nichols, a spokeswoman for Gephardt. ``But the speaker pledged that
Democrats would be full partners.''
</P>
<P>
   A House Republican aide who spoke on the condition of anonymity
said, ``The speaker said he wanted the issue to remain
bipartisan.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican aides emphasized that Hyde would lead the review, and
that House leaders would get an update on Wednesday. But Democrats
aim to use the meeting to press their views.
</P>
<P>
   Another important actor in this drama is Rep. Gerald Solomon,
R-N.Y., who heads the House Rules Committee, which is writing the
resolution governing how the House treats Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, an outspoken former Marine who zealously guards his
committee's jurisdiction, has voiced support for some of Hyde's
requests, but along with other Republicans, may be wary of others.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Solomon issued a news release ``clarifying'' his
position on the proposed resolution covering the procedures the
House would follow in receiving Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   Under the resolution, Solomon said, Starr's full report would go
to the Judiciary Committee, with an executive summary made
available to all House members. If the committee finds sufficient
evidence to go forward with impeachment proceedings, Solomon said,
he would recommend the full report be made available to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   This approach would be a setback for the Judiciary Committee,
whose members initially favored blocking the release any of Starr's
findings to reduce the chance of disclosure to news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Several high-profile congressional investigations in recent
years, including the House Government Reform and Oversight
Committee's inquiry into campaign finance abuses, have been exempt
from longstanding House rules.
</P>
<P>
   The House has waived rules requiring that a lawmaker be present
for all depositions of witnesses, allowing aides to conduct the
interviews. Committee leaders have been granted unusual subpoena
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde is expected to ask for these powers and more, House
Republican aides say, largely to speed the review of Starr's
report.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several weeks, House aides say, Hyde and his top
aides, including Thomas Mooney, the committee's chief counsel, and
David Schippers, the chief investigative counsel, and, to some
extent, their Democratic counterparts, Abbe Lowell and Julian
Epstein, have been developing options to give the panel as much
flexibility and authority as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Besides exempting the panel from House rules on seeking contempt
citations, the panel is considering creating a subcommittee to
conduct the inquiry. This would allow the Judiciary Committee's
counsel, not the House counsel, to decide any legal questions from
the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone has drawn lines in the sand,'' said one
House Republican aide, describing these options. ``I wouldn't
characterize any previous positions as hard and fast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
