<SLUG> BC-SECRET-SUMMIT-570(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NON-ALIGNED MOVEMENT MEETS, OUT OF THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Meanwhile, 6,200 miles to the south
...
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton, representative of the world's lone
superpower, was in Moscow last week bear-hugging Boris Yeltsin,
master of a former superpower, delegates from 113 countries were
holding another summit meeting in the South African coastal city of
Durban.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 12th meeting of the Non-Aligned Movement, which was
founded in 1961, largely at the urging of India, Indonesia and
Yugoslavia, as a forum for nations that were neither pro-U.S. nor
pro-Soviet and considered themselves the blades of grass that
suffer whenever elephants got together in Moscow and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, with the Cold War past, the week began with reporters
pestering them with the same question: ``Nonaligned to what?''
</P>
<P>
   The summit's diplomats had a ready answer: Nonaligned to a world
that still reflects post-World War II and colonialist priorities.
Nonaligned to a global economy in which small countries lose their
shirts overnight when speculators dump their currency. Nonaligned
to a United Nations where the Big Five still have the veto and will
risk their soldiers' lives in Bosnia but not in Congo or Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   As the week went on, the summit's official agenda was eclipsed
by talks about the Congo war. As they ended with no cease-fire and
talks about further talks, the focus shifted back to the main
nonevent.
</P>
<P>
   The chief issues the delegates were said to be discussing were
not those topping the Clinton-Yeltsin agenda in Moscow. They
included Congo, U.S. cruise missile attacks on sites in Afghanistan
and Sudan, the switch by India and Pakistan from nonnuclear to
nuclear states and Libya's hesitation to send suspects in the
Lockerbie plane bombing to the Netherlands for trial.
</P>
<P>
   But one had to take the word of leakers. Since most of the
Non-Aligned Movement's countries are less than open, reporters were
barred from the hall where they were meeting. Instead, reporters
sat in rows at a cavernous exhibit hall nearby, watching BBC TV on
big monitors and trying to arrange interviews with delegates by
calling their South African military escorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would get better credentials if you were from your
government's press,'' a young woman at the accreditation booth told
frustrated reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from a few nations deigned to cross the street to
speak to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Buyoya, the president of Burundi, who came to power in a
1996 coup, appeared to plug his new autobiography, ``Mission
Possible.'' A Thai diplomat came to endorse a candidate. A
Congolese delegation got into a scuffle with a self-proclaimed
transition government of Congolese exiles who had sneaked in past
security.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting's 514-paragraph final communique was not issued
until the midnight after it ended. By then, nearly everyone had
gone home. ``We made 300 copies,'' said Awie Marais, the chief
spokesman. ``There weren't 30 people left to pick them up.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were some serious moments.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat came to reiterate his intention to declare an
independent Palestinian state next May.
</P>
<P>
   And the foreign minister of Sudan came early to outline his
request that the summit meeting demand a U.N. inspection of the
factory destroyed by U.S. cruise missiles on Aug. 20 to determine
whether it produced chemical weapons or pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   The foreign minister, Mustafa Ismail, had wanted to show slides
of the destruction, but the news conference room had been adorned
with potted palms and ficuses, blocking its screens. As Ismail
tried to leave, he was so mobbed by journalists desperate for
quotes that he stepped off the dais into the scenery, crushing a
pot of chrysanthemums.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in the Non-Aligned Movement's history, a U.S.
team was present to keep an eye on charges such as Sudan's. They
were granted ``guest'' status, one rung down from ``observer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The other delegations have been very receptive to our
presence,'' said Princeton Lyman, a former U.S. ambassador to South
Africa who headed the team. ``They seem pleased we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Several diplomats speaking on condition of anonymity said the
Americans lobbied in the halls to temper the communique on some
issues, such as preventing Iraq from inserting language saying it
had fully complied with U.N. weapons inspectors, and asking that
Libya give up the Lockerbie suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans also took part in a delicate debate troubling many
delegates. The Non-Aligned Movement has long opposed nuclear
weaponry, and now two of its leaders, Pakistan and India, have set
off bombs. Diplomats said the two wanted language creating a
``second tier'' of nuclear states, separate from the long-villified
bomb-owners, the United States, Russia, France, Britain and China.
Other states didn't want to condemn India and Pakistan, but wanted
to urge them not to ``weaponize.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final document, many hairs were split.
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan were not mentioned. Instead the conferees
``noted the complexities arising from nuclear tests in South Asia,
which underlined the need to work even harder to achieve their
disarmament objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States' attack on the factory in Sudan was condemned
as ``unilateral and unwarranted,'' but no mention was made of
inspections, and no judgment made about what was in the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain were urged to keep negotiating
with Libya over details of the Lockerbie trial. The two, in
conceding to a trial in the Netherlands, had refused to discuss
other concessions.
</P>
<P>
   The no-flight zones over Iraq, enforced by the United States and
its allies, were ``deplored'' and member states were urged to help
lift the sanctions, but Iraq was not judged to have earned an end
to the sanctions by complying with weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   As always, the summit endorsed clauses championing the
Palestinians over Israel and Cuba over the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The summit did slip off the course along which its South African
hosts wanted to steer. They wanted a new focus on money,
particularly the widening of the gap between rich and poor, the
domination of small debtor nations by the International Monetary
Fund and the vulnerability of small countries to raids on their
currencies by speculators. The final document mentioned such
issues, but did not shift the focus away from politics to
economics.
</P>
<P>
   And the most sought-after character at the summit was definitely
a political figure. President Laurent Kabila of Congo arrived
unexpectedly on Wednesday, avoiding a welcome from South African
President Nelson Mandela. He was reported to have demanded the
first speaking slot of the 86 reserved for national leaders. Denied
it, he borrowed an early slot from an ally, Namibia's president,
and spoke about his military problems.
</P>
<P>
   His aides said he would hold a news conference ``somewhere on
the street'' because the Congolese-exile incident proved the
pressroom was unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   Later, word slipped out that he would talk at a nearby Hilton
Hotel. He kept reporters waiting for five hours, then tried to slip
past them to an elevator. Cornered, he promised elections in six
months and left. He departed on a plane at 4 a.m., skipping a
breakfast meeting about the war and leaving the summit meeting to
muddle on without him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980906.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELPASO-GASOLINE-ART-1     09-06 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELPASO-GASOLINE-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL PASO FEELING GOUGED AT THE PUMP
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ A citizens movement to protest the high price
of gasoline has become the hottest political issue in El Paso,
drawing in Texas officials and entangling itself in a contentious
proposal to open a pipeline from the Gulf Coast _ a kind of cavalry
charging to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   A Dallas oil consortium that hopes to run gasoline through the
dormant pipeline, which once carried West Texas crude oil to
Houston, has fastened itself to the El Paso protest movement,
hoping to override the objections of officials in Austin and
central Texas who say they are worried about potential leaks into
crucial waterways.
</P>
<P>
   The squabble reveals not only the image that many El Paso
residents have of themselves as beleaguered victims of a
``continual and unrelenting fleecing at the hands of an
out-of-control industry,'' as Ken Haverfield, head of the consumer
group that is leading the movement, put it, but what has in recent
years become an endless tug-of-war of economic, political and
environmental interests in the nation's second largest state.
</P>
<P>
   Haverfield first heard about the consumer group he heads,
Make-a-Difference, or MAD, when he was turning the radio dial. The
group had just been formed and was having one of its first
gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prices in El Paso are higher than just about anyplace,''
said Haverfield, a substitute teacher. ``Rent, milk, you name it,
but especially gas. So I went to their meeting several months ago
and kind of got caught up in it.'' Two meetings later, he was
chairman. Not long after, he was president. And last Thursday,
Haverfield found himself sitting before a microphone in the El Paso
Civic Center, testifying to a pair of reassuring congressmen.
</P>
<P>
   Haverfield and his supporters say that until recently gasoline
prices for most of the last 20 years have been 10 to 20 cents a
gallon higher in El Paso than in Houston. They believe it is the
result of a conspiracy by producers to artificially inflate prices.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is not so sure. John Cook, director of
the oil and gas division of the Federal Energy Information
Administration, said that while his agency did find a history of
high gasoline prices in El Paso _ 10 to 15 cents a gallon higher
than in Houston _ the differential is not unusual. There are many
such regional differentials in the United States, he said, caused
by variations in taxes, geography, competition and the laws of
supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of El Paso's gasoline problem is geographic. The city
is more than 700 miles from the Gulf of Mexico, where gasoline is
cheaper to produce; residents often note they are about as close to
Los Angeles, three states away, as they are to Houston. And while
there are many refineries on the Gulf Coast, drawing crude oil from
all over the world, there is only one in El Paso, a relatively
small Chevron plant that draws its crude solely from the more
expensive West Texas fields. The rest of El Paso's gasoline is from
fields and refineries farther west, where gasoline is more
expensive to produce than it is on the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's geography or not, I don't know, but we're like a
lot of people wondering why it is that gas is so expensive in El
Paso,'' said David Morales, spokesman for the Cab Association of El
Paso, another proponent of lower gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the consortium, Longhorn Partners Pipeline, took over
an 18-inch-wide, 430-mile-long Exxon pipeline that had been
carrying crude from the West Texas fields into Houston and the Gulf
Coast refineries. The plan was to clean out the pipe, test its
structural integrity, build a 250-mile extension west into El Paso
and ship gasoline, diesel and jet fuel through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to go out to El Paso three or four years ago,'' said
Carter Montgomery, president of Longhorn, which includes Amoco and
Exxon among its investors. ``The attitude out there has always
been, bring on the pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   But a lawsuit filed earlier this year on behalf of several
ranchers charges that the pipeline project violates environmental
restrictions. The suit is being underwritten by the Navajo Refining
Co., a leading distributor of gasoline to El Paso, Montgomery said,
and a potential competitor of the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   So last month, Longhorn filed suit against Navajo, charging it
with violating antitrust laws ``in an attempt to maintain
artificially high gas prices'' in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   The suit against Longhorn, though, attracted the attention of
politicians and water officials in central Texas. Both the city of
Austin and the Lower Colorado River Authority joined in the suit,
demanding that Longhorn conduct an environmental impact study
before using the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a U.S. District judge in Austin agreed and ordered
the study, which Montgomery said would delay the project up to two
years. It is unnecessary, Montgomery said, since the pipeline
consortium has already conducted sufficient tests.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rose, general manager of the Lower Colorado River
Authority, said his group's concern was one of safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our issue is that they are reconverting a 50-year-old pipeline
that once carried West Texas crude to now carry gasoline, diesel
and jet fuel,'' Rose said. ``The goal to get gasoline to El Paso is
a noble one. We just hope it doesn't turn out to be tragically bad
for everyone in central Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery said that Longhorn was continuing to build the
pipeline and appealing the judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   The high prices in El Paso, which has a per capita income well
below that of other major Texas cities, remain a staple of the
talk-radio shows. But Wayne Ederer, regional marketing director for
Chevron, cannot see why. ``I feel there is a lot of
misunderstanding out there among the citizens,'' he said. ``They
see a refinery here and refineries in Houston and wonder why prices
are higher here. They don't understand the cost situation that we
have, using more expensive West Texas crude.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Haverfield said that the producers have no one to blame but
themselves for the widespread distrust. ``We've tried to get
answers from them,'' he said. ``If you can get them on the phone,
all you end up with is scrambled eggs. You can't figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   A dip in the price of gasoline here since March has further
muddied the situation. Chevron and other distributors say it is a
result of an increase in the local supply. Haverfield and others
believe it has something to do with the pressure applied by his
organization and by local politicians, including Mayor Carlos
Ramirez and Democratic Rep. Silvestre Reyes of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did notice that the price of gasoline here this morning was
competitive with what it was when I left Houston,'' said Rep. Gene
Green, a Houston Democrat who joined Reyes at the public hearing in
the civic center last week. ``If it'll help keep the prices down,
I'll be glad to come out here every couple of weeks for a public
hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery says it has become a pleasure for Longhorn officials
to visit El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a 5-K road race a while back that we agreed to help
sponsor,'' he said. ``At the end, when they read the list of
sponsors and they got to our name, everybody in the audience stood
up and applauded. I mean, we had 2,500 people standing up,
applauding us.''
</P>
<P>
   This, he said, does not happen every day in the pipeline
business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
