<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WHITESOX-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRABU IS SPINNING OUT OF YANKS' ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Hideki Irabu was a Cy Young award candidate in May, a
possible All-Star in June. Now he is in jeopardy of being dropped
from the Yankees' rotation and, eventually, from their playoff
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Warned before he took the mound Sunday that he needed to
improve, Irabu regressed, giving up six runs in two and one-third
innings to the Chicago White Sox, with George Steinbrenner in
attendance. The Yankees never recovered from the hole Irabu dug for
them, losing, 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have lost 10 of their last 18 games, their chances
of breaking the single-season record for victories waning; they
must win 17 of their last 22 to pass the mark of 116, set by the
1906 Chicago Cubs. But their focus seems to have shifted, from
winning every game possible to preparing for the playoffs that
begin Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre is operating his team as he might in spring
training, resting at least one regular player daily, placing
relievers in situations they may face in October. These are war
games, not the real thing. But Irabu (11-8) has been terrible in
his last four starts, compiling a 16.07 ERA, his composite ERA
climbing to more than four runs per game _ it is now at 4.28 _ for
the first time all season.
</P>
<P>
   Torre indicated after the game that Irabu would make his next
scheduled start, against Toronto on Friday in Yankee Stadium.
Immediate shifts are always possible with the Yankees, however;
asked about Irabu, Steinbrenner said, ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre left open the possibility that Irabu may be switched to
the bullpen if he does not get better, and Irabu knows he is
pitching on the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not entirely sure what my position is going to be, going
forward,'' Irabu said, through an interpreter, in an even tone.
When his teammate Derek Jeter tried getting Irabu's attention and
making a joke to get a smile from Irabu, the pitcher barely
responded. He spoke more expressively Sunday, more analytically
than he has in months.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm going to be speaking to my pitching coach and my
manager about what they want me to do,'' he said. ``They're going
to decide, and I'm going to leave it up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu had a league-leading 1.59 ERA on June 10, his record 6-1,
winning with an erratic array of pitches. Some days only his
fastball would be effective, but he would change locations,
sometimes throw it low and sometimes high and always hard. Some
days he had a good split-finger fastball, getting ahead in the
count and then luring opposing hitters into swinging at the
splitter in the dirt. He mixed in a curveball in a couple of
starts.
</P>
<P>
   As catcher Jorge Posada explained after Sunday's game, Irabu now
is throwing his fastball in one spot, on one plane and throwing his
splitter high as well. He walked the first two hitters he faced
Sunday before repeatedly throwing fastballs and splitters
thigh-high, and the White Sox rocketed hits from foul line to foul
line, all line drives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza, who was removed from the rotation when Orlando
Hernandez was promoted in June, relieved Irabu and pitched four and
two-thirds strong innings. Torre mentioned that in picking his
post-season starters, reliability will be important, because the
margin for error in a three-of-five or four-of-seven-game series is
greatly reduced. In three of Irabu's last four starts, he was
knocked out in the first four innings. Mendoza is unspectacular and
does not produce strikeouts, but he was reliable as a starting
pitcher before being supplanted by Hernandez in June.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting Mendoza to the rotation protects the Yankees in two
ways. First, he is a better pitcher than Irabu is now, and second,
if Jeff Nelson's back fails and Hernandez is shifted to the bullpen
to replace Nelson, Mendoza would be one of the Yankees' four
post-season starters. If Nelson's back holds up, then Hernandez
would probably be one of the Yankees' four starters, with Mendoza
moving to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Torre intends to keep 10 pitchers on his post-season roster, and
barring injury, at least nine of those spots are clinched: David
Cone, David Wells, Andy Pettitte, Hernandez, Mendoza, Mariano
Rivera, Graeme Lloyd, Mike Stanton and Jeff Nelson. Mike Buddie,
Darren Holmes and Irabu are vying for that last spot.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he was pleased with Irabu's effort Sunday, but in
recent starts, Irabu has appeared frustrated on the mound,
discouraged and passive. Pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre would like
to see that change; he wants to see Irabu fight on the mound,
attack hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myself, I wish he'd get a little bit more fire,'' Stottlemyre
said. ``I know he's upset and he gets mad when he comes in here'' _
the clubhouse _ ``but I wish he'd just get more aggressive with
strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu may have one more start to be aggressive. Or maybe he does
not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
