<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S FATE ON MANY MINDS AS CONGRESS RETURNS TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-HYDE, MIDTERM-POLITICS) 
(sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Democratic hand-wringing over President
Clinton's personal behavior is intensifying as Congress returns to
Washington this week for its final month of business.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a full agenda of appropriations bills and a now-likely
showdown in the Senate on campaign finance, the president's fate
remains Topic A since he admitted three weeks ago to having had an
inappropriate relationship with Monica Lewinsky, a former White
House intern, and lying about it.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Moran, D-Va., and strong political ally of the
president, said on Sunday that Clinton would be lucky to get away
with only a censure by Congress. More likely, he said, the
president would face impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I now don't think that that is really an option,'' Moran said
of censure, speaking on Fox News Sunday. ``I think we're bound to
go through with impeachment proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, one of the leading
Democrats in the Senate, said that there was ``a crisis in the
regime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot have this kind of conduct as normal and acceptable
and easily dismissed unless there is a great effort to do so,''
said Moynihan, speaking on the ABC News program ``This Week.''
``And if, in addition to what we know, there are things we don't
know, that will make it worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan said that Congress, which is planning to adjourn early
next month so members can campaign for re-election, should stay in
session as long as it takes to resolve the president's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is anxiously waiting for Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater
independent counsel, to send a report of his investigation of
Clinton to the House Judiciary Committee. Only then can it set a
course of action.
</P>
<P>
   Discouraging words are coming, too, for the president from two
Democratic strongholds, New York and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Some New York Democrats have begun quietly suggesting that the
president delay a major fund-raising event for the Democratic Party
in New York set for Sept. 14, the night before the primary, saying
that it could create an awkward moment for the Democratic Senate
candidates. But Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, chairman of
the Senate Democrats' campaign committee, said Sunday on the CBS
News program ``Face The Nation'' that the New York fund-raiser,
expected to be the biggest in the party's history, was on track.
</P>
<P>
   And Parris Glendening, the Democratic governor of Maryland, has
canceled an October fund-raising appearance with Clinton, fearing
it could backfire on his tenuous bid for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The moves and comments follow a severe dressing-down of Clinton
on Thursday by Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., who appears to have
opened the way for more Democrats to express their concern about
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties said on Sunday that they perceive
Clinton as severely weakened politically and are openly discussing
the effect of his continuing crisis in confidence on the fate of
legislation and on world events.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a crisis of the regime,'' Moynihan said. ``We have
nothing more important to do in the nation's interest,'' he said of
getting the Starr report and a quick congressional response. ``This
is a distraction which is doubly dangerous because of the world
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Moran: ``His credibility is obviously severely diminished.
I don't know how he can ever recover the strength of the bully
pulpit that he needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., said that the president would be
hard-pressed to veto tax cuts that he has rebuffed in the past as
unaffordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we have a chance to put through a tax bill that
would get rid of the marriage tax penalty, that will lighten up
death taxes somewhat,'' Cox said on Fox News Sunday. ``And this is
something that wouldn't have been possible if the president were
stronger.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader, promised
Sunday on the NBC News program ``Meet the Press'' that the Senate
would take up campaign finance legislation, perhaps as early as
this week. Lott and other Republican leaders had resisted bringing
up the measure, but they faced more pressure to do so once the
House, in a surprise vote, passed the overhaul last month.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said under conditions of anonymity on Sunday that
Lott had two motivations in bringing up the dicey issue: to avoid
an internal Republican split with senators who supported
overhauling the campaign finance laws, and to give more credence to
Republican calls for Janet Reno, the attorney general, to appoint
an independent counsel to investigate Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore for possible campaign finance abuses in the 1996 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he was uncertain whether the campaign finance measure
would pass, but it is clear he wants to avoid an internal spat that
would, even temporarily, divert the spotlight from Clinton's
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The bill expected to be under consideration would ban the
unregulated ``soft money'' that goes indirectly to political
campaigns. The bill's sponsors, Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and
Russell Feingold, D-Wis., had threatened to attach it to other
legislation headed for the floor, which could severely disrupt
Senate action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
