<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHEN A RACE BECOMES A RIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What is the sound of three hands clapping?
</P>
<P>
   New York's 1998 Democratic Senate primary was supposed to be
brutal. It was supposed to be filled with vicious attack ads, ugly
slurs and deliberately circulated innuendoes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, to the mystification of voters and the immense
disappointment of journalists, the race is shaping up more as an
enigma than as a blood bath. What is it about? No one can quite
agree. This includes the candidates themselves, who, rather than
campaign against one another would prefer, it seems, to play
make-believe.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City public advocate, Mark Green, is pretending
that the race is a two-man contest between him and Rep. Charles
Schumer. By Green's account, the key issue is a series of votes
that Schumer cast, starting in the mid-1980s, that when properly
interpreted, reveal him to be a crypto-middle-of-the-roader. That
Geraldine Ferraro is also running is a fact Green has simply chosen
not to notice.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, meanwhile, has chosen just as pointedly not to notice
Green. Shrugging off the criticisms of his votes, he has devoted
himself to spending his sizable war chest on upbeat television ads.
The race, he often states, is about who has the strongest record of
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro has, for her part, feigned indifference toward both
Green and Schumer, acting as if they were not so much her rivals as
mere extras in her own life drama. To the extent that she has
defined the race at all, she has cast it as a referendum on star
power: Who among the candidates is famous enough to play in the big
leagues?
</P>
<P>
   The lack of direct engagement has given the race a
disconcertingly Pirandello-like quality. One could call it ``Three
Candidates in Search of an Issue,'' except that would imply they
were actually trying to find one.
</P>
<P>
   Some have suggested that the preternatural calm of this year's
primary is a matter of consensus, of candidates so similar in
outlook that they have nothing much to debate. But that was
precisely the marvel of Democratic primaries in the past: watching
candidates destroy each other over the subtlest shades of
ideological difference.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate primary race, there is a great deal of common
ground, especially between Schumer and Ferraro. But the
contestants, by disposition, background and belief, are hardly soul
mates. If they wanted to find something to argue about, there is
more than enough material to work with. It is rather that they
have, quite deliberately, elected not to.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Democratic leaders seem greatly relieved that the race
is as lifeless as it is. They happily compare it with the
all-too-dramatic Senate primary of six years ago, when Ferraro ran
against Elizabeth Holtzman, then the city comptroller; Robert
Abrams, then state attorney general; and the Rev. Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams carried the day but went on to lose the general election
to Sen. Alfonse D'Amato. The margin was small enough that Democrats
widely blamed his defeat on the destructive nature of the primary
that had preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, the campaign has been positive,'' said John Marino,
the former head of the state Democratic Party, referring to this
year's Senate contest. ``It's definitely not 1992; since I was the
chairman then, I can tell you that. And I think that's bad news for
Al D'Amato.''
</P>
<P>
   In the remaining week of the race, this year's Democratic
hopefuls could, of course, still lose their reserve and revert to
more confrontational tactics. Not infrequently, campaigns do turn
bitter in the final days, when the contenders feel themselves
running out of alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, at least, the lesson of 1992 seems to be sticking.
Just as the Senate race is eerily becalmed, so, too, is the
gubernatorial primary, despite the provocative presence of Lt. Gov.
Betsy McCaughey Ross.
</P>
<P>
   During a debate last week, just before Wilbur Ross officially
cut back his wife's allowance, all four Democratic candidates for
governor made a point of crediting one another with good ideas and
underscoring their agreement on everything from education to health
care.
</P>
<P>
   If the trend keeps up, it will soon no longer be possible to
make fun of the Democrats for their fratricidal antics. But if that
happens, it isn't clear that voters or reporters will be paying
enough attention to notice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
