<SLUG> BC-SAPELO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lighthouse: New life for coast landmark
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAPELO ISLAND, GA _ One of the most enduring symbols of
Georgia's maritime heritage was given new life Sunday night: For
the first time in nearly a century, the Sapelo Island lighthouse is
once again guiding ship captains and fishermen through Georgia's
coastal waters.
</P>
<P>
   With red stripes accenting its gleaming white tower, the
80-foot-tall lighthouse has been restored, making it the third
working lighthouse on the Georgia coast. The other two are on Tybee
and St. Simons islands.
</P>
<P>
   With the flick of a switch, Gov. Zell Miller turned on the
light, flashing in the original sequence used more than a century
ago to guide sailing vessels through the treacherous coastal
waters. The beam can be seen 12 miles out to sea and in the
surrounding sounds and estuaries.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this week, three-hour tours of the lighthouse and the
island will be offered on Saturdays by the state Department of
Natural Resources. Visitors will be able to climb the spiral
staircase and enjoy spectacular vistas of the island, Doboy Sound
and the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Rising from a clump of red cedars, wax myrtles and pines on a
marshy spit of the remote island, the Sapelo lighthouse stood
weather-beaten, forlorn and darkened until lighthouse aficionados
undertook an eight-month, $500,000 effort to save it. The makeover
shored up the lighthouse's crumbling, 65-foot-tall brick tower _
originally built in 1820 _ and added a stucco exterior that was
painted with the distinctive red and white bands. New glass and the
new light were installed in the 15-foot-tall, cast-iron cupola at
the top of the tower, and the termite-infested wooden staircase was
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a lighthouse that looks much as it did more than a
century ago when its beacon guided lumber-laden schooners from the
bustling port of nearby Darien. ``It's a true monument to Georgia's
rich maritime heritage,'' said Lonice Barrett, commissioner of the
Department of Natural Resources who helped lead the restoration
effort. The Sapelo lighthouse was one of 15 that once stood along
Georgia's 100 miles of coastline. Sapelo's light was darkened in
1898 when a hurricane severely damaged its tower. It was replaced
in 1905 by a 100-foot steel lighthouse, which was active for nearly
30 years until it was dismantled and shipped to Fox Island in Lake
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
