<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Malloy's amazing vs. Mets
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the land of the unlikeliest Atlanta longballs,
where Rafael Belliard went once-in-a-decade deep last September,
what Marty Malloy did Sunday rendered Raffy's homer a relatively
sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' said a stunned Malloy, who was
called up from Class AAA Richmond in the middle of the night,
arrived here 2 1/2 hours before Sunday's first pitch and, in his
second big-league at-bat, hit one of Atlanta's four solo homers to
help propel John Smoltz to a 4-0 win over the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no words that can de- scribe today,'' said Malloy, who
started at second base on 90 minutes sleep and batted second, ``and
just getting called up, and a guy who doesn't hit many home runs in
the minor leagues, and my first hit in the big leagues is a home
run.''
</P>
<P>
   In seven seasons in the minors, from Idaho Falls to Richmond,
Malloy had hit just 33 homers in 2,906 at-bats. In his second
major-league at-bat, on the ninth pitch he saw from Rick Reed
(who'd caught Malloy looking in the first inning), Malloy drilled a
2-2 inside fastball into the Mets bullpen. Then he used the word
Casey Stengel once used to describe the original Mets: ``Amazing.
That made it 2-0, Ryan Klesko having hit his 17th home run in the
second inning. Andruw Jones' 27th homer (and fifth in 11 games) was
nice, but unnecessary. So, too, was No. 43 by Andres Galarraga,
back in the lineup after a three-game suspension. The way Smoltz
threw Sunday, Klesko's first homer in nearly a month was enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel if I throw like that, there's a lot of lineups I'm
going to have success against,'' said Smoltz (14-3), who struck out
a season-high 12, walked none and allowed just three singles for
his second shutout of the season and 13th of his career. ``I had my
fastball today. Because I was banging strikes, they had to come out
and swing at the most hittable pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just got good (stuff),'' said Tony Phillips, who, like
John Olerud, struck out three times in his first look at Smoltz.
``He's just good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
