A1723 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COX     09-06 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Solid Falcons on the right track
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlotte, NC -- This franchise has taken so many wrong turns
that even a glimpse of the Right Way seems disquieting. How can we
be sure that this isn't just another false clue, another buildup
destined to spawn only deeper disappointment?
</P>
<P>
   Because this time looks different, feels different, is
different. That's how.
</P>
<P>
   A Falcon since 1987, Jessie Tuggle had never opened a season on
the road and gone home a winner, never until Sunday. A Falcon for
11 of the darkest seasons any player has known, Tuggle had absorbed
every sort of galling defeat known to man. And it was possible,
even on the final snap, that this day would bring another. But you
know what? Even Tuggle didn't believe that an end-zone tip would
undo his team. Not this time. This time felt ... different.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in the same situation so many times and one little
thing has gone against us,'' Tuggle said. ``But this time we got a
break. We finally got a break.''
</P>
<P>
   A batted ball, there for Carolina's catching, hit the turf. The
Falcons won. They won by being both good and lucky, two things they
absolutely haven't been for most of their existence. They won not
just because they survived the last play but because they prevailed
on the majority of those preceding it did. They outfought and
outskilled an opponent that spent a record $27 million on free
agents. They were the more solid team in a test of solidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying it the last five years,'' said Chuck Smith,
the assertive defensive end. ``This is exactly how you win. Morten
(Andersen) made the kicks. We stopped them when we had to.''
</P>
<P>
   It was nothing fancy, nothing to inspire awe on the part of any
witness. At the same time, there was never a moment when the
Falcons seemed anything less than the stronger side. ``Physically
we dominated this football game,'' said defensive tackle Travis
Hall, correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chandler made enough precise throws. The offensive line
and Jamal Anderson killed off five vital minutes near the end. The
Falcons made no turnovers. This was good, basic football, the brand
Dan Reeves promised upon taking this job.
</P>
<P>
   With free agency and the salary cap, the day of the overpowering
NFL team is gone. Every club has similar resources. The teams that
win are those that maximize theirs. You maximize not by dazzling
gimmickry but by boring old repetition. ``Consistency,'' said
running back Anderson, ``that's the thing Dan Reeves preaches.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, that's what separates Reeves from Glanville and
Henning and June Jones. The Reeves Method isn't going to erode over
time. The fundamental endures. Said Tuggle: ``It's about solid
techniques, about playing good football on offense and defense.
It's not like we're out there tricking people or playing some crazy
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to suggest that the Falcons are bound for the Super
Bowl, even a measly wild card. This is Year 2 of a process. But
having beheld so much bleakness with this team, it is possible to
look upon these Falcons and see only promise. ``So many times we've
thought we were on the right track,'' Tuggle said, and this time
they are.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
