<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALSIDEA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dwight catching on
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his final game at Iowa last year, Tim Dwight broke free on a
post pattern, setting up a dream finish to his sparkling college
career. But a bad thing happened on the way to a long touchdown. He
dropped the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to Sunday at Ericsson Stadium for the rookie's
first regular-season NFL game. Dwight ran past the Panthers'
secondary in the third quarter, just like he did in his last
collegiate home game. The ball, from quarterback Chris Chandler,
floated toward Dwight. ``It seemed like it took a year to get
there,'' Dwight said.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough time for Dwight to recall his gaffe at Iowa. ``My
heart stopped beating while the ball was up there,'' he said. ``It
took a long time to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ball arrived, Dwight cradled it and sprinted into the
end zone to complete a 44-yard touchdown that was significant in
the Falcons' 19-14 victory over Carolina. He ran as fast to the
bench after the score as he did in getting open. And he had a
souvenir to mark the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe I caught an NFL touchdown,'' he said. ``But
I sure as heck was going to keep that ball.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, nobody wanted to take it from him. Dwight has been a
eager student under veterans Terance Mathis and Tony Martin, and
his efforts Sunday confirmed their preseason thoughts of the
5-foot-8, 184-pound return specialist drafted in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone talks about Randy Moss (the receiver taken by
Minnesota in the first round),'' Mathis said. ``Our guy returns
punts, kickoffs and scores on offense. I don't know. I think
everyone's looking at the wrong guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Moss showed his brilliance in his first pro game
Sunday with two touchdowns in the Vikings' demolition of Tampa Bay.
The point really was that Dwight brings to the Falcons elements the
team sorely needed.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight, who led the NCAA in punt returns last season with a
19.3-yard average, got only one chance Sunday _ and that was a fair
catch. But he did amass 70 yards on three kickoff returns to go
with the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's explosive on punts,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``A guy
breaks free, and he makes him miss. He has speed, great vision. And
he's a tough, hard-nosed receiver. He doesn't shy away from blocks.
And he's a big target because he uses his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight played only four offensive plays in the game. In the
first three, he was not involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a long way to go,'' Dwight said. ``I did some things
right and some things wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More right than wrong,'' Mathis told him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
