<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson's carries eat precious time
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, NC _ The hope in Suwanee all summer was that the
Falcons' opening day performance would bare some resemblance to a
team that won six of eight games down the stretch. Instead, for two
quarters, the offense resembled the biggest reason most fans
stopped watching after a 1-7 start.
</P>
<P>
   Stunts and blitzes confused Atlanta's defensive front. Jamal
Anderson was averaging 1.9 yards per carry. Chris Chandler was
sacked three times on 19 pass plays.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Falcons did something unusual. They kept trying to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew if we kept pounding the ball, eventually it would pay
off,'' center Robbie Tobeck said. ``That hasn't been the case in
the past, but it hasn't been the philosophy of our coaching staff
in the past to keep running. We started to make the transition last
year, but it takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's post run-and-shoot efforts to establish a rushing
attack paid dividends in the second half against Carolina. Anderson
rushed for 67 yards in the second half (88 in the game), enabling
the Falcons to consume time, keep Carolina's weary defense on the
field and pull out a 19-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came into this game knowing we had to run to win,'' Anderson
said. ``You don't come here just thinking you're going to smash
Kevin Greene and Sean Gilbert. But you need to get the running game
going to win. I think the Denver Broncos proved that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, already a starter, saw his role become even more
important after the season-ending knee injury to Byron Hanspard,
who figured to get about 10 carries per game. Harold Green was the
team's second-leading rusher with just 4 yards Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we lost Byron, I knew we wouldn't have that one-two
punch,'' said Anderson, who ran for 23 yards his first two carries
of the second half. ``Since I've been here, it was by (Erric)
Pegram or me and Ironhead (Heyward) or me and Hanspard.''
</P>
<P>
   The 28 carries in the late-summer heat took it's toll on
Anderson, who said, ``It's hot and I'm not skinny.'' But Carolina's
front seven wore down faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we talked about doing all training camp,'' guard
Calvin Collins said. ``You could tell they were getting tired in
the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Tobeck: ``You play football because you love to be
physical. There's no better feeling than when you win a game like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
