<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY, IN HIS OWN METHODICAL WAY, PREPARING 2000 PRESIDENTIAL
RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SURF CITY, N.J. _ In his Hall of Fame career with the New York
Knicks, Bill Bradley lacked the insouciant grace of a natural
athlete. Instead, his were the precise rhythms of a workaholic who
had practiced every move, from his signature pull-up jumpers to his
scoop shots and reverse dribbles, hundreds of thousands of times.
</P>
<P>
   So it is these days with Bill Bradley the politician. In his
methodical way, Bradley, 55, has begun building the architecture
for a presidential campaign in 2000, piece by tiny piece. Though he
says he has not decided whether to run, he is talking more
seriously about it with close advisers, and taking more concrete
steps to prepare for it, than at any other time since 1988, when he
was first mentioned as a possible presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's advisers say that his goal is to have a shadow
campaign in place so that if he does run, he will be able to
quickly assemble a powerful political and fund-raising network. He
will need one to compete with other likely Democratic candidates
who have been building campaign machines for years, particularly
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just him flirting with the idea'' of running for
president, said Rep. Robert Menendez, D-N.J., a friend of Bradley.
``This is someone who has steadfastly plodded along toward that
goal. He is just doing it in his Bradleyesque way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has hired two full-time aides, one of whom, Ed
Turlington, is a seasoned campaign operative who most recently
worked for North Carolina Gov. James Hunt. He has revived his
political action committee, Time Future Inc., and begun
contributing money to candidates across the country who could play
important local roles in a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He has asked contributors and politicians around the country not
to commit to other candidates until he makes up his mind _ by the
end of this year, he said. He has recruited politicians to help run
local operations, including the minority leader of the New Jersey
state Senate, Richard Codey, who has agreed to help manage a New
Jersey campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He has even begun some street campaigning: Sunday he shook hands
in seven towns along the Jersey Shore, reviving a Labor Day
tradition from his three terms in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and people close to him say that there are some very
personal reasons he is considering a presidential run more
seriously than ever before. Most important, they say, is the
improved health of his wife, Ernestine, who was found to have
breast cancer in 1992. The disease has been in remission, Bradley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also said that he felt better prepared mentally to be
president than he has in the past, having gained foreign policy
experience in the Senate and extensively traveled the country as a
speaker, television commentator and visiting professor at Stanford
and Notre Dame universities. He is also about to launch a national
promotional tour for his third book, ``Values of the Game,'' about
the life lessons learned from playing basketball.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters say there is another reason they are strongly
urging Bradley to run in 2000: At a time that President Clinton's
problems with the Monica Lewinsky matter and campaign finance
practices may have begun to tarnish Gore, Bradley is perfectly
positioned to run as the un-Clinton, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that people are going to be looking for someone
who is not just Mr. Clean, but that has character and integrity,
after the debacle of the last six years,'' said Herbert Allen, an
investment banker who has contributed to Bradley for years. ``There
is an underlying current that this is one of the most corrupt
administrations in history, and Bill is the antithesis of that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore is facing a preliminary investigation by the Justice
Department of possible campaign finance abuses _ an investigation
that could lead to the appointment of an independent prosecutor _
Bradley can point to speeches he made as a senator warning against
the corrosive influence of money on politics and advocating an
overhaul of campaign finance rules.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley denies that the Clinton administration's problems, or
Gore's perceived weaknesses, will have any affect on his decision.
``You don't make this kind of life decision on a tactical basis,''
he said in an interview between beach stops Sunday as he munched on
baby carrots.
</P>
<P>
   But sunbathers along the hazy New Jersey shore, many of whom had
hearty greetings for Bradley, seemed to have President Clinton's
problems vividly on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need some moral character, and from what I know of Bill
Bradley, he's got that,'' Brad Henson, a municipal prosecutor from
Surf City, said after shaking Bradley's hand.
</P>
<P>
   When Bradley asked another man, Jeffrey Rosen from West Orange,
whether he should run for president, Rosen replied: ``I think it's
a wonderful idea. We need the best of our people to run,
particularly given what's going on.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his lectures at Stanford and Notre Dame, Bradley has clearly
been trying out broad themes that he believes could resonate with
voters. These include helping Americans adjust to the globalization
of markets, assisting single-parent families and families with two
working parents, and giving people a greater sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most tellingly, his lectures include a call for reviving
America's battered political soul with a new kind of unheroic
leadership that sounds suspiciously like a description of, well,
Bill Bradley: laconic and undramatic. As he put it, ``An orchestra
leader rather than a white knight.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say Bradley faces several major obstacles if
he does choose to run, including a relatively late start in
fund-raising. Some Democrats also say Bradley must mend fences with
Democrats who feel that he denigrated the party by saying American
politics was ``broken'' when he retired from the Senate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats say that his anti-politician style _ he has
spent much of the last two years railing against special interest
politics and poll-driven policy making _ will strike many voters as
quixotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say Jerry Brown was a breath of fresh air,'' said Rep.
Eliot Engel, D-N.Y. ``But others called him Governor Moonbeam. The
same might be said of Bill Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, a fiercely private man, seems to be grappling with
more personal concerns as he ponders whether to run: the loss of
freedom and the intense public scrutiny that accompany national
campaigns today.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what were his main concerns about running, he said that
the first was whether he was the best person to run the country at
this moment in history. The second, he continued, was whether ``my
wife and family and I want to jump off a 50-story building with no
idea whether there is a net at the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' he said. ``I've never done it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
