<SLUG> BC-NY-GOVERNOR-DEBATE-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE FRIENDLY EXCHANGES IN GUBERNATORIAL DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is standard practice in politics to gang up on the
front-runner. But for the second time in four days, the Democrats
running for governor held a televised debate Sunday and the
candidate recognized by his rivals as the leader, Peter Vallone,
emerged largely unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   The only criticism of Vallone, the New York City Council
speaker, was aimed at his fund-raising success, as his rivals
claimed to be the true champions of campaign finance reform and
pleaded virtue in their relative poverty. For much of the hour, the
candidates continued the friendly tone that marked a debate
Wednesday night in Troy, N.Y., referring to their foes by first
names and even praising one another's arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Two candidates, District Attorney Charles Hynes of Brooklyn and
James Larocca, a former state transportation commissioner, said
going into the session at the WABC television studios in Manhattan
that they would begin to turn their sights on Vallone. But the
zingers never materialized. Instead, they saved their sharpest
barbs for another rival, Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross. The event
was broadcast live Sunday morning and again Sunday night on WABC,
and was carried on other ABC affiliates around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a week before the Sept. 15 primary, with polls showing
Vallone ahead, his rivals are running out of time to draw interest
to their ill-financed candidacies in a race that has hardly
galvanized public attention. As the candidates themselves have
often noted, there is little that separates them on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins will have a difficult time against the popular
Republican incumbent, Gov. George Pataki, in no small measure
because Pataki is expected to spend as much as $20 million on this
race. With two months to go until the general election, Vallone has
been the top Democratic fund-raiser, collecting $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   All four Democrats railed Sunday against the current system,
which they said favored wealthy donors and the politicians who did
their bidding. Vallone boasted, as he often does, of the New York
City rules he helped create that limit political contributions,
provide public financing of campaigns and restrict ``soft money,''
the unlimited contributions to political parties. But Hynes noted
that Vallone had taken contributions from business interests that
seek contracts or zoning decisions from the city. He asserted that
the need for reform would be an issue in the general election, and
that the Democratic nominee would need to be able to tar Pataki as
a captive of special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make that case credibly,'' he said. ``Peter Vallone
cannot.''
</P>
<P>
   Larocca noted that he was the only candidate who was not an
elected official. ``The real problem we have here is that money is
washing over our political system,'' he said. ``I'm the only member
of this panel who is not part of that system.''
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, Vallone called the criticism inaccurate,
saying, ``I have something like 3,500 contributors, many of whom
have contributed under $100.'' He said that Larocca's and Hynes'
stances amounted to advocating that the Democrats unilaterally
disarm in the face of the Republicans' fund-raising advantage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross, who switched from the Republican Party last
year, was considered a leading contender for the nomination for
much of this year, but her campaign has stumbled badly. Last week,
her husband, Wilbur Ross Jr., a wealthy investment banker, withdrew
more than half of the $4 million he had committed to her effort.
There has also been turnover and dissension within the campaign,
and after campaigning energetically for months, she has made few
public appearances of late.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's debate, the lieutenant governor seemed oddly
detached. She sometimes wandered so far from the questions that she
was chided by the moderator, Robb Hanrahan, a WABC reporter. She
also refrained from attacking Vallone, a tactic that she later said
was a conscious decision.
</P>
<P>
   As she has throughout the campaign, Ms. McCaughey Ross, who was
Pataki's running mate in 1994, was questioned about the sincerity
of her party conversion. But on Sunday, she seemed unable to muster
much of a response.
</P>
<P>
   When a question came up about health care, the policy area of
Ms. McCaughey Ross' expertise, Larocca mentioned her rise to
national fame as the author of an article attacking President
Clinton's health care plan in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Though she has persuasively defended that article to Democratic
audiences in the past, she did not even try on Sunday; she
reiterated instead her support for universal health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   She was asked by a reporter to justify her switch to progressive
Democrat from conservative Republican and supporter of Newt
Gingrich. ``You know, I've taken a lot of hits lately, including
unfair ones like this, because I have never supported Newt
Gingrich's right-wing agenda,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hynes responded, ``The lieutenant governor, for two-and-a-half,
almost three years, supported the governor with laudatory
comments.''
</P>
<P>
   And Larocca said: ``To suggest the question is not fair is to
suggest again that you're being victimized. You're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Vallone, adhering to the classic front-runner's strategy,
refrained from saying anything negative about anyone. But just a
few minutes after the debate ended, his aides were handing
reporters a sheet of paper juxtaposing Ms. McCaughey Ross'
disavowal of Gingrich Sunday with a statement she made four years
ago, saying that she supported most of Gingrich's ``Contract With
America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
