<HEADLINE>
SOSA GOES 2-FOR-5, BUT NO HOME RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The McGwire-Sosa confrontation in St. Louis on
Monday and Tuesday is being so eagerly awaited that even the
players are having trouble finding tickets.
</P>
<P>
   This memo went out to the Chicago Cubs Sunday from the team's
traveling secretary, Jimmy Bank: ``Players and coaches will get
only six tickets each game. No exceptions! Especially you.''
</P>
<P>
   This memo came back: ``Traveling secretaries are allowed to go
through the post-game spread one time. No grazing or takeouts. No
exceptions! Especially you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs lost a game Sunday in extra innings in Pittsburgh, and
Sammy Sosa stayed at 58 home runs, but the players and coaches are
having a great time playing games that matter _ in September. This
is the first Cubs team since 1989 to have a meaningful game after
Sept. 1. The Cubs remain one game ahead of the New York Mets, who
also lost Sunday, in the National League wild-card race. And Sosa
remains two home runs behind Mark McGwire of the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Staying focused on the playoffs will be a chore in St. Louis, as
the dueling home run derbies (and their news media packs) collide
for games Monday afternoon and Tuesday evening at Busch Stadium.
Everyone seems to expect Roger Maris' record of 61 home runs to
fall any minute. The record shows, however, that McGwire has gone
as long as nine games without a home run this season, and Sosa 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation will be a little bit out of control tomorrow,''
Sosa said after Sunday's game. ``Tomorrow is going to be like the
World Series. I don't want to get out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would go to bed Sunday night thinking of questions to
ask McGwire if they meet at first base.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs players are at a high point on a roller-coaster season.
Each winning stretch this year has been followed by a bad streak.
Now they have won six out of seven, and eight out of 10. The Cubs
have their best record since 1989, when they won the National
League East.
</P>
<P>
   ``The home run thing is of great interest, but it's secondary,''
said Jim Riggleman, the Cubs' manager. ``Tomorrow will definitely
be a zoo.''
</P>
<P>
   On a blistering day on the carpet at Three Rivers Stadium, the
Cubs lost in the 10th inning, 4-3, on a home run by Jason Kendall,
the Pirate catcher. The Pirates broke an eight-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who drew applause from Pirates fans all weekend, faced a
left-handed pitcher, Chris Peters. Only nine of the 58 home runs by
Sosa, a right-hander, have come against left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa went 2-for-5, but never got enough loft on a ball to
threaten a home run.
</P>
<P>
   With the two home run combatants playing each other, the
question arises whether the pitchers will throw strikes. Would a
Cub pitcher allow McGwire to break the record ahead of Sosa? Would
the Cardinals allow Sosa to pull even with McGwire?
</P>
<P>
   ''It will depend on the game situation,'' Riggleman said. ``We'd
certainly like to see Sammy do it, but I think both guys will get
their pitches, and we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those tickets, don't expect to get them from the Cubs
secretary. ``They still ask,'' Bank said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
