<SLUG> BC-TEN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A NEW PERSPECTIVE SPURS SELES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also TEN-USOPEN) 
(mk) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The wind swirled Sunday and blew her tennis shots
this way and that. She broke four rackets _ count `em, four rackets
_ during her match. And Monica Seles, in white baseball cap and
short, white dress, seeded sixth in the U.S. Open, was forced into
a third set with unseeded Kimberly Po, the winner going into the
quarterfinals. It was not a terribly good day for Monica Seles,
but, as she would be the first to admit, she has dealt with worse.
</P>
<P>
   It was not necessary for the large, enthusiastic crowd, shading
their eyes from the brilliant noonday sun in the steep,
multilayered center-court stands of Arthur Ashe Stadium in Flushing
Meadows, to be reminded of the dark days of her young life.
</P>
<P>
   ``And sometimes,'' she said after Sunday's 6-2, 4-6, 6-3
victory, ``sometimes my mind would wander out there.''
</P>
<P>
   She spoke about losing concentration after going ahead by 6-2 in
the first set. ``I just started serving with no thought process
where I'm going to serve,'' she said, ``or what shots I'm going to
do.'' At such times her mind always goes back to the tragedies in
her life: when she was stabbed in the back in 1993 while seated
during a change-over in a tournament in Hamburg, Germany, when she
was 19 years old and the greatest woman tennis player in the world;
and the death of her father, her coach and dear friend, from cancer
last May; and at around the same time came another death, that of
her best friend.
</P>
<P>
   During the French Open, which began in late May, about two weeks
after her father's death, Seles wore his wedding ring around her
neck. ``I don't wear it anymore,'' she said. ``It's too much of a
constant reminder. It's too tough. There's too much of a void that
he left in me.''
</P>
<P>
   When things are not going well, on the court or off, she still
draws strength from the memory of her father, a professional
cartoonist. ``He could make a lot of even the most disastrous
things,'' she said. ``There came a point when he could, with just a
stroke or two of his pen, draw something _ even about the stabbing
_ that made me laugh to the floor. It was dark humor, but he just
had a certain knack. He could make you relax, and stop feeling
sorry for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Po drew even with a 6-4 second set. In the third set, after four
games, they were tied, 2-2. There were cheers to encourage Seles,
and, sitting in the stands, it seemed that that's where the fans'
hearts were. But Po had her supporters, too. ``Let's go, Kim,''
shouted someone as Po set to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Po happened to be the first person to play Seles, in a
tournament in Toronto in 1995, after Seles had stayed out of
competition for a little over two years, until her heart and psyche
were mended enough to try tennis again. The response to Seles'
entrance then was unforgettable. ``I walked out on that court and
the response for her was unbelievable,'' Po said. ``It was great. I
got chills.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday? ``Well, when you play Monica _ when you play any of
the great players _ you just think you have to do more, you have to
hit better, you have to hit lines.''
</P>
<P>
   But no, now she didn't think during play about being sympathetic
to her because of her personal problems. Now she just wants to beat
her, and advance in the tournament. Monica had similar ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Looking across the court at Seles, Po sees a different
individual. ``She is just a bigger person than before,'' Po said.
``She grew in every way. Before, she was a small girl. And now
she's grown up.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles, 24, has gotten physically bigger, and while her game
remains one of power, she still covers the court with grace, though
perhapsnot as well as she once did. But she has grown in other
ways, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think, `Why me?''' she said. ``But then I learned
that so many people can relate to some of the things that have
happened to me, that they've suffered tragedy at some point in
their lives. And I think the feeling to me has changed from when I
was a child. I did so well so suddenly, that maybe some people
resented that I got to the top so quickly. But sure, the man that
stabbed me took a lot away from me, some great years, some Grand
Slam wins. It was a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never going to be the same, but I think, `I'm still lucky
to be playing tennis, to still play a sport.' Like my dad said, if
the knife had plunged a half-millimeter to the left, I'd be
paralyzed and in a wheelchair today.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I see the world from that point of view,'' she continued.
``And when I see a 10-year-old boy who is terminally ill with
cancer, I understand how fortunate I've been, and appreciate how
good it feels to hit a backhand crosscourt winner, the feeling that
goes right through your body.'' She hit just such a shot to break
Po's serve and go ahead by 3-2 in the final set.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I can still be a little girl,'' she said. ``I still love
going into FAO Schwarz and picking out stuffed animals. I have a
stuffed animal collection _ and they have everything there.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles took the final two games to win the set and the match. She
had survived the wind, the sun, the brittle rackets and a
determined and worthy foe. Po congratulated her across the net. The
crowd applauded warmly, and Monica Seles smiled and waved back,
and, with her good rackets and bad in possession, disappeared under
the stands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
