<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOLTZ DOMINATES AS STRIKE ZONE FOOLS METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Few hitters have a better idea of their strike zone
than John Olerud. To see Olerud, the New York Mets' first baseman,
argue a called strike is rare enough. To watch him toss his bat
away and begin running to first base thinking he has walked, only
to be called back, is rarer still.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at Shea Stadium, when the Mets faced the Atlanta Braves'
John Smoltz, Olerud did both. And when Olerud began running toward
first in the bottom of the ninth inning, just before the plate
umpire, Larry Vanover, called a pitch strike two, it epitomized the
Mets' day against Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz went on to fan Olerud for the last of his 12 strikeouts,
putting the finishing touch on a 4-0 victory over the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   It took only 2 hours 15 minutes for Smoltz (14-3) to complete
his three-hit shutout. (All three hits were singles.) The Mets
(79-64), who were without Mike Piazza because of a bruised left
index finger, remained a game behind the Chicago Cubs in the
National League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Of Smoltz's 106 pitches, 75 were strikes. And of the 30 Mets
batters, only Olerud was able to work a three-ball count, which he
did twice.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud, who was second in the league in hitting when the day
began and leads the Mets with 80 walks, had a first-inning
conversation with Vanover after he was called out on strikes for
the first of three times. Asked later what he had said, Olerud
paraphrased it as, ``Is it me?''
</P>
<P>
   Mets right fielder Lenny Harris, who went 0-for-3 with a
strikeout, said of Vanover's strike zone: ``It was big enough that
the leading hitter in baseball couldn't make contact. I'm not
taking anything away from Smoltz. But he's the type of guy that
doesn't need that help.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanover was consistent: there were no walks on either side. Rick
Reed (16-9) had the benefit of a large strike zone, too, as 79 of
his 120 pitches were strikes. But of the seven hits Reed allowed in
his seven and two-thirds innings, three were solo home runs: to
Ryan Klesko in the second, to Marty Malloy (his first major-league
hit) in the third and to Andruw Jones in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said that only one of them came on a mistake, a hanging
change-up to Jones. But that was one too many against Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he made one mistake,'' Reed said. ``But you can
look at the scoreboard and get that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reed had one of the three singles off Smoltz; Edgardo Alfonzo
and Brian McRae had the others. Olerud said he did something he
almost never does: he moved closer to the plate in an effort to
reach Smoltz's pitches in the area that Vanover had deemed the
outside corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``John moved up a foot on the plate, Lenny even further, and
they still couldn't touch his pitches,'' Mets Manager Bobby
Valentine said, adding that the Mets had just won three consecutive
games against three of the better pitchers in the league, San
Diego's Andy Ashby and Atlanta's Tom Glavine and Kevin Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then today we faced a real good guy who kept throwing
where we couldn't hit it,'' Valentine said. ``A couple of them were
strikes, too. I've never seen John Olerud take three called third
strikes, and that's only because he never has in his career. But
Smoltz was doing a great job of hitting spots. Give him credit for
that. Our left-handers couldn't hit the pitches he was throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   After a while, the Mets gave in and began swinging at anything
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very aggressive,'' said Smoltz, who said both his
fastball and his curve were working well. ``I knew that going in.
They're playing for the playoffs. So they're playing with a lot of
character. At the same time, we're playing to get the best
record.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley went 3-for-4 with a two-run home run and five runs
batted in for Class AAA Norfolk in a 9-4 victory at Richmond
Sunday. In seven games in his second rehabilitation stint with the
Tides this season, Hundley, who played left field Sunday, is
10-for-20 with three homers and 11 RBIs. Hundley homered from the
right side of the plate on Saturday and from the left side of the
plate in the first inning Sunday. ... Marty Malloy went 2-for-4 for
the Braves in his major-league debut after his contract was
purchased from Class AAA Richmond Sunday. To make room on their
roster, the Braves transferred struggling reliever Mark Wohlers to
the 60-day disabled list. ... Atlanta's final run came on a mammoth
home run estimated at 447 feet by Andres Galarraga off Jeff Tam in
the top of the ninth. Galarraga had been suspended for the first
two games of the series, both Mets victories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
