<HEADLINE>
NORTHWEST STRIKE MEDIATOR SENDS THE NEGOTIATORS HOME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Mich., Ill., Tenn., N.D., Fla.)   (jw) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After shuttling between negotiators for Northwest Airlines and
its striking pilots for two days, a federal mediator sent the two
sides home Sunday and asked them to try harder to bring an end to
the nine-day strike, which has grounded Northwest's nearly 1,700
daily flights.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse statement, the National Mediation Board, which has
been supervising negotiations between the airline and its 6,200
pilots since June, said that further meetings would be held in
Minneapolis on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   People briefed on the discussions said that little progress was
made at the weekend session, which was called by the board last
week at the behest of Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater to see
if resuming negotiations would be productive. The meeting took
place at a hotel near Chicago's O'Hare International Airport. The
two sides met separately with the mediator.
</P>
<P>
   The board's statement said the weekend meetings ``involved the
parameters of a settlement,'' but it did not elaborate. The
statement pointed to the substantive differences between the two
sides and asked them to reconsider their positions.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest is the country's fourth-largest airline. It dominates
air service in the upper Midwest and middle South, normally flying
80 percent of the flights out of Detroit and Minneapolis, and more
than half the flights out of Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   The governors of several states, including Minnesota, Michigan
and North Dakota, have called on President Clinton to halt the
strike. Last year, Clinton ordered pilots at American Airlines back
to work minutes after they struck, saying that a strike would cause
too much disruption to the economy. The White House, while
following the situation closely, has resisted intervening in the
Northwest strike, a move the company would welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Pay and job security are the main issues in the strike, which is
the longest in the industry since Eastern Airlines machinists
walked out in 1989. Analysts say that the hard line taken by each
side overshadows the narrow differences between the positions. The
pilots say their demands would cost the company only $70 million a
year; Northwest says the figure is closer to $170 million. The
strike has already cost Northwest an estimated $300 million in
expenses and lost revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots are angry that Northwest has resisted giving them a
substantial raise after they and other unions made wage concessions
in 1993 to save the airline from bankruptcy. Since then, Northwest
has posted four years of record profits and its executives have
cashed in stock options worth millions.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest, which is also in contract negotiations with unions
representing its flights attendants, customer service
representatives and machinists, says that it cannot afford to give
the pilots what they demand.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Tuesday's meeting would lead to a
resumption of negotiations, which were last held on Aug. 28, hours
before the pilots walked out.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the board declined to comment on the talks, as
did representatives of Northwest and the Air Line Pilots
Association. The two side were asked by the board not to make
public statements.
</P>
<P>
   Another airline, Airtran, narrowly averted disruption over the
weekend when it reached agreement on a new four-year contract with
its flight attendants. The tentative agreement would give 500
flight attendants an immediate 10 percent raise plus 4 percent
annual raises.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first tentative contract for the Association of
Flight Attendants at Airtran, which is based in Orlando, Fla., and
was formerly called Valujet. The flight attendants had been without
a contract since they organized three years ago and had threatened
random walkouts that would have disrupted flights over the holiday
weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
