<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: SOUTH OF THE BORDER, LONG AGO; LANDSCAPES OF 2
CONTINENTS; CHINESE CLASSIC ON LONDON STAGE; JAZZ WITH LATIN SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Conn., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men and women feast, war and woo. Fanciful animals frolic. The
time is the millennium from 800 B.C. to A.D. 200, and a new exhibit
that reveals the era's creativity, ``Ancient West Mexico: Art of
the Unknown Past,'' is at the Art Institute of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The show has more than 225 works, mostly terra-cotta sculptures,
and is trumpeted as the most comprehensive exploration of the
artistic and cultural traditions of those who once inhabited parts
of what are now the Mexican states of Jalisco, Colima and Nayarit.
The show runs through Nov. 22. Information: (312) 443-3600.
</P>
<P>
   Two Worlds
</P>
<P>
   The landscape traditions of two emergent nations, Australia and
the United States, will be explored beginning on Friday in an
exhibition at the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford, Conn. With more
than 100 paintings, roughly half from each country, the show, ``New
Worlds From Old: 19th-Century Australian and American Landscapes,''
draws on the collections of 32 American, 11 Australian and two
European museums and galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 37 American artists represented by major works are
Thomas Cole, Frederic Edwin Church, Albert Bierstadt and Winslow
Homer. Nearly all the historical landscapes by the 23 Australian
artists, including Eugene von Guerard, Arthur Streeton and Tom
Roberts, have never been shown outside that country. The exhibition
continues through Jan. 3. Information: (860) 278-2670.
</P>
<P>
   Blossom Times
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials may have seen to it that the epic 16th-century
opera ``The Peony Pavilion'' never played at Lincoln Center
Festival '98 this summer, but a chance to see ``Peony Pavilion''
arises this week at BITE:98, the Barbican International Theater
Event in London.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Peony Pavilion,'' directed by Peter Sellars, is not the
19-hour version that was to have been seen in New York, but a
roughly 3-hour avant-garde interpretation of the opera's central
love story that had its world premiere at this year's Vienna
Festival. This 400th-anniversary production of Tang Xianxu's
classic includes specially written music by Tan Dun and a cast that
features Hua Wenyi, a leading Kun opera exponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peony Pavilion'' opens on Thursday for a nine-performance run
through Sept. 20 at the Barbican Theater. Information:
011-44-171-638-8891.
</P>
<P>
   A Latin Beat
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As far back as turn-of-the century New Orleans, Jelly
Roll Morton was proclaiming the importance of a ``Spanish tinge''
to jazz, and Latin idioms have long been a component of the music.
So when Jazz at Lincoln Center opens its 1998-99 season beginning
at 8 p.m. Thursday at Alice Tully Hall, its three-night series will
be titled ``Con Alma: The Latin Tinge in Big Band Jazz.''
</P>
<P>
   The event explores the interaction between Afro-Cuban rhythms
and rich big-band textures through works by Machito, Chico
O'Farrill, Duke Ellington, Tito Puente and Dizzy Gillespie.
Information: (212) 875-5299.
</P>
</TEXT>
