<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE UNDERSTUDY OUT THERE ON THE `ISLAND' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ As the Giants' right cornerback, Conrad
Hamilton was not only out there on what is known in pro football as
``the island,'' he was also out there as an understudy to the star.
With Jason Sehorn awaiting knee surgery on Sept. 22, it was as if
Hamilton had suddenly replaced Tom Hanks or Tom Cruise in a feature
film.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Redskins burned the 5-foot-10-inch cornerback with
a 17-yard touchdown pass from Gus Frerotte to Leslie Shepherd early
in the first quarter, the understudy appeared to be flubbing his
lines.
</P>
<P>
   But early in the second half, Hamilton stole what turned out to
be the crucial scene in the Giants' 31-24 victory in their season
opener. On a pass from Frerotte to Shepherd that popped out of
cornerback Phillippi Sparks' hands, the understudy snatched it out
of the air at the Redskins' 19-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should've scored,'' Hamilton said later.
</P>
<P>
   He was stopped at the 2-yard line, but his interception return
positioned Charles Way's touchdown burst for a 17-10 lead. On the
Redskins' next possession, defensive end Michael Strahan rumbled 24
yards with another interception of a Frerotte pass for a 24-10
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed Conrad Hamilton how to get in the end zone,'' the
6-4, 280-pound Strahan said later, joking. ``I looked pretty good
when I turned my face mask up.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the Giants hung on to win, Hamilton could have joked
too, but he didn't. He's too serious for that, too quietly
confident that he can do what Sehorn did. Maybe not quite so
smoothly, but effectively enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know,'' Hamilton said of his coaches and teammates,
``what kind of a football player I am. I'm a pretty decent football
player. I'm a good tackler, a very good tackler.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins apparently knew, too. With a chance for the tying
touchdown on their last two possessions, their backup quarterback
Trent Green (who had replaced the groggy Frerotte) didn't throw
into Hamilton's area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted them to come at me at the end,'' Hamilton said. ``In
the first half, too. I wanted to make a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fassel said Hamilton did make a statement with his
interception. ``You saw how he reacted,'' the Giants' coach said,
alluding to Hamilton's comeback after the Redskins' early
touchdown. ``He kept fighting. He kept playing. He knocked some
balls down. That was a great play when that ball was tipped and he
picked it off and almost ran it in. That's him, and that's how I
want the attitude of this football team to be. No matter how the
game goes, you keep coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel remembered how the other Giants had reacted to Hamilton
after Shepherd's early touchdown. ``When he came to the sideline,''
the coach said, ``no one was saying anything to him but `stay in
there,' `stay right on top of it' and `play aggressively.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn was on the sideline too, but he purposely stayed away
from Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't talk to Conrad about the Redskins during the week
either,'' Sehorn said. ``He's got enough coaches, and I'm not a
coach. I'd probably confuse him anyway. He didn't need me to talk
to him. He did a great job. After he had some adversity, he bounced
back and made a big play.''
</P>
<P>
   He also led the Giants in tackles with eight, plus an assist on
another tackle. But according to the play-by-play sheet, the
Redskins completed 6-of-7 passes in his area for 88 yards. Oddly,
the Redskins rarely threw to Michael Westbrook in his area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I'd be matched up against Westbrook more, but they
usually had Shepherd on me,'' Hamilton said. ``They tried to pick
on me a little bit; if you were the Redskins, wouldn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Except for one start as a nickel back as a rookie two seasons
ago, this was Hamilton's first appearance in the starting lineup
since he was a Little all-America defensive back at Eastern New
Mexico before becoming the Giants' seventh-round choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was definitely a little pressure,'' he said. ``But not
because of who I was replacing, not because I was starting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was presumably referring to the normal pressure that
surrounds any cornerback out on that ``island'' _ all by himself.
And he'll be out there again next Sunday at Oakland, especially
whenever Tim Brown, the Pro Bowl wide receiver, lines up against
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing I can't accomplish, but it's definitely a
challenge,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   And with the confidence that every cornerback needs, Hamilton
sounded as if he would enjoy the challenge. Even as an understudy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
