<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWS MIXED ON A CLINTON RECOVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator Joseph I. Lieberman, a Connecticut
Democrat, said Sunday that publicly chastising President Clinton
for ``immoral'' conduct was ``the hardest thing I've ever done in
my political career,'' and that he hoped Clinton could now rebuild
his presidency and finish his term with punishment no more severe
than a congressional censure.
</P>
<P>
   But Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, appearing after
Lieberman on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' said that the president
probably had committed impeachable offenses in denying his affair
with Monica S. Lewinsky, a former White House intern, and that it
was unlikely Congress would be content with votes to censure or
rebuke him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying'' censure ``is not a possibility,'' said Lott,
a Mississippi Republican, ``but right now I'd say that's not
likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that he signed a petition to censure President
Nixon in 1974, Lott said he knows more about censure now and has
concluded it is a meaningless sanction. ``I don't think the
circumstances now call for something that would be interpreted by
anyone as nothing,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Lieberman stood alone on the Senate floor and
delivered a stinging rebuke of Clinton, saying he had diminished
his office, undermined his moral authority, set a terrible example
for children, and inadequately apologized or explained his behavior
to Americans. A moderate and longtime friend of Clinton's,
Lieberman was the first Democrat to speak out so forcefully in
public, but he stopped short of calling for Congress to censure
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Lieberman said he hoped a censure vote would ``be the
maximum we will want to do to end this chapter in our history.'' He
said that he believed ``very, very few Democrats or Republicans
want a presidential impeachment or resignation,'' and that any talk
about either must wait until the independent counsel, Kenneth W.
Starr, sends Congress his report, which is expected this month.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, congressional Democrats, who are anxious about the
contents of that report and still very unhappy with the president's
conduct and apologies, expressed serious doubts about the
president's ability to survive the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Representative James Moran, a Virginia Democrat and Clinton
supporter, said on ``Fox News Sunday'' that the president now would
be ``fortunate'' to get censured, and that he believed the Congress
was ``bound to go through with &UR;  &LR; impeachment proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think this is the most serious crisis'' the president
``has ever faced, and I don't really see any way out of it,'' Moran
said. ``His credibility is obviously severely diminished. I don't
know how he can ever recover the strength of the bully pulpit he
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Moran said he was ``profoundly disappointed'' that the president
had tried to talk his way out of his troubles with ``a twisted
logic that uses the legal system to subvert what we know to be the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said Sunday they could not speculate on the
possibility of impeachment until Starr delivered his report and
catalogued Clinton's alleged offenses, which could include perjury,
obstruction of justice, and abuse of power. Lott said that while it
would be up to the House to decide when, and if, to hold
impeachment hearings, he would prefer any proceeding be delayed
until next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinct tells me that we should not rush to judgment and
that to try to do it in the middle of a campaign or even in a
lame-duck session, I'd want to think very carefully about doing
that,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a New York Democrat, said
both a ``crisis in the regime'' and a host of dangerous, looming
international situations requires the Congress to take up an
impeachment procedure as soon as it receives the Starr report and
stay in Washington until it completes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing more important to do in the nation's
interest,'' said Moynihan, who appeared on ABC's ``This Week with
Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts.'' ``The president is not going to
resign. He is going to see how an impeachment proceeding goes or
does not go.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan said he believed the president could reestablish the
public trust he has lost, and Lieberman said Clinton's apology
Friday in Ireland was ``heartening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one better than Bill Clinton at communicating with
people, and this in the days ahead may be the greatest test he's
ever had,'' Lieberman said. ``But I'm confident he can restore the
full moral authority of his presidency and go on to finish ...
honorably.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he had not spoken to the president since his
remarks Thursday, though he did talk with him twice before publicly
rebuking him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did tell him I was going to make a public statement ... and
though I knew parts of it would be very uncomfortable for him to
hear, I honestly felt it was the best thing to do for him and his
presidency,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
