<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTY SCHNYDER, THE UNKNOWN SWISS, UPSETS GRAF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos of Patty Schnyder and Monica Seles are being sent
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036. 
(lh) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Having never before faced the stare and sting of
Steffi Graf across the net, Patty Schnyder, a 19-year-old power
hitter who is a virtual unknown outside Switzerland, had no cause
to fear her. On Sunday night at the U.S. Open, ignorance proved to
be bliss for the 11th-seeded Schnyder as she blasted her way to a
6-3, 6-4 upset of the eighth-seeded Graf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to see her like anyone else,'' said Schnyder,
who confessed that she hadn't a clue how she kept her jitters _
about facing Graf in a main event match in Arthur Ashe Stadium _
completely under control.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, a five-time Open champion who missed this Grand Slam event
last year while recuperating from career-threatening knee surgery,
made her earliest exit from this major championship in 14 years.
Not since she was a rank rookie of 15 had Graf failed to secure a
berth in the Open's quarterfinal round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I made a lot of mistakes, easy mistakes,'' said
Graf, who plopped out 33 unforced errors and was constantly in
trouble trying to counter the left-handed Schnyder's bold
cross-court forehands with her backhand slice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just never found my game. I couldn't get any depth in my
shots, so it was difficult to get a positive attitude,'' said Graf,
who had hoped her victories against second-ranked Lindsay Davenport
and third-ranked Jana Novotna en route to the New Haven title a
week ago would bring her Open campaign together on an invincible
note.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Graf found herself making an Open exit on a very
vulnerable note, as the first marquee name on the women's side to
drop out of the chase for the 1998 title.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, Carlos Moya was once again obliged to
impersonate Houdini. First he reversed a two-sets-to-none deficit
under the spotlights at the U.S. Open against Michael Chang, a
second-round ordeal that lasted nearly four hours. That left Moya,
the defending French Open champion, wasting away on the trainer's
table in the wee hours on Saturday morning. But it left him
relieved to be in contention at the year's last major championship
as he beat Chang, the battler who wrote the book on surviving five
set marathon hauls. If the Spaniard could beat Chang at his forte,
who else could hurt him here?
</P>
<P>
   But then, almost before Moya was ready, his first-ever visit to
the Open's third round beckoned. Moya was nursing aches and pains
beyond his 22 years. And darned if the American challenger in this
round didn't look like a strapping specter straight out of an
exercise video. Jan-Michael Gambill and his baseline calisthenics
were definitely not a sight for Moya's sore eyes as he shuffled off
to do his duty in Round 3.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there he was back in action Sunday, taking his lumps in
yet another five-set march to the far side of exhaustion and, for
the second consecutive match, living to tell a victorious tale.
This time the 10th-seeded Moya toiled for 2 hours 58 minutes in a
topspin-spoiling wind. He needed a sudden-death tie breaker before
sneaking past Gambill, 6-2, 3-6, 3-6, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4) after Gambill
buried a two-fisted forehand into the net on Moya's third match
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him the match, basically,'' Gambill said. ``Moya is one
of the toughest competitors on the Tour, so I don't have to give
him credit _ he's earned that credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambill praised Moya and berated himself for his shot selection
in the tie breaker, where a double fault left him 2-0 in arrears
right off the bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played a good tie breaker, but he didn't do anything
special,'' said Gambill, a 21-year-old Star Trek fan from Spokane,
Wash., after making his best-ever major-championship showing in his
first full season on the main circuit. Despite his inexperience,
Gambill is expected to be named to play singles for the U.S. Davis
Cup team in its semifinal against Italy in Milwaukee later this
month owing to the no-show status of Pete Sampras, Andre Agassi,
Jim Courier and Chang.
</P>
<P>
   ``A loss is never the end of the world to me,'' said Gambill,
who established his credentials as an upset artist when he stunned
Agassi in the quarterfinals at Indian Wells. ``I'm going to learn
from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambill's arduous exit left just two American men, Sampras and
Agassi, afloat in the Round of 16, an open-era low.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the hot, gusty breeze seemed to emanate from a
steam kettle and yanked everybody's favorite shots skyward like
kites, Moya wasn't the only seeded player to receive a rough ride.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Krajicek, the 1996 Wimbledon champion, who was seeded
fifth here, dropped out of his third-round match against Sweden's
Thomas Johansson at 7-6 (7-5), 4-5 due to a flare-up of the chronic
tendinitis in his left knee. And 13th-seeded Tim Henman of Britain
was so befuddled by the wind and glare that he needed four sets to
fight off 149th-ranked Michael Kohlmann, a German qualifier who was
the lowest-ranked man left in the event, 6-3, 7-5, 1-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a real glare on the court, and the wind's just
coming from all directions,'' Henman complained. ``I think I got
the job done, (a) in difficult conditions, and (b) playing pretty
ordinary, pretty ugly tennis at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Henman's complaints were echoed by sixth-seeded Monica Seles,
who called the playing conditions ``unrealistic'' and unkind. Seles
dropped her first set of the tournament, squandering a 4-1
second-set lead, before righting herself against Kimberly Po and
advancing 6-2, 4-6, 6-3 to a quarterfinal meeting with top-seeded
Martina Hingis, the Open's defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more than wind,'' said Seles, whose composure was
further tested by the four racquets that cracked in the hot
sunshine after making the transition from the overly
air-conditioned players' lounge to the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Like Seles, Hingis was not overly pleased with the Round of 16
victory, a mistake-marred 6-4, 6-4 ouster of Nathalie Dechy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just kind of escaping every day,'' Hingis said of the
errors that seem to be compromising her attempt, at 17, to become
the youngest Open champion to mount a successful title defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was motivated when I came here to do well again,'' she said.
``Instead of getting better, I'm getting worse, is what I have the
feeling of right now. If I'm going to continue playing like this,
I'm not going to go anywhere. I definitely have to raise my
level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
