<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RECOVERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISSAIR FLIGHT-DATA RECORDER IS FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ Divers recovered the flight-data recorder
of Swissair 111 Saturday, providing investigators with potentially
mystery-solving evidence about the trans-Atlantic flight that ended
with the deaths of 229 people Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Working 190 feet below the ocean's surface, military divers with
as few as 6 minutes apiece to scour the murky, rocky bottom found
the so-called black box among three large pieces of debris that may
be part of the MD-11's fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   Placed in a pail of seawater for protection, the recorder was
hand-carried to waiting investigators who flew the evidence to the
Canadian Transportation Safety Board's engineering lab in Ottawa
last night for days of round-the-clock analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The recorder monitored about 100 systems aboard the aircraft. If
the titanium-protected box is in good condition _ and if its power
was not cut off before impact _ the data should pinpoint what
malfunctioned aboard the seven-year-old aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``These boxes are pretty robust,'' said Jim Harris, an
investigator with the Canadian safety board. ``This could go a long
way to explaining the puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said that the recorder must be cleaned and decontaminated
before a multinational team of analysts can begin its work at what
the investigator called a ``very sophisticated lab.'' The
preliminary work will take several days, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The recorder was retrieved after divers returned to an area 5
nautical miles off Peggy's Cove where pinging from a transponder
had been heard Saturday. Rough weather forced divers to call off
that effort, but their return Saturday yielded what one Canadian
Navy commander called ``the honeypot'' of the search.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery was made despite 10 feet of visibility and
football-size rocks that are constantly moving because of tide and
weather, Navy Captain Paul Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   Three pieces of wreckage were found around the recorder that
officials are ``relatively sure'' are part of the fuselage, said
Vic Gerden, the chief investigator.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces will be retrieved and brought to the Shearwater
military base near here, where other remnants of the aircraft have
been stored for reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The base is also where collected human remains have been placed
in refrigerated containers while victims' relatives supply DNA
samples to help with the painstaking identification process. The US
Defense Department has been asked to assist in the DNA analysis.
</P>
<P>
   By late Saturday, only one body had been found intact, that of a
French woman. The partially intact body of an infant has also been
retrieved. Officials have said it is possible that no more complete
bodies will be found.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Butt, the provincial medical examiner, Saturday
described in emotional words Saturday how he and his staff have
tried to both console and inform the many relatives and friends of
the victims who have come to Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an experience that we can only imagine,'' he said of
the relatives' grief.
</P>
<P>
   The search and recovery effort, which is being aided by the
United States and Switzerland, will now focus on finding the
cockpit voice recorder, the other black box, that may give
investigators a picture of what the pilots knew, and when.
</P>
<P>
   The pinging from that box's transponder has not been picked up,
but Webster of the Canadian Navy said that the flight-data
recorder's signal may have been stronger and obscured it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, help is on the way from the US Navy, which has
dispatched the salvage ship USS Grapple to the scene. The ship,
which aided in the TWA Flight 800 crash investigation off Long
Island, sailed from Philadelphia Saturday and is expected off Nova
Scotia by Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the cause of the Swissair tragedy is a mystery. Part of
the puzzle is what prompted the pilots to issue a distress call 70
miles southwest of Halifax. They reported smoke in the cabin to
air-traffic controllers in New Brunswick, and British Airways
pilots who overheard the transmission told investigators they felt
certain that the Swissair crew had donned oxygen masks.
</P>
<P>
   The British pilots have said they discerned ``no panic'' by
their Swissair counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The chief investigator of the crash said Saturday that the
debris retrieved so far gives no indication of the origin of the
smoke. No evidence of a fire has been found on the wreckage, Gerden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another question is why the Swissair crew, told by air traffic
controllers that they were 30 miles from Halifax International
Airport, suddenly realized they were too high to make an emergency
landing. The pilots requested permission to break off their
approach and circle back out over the ocean to dump fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the pilots declared they needed to land
immediately. Radio contact was soon lost, and within six minutes
the aircraft had plunged violently into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the aircraft should have begun dumping fuel 70 miles
from Halifax, and thus saved itself some precious time, is among
``the questions we are asking ourselves now,'' said Harris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
