<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-680(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SENATE RACE, THREE CITY CANDIDATES ACCENTUATE UPSTATE TIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERTOWN, N.Y. _ Before a dinner of pizza and beer in a back
room at Pete's, an Italian restaurant and bar here in the
northernmost reaches of New York state, Mark Green on Friday
offered what has become his trademark serenade to voters outside of
New York City as he pursues the Democratic nomination for U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in Brooklyn, raised in Nassau,'' Green said. ``My
wife grew up in Westchester.'' He added that he attended Cornell
University in Tompkins County and hastened to introduce his
19-year-old daughter, Jenya, who is a sophomore at the school in
Ithaca and had accompanied her father to underscore the point.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Geraldine Ferraro, the former vice
presidential nominee who is also seeking the nomination, made a
point of reminding voters in Middletown, her first stop on a
three-day upstate campaign swing, that she was born in Orange
County and spent her earliest childhood years there.
</P>
<P>
   And on his visits north, Rep. Charles Schumer of Brooklyn, the
third major Democratic contender, sometimes tells people that his
father was born in Utica. And for good measure, he tries to
demonstrate his local affinity by traveling with congressional
colleagues or other area officials who support his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   In the upper corridors of New York state, these final days
before the Sept. 15 primary are treating Democratic voters to the
spectacle of three quintessential New York City politicians
striving for votes by grasping for ties that stretch beyond the
five boroughs and their suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who is New York City's public advocate, lives on the
Upper East Side of Manhattan, and dresses it. Schumer, the
nine-term congressman, lives in Park Slope, Brooklyn, and sounds
it. And Ms. Ferraro, who is a former representative from Queens,
still has a home in Forest Hills Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   So, running for statewide office presents a beguiling challenge:
how to connect to the voters of western, central and northern New
York, who are generally skeptical and often feel as shunted to the
margins politically as they are geographically.
</P>
<P>
   That obstacle can be even greater in a Democratic primary
because rural voters, even registered Democrats, tend to be more
conservative and because the conventional wisdom suggests that
their votes matter little. Typically, more than 70 percent of
primary ballots are cast in New York City and its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling up here sometimes among Democrats that we're
ignored,'' said Mike Schell, the former Democratic chairman of
Jefferson County who now heads the Democratic Rural Conference, a
coalition of party leaders from the state's 41 smallest counties.
</P>
<P>
   But with Ms. Ferraro, Green and Schumer all extremely well-known
in New York City, the candidates and their aides say that votes
north and west of Rockland County could prove crucial in the
primary.
</P>
<P>
   At her campaign stop in Middletown, Ms. Ferraro said that she
expects the major candidates ``will split the city a third each.''
She said that to lift her to victory this year, she is ``banking
on'' the city's suburbs and upstate, where she scored well in her
unsuccessful bid for the nomination in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who was the Democratic nominee in 1986 but lost to
Alfonse D'Amato, the Republican who still holds the seat, has also
put higher stakes in his upstate campaign. He began courting the
Democratic Rural Conference when it was first created two years ago
and won the group's endorsement in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of room to grow upstate because I'm less
well-known there,'' said Green, whose campaign began airing two
television advertisements in upstate media markets within the last
week. ``I gain more and more rapidly once they know I'm not just
some downstate stranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has declined to characterize any region of the state as
more or less important to his campaign strategy. But he has made a
point of emphasizing particular local issues whenever he travels
north and has enlisted many upstate elected officials to boost his
candidacy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Any candidate from anywhere in the state can become well-known
upstate if they do one of two things _ visit frequently or appear
in the media frequently,'' said Robert Cook, the Monroe County
Democratic chairman. ``Schumer has been pretty generous with media
buys. People know him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook has not endorsed any of the candidates but many county
chairmen have. Of the state's 62 counties, Green claims 31 as his
supporters, Ms. Ferraro says she has the backing of 13 and Schumer
has six behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the candidates has taken a different approach to
practical campaigning upstate. Green has campaign offices in
Buffalo and Rochester. Ms. Ferraro, who had a highly organized
upstate effort in 1992, has more loosely organized support this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who has raised far more money than either Green or Ms.
Ferraro, has made quick trips upstate by airplane to hold news
conferences or attend events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had Chuck on a cycle,'' said G. Steven Pigeon, the Erie
County chairman, who is supporting Schumer. ``He's campaigning like
he's running for county executive, hitting all the public events,''
Pigeon said.
</P>
<P>
   Schell, of Jefferson County and the Rural Democratic Conference,
said Green's manner appealed to northern voters. ``He is able to
bridge whatever differences there are in personalities upstate and
downstate,'' he said. ``That probably comes from his being educated
up here and growing up in the suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Glavin, the Rensselaer chairman, who is supporting Ms.
Ferraro, said, ``You have got to have someone on the line who can
generate the enthusiasm. She's the only one who can beat D'Amato.
It's important to have someone who can appeal to the whole state,
especially upstate.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's northern and western tiers are far more crucial in a
general election than in a primary. D'Amato proved that in 1986
when Green fared better in New York City but D'Amato retained his
seat by trouncing Green in the suburbs and upstate.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the candidates gently tailor their messages to the
upstate crowds. Green, for instance, speaking to aides, described
his support by the Democratic chairmen of the seven most
northeastern counties as a ``yarmulke on New York State.'' But in
the speech later at Pete's restaurant, he said they ``formed a cap
on the north country.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of issues, all three candidates put more emphasis on
the upstate economy, which has not kept pace with the growth
downstate. On the campaign trail, the candidates often face
questions ranging from their views on the dairy industry to the
Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their efforts, voters say the New York City
candidates still have work to do. At The Crystal Restaurant in
Watertown _ which opened in 1919 and still has an ``All Legal
Beverages'' sign dating from Prohibition _ Jim Walsh, a life-long
Democrat, said he felt little attachment to any of the primary
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Ferraro, I used to watch her on Crossfire,'' said
Walsh, who is 67. ``But I don't like her husband and his antics.
Mark Green doesn't mean much to me because he's never been brought
to the forefront here. He's pretty much a city boy. Schumer, he's
another. He's a House of Representatives guy. That's all I know
about him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
