<HEADLINE>
BIG MARKETERS JOIN TO UPGRADE INTERNET ADS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn.)  (lb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seven top marketers are joining At Home Corp., which operates
the At Home Network Internet service, to create and test the
larger, more elaborate types of online advertising that were the
subject of a meeting last month on interactive marketing sponsored
by Procter &AMP; Gamble Co.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Bratton, advertising director for the At Home Network in
Redwood City, Calif., identified the marketers as AT&AMP;T Corp., the
Bank of America unit of BankAmerica Corp., First USA, Intel Corp.,
Johnson &AMP; Johnson, Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. and Toys ``R'' Us.
</P>
<P>
   The marketers will run ads that use so-called rich media
techniques, which take advantage of the large bandwidth, or network
carrying capacity, of At Home. Such ads are bigger than those now
usually associated with the Internet and can offer animation, sound
and full video.
</P>
<P>
   The test, to be conducted by IPSOS-ASI, a market research
company in Stamford, Conn., and co-sponsored by Intel, will
evaluate the effectiveness of the ads using traditional
measurements like recall, awareness and intent to purchase the
products advertised. Results are to be made available in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980906.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BANKRUPTCY-FEUD-10     09-06 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BANKRUPTCY-FEUD-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEUD HAMPERS EFFORT TO RESOLVE BANKRUPTCY IN UPSTATE NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the sort of fight usually found on a playground, complete
with glares, name-calling and a tussle over strawberry Twizzlers.
</P>
<P>
   But this dispute is going on in a courtroom in upstate New York,
where two men who are supposed to be unraveling an enormous
financial mess are fighting each other instead.
</P>
<P>
   Their battle is just the latest twist in the case of Bennett
Funding Group, a Syracuse, N.Y., operation that the authorities
call the biggest pyramid scheme in American history. When the
concern, which financed equipment leases, collapsed in 1996, about
10,000 people _ many of them retirees from New York, New Jersey and
Florida _ lost as much as $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Breeden, former chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, is responsible for trying to get their money back. As
trustee of the Bennett companies' bankruptcy, he has already had
unusual success, recently mailing checks to investors totaling $50
million. While that amounts to only about 6 cents for every dollar
lost, most victims of pyramid schemes are lucky to get even a penny
back.
</P>
<P>
   And Breeden promises more to come, including $125 million from
an insurance settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But in the course of his efforts, he has run afoul of Guy Van
Baalen, a Justice Department official based in Utica, N.Y., whose
job is to supervise bankruptcies in northern New York.
</P>
<P>
   In court documents, Van Baalen accuses Breeden, whose pay as
trustee amounts to $600,000 a year, of overbilling for his work
(and for personal expenses like candy), and with creating conflicts
of interest so serious that he should be removed from the case.
Among other things, Van Baalen criticizes Breeden for serving as
chairman of Equivest Finance Inc., a company invested in by the
Bennett group, whose ownership stake has been taken over by the
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Breeden contends that Van Baalen is a petty bureaucrat who has
willfully misunderstood his efforts to help the investors. ``I
control the company because it's the creditors', and I want to be
damn sure how their money is spent,'' Breeden said of his role at
Equivest, which finances consumers' purchases of time-share
resorts.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has delayed _ and may ultimately derail _ Breeden's
efforts to sell stock in Equivet, which he describes as the only
valuable asset Bennett has. But even if the sale occurs, Wall
Street's sharp decline has cut into the value of the stock, which
was trading for almost $175 million in late July but today is worth
less than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Van Baalen opposes the sale, saying Breeden has not given the
court enough information about it. But he says he understands that
it is the foundation of Breeden's efforts to recover money for the
investors. ``The trustee has put so much into this sale of stock as
really crucial, that if it doesn't go ... oh, my God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All of which has some people involved in the case rolling their
eyes in exasperation. Indeed, a creditors' committee that
represents almost all the individual investors in the case asked
the bankruptcy judge in the case to put off any discussion on the
conflict-of-interest allegations until after he rules on the
Equivest sale, which he may do this week.
</P>
<P>
   While the committee has criticized Breeden's fees _ and what it
calls his high-handed ways _ it wants the stock sale to go through,
said Daniel Stolz, a lawyer for the creditors.
</P>
<P>
   How this dispute is resolved has enormous implications for the
reputations of the men involved and for the thousands of investors
who are awaiting more cash.
</P>
<P>
   It may also affect the criminal trial of Patrick Bennett, who
ran the Bennett companies and has been charged with 37 counts
related to securities fraud. His trial is to begin in November in
U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute may ultimately have implications for Syracuse, the
struggling upstate city of 164,000 where the whole mess began.
Though the city's economy is starting to show signs of growth after
years of stagnation, the pace is slow _ the city added just 200 new
jobs in the year ended in June, according to the state Department
of Labor, an increase of 0.1 percent (in New York City, by
contrast, jobs increased by 2.3 percent in the same period).
</P>
<P>
   So Syracuse is still a place where every job counts. At its
peak, the Bennett group employed 250 people, the bulk of whom still
work there but could become unemployed as the bankruptcy winds
down. Breeden hopes Equivest will be able to hire some of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Bennett companies were founded in 1977 by Edmund Bennett,
known as Bud, and his wife, Kathleen. The bulk of their business
came from financing leases on office equipment, like copiers and
fax machines, which are often rented by state and local
governments.
</P>
<P>
   The company appeared to be extremely successful. From 1985 to
1987, it made Inc. magazine's list of the 500 fastest-growing
private companies in America. The elder Bennetts, and their two
sons, Patrick and Michael, became important figures and
philanthropists in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, according to court documents, the Bennetts began
selling the leases, and pools of leases, to investors. Most of the
sales were done through small brokerage firms, which described the
leases to clients as very conservative investments.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators were not so sure. In 1994, the Securities and
Exchange Commission began looking into the Bennett empire.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, the SEC sued the company and Patrick Bennett,
accusing him of selling $570 million of unregistered securities and
of running a giant Ponzi scheme, in which early ``investors'' were
paid off with the money put in by later ``investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Some leases had been sold to more than one investor, and some
were made up out of whole cloth, Breeden said. All the money that
came in as lease payments, and all the money paid out to investors,
came from a general fund that he calls ``the honey pot.'' The
Bennetts themselves used money from the pot to buy various things,
but seemed to specialize in unprofitable gambling properties,
including an unfinished riverboat, a defunct casino and a failing
race track.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The day after the SEC filed suit, the Bennett companies filed
for bankruptcy protection. The following month, Breeden, with the
support of his old agency, was appointed trustee by the Justice
Department. It was a decision made over the head of Van Baalen's
predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   That may have been the start of Breeden's problems, although the
life of a trustee is almost never a happy one. The trustee often
becomes a focus for the anger of all the people affected by the
bankruptcy, who resent the trustee for making money off their
misery.
</P>
<P>
   That is particularly true when, as in Breeden's case, he is
making quite a lot of money. He stands to make millions of dollars,
depending on how much he recovers for creditors, in addition to his
annual $600,000 salary, which, he asserts, is not too much for
someone who is running an enormous, complex operation.
</P>
<P>
   But it sure looks like a lot in Syracuse, where the average
worker makes less than $28,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   And Breeden has taken some very unpopular steps, including suing
the defrauded investors to adjust the amounts of their claims.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors continue to believe in the Bennetts, noting that
the allegations of fraud have never been proved in court. The elder
Bennetts have never been charged; according to court documents,
Michael Bennett, who was charged with one count each of conspiracy
and obstruction of justice, is expected to reach a plea agreement
with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Bennett denies that there was any scheme to defraud
investors. ``In his opinion, there were enough assets there to pay
the creditors, and if they were short, it was only 5 percent or 10
percent,'' said Richard Croak, an Albany lawyer who represents
Bennett in the bankruptcy case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat is just an ordinary guy from Syracuse who got involved in
this thing,'' Croak said. ``He's not a criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Breeden has won some skirmishes in his battles over the
bankruptcy, and lost others. Last month, for instance, Judge
Stephen Gerling of federal bankruptcy court in Utica ruled that
Croak could not depose Breeden about some of the potential
conflicts raised by Van Baalen.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last week, Gerling ruled that Breeden must either resign
as trustee or give up another of his jobs, as consultant to the
accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche. The problem, the judge said, is
that Deloitte will not reveal all of its clients, some of whom may
be involved in the bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge's underlying complaint, and one of Van Baalen's as
well, is that Breeden was slow to tell them about the consulting
job, and provided little information when he did tell them. ``The
trustee appears to believe that the court and the parties should
simply rely on him as a fiduciary to make an independent
determination that he remains disinterested,'' Gerling wrote
disapprovingly.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what Breeden says. Saying that he is doing what
is best for the defrauded investors, he interprets Van Baalen's
queries as attacks on his integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a trustee more honest or who has worked
any harder than I have,'' Breeden said. ``This is not a game _ it
is a system that needs to insure the best results'' for creditors.
</P>
<P>
   And results, he added, ``speak louder than words.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
