<HEADLINE>
CHURCH SERVICE HONORS CRASH VISTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES-RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTER, Nova Scotia _ Never has the small church on the hill
that has stood here in the ocean wind for 223 years held a service
such as the one at 3 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``An ecumenical service of witness and remembrance for the
victims of Swissair Flight 111'' at St. Stephen's Anglican Church
was the idea of a cherub-faced pastor named Daniel Greene, who
works at the nearby Chester United Baptist Church. Greene said the
suffering among people on the south shore here has been tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   While private memorial services have been held for relatives of
the victims, the St. Stephen's liturgy was one of at least five
public services scheduled for this area.
</P>
<P>
   As an organ played softly from the balcony, about 300 people,
most of them elderly, filled the wooden pews. But it was the
entrance of six uniformed Air Canada pilots that caused the
greatest commotion, moments before the opening hymn: ``O God, our
Help in ages past, our Hope for years to come, our Shelter from the
stormy blast, and our eternal Home!''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Joe Gallagher, a pilot based in Toronto, listened from
the third row, and struggled to hold back the tears. He did not
know the pilots of Swissair 111, he said, but at the same time said
he felt he did know them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been any one of us,'' he said. ``We came to pay
our respects, in uniform, especially to the families of Urs
Zimmermann and Stefan Lowe. We came because it happened in our own
backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Brian Murphy of St. Augustine's Roman Catholic parish read
Psalm 27, which holds the following words: ``For he will shelter me
in his day of trouble. He will conceal me under the cover of his
tent, he will set me high upon a rock.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past two days, families of the victims have been brought
to green army tents on the rocks in Peggy's Cove, 5 1/2 miles from
where the plane crashed into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Anne Palmeter of Geneva came to the service, she said,
because she knew the parents and grandparents of two of the
victims. She did not say who they were, but said the relatives had
spoken to her on the phone from Europe earlier in the day, said
Palmeter, who was visiting Nova Scotia when the accident occured.
</P>
<P>
   As Pastor Phillip Williams of Tancook Island sang a religious
folk song called ``Higher Ways,'' Grant Richardson, a retired
fisherman from Mill Cove, could not stop himself from crying. His
wife, Beverley, said the tears were unusual, but justifiable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened right over our cottage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear those poor people must have felt,'' said Richardson.
``We felt we had to come here today. It's all we could do.''
</P>
<P>
   And the song went on: ``If I could only fly I'd go up and look
down from the sky. ... There's so much going on down here that I
must confess I don't understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
