<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN, TATA MAKE COMEBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of UCLA's most inspirational stories are unfolding at
defensive end, where seniors Jayson Brown and Vae Tata celebrate
every step they take.
</P>
<P>
   Tata missed the 1996 with a knee injury and the 1997 season with
multiple injuries resulting from a serious off-season car accident.
He has lost size and speed and is currently third on the depth
chart behind Pete Holland and Travor Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the same as he was,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown is expected to contribute _ probably as Kenyon
Coleman's backup on the other end _ and that is a testament to hard
work and modern medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Brown played in just five games the past two seasons because of
a dislocated left kneecap that required three surgeries. In the
most recent operation, last October, his patella was detached,
moved an inch to the right, and reattached. He petitioned the NCAA
and in April received a rare sixth year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   What he lacks in size (260 pounds) and speed, he makes up for in
experience and perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main goal last year was to play against USC _ meaning I'd
have gone through the whole season,'' he said. ``At this point, I
can't take anything for granted. I feel as good as I'm going to
get. I just hope I make it until the USC game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tata, No. 90, and Brown, No. 91, have adjoining lockers.
</P>
<P>
   Texas update: The Longhorns scored 66 points _ sound familiar? _
in a season-opening victory over lowly New Mexico State. Tailback
Ricky Williams, the top returning Heisman Trophy vote getter,
scored six touchdowns and rushed for 215 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was disappointed at halftime when he saw he had 101
yards,'' Texas coach Mack Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Longhorns weren't perfect in their first game under
Brown, who replaced John Mackovic. New Mexico State gained 483
total yards (233 rushing) and scored 33 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play defense (against UCLA) like we did in the second
half, they'll get 66 points again,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is ranked 23rd in the latest Associated Press poll, its
first ranking since the 66-3 loss to UCLA last year.
</P>
<P>
   Off and on: While Texas thrashed New Mexico State, the Bruins
had the weekend off. Advantage, Longhorns?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a huge advantage,'' Toledo said. ``You probably
improve the most from the first to the second game. They've had a
chance to iron out the wrinkles. We'll go through the growing pains
(Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   Texas tickets: A crowd of 80,000 is expected for the 12:30 p.m.
kickoff. The first 10,000 fans entering through tunnels on the east
(sun) side will receive a visor and bottle of water.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to arrive early: the Arroyo Seco is not a model
for traffic flow, as the Washington game (86,000 spectators) proved
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Parking is available outside the Arroyo at the Parsons
Engineering Building in Pasadena (shuttle service to the stadium)
and inside the Arroyo at the Brookside Golf Course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
