<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DIANA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF SILVER DEFIES HER MEDICAL CHART AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ They were two of the finest
grass-racing fillies in the country, Memories of Silver and Auntie
Mame, and they tangled in Saratoga's prestigious Diana Handicap on
Sunday and toughed it out down the homestretch. But at the wire,
with the long shot B.A. Valentine tucked in between them, Memories
of Silver streaked home with her third straight victory and a
perfect postsurgical record for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's far in front of her division,'' said Jimmy
Toner, who trains Memories of Silver for Joan and John Phillips.
``Our ultimate goal is to get an Eclipse Award.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been a certain air of drama surrounding Memories of
Silver. At the age of 2 and again at 4, she sustained hind-leg
fractures, and last winter even underwent surgery to repair the
damage from a stress fracture. Now, at the age of 5, she runs with
metal screws in one of her legs, but she wins.
</P>
<P>
   She won the Diana after Jerry Bailey steered her through traffic
to overtake B.A. Valentine in the stretch, and then prevailed in a
three-horse drive to the finish. She got there first by a length
and three-quarters over B.A. Valentine, who also ran second in the
Diana last year and who had three-quarters of a length on Auntie
Mame, with Witchful Thinking fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was optimistic,'' Bailey said, ``because with her courage, I
knew she would be able to overcome the nature of the injury she
sustained last winter. Now she's probably as good as she ever was.
This horse would run through the eye of a needle, and that's all
she needs. All we needed was a crack to shoot through, and that's
what we got.''
</P>
<P>
   John Velazquez, who also had a lot of steering to do aboard
Auntie Mame, said: ``When I got to the first turn, I found myself
running up behind horses, so I had to take back a bit. At the
three-quarters pole, I pulled her out, and she really responded.
The only thing was that I had no choice but to go wide.''
</P>
<P>
   Memories of Silver ran the mile and an eighth in 1:46, returned
$4.60 for a $2 bet and earned $180,000, raising her bankroll to
$1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the race before the Diana, an allowance with a purse of
$52,000, the favored Richter Scale surrendered his lead to
Victoriously as the field turned for home. Victoriously won by more
than three lengths, with Richter Scale second and Golden Larch
third.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, trained by Jimmy Jerkens, ran the mile and an eighth
under Jorge Chavez in 1:49 4/5 and paid $12.60. Richter Scale,
trained by Bill Mott with Bailey riding, has won six of 12 starts
but lost his last three.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
