<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Call-up, then HR shock Malloy
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ Seven long years. From Idaho to Macon, Durham to
Richmond. After 774 games, 2,906 at-bats and untold moments of
doubt and frustration, Marty Malloy finally made it to the major
leagues Sunday. And then the most wonderful thing happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the ball,'' Malloy said, ``and it just happened to go
out of the park.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a homer that later left him momentarily speechless on a
day he later called ``Joyous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just getting here finally, after what seems forever,'' Malloy
said, ``and hitting that ball and it going out, I can't describe
it. And just all the people who believed in me over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   People like his parents, Tommy and Beverly, back home in
Trenton, Fla. His wife, Lacy. Bobby Dews, now the Braves' third
base coach, who worked with Malloy throughout the Braves' farm
system. And Paul Hemphill, the Atlanta novelist who chronicled
Malloy's 1994 season with Class A Durham in his book, ``The Heart
of the Game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Marty wasn't gonna go quietly,'' Hemphill said by phone
from his home. No, Marty arrived with a bang.
</P>
<P>
   With Keith Lockhart still out with a strained right hamstring
and Tony Graffanino in a 3-for-37 slump and hitting .204, manager
Bobby Cox wanted Malloy. Reliever Mark Wohlers, already on the
15-day disabled list, agreed Saturday to go on the 60-day DL to
make room on the 40-man roster for Malloy.
</P>
<P>
   When the Richmond Braves arrived home at 1 a.m. Sunday from a
series in Norfolk, Malloy got off the bus. ``I was fixin' to get in
my car and go to my apartment,'' he said. Instead, Richmond
pitching coach Bill Fischer called Malloy into manager Max
Venable's office, where he learned of his call-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock,'' said Malloy, caught completely unaware. ``I
didn't know what to do. It was probably the happiest day of my
life, something you hope for from the day you start playing. Not
being on the (40-man) roster, I didn't think I had a chance at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Malloy's car was already packed with his belongings. He and Lacy
were planning to drive back home to Chiefland, Fla., after
Richmond's season finale today. Instead, Malloy returned to their
Richmond apartment, got to sleep at 5 a.m. and awoke at 6:30 for an
8 a.m. flight to Philadelphia. He changed planes for a flight to
LaGuardia Airport, caught a taxi to Shea Stadium, walked into the
clubhouse at 11:15 and shook hands with assistant general manager
Dean Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations, Marty,'' Taylor said. ``You're batting
second.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good story, Marty,'' said Cox. ``A hard-nosed guy.
Maybe he'll give us a spark. He certainly deserved a chance to
play. There comes a time when you owe it to guys in the
organization to give 'em a crack. Marty's one of those guys. He's a
tough little kid. He doesn't have all the ability in the world
probably, but he's a good player. He's a dirt guy, like Lemke.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Malloy was given Mark Lemke's old No. 20 uniform. In his
first at-bat, Malloy took three straight called strikes from Rick
Reed, the last two on the inside corner. ``My second at-bat,
Lockhart and Chipper (Jones) told me he was gonna come in until I
proved I could hit it,'' said Malloy.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after singling and making a nice play afield, Malloy
said, ``I didn't feel any pressure. But I felt I had to go out and
get something done. It just happened to be a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back, Cat
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling strong,''said a smiling Andres Galarraga, who
returned from his three-game suspension Sunday and smoked his 43rd
homer in the ninth inning off Mets reliever Jeff Tam.
</P>
<P>
   After striking out twice in his first three at-bats, Galarraga
homered beyond the visitors bullpen in deep left, but was more
delighted with Malloy's homer. ``Oh man,'' he said, ``I'm so happy
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   On hold
</P>
<P>
   With one hit in his last 22 at-bats, and sitting upon Malloy's
arrival, Tony Graffanino is befuddled by the worst slump of his
young career. ``I have no idea,'' he said. ``I felt fine all day
(Saturday, when he went 0-for-4 with three strikeouts). Thought I
saw the ball well, had good swings at it, thought I was on the ball
a few times. I don't feel like I'm looking hideous up there, not
swinging at garbage pitches and having no idea. The only thing I
can do is keep playing defense.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
