<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons survive Carolina opener
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. -- Fans who saw the Atlanta Falcons play Sunday
probably will agree that their performance against Carolina was no
work of art. Then again, given a hideous historical perspective
from which to view the 19-14 victory over the Panthers, it was
perhaps as aesthetically pleasing to the Falcons as is possible for
a season opener.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had not won a road opener since 12 years ago. They
were 0-for-3 in the home of Carolina, their closest NFC West rival.
And maybe the 65,129 fans at Ericsson Stadium witnessed a
masterpiece after all.
</P>
<P>
   That's what it was in the eyes of the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was huge,'' said middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle, a
participant in road-opening losses each of his 11 previous seasons.
``We wanted to set the tempo for the season, and get rid of a lot
of ghosts, and we did. Huge win, man!''
</P>
<P>
   Credit quarterback Chris Chandler, who took a beating while
suffering through six sacks. Chandler passed for 268 yards,
including scoring passes of 11 yards to Terance Mathis (six
catches, 74 yards), and 44 yards to rookie Tim Dwight.
</P>
<P>
   And throw a bouquet to the Panthers' punt team.
</P>
<P>
   If not for a bad snap that sailed over the head of Carolina
punter Ken Walter and resulted in a safety in the third quarter,
and a blocked punt in the fourth quarter (leading to a 43-yard
field goal by Morten Andersen), these teams might have played into
the night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Falcons won after surviving a King Kong-sized scare
at the end.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers' last possession began at their own 12 with no
timeouts and 1:02 remaining. Passes by Kerry Collins of 9, 16 and
22 yards, and an encroachment penalty against Atlanta moved the
ball to the Falcons' 36. The clock stopped with five seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Collins threw high and deep. Atlanta safety Eugene Robinson may
have gotten a hand on the ball, but so too did Carolina receiver
Muhsin Muhammad. It also caromed off the helmet of the Falcons'
Juran Bolden and began falling to earth _ very near Panthers
receiver Raghib Ismail, who was on his back in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   When the ball hit the ground, there was instant relief felt by
the Falcons, who are in position to go for their first 2-0 start
since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow. Wow. Wow,'' Falcons general manager Harold Richardson
muttered in the press box.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought hard on the road against a lot of crowd noise, a lot
of heat,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``There were a lot of things we
had to overcome mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons started first-half drives at their 7-, 5-, 2- and
10-yard lines. Penalties didn't help; Atlanta had seven of its 11
in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   But on their third possession, the Falcons went 98 yards on 11
plays, taking a 7-0 lead on a pass to a wide-open Mathis with 7:54
left in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina responded when Collins (21-of-37, 270 yards, two TDs,
one interception) hit Rae Carruth for a 47-yard gain, then found
Wesley Walls alone in the end zone for a 6-yard touchdown and a 7-7
tie at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons caught a break in the middle of the third quarter,
when Walter couldn't handle a high snap, and fell on the ball in
the end zone for a safety. Atlanta's 9-7 lead grew to 16-7 when
Chandler hit Dwight down the middle with 2:07 left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   But Carolina's Michael Bates raced 45 yards down the left
sideline with the kickoff. On the next play, Atlanta cornerback Ray
Buchanan stumbled, and Ismail was alone on the left sideline for a
56-yard touchdown, cutting Atlanta's lead to 16-14 with 1:46 left
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons made their own break on Carolina's next possession.
Walter was about to punt when he saw Bolden bearing down from his
left. He dropped the ball to kick it, but changed his mind _
stopping his leg swing _ at the same time Bolden arrived. Bolden
was credited with a blocked punt.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta got the ball at the Carolina 42, and Morten Anderson
added a field goal with 8:46 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta got production from its running game down the stretch,
with Jamal Anderson getting 61 of his 88 yards in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many times we had (Atlanta) in third-and-long situations,
and they were able to convert many of those,'' said Carolina coach
Dom Capers. ``We can't afford to give up five points in the kicking
game. The margin was the safety, and the field position we gave
them on the punt in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was especially happy about a run defense that held
Carolina to 54 yards on 19 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a long ways to go,'' he said, ``but we're on the
right road.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
