<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home run showdown in St. Louis
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It's the sixth inning Sunday afternoon, Cardinals
first baseman Mark McGwire at the plate, Brett Tomko on the mound
for the Reds. Tomko lets go a fastball, McGwire uncoils his big
swing and rips the ball down the left field line.
</P>
<P>
   No. 61?
</P>
<P>
   Nope, just the most memorable foul ball in major league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every times he steps to the plate it's mind-boggling,'' said
commissioner Bud Selig, who was sitting right behind the plate.
``You just feel like you're suffocating. When he hit that ball I
thought, `Oh, here it ...'''
</P>
<P>
   So McGwire's bid to tie Roger Maris goes on another day and sets
up a two-game series matching the two hitters trying to bang away
at history.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa and the Cubs will be in town for a Labor Day matinee
and another game Tuesday night. Sosa, who didn't go deep Sunday in
Pittsburgh, remained at 58. McGwire is at 60. What drama. What
excitement. Can anyone sleep?
</P>
<P>
   ``These two men,'' Selig said, ``have captured this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Cardinals outfielder Brian Jordan, ``It's going to be
pandimonium here.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sosa, ``It's will be like the World Series in St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   The first pitch is at 2:10 p.m., and Steve Trachsel (14-7) will
pitch for the Cubs against former Brave Kent Mercker (9-11).
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a group of reporters how he would pitch Sosa, Mercker
laughed and said, ``I'm not going to tell you. You'd fax the
interview to Sammy.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago's 4-3 extra inning loss to the Pirates Sunday, Sosa
was 2-for-5, but didn't homer for the first time in four games.
McGwire, meanwhile, was 0-for-3 with a walk. On his first at-bat,
he lined the ball to short. On the second at-bat, McGwire was
walked on four pitches. Then came the foul ball on his third trip
to the plate, missing the foul pole by about seven feet. He would
then strike out. On his final at-bat, McGwire lined a ball up the
middle, but the Reds had shifted their infield and second baseman
Brett Boone threw him out.
</P>
<P>
   Maris' family, except his widow Patricia, was in attendance. She
was in satisfactory condition after being admitted to Barnes-Jewish
Hospital with an irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't appear anything is going to put a damper on what
is taking place here at Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so good, it's hard to believe,'' Selig said. ``There is
no way we could have orchestrated this, especially these next two
days with the Cubs coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
