<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seles-Hinges showdown set
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Martina Hingis says her game's getting worse, and she
wasn't smitten with Monica Seles' play either after the two former
women's champions won ugly matches Sunday at the U.S. Open to set
up a quarterfinal showdown Tuesday in Arthur Ashe Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, the defending champ and No. 1-ranked player on the WTA
Tour, defeated French teenager Nathalie Dechy 6-4, 6-4 and was
among the many confounded by swift and capricious winds in the
stadium court. She thought she'd double-faulted 20 times and was
startled to hear it was only nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just kind of escaping every day,'' said Hingis, who needed
three sets in the third round to beat another French teenager,
Amelie Mauresmo. ``Instead of getting better, I'm getting worse.
... If I continue playing like this, I'm not going to go
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles, a two-time champion, was leading American Kimberly Po
6-2, 4-1 before surrendering five straight games and the second
set. She played defensively in the third and let Po beat herself,
6-2, 4-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my mind just wandered off,'' said Seles, who also had
choice words for the wind. ``I never felt in control of where the
ball was going. ... Wind is wind, but this is more than wind. I
mean, you hit the ball and it goes here instead of there. By two
meters it can vary. I never played in conditions like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles has beaten Hingis in their only two meetings this year,
but Hingis, whose candor is often confused with disrespect, didn't
agree Seles is playing her best tennis since the 1995 comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like today, I don't think it was one of her best matches,''
Hingis said. ``She always is saying her back's bothering her or
something. She also lost to Lindsay (Davenport) the last two times.
So I don't think she's on her best, but me neither. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon champion Jana Novotna beat last year's U.S. Open
runner-up, Irina Spirlea 6-3, 6-3. Novotna is 6-0 in her career
against Sprilea.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just getting more and more devastated (mentally),''
Novotna said. ``I know how that feels when you play somebody and
you can't beat them for a while. Basically, all she can do is hope
I have a bad match.''
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, fifth-seeded Richard Krajicek retired with a
knee injury against Thomas Johasson, and Americans Jan-Michael
Gambill and Geoff Grant lost five-setters. Gambill went down to
10th-seeded Carlos Moya 6-2, 3-6, 3-6, 6-3, 7-6 (4). Grant, a
former Duke player who quit the tour three years ago, fell to
Germany's Oliver Gross 7-5, 6-7, 5-7, 6-3, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   No. 11 Yevgeny Kafelnikov and No. 13 Tim Henman advanced easily
to the round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
