<SLUG> BC-NY-YOUTH-HARLEM-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAY AFTER: HARLEM RESIDENTS ANGRY WITH GIULIANI 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also: NY-YOUTH-MARCH, NY-YOUTH-POLICE) 
(nk) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A home health care aide who works in Harlem spent two
hours on Saturday trying to get home to the South Bronx. A woman
trapped in front of her apartment on Malcolm X Boulevard was an
hour late getting to work. And a Harlem woman trying to visit a
shoe-repair shop was directed by police through a circuitous maze
of blue barricades, only to find the shop closed for the day.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Harlem found their neighborhood turned upside down
by the war of wills between City Hall and the organizers of a rally
billed as the Million Youth March. All day Saturday, the police
were posted atop apartment buildings. Block after block was
cordoned off, making it impossible for many residents to venture
beyond their stoops. And subway service was suspended in and out of
the heart of Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, even as normality returned to the neighborhood, many
people remained furious. And even those who, like Yvonne Bacott,
denounced the rally's chief organizer, Khallid Abdul Muhammad,
accused Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of turning what could have been a
quiet, uneventful affair into an unnecessarily tense afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bacott, a Harlem resident, had no desire to join the rally.
But the rally and the police presence that it inspired made it
impossible to run a simple errand _ to pick up her daughter's shoes
from a repair shop around the corner. She circled several blocks
lined with officers, passed neighbors who shook their heads in
disbelief and discovered that she could not even board the subway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call this a village,'' said Ms. Bacott. ``This village was
disenfranchised from the rest of the world. How dare he!''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Bacott, many of the men and women who poured out of the
Canaan Baptist Church on 116th Street on Sunday said they did not
hold Muhammad in high regard. And some were especially disturbed
that he had urged young people at the rally to defend themselves by
seizing police officers' guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a mission statement for unity and harmony,'' she
said. ``That's a mission statement for destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   But in their eyes, Giuliani also acted improperly. A heavy
police presence, said Dorothea Caldwell-Brown, a lawyer from Crown
Heights, Brooklyn, only seemed to encourage Muhammad in his
message. And when officers in riot gear assembled behind the stage
minutes before the rally was scheduled to close, she said, they
only reinforced the belief that many black New Yorkers hold _ that
neither the police nor City Hall respects them, and particularly
their young.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions of this Giuliani feed these young people to
Khallid,'' Ms. Caldwell-Brown, 47, said. ``He stands up and says,
`Look at how they treat you,' and here they come rushing in doing
exactly what he says. Giuliani and Khallid are in concert, in my
opinion. They need one another.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For some, the rally was not only about Muhammad. Sunday, there
were those who said they knew little about him, only that they were
drawn to the Million Youth March because they thought it could keep
young people out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's his name Muhammad, he's got his beliefs or whatever,''
said Maurice Barrett, 30, who saw the rally from in front of his
apartment on Malcolm X Boulevard, a section of Lenox Avenue. ``He's
against Jews, whites, even blacks half the time, but a lot of
people didn't come for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Giuliani administration officials renewed their calls
for the arrest of Muhammad on charges of inciting to riot.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Canaan Baptist Church, the Rev. Wyatt Tee Walker shook
his head at the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Giuliani should be indicted for the police riot on the
Brooklyn Bridge of which he was a part a few years ago,'' he said,
referring to a rowdy demonstration by police officers in 1992,
which Giuliani joined before becoming mayor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
