<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SOSA-COX     09-06 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sosa satisfied out of spotlight
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa doesn't hold a special press conference before every
series. ``Writers,'' he said, ``can talk to me whenever they want.
Well, not when I'm hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have a security guard walking him through the crowds.
``I like being around the fans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't take muscle-building supplements. ``Just those little
Flintstone vitamins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the other hitter in the chase to catch Roger Maris. Sosa,
who continues to yield the spotlight to St. Louis first baseman
Mark McGwire, arguably has had the better season.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is leading the home-run chase, 60-58, and everyone
expects him to break the record en route to baseball's Hall of
Fame. But with his team out of the playoff race, McGwire has been
able to swing for the fences on every pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa can't take that approach. His Cubs are in the middle of
heated wild-card race with the New York Mets and San Francisco
Giants. He is playing team ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of there being a more valuable player in
baseball,'' Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said. ``He has meant so much
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has been marvelous on and off the field. He continually has
pushed the attention of the chase to McGwire. ``I want Mark to
break the record,'' he said. ``To me, I'm a winner already. I've
gone so far this year, and a lot more (home runs) are going to
come. To me, just being behind Mark McGwire is being a winner. I'm
enjoying every moment of this. We have a chance to go to the
playoffs, and I'm taking over.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, McGwire and Sosa continue the chase at Busch Stadium in
an historic two-game series between the Cubs and Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been waiting for this moment,'' Sosa said. ``It's
going to be tremendous. I'm sure they'd like to see Mark and I
together for the last time this year. I'm willing to have a good
time, like always.''
</P>
<P>
   That is prototype Sosa, a free-swinging, free-talking player
liked by everyone in the Cubs clubhouse. While McGwire has been
inaccessible except for preseries press conferences, Sosa spends
much of his pregame time fielding questions.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't hurt him. Many of his offensive numbers are better
than McGwire's _ batting average (.314 to .296), RBIs (140 to 127)
and average with runners in scoring percentage (.323 to .275).
</P>
<P>
   In short, it has been a breakthrough season. Sosa hit 38 homers
last season and struck out a league-leading 174 times. The scouting
report said Sosa was a great talent, but an undisciplined hitter
who couldn't hit in clutch situations.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa started in the Texas organization, was traded to the White
Sox in 1989 and then to the Cubs in the winter of 1991. The Cubs
began understanding what they had in 1993, when Sosa hit 33 homers
and drove in 93 runs. He improved his average by 39 points to reach
.300. But he continued to strike out. From 1995-97, he averaged 147
strikeouts a season. He also hit only .246 with runners in scoring
position last year and .159 on two-strike counts.
</P>
<P>
   So during the spring, the Cubs decided to rework his swing.
Bench coach Billy Williams and hitting coach Jeff Pentland pulled
videos of other hitters, including Atlanta's Chipper Jones, and
showed Sosa how to work the strike zone and quit swinging wildly at
balls outside. They shortened his swing and stressed patience. The
result? Sosa is down from one strikeout every 3.68 at-bats last
season to one every 3.93 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he knew he was maybe a half step behind some of the
other guys,'' Pentland said. ``I think inside he felt he was as
good, had the same amount of tools as the (Ken) Griffeys, and
(Barry) Bonds and McGwires and (Gary) Sheffields.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa started slow this season, hitting 13 homers in the first
two months. But he hit an amazing 17 homers in the first 21 days in
June and was back in the chase. He led the race once _ for 45
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Sosa, from the Dominican Republic, is thankful
for these good times. His father died when he was 7, so Sosa shined
shoes for 25 cents and sold oranges for a dime to help put food on
the table. As a child, he used milk cartons for baseball gloves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having the best time of my life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa admits that breaking the record would be great, but he
would rather see his club make it to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to choose between the record and the playoffs, I'll
take the playoffs,'' he said. ``That is something that everyone (in
Chicago) is looking for. That doesn't happen every day, and I want
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
