<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Manning shows promise in defeat
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Surveying the sea of fans dressed in royal blue
shirts and those in burnt orange uniform jerseys which co-mingled
in the RCA Dome for Sunday's season-opener, someone noted to Jim
Irsay that he might consider renaming his franchise to satisfy
loyalists from both the Colts and the Vols.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about the Volts, huh?'' responded the witty Indianapolis
owner, referring to the unusual alliance forged by Peyton Manning
admirers.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, with the Colts having demonstrated a dearth
of offensive firepower in a 24-15 loss to the Miami Dolphins, that
suggestion seemed incredibly incongruous.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, so did the notion quarterback Peyton
Manning won't immediately be a force in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell the truth, he played even better than I thought he
would, and you're talking to a guy who thinks the world of him,''
assessed Colts coach Jim Mora of his prized rookie's uneven debut.
``There were two things that impressed me: He made a lot of big
plays for us. And he came back from adversity when he had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning hit 21 of 37 passes for 302 yards, and had six
completions of 16 yards or more. But the former Tennessee star
didn't get his club into the end zone until the final play of the
game and threw three costly interceptions which led to two Miami
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Forget those familiar strains of ``Rocky Top'' he grew
accustomed to hearing during four seasons in Knoxville. The
Dolphins defense, arguably the quickest unit in the NFL, made it
rocky, period, for Manning much of the day, sacking him four times.
</P>
<P>
   Like most rookies, Manning exhibited a habit of going to often
to one receiver _ in this case, wideout Marvin Harrison _ and the
tunnel vision was costly. Dolphins cornerback Terrell Buckley
intercepted two passes intended for Harrison and returned one of
them 21 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rookies tend to adopt' certain receivers, get a little cozy
with them, you know?'' said Buckley. ``We knew (Manning) would go
to Harrison about a dozen times.'' Actually 16 of Manning's 37
throws were for Harrison, who finished with five catches for 102
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as damaging to Manning as his interceptions was
Indianapolis' unproductive running game, which netted only 64 yards
on 26 rushes.
</P>
<P>
   Still the Colts had an outside chance to force overtime when
they gained possession at their 4, trailing 17-9 with 1:32
remaining. On first down, Manning had slot receiver Torrance Small
streaking deep down the right seam on a pattern the two had
modified on the sideline. The pass was barely tipped, though, by
Miami free safety Brock Marion. On the next play, Buckley snatched
an underthrown pass and scored.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
