<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. underdogs lose heartbreakers
 &HT;    By TODD HOLCOMB
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- Only two Americans _ Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi _
are in the men's round of 16 at the U.S. Open, but two others _
underdogs Jan-Michael Gambill and Geoff Grant _ nearly joined them
Sunday before losing heart-breaking five-set matches.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill, ranked No. 57, was up a service break in the fifth set
against French Open champion Carlos Moya but mishandled a 40-15
lead at 4-3 and lost 6-2, 3-6, 3-6, 6-3, 7-6 (4).
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him the match, basically,'' said Gambill, who has
improved his ranking more than 100 spots this year but is now 0-4
against top-10 players. ``He should never have broken me in the
fifth set. He didn't do anything special.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambill, 21, is the youngest American in the top 100 and figures
to make the U.S. Davis Cup team that will play Italy later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   More unexpected was the run of Grant, a wild-card entry who quit
tennis for nine months in 1995 and found work as a teaching pro, a
part-time model and a radio sales telemarketer for his father's
company. The former Duke All-American was beaten 7-5, 6-7, 5-7,
6-3, 7-5 by Oliver Gross, a German journeyman.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, 28, said the U.S. Tennis Association, which granted him
the wild card, is only now beginning to support former college
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were considered to have no chance (on the tour) if you
went to college and graduated,'' Grant said. ``I think their
philosophy has changed. Thank God they recognized what I've been
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's highlights
</P>
<P>
   There's no TV today for the afternoon matches, when Andre Agassi
and Venus Williams are endangered by potential upsets. Agassi plays
underrated ninth seed Karol Kucera, who hasn't dropped a set in
three matches. Williams faces Mary Pierce. USA Network will
televise live tonight beginning with Lindsay Davenport vs. Nathalie
Tauziat at 7:30, followed by the tournament's best matchup thus
far, defending men's champ Patrick Rafter vs. Goran Ivanisevic.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for Cinderella
</P>
<P>
   The men's semifinals will include at least one player not seeded
among the top 10. That was assured Sunday when fifth-seeded Richard
Krajicek retired with recurring tendinitis in his knee while
trailing Thomas Johansson 7-6, 4-5. Remaining in that quarter of
the draw are No. 11 Yevgeny Kafelnikov, No. 13 Tim Henman and Mark
Philippoussis.
</P>
<P>
   Locals at the Open
</P>
<P>
   The only Atlanta players left playing are Luke and Murphy Jensen
and a pair of junior girls. The Jensens have won two rounds and
face seventh-seeded Martin Damm and Jim Grabb today. In the junior
girls draw, Ansley Cargill, a junior at Westminster, plays Uzma
Kahn of Italy in today's first round. Scaringe, a senior at
Lassiter, plays sixth-seeded Nadejda Petrova of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
