</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDINALS-REDS-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE REMAINS AT 60 IN A QUIET DAY AT THE PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Two members of the St. Louis Cardinals smacked home
runs in the eighth inning of their game against the Cincinnati Reds
Sunday, and even though Mark McGwire batted against John Hudek in
that inning, he was not one of them. Fernando Tatis was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people don't want to see me hit a home run,'' said Tatis,
who has eight home runs this season to McGwire's 60. ``The people
want to see him hit a home run. I want to see him hit a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Cardinals victory was the next best thing, albeit a poor
consolation prize, to a McGwire home run for the 47,904 fans at
Busch Stadium, and the home runs by Ray Lankford and Tatis
following McGwire's out gave the Cardinals a 5-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's inability to tie Roger Maris' single-season home run
record, or even break it, Sunday set the stage for a marvelous
scenario the next two days because Sammy Sosa is coming to town
with the Chicago Cubs. Sosa also failed to hit a home run Sunday in
Pittsburgh, and he will go into the Monday afternoon Cardinals-Cubs
game with 58 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Tatis, the Cardinals' young third baseman, was among those who
was looking forward to the face-to-face confrontation with great
anticipation. He has more than the average rooting interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If McGwire does it, I'm going to be happy,'' Tatis said. ``If
Sammy does it, I'll be happy for him. McGwire is on my team, Sammy
is my friend. I hope they both do it. I want them both to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatis and Sosa are friends from the Dominican Republic; Tatis
became a teammate of McGwire's when the Cardinals acquired him from
the Texas Rangers in July.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit three balls wickedly hard Sunday, but got two outs
and a foul ball for his trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, with Brett Tomko pitching, he hit a line
drive between shortstrop and third base that Barry Larkin speared
with a lunging grab, his body parallel to the ground. Tomko walked
McGwire on four pitches in the fourth inning, then got him on a
called third strike in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   On the first pitch of that sixth-inning at-bat McGwire drove the
ball into the left-field stands, but it landed in the first section
on the wrong side of the foul pole. Did McGwire think the ball had
a chance to become No. 61?
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, on contact, yes,'' he said. ``But as it got into the
outfield, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomko had recently talked in a television interview about
grooving a pitch for McGwire, but he said his comments had been
taken incorrectly. He said he didn't let the perceptions of others
affect the way he pitched to McGwire Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he said. ``The way it was said was I was going
to be aggressive. I think Mark knows that I went after him
aggressively, so I don't think there's even an issue. Now I can say
I struck him out with history on the line.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hudek, who struck out McGwire on Saturday, faced him again
Sunday in the eighth inning and almost paid for his efforts. After
swinging at and missing two pitches between taking two other
pitches for balls, McGwire drilled a line drive near Hudek's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize any ball that he hits in fair territory and is
coming in your direction has to be very, very hard,'' Hudek said.
``I was moving as quick as possible to make sure I got out of the
way, or something on the ball, like my glove, rather than my
body.''
</P>
<P>
   The reliever said he didn't know how close the ball came to his
head, but said: ``It looked like it was coming right at me. It had
to go right over my head. Did it bounce? It did? I guess that means
it was closer than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball hit the ground after it whizzed past Hudek. Bret Boone,
the Reds' second baseman, who was playing on the shortstop side of
second in the Reds' McGwire shift, snared it with a diving stop and
from his knees threw out McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   But then Lankford and Tatis hit home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who hurt me today weren't the big guns,'' Hudek said.
``How does that happen? Today it happened because I pitched lousy.
I got lucky with the pitch, the breaking ball, I threw to McGwire
that he hit up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a good one. I think what I did was I fooled him on
speed. He was looking fastball possibly, and I threw a breaking
ball. It wasn't a real good one, and he got a piece of it. If I
threw a fastball, who knows where it would have ended up?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
