<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-REDSKINS-N     09-06 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-REDSKINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 GIANTS' DEFENSE WASHES AWAY BITTER TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New York Giants returned to Giants
Stadium on Sunday, hosts again to a pivotal game, before a sellout
crowd, with the ghosts of all that had gone wrong in their last
game in the building an uninvited but insuppressible companion.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening game of the 1998 season, the Giants sought
redemption for their inglorious playoff exit late last year. After
a little more than three hours, what they had found in themselves
was a ball-hawking defense and a mostly mistake-free offense.
</P>
<P>
   And with that came liberation from the haunting memories of the
last disappointing day of the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   The victory within the 31-24 victory over the Washington
Redskins on Sunday was a Giants team playing in the same manner
that brought unexpected prosperity to a slumping franchise a year
ago. And in the end, the Giants believed that was the best way
possible to launch a new season.
</P>
<P>
   The daring Giants defense, which produced an improbable
interception and end-zone dash by the 285-pound defensive end
Michael Strahan, again saved an uncertain offense. And when the
Redskins threatened to spoil it all with a late rally, the Giants
defense and offense combined to play just well enough to assure the
Giants of their second consecutive season-opening victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our last game last year was in the back of everybody's mind
today,'' quarterback Danny Kanell said of the Giants' 23-22 playoff
loss to the Minnesota Vikings, a game the Giants led by nine points
with 90 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show we could finish off a team when we led late.
It was important that we put that game to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout a cheery, giddy Giants locker room Sunday afternoon,
there was relief that the Redskins had not gained revenge for the
Giants' 20-point, division-clinching victory here nine months ago,
and satisfaction that the Giants had vanquished the memory of their
implosion against the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That we didn't always play well today, but still won and held
on, that shows we've matured,'' said defensive tackle Robert
Harris. ``We had to hear that we fall apart in the fourth quarter
for a long time. It was brought up amongst ourselves and by our
coaches. It became a motivation for this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we didn't let the things that brought us down last year
bring us down this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' defense, with new starters in Conrad Hamilton at
cornerback and Marcus Buckley at strongside linebacker, appeared
disorganized and surprisingly overpowered at times.
</P>
<P>
   But the aggressive design of the defensive coordinator John Fox
is to seek the turnover despite the potential risk of a big play.
On Sunday, while the Redskins outgained the Giants in yards by
331-235, the Giants' two second-half interceptions and a fumble
caused by a sack turned the game in the Giants' favor.
</P>
<P>
   The action-packed second half followed a plodding, uneven first
half that ended in a 10-10 tie. Redskins quarterback Gus Frerotte
played well and successfully picked on Hamilton early, especially
on the game's first score, a 17-yard touchdown pass to Leslie
Shepherd.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell, who finished with a typical game for him (15 for 28
passing for 159 yards), and the Giants' offense started slowly, as
usual. Late in the second quarter, though, after an interception by
Washington cornerback Cris Dishman was nullified by a penalty,
Kanell found wide receiver Chris Calloway in the end zone for a
game-tying 5-yard touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   In their first possession of the second half, the Giants did not
pick up a first down and again looked listless, but a well-placed
pooch punt by Brad Maynard put the Redskins on their own 5-yard
line.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's first-down play from this dangerous part of the
field was a pass into the flat that cornerback Phillippi Sparks
deflected and bobbled. Hamilton, charging over on the play,
eventually grabbed the ball as it came off Sparks' hands. Hamilton
returned the interception to the Redskins' 2-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Charles Way scored on the next play for a 17-10 Giants
lead. It was a minor highlight for the feeble Giants running
attack; Way, Tiki Barber and Gary Brown combined to rush for just
82 yards on 30 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays after Way's touchdown, Frerotte looked to his left for
tight end Jamie Asher, who had raced across the field from the
right side of the Redskins' formation.
</P>
<P>
   Fox had called a zone blitz, which meant that a group of Giants
defenders on the right side tried to overload the blockers. To make
up for those Giants who are blitzing, Strahan is forced into
coverage; his responsibility is whatever receiver comes off the
line near him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a scary call,'' Fox said. ``Because Strahan can
match up on a wide receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   But the athletic Strahan sprinted just in Asher's wake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see the quarterback over the offensive line, so I
knew the quarterback couldn't see me,'' Strahan said. ``I moved up,
and then I saw the ball. I would have had the whole city of New
York mad at me if I dropped it.''
</P>
<P>
   Strahan caught the pass at the Redskins' 24-yard line. ``I put
my head back between my shoulder blades and ran,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With a two-touchdown lead following Strahan's score, the Giants'
defense swarmed over Frerotte, who left the game one series later
groggy from a sack and with an injured shoulder. The backup
quarterback, Trent Green, who played in one of 1,028 Washington
plays last season, came on and rallied Washington to within a
touchdown. At one point, Green completed nine straight passes.
</P>
<P>
   But late in the third quarter, Giants defensive tackle Christian
Peter sacked Green, causing a fumble that led to a Kanell-to-Amani
Toomer touchdown pass that extended the Giants' lead to 31-17.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, Green again cut the Redskins' deficit to
7 points.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Redskins had a last chance in the final minutes, they
were forced to begin from their own 20-yard line and never
threatened inside Giants territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at this as the biggest game of the season,'' Strahan
said. ``We're in first place in the division again, and we've
brought some joy back to New York. This should give the fans some
reason to believe that this is going to be a good season. Today, I
know that's how we feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
