<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEFENSE TO LEAN ON KEEPS GIANTS STANDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., N.J.)  (js) 
 BY WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Big Blue defense bailed out the offense
again Sunday. Like big brother or big sister who keeps the bully at
bay, the Giants' bruising defense swatted Washington back whenever
it got a bit too close and the Giants escaped with a pleasant,
season-opening victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't pretty, but we'll take it,'' offensive tackle Roman
Oben said
</P>
<P>
   What do you take away from a 31-24 victory like this? So early
in the season yet so crucial a game for a team that has such high
hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Danny Kanell said, ``I think we got off on the right
foot.''
</P>
<P>
   But if they want to go any distance, the Giants better get some
of those offensive feet churning _ and choreographed for long,
bone-crunching drives. That's the only thing defenses seem to fear.
Nobody is afraid of the Giants' running game, which generated only
82 yards Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Big Blue defense bailed the Giants out. Not that defensive gifts
are anything to scoff at.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the defense plays great all year and does that, it'll be
great for us, but we don't expect that all the time,'' Oben said.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Giants' four touchdowns were scored or set up by
the defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were in a 10-10 tie early in the second half when
Conrad Hamilton made a circus interception and ran to the
Washington 2-yard line. A play later, fullback Charles Way scored.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, defensive end Michael Strahan intercepted a pass
and scored to make it 24-10 and the Giants' young offense faced its
first test of the new season.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are only eight months removed from a dismal, painful
playoff loss to Minnesota in swirling snow and rain _ right here.
The Giants blew a 9-point lead and lost to the Vikings, 23-22.
</P>
<P>
   The big story that day was a last-gasp Minnesota touchdown pass.
The real story was the Giants' offense's inability to convert two
critical series when the Giants had an opportunity to break that
game open after Minnesota fumbled on consecutive series in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The question Sunday was whether the young Giants offense could
squeeze the hope out of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. After the Giants' defense held on to the Redskins'
next possession, the Giants' offense took over on the 40, huffed
and puffed up to midfield, then slid back down: a penalty; two
incomplete passes, a punt.
</P>
<P>
   Washington started coming back under the guidance of Trent
Green, an obscure, third-string quarterback who was pressed into
action when Gus Frerotte was knocked out of the game. Green was in
on only one of Washington's 1,028 plays last season, but he looked
like an All-Pro Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Green completed five of five passes on his first drive and
pulled Washington to within 24-17 with a 4-yard touchdown pass to
Larry Bowie. The Giants seemed headed for a familiar finish.
</P>
<P>
   The loss to the Vikings had been remarkable not only for its
suddenness, but for it's resonance. Days later _ weeks later _ the
staff was still stunned. ``It's a very bitter pill to swallow,''
Coach Jim Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   This all seemed like ancient history until the Giants faced
third-and-2 with 2 minutes left to play, clinging to a 7-point
lead, and failed to convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 'em blocked right up nicely, and one guy slipped off
and made the tackle,'' Fassel explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to grind and get first downs and massage the clock,''
he said. ``You can't have breakdowns. When you start getting into
packages where you're protecting a lead, you've got to block 'em
all up with nobody slipping off.''
</P>
<P>
   Way put the challenge of securing one and two yards in simpler
terms: ``We've got to start getting that,'' he said. Indeed they
do.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants want to get to that next level: and they'll have to
run to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Things worked out on Sunday, the Big Blue defense made sure of
it. But sooner or later, a team that wants to cross that River
Jordan must have an offense that can drive from end to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scored 31 points but the defense put us in opportune spots
a lot of times and it was still a close game,'' Oben said. ``We
need to pick it up and start making some long drives, but it'll
take time.''
</P>
<P>
   The statistics showed the Giants' shortcomings. The Giants came
up short in time of possession by four and a half minutes (32
minutes 10 seconds for Washington, 27:50 for the Giants) and number
of offensive plays (68 for the Redskins to 59 for the Giants).
</P>
<P>
   The good news, the bottom line in a money game, is that the
Giants are 1-0 and defeated a division rival. The Giants have not
come close to establishing this kind of dominance, though some may
feel it's too early to begin fretting.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Cross, the 10-year veteran tight end was optimistic and
realistic after Sunday's game: ``We'll be OK right now, guys are
still feeling their way through things. We expect everything to
happen all at once, but it doesn't always work like that. It's all
a process.''
</P>
<P>
   This may only be September, but December will be here before you
know it. No one wants to go through those tears again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
