<HEADLINE>
TIME TO SET THE MILLENNIUM CLOCK  
 SEEKING COMPROMISES ON INTERNET DOMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., Va.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Budd Goldman, an inventor in Mineola, N.Y., has earned his
living for two decades making doo-dads. ``Toilet paper holders that
look like the back of cars, masks over shower heads that looked
like celebrities, a little black box that you pushed it and it
cursed,'' Goldman said, describing a few of his greatest hits.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes, at the end of the 20th century, what Goldman
considers his crowning achievement: the Millennium Clock. ``I've
been practicing to get to this one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The desktop clock is a relentless reminder of the remaining
days, hours, minutes and seconds until the arrival of Jan. 1, 2000
_ as determined by the time zone of the person who sets it.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said the idea came to him in 1986, as he walked down a
street in Seoul, South Korea. ``There were billboards counting down
to the Olympics,'' he said. ``The idea germinated, and I decided to
make a small version of a countdown clock,'' which would use an LCD
display to count the days until an impending milestone, like a
birthday or an anniversary. But the idea flopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sell any,'' he said. ``Zippo.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward a decade to 1996, just as millennium fever was
starting to infuse the country. ``I was on the corner of 34th and
Seventh and there was this billboard from a restaurant saying,
`We'll be feeding customers into the new millennium.''' he said.
``The light bulb went off.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said he has already sold a million millennium clocks,
mostly to department stores and to corporate clients who put their
own logos on the clock's face and give them away as premiums. The
clocks can be ordered through the Countdown Clock International
Inc. Web site (http://www.countdownclock.com) for $24.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole emotionality going on, counting down to the
future,'' he said. ``I'm a lucky guy to have been able to give this
to the world _ and to make a couple of bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Once New Year's Day 2000 arrives, the devices will still have a
function, because they can double at any time as a regular clock.
And Goldman hopes his business, Countdown Clocks International
Inc., will still have a purpose, too. He is about to announce
countdown models for wedding days and pregnancy due dates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Napoli
</P>
<P>
   Seeking Compromises On Internet Domain
</P>
<P>
   With the Clinton administration planning to end federal
financing for the management of Internet domain names on Sept. 30,
the disparate forces struggling to constitute the global network's
first legitimate governing body remain divided on issues trivial
and profound.
</P>
<P>
   As negotiations continue behind the scenes, the Berkman Center
for Internet and Society at Harvard University has canceled a
planned compromise session for next weekend that had been set at
the behest of one coalition that has sponsored a series of
international meetings on the subject this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not convinced it's a productive thing to do,'' said Joe
Sims, a lawyer who is advising Jon Postel, the man who has handled
the administrative end of the Internet's address system for the
last 30 years under the auspices of the federally financed Internet
Assigned Numbers Authority, or IANA.
</P>
<P>
   To replace IANA, Postel has proposed a new administrative body
that would balance the interests of trademark holders, domain name
registrars, national governments and individual Internet users _
and still allow engineers to keep the addresses straight. His
approach has been embraced by the Internet's technical community.
</P>
<P>
   But Network Solutions Inc., the company based in Herndon, Va.,
that currently holds an exclusive contract with the U.S. government
to allocate the most popular domains _ including addresses ending
in ``.com'' _ has declined to sign on. So has the International
Trademark Association.
</P>
<P>
   Among the points of dispute are whether the new group would be
likely to favor adding many more domain names, which trademark
holders oppose, or to impose regulations on registrars _ something
Network Solutions opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ira Magaziner, the senior White House adviser on Internet
issues, said he was optimistic that a compromise would be reached
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any negotiation,'' he said, ``if you get things down to two
factions you can lock them in a room and push them to have an
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Amy Harmon
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
