<SLUG> BC-FBN-RICE-JOHNSON-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERHAPS OLD JERRY RICE MET THE NEW JERRY RICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 BY MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Right before halftime of Sunday's spectacular
game between the Jets and the 49ers, San Francisco wide receiver
Jerry Rice got into a scuffle with a New York Jets player. The two
started pushing and shoving, and Rice was not about to back down.
Later, Rice could not remember what started the argument, but he
did remember who broke it up. It was Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Jerry, Jerry, just relax,''' Rice said of the Jets'
wide receiver. ``He was trying to calm me down.''
</P>
<P>
   It was revealing that Johnson, considered a trash-talking,
smart-mouthed player by many in the National Football League, was
trying to calm down Rice, considered an even-tempered, class act.
The revelations didn't stop there.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the excitement of the 49ers' 36-30 overtime victory was
something not as obvious as the great game, but in a way just as
powerful. It was the spectacular performance by Johnson, which
propelled the wide receiver to the level of other great young
receivers in the game. In a way, Johnson made a solid argument that
he is the next Jerry Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is a future Hall of Famer, and despite missing most of last
season with devastating knee injuries, he still had a dazzling
14-yard touchdown catch Sunday, showing that there is still
something left. The play he scored on was called ``sprint left
option'' and it was the 38th time Rice had scored a touchdown on
it. Despite being double-teamed often, especially near the end
zone, Rice still managed six catches for 86 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson made a statement of his own, exploding for two
striking touchdown catches of 41 and 21 yards. What Johnson did
with his nine catches for 126 yards _ his most productive day as a
pro _ was elevate himself to the level of a top-10 receiver, maybe
even top five. He has always had a Pro Bowl mouth, but this day put
him on the level of the new crop of young receivers in the league,
players like Minnesota's Randy Moss. The next generation of great
receivers is coming into focus, and now Johnson is among the top
players on that list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Keyshawn is very talented and he proved that today,''
Rice said. ``The thing about Keyshawn now, as opposed to before, is
that he does his talking on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson, the Jets are assured of being a contender this
season, not simply for the division title but for a Super Bowl
berth. Johnson is now that good. He provides the explosiveness that
teams need to make a serious playoff run. Seeing the Jets in the
playoffs after such a horrible loss may seem ridiculous, but
remember, many thought there was no way the Jets could win this
game. Not only did they come close, but they beat up a 49ers team
some are picking to win the National Football Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is still great, but it is noticeable that receivers like
Johnson and Moss are beginning to pass him by. These are hard words
to write, of course, and Rice should be given a break. This was his
first game back, so you can expect his performance to improve
dramatically as the season goes on. And once anyone even raises the
question of whether or not Rice is being surpassed, Rice will use
that as motivation the way the sun uses hydrogen as fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically want to take it slow right now and slowly work my
way back into it,'' Rice said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet it was hard not to compare the way Johnson looked to the way
Rice did. Rice always had incredible explosion after a catch; so
does Johnson. Rice always scared teams; now Johnson does. Rice can
still cause nightmares, but Johnson is the now the one wearing the
ski mask. Johnson is now even better at doing what Rice has always
been great at, pushing off the defender to get separation while the
officials have their heads turned. Johnson did it several times,
and it worked perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the Jets have done with Johnson since Bill Parcells
became coach has worked. Johnson has evolved from a receiver with
potential to a player with talent and moves and a killer instinct.
On both touchdown passes, he so badly faked out the safeties and
cornerbacks covering him that he had at least 5 yards of space. It
was a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Now what Johnson needs to develop are his leadership skills.
That does not mean writing books ripping teammates, coaches and
members of the news media, or talking about how good you are. It
means running hills until you drop in the off-season, or getting up
at 5 a.m. and lifting weights until noon, like Rice has done almost
every day in his career. Like Rice said, Johnson now lets his
performance do the talking. Let's hope it stays that way.
</P>
<P>
   Rice won't pass the torch; he's too much of a competitor.
Someone will have to take it from him. Johnson is so good right
now, he might just do it, sooner than anyone thinks.
</P>
</TEXT>
