<HEADLINE>
STEELERS' POISE THWARTS RAVENS' POTENTIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ It was like a shiny new penny, glistening from end
to end. The Baltimore Ravens' new $223 million stadium (no name
yet) was packed with 68,847 people Sunday afternoon and it was hot
(91 degrees). Loud jets flew overhead and louder fireworks popped
and the band played on. The Ravens were ready to do something big
to Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   But the Steelers had that look in their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens hustled from the start, popping Pittsburgh, holding
Jerome Bettis to 9 rushing yards in the first half. They stymied
Pittsburgh quarterback Kordell Stewart _ he had no touchdown passes
and was intercepted twice in the half. It was tied, 3-3, at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   But the Steelers returned with that look in their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The look of champions. The look of a team that had won the last
five American Football Conference Central crowns. The look of a
team ready for the moment, ready for the challenge of an improved
team, a team unbeaten in the preseason, a team intent on setting a
new standard in the division. What Pittsburgh has done, Baltimore
wants to do. But the Ravens are not quite ready.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have that look.
</P>
<P>
   They played hard. They did not play smart.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers won this '98 debut for both teams, 20-13, because
they recognize success and how to play hard and fight through tough
times. They know how to let a team choke itself and then bury that
team in its own panic and chaos. And, in part, that is what
happened Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Said Steelers back Fred McAfee: ``There was a lot of pomp and
circumstance here. A lot of hoopla. We just went out and did what
we do. We smash-mouth. They are a talented squad. They had a lot of
opportunities. They could have won. But they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   It went this way:
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers scored a field goal on their first drive. On their
second drive, Rod Woodson _ now a Raven, formerly a Steeler _
dropped a potential interception near the Pittsburgh 37. The Ravens
scored on a field goal. The Ravens got an interception, but Matt
Stover missed a 42-yard field goal right. With nine minutes left
before halftime, Ravens quarterback Jim Harbaugh left the game for
good with a broken ring finger on his right (passing) hand. He is
questionable next week for the Jets game. Then, after a shaky snap,
Stover missed a 42-yard field goal left.
</P>
<P>
   On the opening drive of the third quarter, Stover missed a
45-yard field goal left. Pittsburgh scored a field goal to take a
6-3 lead, and on the next possession, the Ravens botched a snap on
a punt, the Steelers recovered at the Ravens' 5 and scored a
touchdown to make it 13-3. The Ravens never got back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens jumped offside three times on third-and-short plays.
Receivers dropped passes, one an apparent easy touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh built its lead to 20-3 early in the fourth quarter on
a spiffy Stewart-to-Charles-Johnson play-fake pass for 20 yards.
The Ravens fought valiantly, though, with Stover finally making a
25-yard field goal with 6 minutes 56 seconds remaining and on a
64-yard score from Eric Zeier to receiver Jermaine Lewis with 2:48
left. The Ravens got the ball once more, after the Steelers' last
possession, but even that didn't work out. Steelers punter Josh
Miller booted the ball 68 yards to the Ravens' 4-yard line with 27
seconds and no Ravens timeouts left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts a great deal,'' Ravens Coach Ted Marchibroda said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
