<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-GRANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES, MONEY AND ANOTHER LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Geoff Grant walked out of the locker room and toward
the light Sunday, his coach and manager, Terry London, filming him
from behind. Grant was heading for Stadium 3 and a third-round date
with another tall tennis player with a low profile, and London
wanted this walk for Grant's video archives.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted a record of the atmosphere: the encroaching crowds,
the U.S. Open operating at full throttle on this first Sunday. But
when Grant trudged back to the locker room nearly four hours later,
London's camera was no longer rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, a 28-year-old tennis player in a hurry to make up for
missed Grand Slams, had come tantalizingly close to reaching the
Round of 16 at his nation's most important tournament. He had led
two sets to one and had been 2 points from victory in the fifth set
on Oliver Gross' serve. But in spite of the cramps that Gross said
he began feeling early in the fourth set and in spite of the
subjective crowd that had taken Grant to heart on this dry,
daunting afternoon, the unlikely German, not the unlikely American,
would end up the winner by 7-5, 6-7 (5-7), 5-7, 6-3, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little painful,'' Grant said of his 3 hour 38 minute
adventure. ``But that's what this sport is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennis has delivered some body blows to Grant as he has
struggled to carve out a career. Until recently, there has been a
shortage of money, a shortage of recognition and a shortage of
encouraging words from the people who control the purse strings and
keys to tennis in the United States. Grant has been playing almost
exclusively in the minor leagues of tennis _ satellite and
challenger events _ since he graduated from Duke with a degree in
political science.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finished college, which is somewhat rare in professional
tennis, and I was kind of penalized in a way for doing that back in
the early '90s,'' he said. ``I think you were considered to have no
chance if you went to college and graduated. You were considered
old at like 22 or 23. They neglected to give support to guys like
myself, but now I think their philosophy has changed quite a bit.
They're helping out a lot of guys who have gone to college and
rightly so. I think we can be a good asset to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant quit for 10 months in late 1994, only to return because he
realized that the workaday world was not going to quell the nagging
voice in his head. ``They're both the real world,'' he said. ``I'd
rather be in the tennis world. I look forward to the business world
when I'm done, but I hope that time isn't for a little bit longer:
at least five or six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are sanguine words from a man whose serve is not big
enough to win many easy points, but Grant was in a mood to
emphasize the positive after his match Sunday. He had requested to
play on Stadium 3, the most intimate and boisterous of the three
show courts at the National Tennis Center, and for a man who has
played in front of many empty seats, the shrieks and the shouts and
the stomping of feet were an elixir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll remember it forever,'' he said. ``I hope that can get me
a little bit more recognition. It's tough to get recognition in
this country unless you're Top 10 in the world or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant is 133rd, and with his blue bandanna, wavy red hair and
rope necklace, he looks like the sort of athlete who might feel the
pull of ultimate Frisbee or climbing a sheer face at Yosemite
instead of tennis. But his flat, two-handed ground strokes, speed
and ability to finish off points at the net make him a dangerous
hardcourt player. And the two matches he won here, beating Javier
Sanchez and Andrei Medvedev, gave him his first Grand Slam
victories and the best payday of his career: $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally out of debt,'' he said. ``I'll probably do a little
bit of shopping tomorrow.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
