<HEADLINE>
TWO MORE TV STATIONS DROP HOWARD STERN'S SHOW  
 HIGH-PROFILE AUTHORS TURN TO MUCH YOUNGER READERS  
 HOLLYWOOD TAKES BREAK OVER LABOR DAY WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif., Texas)   (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.)  
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two more television stations, in Phoenix and in San Diego,
dropped Howard Stern's late-night show from their schedules last
week, joining a station in Lubbock, Texas, which did so last
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Why now? Didn't station executives know the
content of ``The Howard Stern Radio Show,'' as the television show
is titled, before they bought it?
</P>
<P>
   Evidently hearing is not believing. Even those familiar with
Stern's daily radio show, from which the TV show's segments are
culled, find it a different matter to experience the same jokes
visually.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schwartz, the vice president for programming at KTVK, an
independent station in Phoenix, who made the decision to drop
Stern's show, said on Friday: ``As popular as he is and as funny as
he is on the radio _ and on the radio he really does funny bits _
it seems that when you add pictures to that humor, as he has done
with his television show, it ceases to be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, which had its debut Aug. 22 and is distributed by
Eyemark Entertainment, a syndication company owned by CBS, is still
begin carried by 76 stations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schwartz said she had bought the show because she knew how
popular Stern was with men, especially young men, and wanted to
attract more male viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the cruelty was what we just couldn't handle,'' Ms.
Schwartz said, citing segments in which mentally disabled people
entered a ``Frankenstein beauty contest'' and played a dating game.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McKinnon, vice president for broadcast operations and
programming at KUSI, an independent station in San Diego, could not
be reached for comment, but the station confirmed that McKinnon had
dropped the show.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   High-Profile Authors Turn to Much Younger Readers
</P>
<P>
   Several high-profile authors have recently written or agreed to
write children's books, and Hyperion Books for Children has created
a new imprint, Jump at the Sun. It will produce children's books
with an African-American emphasis by authors like Toni Morrison and
Bell Hooks.
</P>
<P>
   This trend has the potential to bolster the flat sales of
children's hardcover books, but publishers said the string of
titles by highly marketable authors was coincidental and reflected
the desire of many authors to write children's books.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Carol Oates' first book for children, ``Come Meet
Muffin!,'' a story about a cat, is scheduled to come out on Sept.
21 with a first printing of 10,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone warned me to make sure the book wasn't seen as a
famous fiction writer taking the day off to write a children's
book, slumming it, so we promoted it as an important book,'' said
Dan Halpern, editor in chief of the publisher, Ecco Press. ``I'd be
surprised if it's a trend, because kids' books are very hard to
sell. Just having a big name writing a children's book doesn't help
unless the book is really good and the illustrations are great.''
</P>
<P>
   Next spring, Patricia Cornwell will move from murder to magic
realism for children with ``Life's Little Fable,'' published by
Penguin Putnam Books for Young Readers, a unit of Pearson PLC.
</P>
<P>
   And Louise Erdrich's second children's book, a novel called
``The Birchbark House,'' set to be released in April 1999 from
Hyperion Books for Children, part of Walt Disney Co., will be the
first in a proposed series about an American Indian family in the
mid-1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Jump at the Sun will release the first children's books by Ms.
Morrison and Ms. Hooks in fall 1999. This month, ``Marisol and
Magdalena,'' a young-adult novel by Veronica Chambers, a culture
writer for Newsweek, will be in stores.
</P>
<P>
   _ KAREN ANGEL
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Takes Break Over Labor Day Weekend
</P>
<P>
   Movie addicts who were eager for a hot new film over the Labor
Day weekend found slim pickings. But that was intentional on
Hollywood's part. For filmmakers, the good news about Labor Day is
the lack of competition; the bad news is the dearth of potential
moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the only major new release _ defined as opening at
more than 1,200 screens nationwide _ was Sony's ``Knock Off,''
starring the martial artist Jean-Claude Van Damme. With little
competition, the film has free sailing for the next couple of
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Long holiday weekends, with their extra day of leisure, are
typically a popular time to introduce films. But movie companies
tend to shy away from Labor Day, when many families are distracted
by the back-to-school drill, and studios do not want to compete
against entrenched films that have been playing throughout August
and have already built up audience demand.
</P>
<P>
   The next big bumper crop of movies does not arrive until
Thanksgiving weekend, a prime movie-watching period when at least
six high-profile films are scheduled to open _ including ``A Bug's
Life'' and ``Enemy of the State'' from Walt Disney, Columbia's ``I
Still Know What You Did Last Summer'' and Paramount's ``Rugrats.''
</P>
<P>
   So why did Sony choose Labor Day to open the Van Damme vehicle?
</P>
<P>
   ``You grab an open weekend any time you can get it, and we are
certainly not spending a lot of money on this one,'' said Sony's
head of distribution, Jeff Blake.
</P>
<P>
   _ GERALDINE FABRIKANT
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980906.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1829 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      09-06 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY MARK VEVERKA
</HEADLINE>
  
 Flap Over Friendliness at Safeway Gives Unions a Bad Name   &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In honor of Labor Day, I would like to weigh in on the
labor-management flap between Safeway and a couple of the
supermarket chain's local unions in the East Bay.
<P>
   The issues raised by United Food &AMP; Commercial Workers Union
Locals 1179 and 373 are asinine, unenlightened and
counterproductive. And the media coverage, especially on talk
radio, has been nothing less than moronic.
</P>
<P>
   Don't we, as an allegedly civilized people, have something
better to debate other than whether supermarket clerks should be
asked by their employer to be friendly to their customers?
</P>
<P>
   Before I go any further, I would like to make clear that I'm not
an anti-union, pro-management lackey. I currently am a dues-paying
member of the Communications Workers of America and have been a
unionized employee at two previous jobs. In addition, I've come to
appreciate the importance of union representation while covering
companies whose employees were represented by the United Auto
Workers and the International Association of Machinists.
</P>
<P>
   But recent accusations made by a couple of UFCW Locals give
unions a bad name. And more important, they don't even represent
the majority sentiment of their own union nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the rub: Five years ago, Safeway of Oakland implemented a
customer service policy intended on making its supermarkets better
places to shop.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Safeway spokeswoman, the ``broad'' initiative
asked employees to greet and smile at customers whenever possible,
to offer help or directions to customers without them asking and to
offer every customer help with their packages as they leave the
store. Pretty heinous, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Now, a union local president who is up for re-election this fall
held a news conference proclaiming that these policies promote
sexual harassment and place her union brethren under additional
danger. The allegation: that some customers have mistaken the
friendly service for sexual come-ons, provoking accostings outside
the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   UFCW Local President Barbara Carpenter did not return telephone
calls. Nor did Sean Harrigan, the western regional vice president
of the UFCW.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, any such incidents should be taken seriously and
prosecuted if criminal. But the facts, according to Safeway, are
that sexual harassment complaints by employees have not increased,
but declined since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; VEVERKA:Page B2 Col. 1 &QL; 
 &QL; 
VEVERKA: Service Is Key to Keeping Customers &QL; 
From Page B1 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; The other fallacy flaunted by the locals' leadership is that
customers don't like the friendly service. Now is that flat-out
idiotic or what?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there may be a vocal minority that don't want to be
bothered by an overly friendly stock person. And admittedly, having
clerks greet customers by name after reading a computer printout or
personal check may cross the line of privacy and seem creepy to
some.
</P>
<P>
   But do you know what? Successful retailers such as Safeway spend
thousands of dollars a year on research to determine if customers
like this stuff. If their customers hated it, why would the
retailers continue to do it? (And if you're a customer who doesn't
like it, shop somewhere else. That will get Safeway's attention.)
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders have been rewarded by Safeway's emphasis on
service. During the past five years, Safeway's return on equity has
climbed 807 percent, with dividends reinvested in stock, compared
with 139 percent for the rest of the supermarket industry,
according to Standard and Poor's.
</P>
<P>
   Union discontent appears to be isolated to the East Bay.
According to the company, the national union, which represents
about 150,000 employees at 1,400 stores, has no problem with the
customer service policy.
</P>
<P>
   You know why?
</P>
<P>
   Because it makes sense. Retail chains, like Safeway, are
fighting to remain profitable and grow. These days, their profit
margins are razor-thin, and the best way to assure that customers
return to their stores is by providing better service than the
chain down the street. Just ask Wal-Mart, Home Depot and Nordstrom.
Each are tops in their segments and renowned for their motivated
and friendly workforces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Service is absolutely one of the key differentiators,'' says
retail consultant Neil Stern of McMillan/ Doolittle in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do people like what Safeway is doing, but they
appreciate it,'' says Stern, who recently monitored California
focus groups for a retail client.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that strong, democratic unions are vital. And
they should stick to important issues, such as workplace safety and
job security.
</P>
<P>
   And the best way for workers to assure their future employment
is to help their employers compete and thrive. In its current
contract, Safeway granted its union workers 100 percent medical
benefits and a 12 percent raise spread over four years. That's not
shabby. And in return, chief executive Steven Burd would like them
to help harried Safeway shoppers find what they need.
</P>
<P>
   Is this really the makings of real labor-management strife?
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Weisel Watch '98: &LR;  With apologies to the defunct British rock
band The Clash, should Montgomery Securities head Thom Weisel stay
or should he go? Weisel met with top executives of NationsBank on
Thursday to discuss his future at Montgomery, according to a source
at Montgomery with knowledge of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Weisel threatened to quit or went so far as to tender
his resignation in unclear. Last week, Bloomberg News reported that
recent decisions by NationsBank would trigger an escape clause in
Weisel's contract, making it possible for Weisel and other key
executives to leave Montgomery early with their severance packages
intact.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank reportedly has changed its mind on who will report
to who when it comes to high-yield bonds, known as junk bonds. Only
six weeks ago, NationsBank declared that Montgomery would control
that part of the business.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before NationsBank brass took a closer look at
their blueprint for meshing its operations with BankAmerica.
Insiders say the Charlotte brain trust realized that it made more
sense to have the high-yield bond business tied to commercial
lending, the traditional domains of NationsBank and BofA.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some pivotal Montgomery executives are being
stripped of their responsibilities, including Jerry Markowitz, the
senior Montgomery official who had been tapped to head high-yield
sales, trading and research.
</P>
<P>
   Also losing their titles are three Montgomery senior managing
directors: Ned Zachar, head of high-yield research; Ashley
Cooperman, head of high-yield sales; and Pete Wilson, head of
high-yield trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world changed with the acquisition of BankAmerica,'' said
one San Francisco investment banker. ``NationsBank paid for
(Montgomery), and they can paint the car whatever color they
want.''
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank has acknowledged to Weisel and his top lieutenants
that their employment terms have been altered, unlocking their
golden handcuffs a year or two early. They are entitled to share
some of the $360 million in partner payments.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who stays and who goes, don't expect any formal
announcements for at least a couple of weeks, especially not before
Montgomery's annual high-tech conference at San Francisco's Ritz
Carlton, which begins on September 14.
</P>
<P>
   Good Point: An anonymous caller pointed out that last week, I
referred to BankAmerica as ``soon to be NationsBank.'' I didn't
presume to know what they will call the combined bank. That
decision hasn't been announced. Actually, speculation from BofA
employees is that the new, larger bank will be called BankAmerica,
just like the holding company. Considering the amount of brand
equity built into the BofA moniker, it would seem logical to choose
it over NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   However, the same caller quibbled over my statement that
NationsBank is taking over BofA. Of course, the public relations
spin-meisters at both banks call the deal a merger of equals, but
in reality, there is no such thing.
</P>
<P>
   As long as NationsBank Chairman and CEO Hugh McColl is the chief
executive of the new entity and the corporate headquarters is in
Charlotte, the North Carolina bank-holding company is taking over
BofA. Get over it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Correction: &LR;  In a column last Wednesday, the closing stock
price on the first day of trading for Broadcast.com of Dallas was
incorrectly stated. The first-day close was $62.75 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
