<SLUG> BC-BBO-STALLARD-MARIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STALLARD SPEAKS OUT: HE FEELS NO SHAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (js) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Tracy Stallard, who seemed to be ducking telephone
calls about his role in the home run record that the late Roger
Maris is on the verge of losing, welcomed a call Sunday to talk
about that very subject. It enabled him, he said, to clear up any
misimpression that might linger.
</P>
<P>
   Stallard, who turned 61 last Monday, has been revived in the
memories of baseball followers because Mark McGwire is on the verge
of tying and breaking Maris' record of 61, and Sammy Sosa is not
far behind. Neither hit a home run Sunday, leaving McGwire at 60
and Sosa at 58.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind talking about it,'' said Stallard, who threw the
pitch that Maris hit for the home run that broke Babe Ruth's
legendary record. ``It's something I've talked about for 30 years.
I still have the same answer. I'm glad you got me because it will
slow this stuff down.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``stuff'' Stallard referred to was the feeling that he was
always bothered by giving up Maris' 61st home run on the last day
of the 1961 season. His failure to return calls to discuss it
reinforced that belief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any shame at all,'' he said from his home in
Virginia, where he had returned for the Labor Day weekend from the
construction job he is working in Cincinnati. ``I didn't have that
feeling. I never said that. I lost the game, 1-0, and I didn't feel
anything about it. People are always trying to read something into
it. But it has never bothered me to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stallard, who was pitching for the Boston Red Sox, recalled that
he had two balls and no strikes on Maris and threw him a fastball,
``maybe a straight ball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went one-on-one, just like these guys are doing with McGwire
and Sosa,'' said Stallard, who was watching the Cincinnati Reds-St.
Louis Cardinals game on television. ``That's all you can do. There
was not that much emphasis on it at that time. We didn't pay that
much attention to it. It's a lot different now with TV and all the
communications.''
</P>
<P>
   When Maris homered that memorable Oct. 1, Stallard said he
experienced no special feeling. ``It just put you behind, 1-0,'' he
said, ``and you're trying to win the ball game. I came up to hit
the next inning, and I wanted to hit a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not, and he lost the game and went into baseball's memory
bank as the pitcher who gave up the home run. Some pitchers asked
in recent weeks said they would not mind giving up the 62nd home
run. A couple even remarked that giving up the home run was the
only way they might be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't understand why a pitcher would want to give up a home
run,'' said Stallard, who had a 30-57 record in seven major-league
seasons, two of which were spent with the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt for the pitchers facing McGwire and Sosa but
said, ``If they really try hard, why should they be ashamed if they
give it up?''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he wished McGwire and Sosa well. ``I'm happy
for whoever does it,'' he said. ``I think they're good athletes,
and good luck to them. I'm pulling for these guys. It would be
great. I'm happy for them, and I think it's good for baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Stallard said he had talked baseball with people over the years
and not just about that pitch and the home run. ``My God,'' he
said, ``that was just one pitch. There's a lot of other things to
talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Stallard described himself as ``sort of a fan,'' but he
obviously had not lost any of his baseball knowledge. Having
watched McGwire take a third strike a few minutes earlier, he said,
``It looks to me like McGwire guessed on the last pitch. They threw
him a good curveball, and he took it.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching on television, Stallard also saw some members of the
Maris family at the game. Four of Maris' sons were at Busch
Stadium, and Pat Maris, their mother, was supposed to be with them,
but she became ill on the flight to St. Louis and was hospitalized
upon arrival for observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm well acquainted with the Maris family,'' Stallard said.
``They're a great family.''
</P>
<P>
   The former pitcher said he also saw Commissioner Bud Selig on
television talking about the interest the record chase has
generated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first thing I've heard him say that was positive in
two or three years,'' Stallard said.
</P>
<P>
   Stallard said he would return to work after the weekend, and the
record chase may come to him if it lasts beyond the series on
Monday and Tuesday between the Cardinals and Cubs. The Cardinals
play in Cincinnati on Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be at the game in Cincinnati Wednesday,'' he said.
``I'll be back then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
