u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BANKRUPTCY-VICTIM-     09-06 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BANKRUPTCY-VICTIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$200,000 LOST AS AN INVESTMENT GOES BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-BANKRUPTCY-FEUD)  
(lh) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes it can be hard to have sympathy for the kinds of
people who fall for securities schemes: the greedy, the gullible,
the gamblers. But in the case of the Bennett Funding Group, lawyers
say, most victims were careful, conservative people who thought
they were putting their money somewhere safe.
</P>
<P>
   Victims included people like Richard Schiff, 77, a retired
businessman from Long Island, N.Y., who now lives in Boca Raton,
Fla. Schiff lost his $200,000 retirement account by investing in
Bennett. While he is not impoverished by the loss, Schiff said,
``That income would have been very useful.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Russian immigrant who ran a small lumberyard in
Brooklyn, N.Y., Schiff made a career selling plastic laminates,
like Formica, and, with his wife of 53 years, brought up two
children. Heart problems forced him to retire about 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Schiff invested in the Bennett group, he thought he was
buying ``leases from the federal government for mail trucks,'' he
said, with an interest rate of 9 percent. In 1996, after having
invested $135,000 directly in Bennett leases, he agreed to put
$65,000 from his individual retirement account into what he thought
was a Bennett-sponsored fund; four days later, the Bennett
companies filed for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff is a supporter of Richard Breeden, the former chairman of
the Securities and Exchange Commission who is trustee of the
Bennett companies' bankruptcy and is responsible for trying to get
investors' money back. Schiff said he was happy to be finally
recouping money from his investment. But the status of the money in
the fund remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Haunted by the fear that the Bennetts or their associates would
somehow get control of that money, Schiff has hired lawyers to
protect his interests and those of the other fund investors. And
despite his ill health, he has traveled to Utica, N.Y., to appear
in bankruptcy court in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only to recover my money _ I won't stand for somebody
getting away with stealing,'' he said. ``I'm angry the system
allowed this to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
