<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RDP-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON COLLEGE FOOTBALL: IRISH PROVIDE EARLY JOLT AS SEASON KICKS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their off-season conditioning encompassed sprints on the sands
of Lake Michigan, as well as pushing a broken-down van around the
circumference of the Notre Dame field. It built the kind of
strength that the Fighting Irish needed to wear down Michigan in
the second half on Saturday and record the college football
season's first major upset.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the polls at least, Notre Dame has momentum, too. The
Fighting Irish's biggest victory since a 1993 upset of Florida
State vaulted them 12 places to No. 10 in the Associated Press news
media poll and 13 places to No. 11 in the USA Today/ESPN coaches
poll. The 36-20 victory came at the expense of Lloyd Carr's
Wolverines, the defending national co-champions, who fell eight
places to No. 13 in the AP poll and nine places to No. 14 in the
coaches' vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big, big win,'' Notre Dame Coach Bob Davie said. ``It
jump starts our season.''
</P>
<P>
   On college football's first full weekend, rankings and title
hopes changed, and the cases of some Heisman hopefuls improved. In
addition to Notre Dame, which is in the national championship mix,
however briefly, others who secured better footing include:
</P>
<P>
   OHIO STATE: The Buckeyes walloped West Virginia, 34-17, in
Morgantown, W.Va., to demonstrate that they deserved both polls'
top ranking. ``They played like the No. 1 team,'' Mountaineer Coach
Don Nehlen said.
</P>
<P>
   BROCK HUARD AND WASHINGTON: Huard, a 6-foot-5-inch left-hander,
capped a 27-for-47, 318-yard, 4-touchdown day with a genuine
Heisman moment: a 63-yard touchdown pass on fourth-and-17 with just
28 seconds left to upset Arizona State, 42-38, in a thrilling
finish and knocked the Sun Devils out of the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the greatest game I've ever been a part of,'' said
Huard, who decided not to enter the National Football League draft
after last season. His heroics moved the Huskies up to No. 11 in
the news media poll and to No. 10 in the coaches poll.
</P>
<P>
   JOE PATERNO AND PENN STATE: The Nittany Lions' 34-6 rout of No.
21 Southern Mississippi was remarkable because Paterno played two
quarterbacks and got 255 rushing yards, mostly from a trio of
backup running backs.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Paterno is certain to notch career victory No. 300
against Bowling Green, and a place in history alongside Bear
Bryant, Pop Warner and Amos Alonzo Stagg. Not only that, but his
young team moved up four spots to take the No. 9 position in both
polls, so Penn State can also be considered in the title hunt.
</P>
<P>
   As for those who lost ground over the opening weekend:
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN: Penn State's Big Ten rival heads the list. Four missed
field goals and an inability to score touchdowns against a Notre
Dame defense they moved at will dropped the Wolverines out of the
top 10 in both polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We threw the ball well, but we have a long way to go and a lot
of corrections to make,'' said Carr, whose quarterbacks, Tom Brady
and Drew Henson, threw for 322 yards against the Irish.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines can't be counted out of the championship picture,
but with one loss they now have to win their remaining games. It is
asking much of a team that plays Syracuse on Saturday and has games
with Penn State and Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   SYRACUSE AND DONOVAN McNABB: The Orangemen now go to Ann Arbor,
Mich., in a familiar hole after losing to Tennessee, 34-33. News
media voters dropped them two spots to No. 19, and the coaches
dropped them four to No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb didn't hurt himself, rallying his team within 1 minute 43
seconds of an upset with a 21-of-27, 298-yard, two-touchdown day.
But a loss at Michigan would eliminate him as a Heisman candidate
because winning the Big East is not the stuff of legend.
</P>
<P>
   WEST VIRGINIA AND AMOS ZEREOUE: The Mountaineers welcomed the
Buckeyes with talk of a national championship behind running back
Zereoue, who was 10th in the Heisman voting last year. Their poor
performance dropped them to No. 20 in both polls, and now, like
Syracuse, West Virginia must focus on the Big East. And Zereoue
hurt himself with a mediocre 77 yards on 20 carries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   North Carolina, Michigan State, Colorado State and Auburn all
lost and dropped from both polls after showing themselves to be
pretenders. The Tar Heels proved to be the worst offenders, losing
by 13-10 to Miami of Ohio, and now quarterback Oscar Davenport will
be out two to five weeks after surgery on his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   The serious Heisman contenders turned in serious performances in
easier circumstances over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Williams ran for 215 yards and a Texas-record six
touchdowns as the Longhorns handled New Mexico State, 66-36.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky's Tim Couch threw for a school-record 498 yards and
tied his own Southeastern Conference record with seven touchdown
passes in a 68-34 rout of Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   And Daunte Culpepper of Central Florida completed 24-of-37
passes for 370 yards and four touchdowns, and added 69 yards and
two more scores on 11 carries in a 64-30 victory over Louisiana
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Notre Dame set off the first tremor in college football
with a performance that put it in the top 10 of the AP poll for the
first time since 1996. As much it meant to a team coming off a 7-6
season, Davie, the second-year coach, was counseling perspective.
Now is the time for strength of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk about statements and phrases and all those
things,'' he said. ``It comes down to playing, and the guys made
the plays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
