Day for the traditional opening of the fall campaigns, Republican
and Democratic candidates say the Lewinsky matter, a jittery stock
market and tumult abroad have thrust them into the most unsettled,
and unpredictable, election season in years. The uncertainty has
already altered the calculations of Republicans, who say they have
the most to gain, particularly from President Clinton's
difficulties. By Richard L. Berke.
