<P>
   MOVING-MUSICIANS (New York) _ For thousands of musicians who
play instruments larger than a piccolo, just getting to a gig is
more than half the battle. And in summer, when musicians crisscross
the continent on the festival circuit, the living is far from easy.
That's where the professionals come in: the travel agents and
cartage companies and production managers who get their clients,
and their clients' equipment, to their destinations and home again.
By Kathryn Shattuck.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-MINOR-OED (Undated) _ In 1879, when Professor James
Murray began the job of editing the first edition of the Oxford
English Dictionary, the call went out for volunteers to supply
quotations to illustrate definitions. The most prolific and
faithful correspondent, represented by more than 10,000 entries,
was Dr. William Minor, a surgeon residing in Crowthorne in the
English countryside in Berkshire. Murray, who had not yet met
Minor, assumed that he was a ``practicing medical man of literary
tastes with a good deal of leisure.'' To his astonishment, he
turned out to be a patient in the Broadmoor Criminal Lunatic
Asylum. A new book details the strange story of the interwoven
lives of Murray and Minor. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   FRICK-MUSEUM (New York) _ Slowly, with judicious infusions of
technology and a good deal of patience, the Frick's new director is
trying to transform one of the most famously old-fashioned
institutions in Manhattan into one that is more `user-friendly'. By
Carol Vogel.
</P>
