<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-JOB-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MORE JOBS, LESS SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Sept. 7:
</P>
<P>
   As America pauses for Labor Day, more people have jobs than ever
before and the unemployment rate is close to its lowest level in a
generation. At the same time, people are less likely to keep their
jobs for long periods, and the level of layoffs is considerably
higher than it was in earlier economic cycles. These facts are
indicative of a vibrant, competitive economy that provides less
security, for either workers or the companies that hire them, than
the American economy seemed to offer in decades past.
</P>
<P>
   This lack of security is reflected in numerous ways. Companies
are more likely to cut costs quickly in response to competitive
pressures than they once were, leading to more layoffs during the
current economic recovery, which has endured for eight years, than
in previous ones. Deregulation of many industries, from trucking to
telecommunications, has led to new patterns of competition in which
some companies must shed workers while competitors are hiring.
</P>
<P>
   The society has changed to cope with that movement. Pension
plans, for example, are more likely to be defined contribution
plans, such as 401(k)'s, which can move with a worker, rather than
defined benefit plans in which benefits are forfeited if a worker
does not stay with a company for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
   That mobility of workers _ sometimes voluntarily through getting
better jobs and sometimes involuntarily through layoffs and
downsizing _ reflects a worldwide trend. Countries that have
accepted it tend to do much better economically than those that
have not, although at a cost of increased worker anxiety. Japan is
only grudgingly moving away from the lifetime employment policy
that damaged the competitiveness of Japanese companies during this
decade. Neither Russia nor China has yet dealt adequately with the
large state enterprises that have provided employment _ and social
services _ for millions but that cannot profitably make products
that people want.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the 1980s and 1990s, economic statistics seemed to
show that real wages _ what workers make, adjusted for inflation _
had stagnated in this country. Some thought that reflected the
declining power of unions _ which now represent about 13 percent of
workers, down from a peak of 23 percent _ as well as fears of job
loss. The problem may have been overstated, however, because
inflation was actually lower than the consumer price index
indicated and recent figures show a better picture.
</P>
<P>
   The August unemployment report, released Friday, showed that
real wages had risen about 2 percent a year for the past two years.
That may not sound like a lot, but it is the largest such gain in a
quarter-century. Workers now are benefiting from the combination of
a tight domestic labor market and an Asian recession that is
holding down the prices of many things people buy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
