<DOCNO> NYT19980906.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CUNY-NYT &LR;      09-06 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CUNY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: THE POLITICS OF REMEDIAL EDUCATION AT CUNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BRENT STAPLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Heavy-handed politics at the City University of New
York has demoralized both faculty and administrators and led to a
legal battle over an initiative that has made CUNY the first
university of such historic importance to forbid remedial education
on four-year campuses. A court ruling has blocked the plan,
scheduled to begin phasing in in 1999, pending a trial on whether
trustees adopted the policy at a session that violated open-meeting
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Trustees controlled by Gov. George Pataki and Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani could conceivably get around the courts by approving the
plan again _ this time in a meeting that complied with the letter
of the law. But that would leave unanswered a second, more serious
challenge, from the state Board of Regents, which has jurisdiction
on educational policy throughout the state and has faulted CUNY for
rushing into this radical plan without examining its potential
impact.
</P>
<P>
   The new remedial rule would bar from four-year colleges all
entering students who fail any of three skills tests in reading,
writing and mathematics. These students would be funneled into
community colleges, where space is so short that some students are
already chosen by lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The community colleges are staffed mainly by part-timers and
offer anemic curriculums. Students who begin at these campuses are
far less likely to receive four-year degrees than those who go
straight to four-year colleges. Students who do not graduate from
four-year colleges are far less appealing in the job market.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study showed that more than 60 percent of CUNY's
graduates _ and 7-in-10 Asians _ started college with at least one
remedial course. Anything that discourages these students would be
a blow to the city's labor force.
</P>
<P>
   The CUNY trustees describe the remedial rule as a way of
boosting standards. But some regents see it as a strategy for
subverting open-admissions requirements that are etched in state
law. They also suspect a stealth plan for shrinking the university
at the expense of new immigrants and poor students who make up the
bulk of enrollment. Most CUNY managers who share this view are
keeping silent for fear of being fired.
</P>
<P>
   The regents' suspicions are spelled out in two letters written
to CUNY by the regents' representative, Deputy Education
Commissioner Gerald Patton. He asked CUNY to document how it would
shift staff, money, facilities and faculty contracts to meet the
new demand at the community colleges. He also pointed out that
students confined to remedial courses _ and barred from taking
college-level courses _ would be ineligible for state tuition aid,
meaning the poorest of them would be driven from school very
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The CUNY trustees will also need to explain why they wish to
make admissions decisions based on a skills test that has not been
nationally normed or statistically validated _ and is not a
reliable predictor of who will fail and who will succeed in
college. In fact, students who fail one, or even two tests often
recover to find themselves among the system's most distinguished
graduates.
</P>
<P>
   The open admissions policy at CUNY required explicit approval
from the regents when it was introduced. In addition, the
Democratic state Assembly took over funding for CUNY's
cash-strapped senior colleges only after extracting a detailed
commitment to provide broad access to the city's disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
   Given its historical role, the state Assembly has been
perplexingly quiet during this fight. The black and Latino caucus,
whose constituents stand to suffer catastrophically, was recently
characterized by one state official as ``cowering in a corner.'' As
though to stiffen the Legislature's spine, the regents have cast
the remedial plan as an attempt by the CUNY trustees to rewrite
state education law.
</P>
<P>
   Some trustees controlled by Pataki and Giuliani see the regents
as a meddlesome bunch that have exceeded their mandate. But with
broad powers outlined in the state's constitution, the regents are
within their rights to intervene in university policy. Just last
year, for example, they berated CUNY's teaching schools for turning
out students who fail the teaching certification exams _ and ruled
that they would shut down teachers' colleges all across the state
unless 80 percent of graduates passed the exam.
</P>
<P>
   Political pressure from the governor and the mayor has forced
the regents to take a more conciliatory tone than Patton began
with. Even so, CUNY's trustees must answer the regents' questions
and submit to probing scrutiny. In the coming months, The regents
will extract an impact report and subject it to evaluations by
outside experts and full-dress public hearings. Even if the regents
fold under political pressure, they will have forced the debate
that should have occurred before this train left the station.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
