<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1965 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLIONYOUTH07-COX     09-06 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLIONYOUTH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson tells Atlanta audience to march on
 &HT;    By Chris Reinolds and Jennifer Brett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, in Atlanta to participate in today's
Million Youth Movement, Sunday night called on youths to ``march to
overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``March to complete Dr. Martin Luther King's business,'' he
shouted during a fiery and deafening speech from the pulpit at
Cathedral of Faith, Church of God in Christ in southwest Atlanta.
The march today _ scheduled to begin at 10 a.m. on Auburn Avenue _
is for equal opportunity, equal protection under the law, fair
share and equal access, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the youth are marching to keep young black people
out of jail and in schools. Without marches, Atlanta would not be
the cosmopolitan city it is today, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't have CNN, the Atlanta Braves or the Olympics in
Atlanta had our (civil rights) marches not succeeded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He encouraged young black people to register and use their right
to vote and use the march to fight a variety of social ills.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Sunday, the Rev. Menelik Kimathi hailed the sacrifices
of civil rights leaders of past decades and urged today's youth to
continue their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are standing on the shoulders of giants who did their part
before us, and now we have a part to play,'' Kimathi told the
congregation of the Shrine of the Black Madonna on Ralph David
Abernathy Boulevard. Today's scheduled speakers include NAACP
Executive Director Kweisi Mfume, Jackson, Southern Christian
Leadership Conference President Martin Luther King III and National
Council of Negro Women Chairman Emeritus Dorothy Height. Among the
youth expected to speak are Jean Ayinde-Baptiste, who addressed the
1995 Million Man March, the Rev. Jamal Bryant of the NAACP,
Kimberly Underdue of the NCNW and Ashaad Muhammad of the Nation of
Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Mohammed, Western regional coordinator of the Million
Youth Movement, estimated thousands of young people have come to
Atlanta for the weekend's events. He said the movement's goals are
to emphasize economic development, spiritual awareness and
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through those three things, you can move ahead in any
society,'' he said. ``All three things work for the good of the
Lord. If it works good for the Lord, it works for the Lord's
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Conner, a Birmingham native who attends Morris Brown
College, said she plans to attend today's march.
</P>
<P>
   ``The youth of America is in a state of emergency,'' she said.
The Rev. Al Sharpton, an outspoken activist who attended the
Million Youth March in New York on Saturday, also spoke at the
Sunday night service with Jackson. He said many young people
participated in positive actions despite the reports of police
clashes in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a rally of hate,'' Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the news media should focus on the march's message,
not the New York problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police rushed the stage and that was very provocative. That
would not happen in Atlanta,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
