<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 6, 1998 -- CLINTON-HYDE, 9-6 -- Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., head of the United States Judiciary Committee,
is seeking sweeping powers never granted to a House panel as it
prepares to accept the report from the Whitewater independent
counsel, Kenneth Starr. House Democrats, led by Rep. Dick Gephardt
of Missouri, have complained that Republicans are laying the
framework for handling Starr's report outlining possible
impeachable offenses without consulting Democrats. (Scott
Robinson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PHILADELPHIA -- Sept. 6, 1998 -- PHILLY-PAPER-MEDIA, 9-6
-- Ralph Cipriano, 44, a reporter for The Philadelphia Inquirer,
filed a libel suit against the paper after the editor, Robert
Rosenthal, publicly questioned the objectivity and value of his
reporting on the Archdiocese of Philadelphia. Last month, Cipriano
was dismissed after he refused to give editors his notes relating
to the story. It is Cipriano's contention in his suit that The
Inquirer ``did not wish to offend the archdiocese'' and risk losing
readers among the area's 1.4 million Catholics. (Sal DiMarco
Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) FLORENCE, Ky. -- Sept. 6, 1998 -- MIDTERM-POLITICS, 9-6
-- Ken Lucas, a Kentucky Democratic candidate who is locked in a
tight House race, greeting Carl Agin. Lucas, who has said he does
not want to appear with President Clinton, is one of the latest
Democrats to spurn Clinton while on the campaign trail. ``I'm
running my own race and I don't plan on running any events with
him,'' says Lucas. ``Here in this particular race in Kentucky,
integrity and taking responsibility for your actions and honesty
are big factors.'' (Mark Lyons/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BALTIMORE -- Sept. 6, 1998 -- TEACHER-BONUSES, 9-6 --
Lasheaka Timmons, 23, of Arizona, accepted a job teaching at the
West Baltimore Middle School, through Teach for America, which
places rookie teachers in urban districts. Ms. Timmons says she
would have had to turn down the job, without a $1,200 loan to cover
moving expenses that school officials in Baltimore offered her.
``Just out of college, unless you come from a background where your
parents can afford to help you, you wouldn't be able to relocate,''
she says. ``It makes you feel they want you.'' (Marty Katz/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
