<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 9/6/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- -- Sept. 6, 1998 -- TEN-USOPEN-2, 9-6 --
Monica Seles, seeded sixth in the U.S. Open, powering her way to
victory over Kimberly Po. Seles dropped her first set of the
tournament, squandering a 4-1 second-set lead, before righting
herself against Po and advancing 6-2, 4-6, 6-3 to a quarterfinal
meeting with top-seeded Martina Hingis, the Open's defending
champion. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- -- Sept. 6, 1998 -- TEN-USOPEN-1, 9-6 --
Patty Schnyder, 19, of Switzerland, seeded 11th in the U.S. Open,
celebrating the moment of victory over Steffi Graf, the
eighth-seeded player on Sunday night. Schnyder blasted her way to a
6-3, 6-4 upset of the eighth-seeded Graf. Graf, a five-time Open
champion who missed this Grand Slam event last year while
recuperating from career-threatening knee surgery, made her
earliest exit from this major championship in 14 years. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1998 -- NY-YOUTH-MARCH, 9-6 --
Khallid Abdul Muhammad, center right, wearing a stripped sash over
his suit, in the middle of riot police and a crowd of people
attending a youth rally in Harlem on Saturday, otherwise known as
``The Million Youth March.'' Tensions about the rally's abrupt
ending are mounting, with the organizers and community leaders in
Harlem accusing Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and the New York City Police
Department of using excessive force to shut down what had been a
peaceful event. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1998 -- FRICK-MUSEUM, 9-6 --
Visitors at the Frick Museum in Manhattan using new digital
multilanguage Acoustiguides. The Frick Collection, with its stately
setting, is seeking to be a ``more welcoming place,'' while still
preserving its air of serenity. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1998 -- MOVING-MUSICIANS, 9-6 --
Susan Salm, a musician with the Raphael Trio, pushing her cello
into a taxi in Manhattan. Ms. Salm, who travels quite extensively,
knows the intricacies of moving her large instrument across
continents and oceans perhaps a bit too well. For thousands of
musicians who, like Salm, play instruments larger than a piccolo,
just getting from point A to point B can be quite an adventure.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 6, 1998 -- CLINTON-HYDE, 9-6 -- Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., head of the United States Judiciary Committee,
is seeking sweeping powers never granted to a House panel as it
prepares to accept the report from the Whitewater independent
counsel, Kenneth Starr. House Democrats, led by Rep. Dick Gephardt
of Missouri, have complained that Republicans are laying the
framework for handling Starr's report outlining possible
impeachable offenses without consulting Democrats. (Scott
Robinson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
